By the time Harry arrived in the kitchen, the three Dursleys were already seated around the table. None of them looked up as he entered or sat down. Uncle Vernon\rquote s large red face was hidden behind the morning\rquote s \i Daily Mail, \i0 and Aunt Petunia was cutting a grapefruit into quarters, her lips pursed over her horselike teeth.\par
Dudley looked furious and sulky, and somehow seemed to be taking up even more space than usual. This was saying something, as he always took up an entire side of the square table by himself. When Aunt Petunia put a quarter of unsweetened grapefruit onto Dudley\rquote s plate with a tremulous \ldblquote There you are, Diddy darling,\rdblquote  Dudley glowered at her. His life had taken a most unpleasant turn since he had come home for the summer with his end-of-year report.\par
Uncle Vernon and Aunt Petunia had managed to find excuses for his bad marks as usual: Aunt Petunia always insisted that Dud\-ley was a very gifted boy whose teachers didn\rquote t understand him, while Uncle Vernon maintained that \ldblquote he didn\rquote t want some swotty little nancy boy for a son anyway.\rdblquote  They also skated over the accu\-sations of bullying in the report \emdash  \ldblquote He\rquote s a boisterous little boy, but he wouldn\rquote t hurt a fly!\rdblquote  Aunt Petunia had said tearfully.\par
However, at the bottom of the report there were a few well-chosen comments from the school nurse that not even Uncle Ver\-non and Aunt Petunia could explain away. No matter how much Aunt Petunia wailed that Dudley was big-boned, and that his poundage was really puppy fat, and that he was a growing boy who needed plenty of food, the fact remained that the school outfitters didn\rquote t stock knickerbockers big enough for him anymore. The school nurse had seen what Aunt Petunia\rquote s eyes \emdash  so sharp when it came to spotting fingerprints on her gleaming walls, and in ob\-serving the comings and goings of the neighbors \emdash  simply refused to see: that far from needing extra nourishment, Dudley had reached roughly the size and weight of a young killer whale.\par
So \emdash  after many tantrums, after arguments that shook Harry\rquote s bedroom floor, and many tears from Aunt Petunia \emdash  the new regime had begun. The diet sheet that had been sent by the Smelt\-ings school nurse had been taped to the fridge, which had been emptied of all Dudley\rquote s favorite things \emdash  fizzy drinks and cakes, chocolate bars and burgers \emdash  and filled instead with fruit and veg\-etables and the sorts of things that Uncle Vernon called \ldblquote rabbit food.\rdblquote  To make Dudley feel better about it all, Aunt Petunia had insisted that the whole family follow the diet too. She now passed a grapefruit quarter to Harry. He noticed that it was a lot smaller than Dudley\rquote s. Aunt Petunia seemed to feel that the best way to keep up Dudley\rquote s morale was to make sure that he did, at least, get more to eat than Harry.\par
But Aunt Petunia didn\rquote t know what was hidden under the loose floorboard upstairs. She had no idea that Harry was not following the diet at all. The moment he had got wind of the fact that he was expected to survive the summer on carrot sticks, Harry had sent Hedwig to his friends with pleas for help, and they had risen to the occasion magnificently. Hedwig had returned from Hermione\rquote s house with a large box stuffed full of sugar-free snacks. (Hermione\rquote s parents were dentists.) Hagrid, the Hogwarts gamekeeper, had obliged with a sack full of his own homemade rock cakes. (Harry hadn\rquote t touched these; he had had too much experience of Hagrid\rquote s cooking.) Mrs. Weasley, however, had sent the family owl, Errol, with an enormous fruitcake and assorted meat pies. Poor Errol, who was elderly and feeble, had needed a full five days to recover from the journey. And then on Harry\rquote s birthday (which the Dursleys had completely ignored) he had received four superb birthday cakes, one each from Ron, Hermione, Hagrid, and Sirius. Harry still had two of them left, and so, looking forward to a real breakfast when he got back upstairs, he ate his grapefruit without complaint.\par
Uncle Vernon laid aside his paper with a deep sniff of disap\-proval and looked down at his own grapefruit quarter.\par
\ldblquote Is this it?\rdblquote  he said grumpily to Aunt Petunia.\par
Aunt Petunia gave him a severe look, and then nodded pointedly at Dudley, who had already finished his own grapefruit quarter and was eyeing Harry\rquote s with a very sour look in his piggy little eyes.\par
Uncle Vernon gave a great sigh, which ruffled his large, bushy mustache, and picked up his spoon.\par
The doorbell rang. Uncle Vernon heaved himself out of his chair and set off down the hall. Quick as a flash, while his mother was occupied with the kettle, Dudley stole the rest of Uncle Vernon\rquote s grapefruit.\par
Harry heard talking at the door, and someone laughing, and Uncle Vernon answering curtly. Then the front door closed, and the sound of ripping paper came from the hall.\par
Aunt Petunia set the teapot down on the table and looked curi\-ously around to see where Uncle Vernon had got to. She didn\rquote t have to wait long to find out; after about a minute, he was back. He looked livid.\par
\ldblquote You,\rdblquote  he barked at Harry. \ldblquote In the living room. Now.\rdblquote\par
Bewildered, wondering what on earth he was supposed to have done this time, Harry got up and followed Uncle Vernon out of the kitchen and into the next room. Uncle Vernon closed the door sharply behind both of them.\par
\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  he said, marching over to the fireplace and turning to face Harry as though he were about to pronounce him under arrest. \ldblquote\i So.\i0\rdblquote\par
Harry would have dearly loved to have said, \ldblquote So what?\rdblquote  but he didn\rquote t feel that Uncle Vernon\rquote s temper should be tested this early in the morning, especially when it was already under severe strain from lack of food. He therefore settled for looking politely puzzled.\par
\ldblquote This just arrived,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon. He brandished a piece of purple writing paper at Harry. \ldblquote A letter. About you.\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s confusion increased. Who would be writing to Uncle Vernon about him? Who did he know who sent letters by the postman?\par
Uncle Vernon glared at Harry, then looked down at the letter and began to read aloud:\par
\par
\i Dear Mr. and Mrs. Dursley,\i0\par
\i We have never been introduced, but I am sure you have heard a great deal from Harry about my son Ron.\i0\par
\i As Harry might have told you, the final of the Quidditch World Cup takes place this Monday night, and my husband, Arthur, has just managed to get prime tickets through his con\-nections at the Department of Magical Games and Sports.\i0\par
\i I do hope you will allow us to take Harry to the match, as this really is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity; Britain hasn\rquote t hosted the cup for thirty years, and tickets are extremely hard to come by. We would of course be glad to have Harry stay for the remainder of the summer holidays, and to see him safely onto the train back to school.\i0\par
\i It would be best for Harry to send us your answer as quickly as possible in the normal way, because the Muggle postman has never delivered to our house, and I am not sure he even knows where it is.\i0\par
\i Hoping to see Harry soon,\i0\par
\i Yours sincerely,\par
Molly Weasley\par
\i0\par
\i P.S. I do hope we\rquote ve put enough stamps on\i0 .\par
\par
Uncle Vernon finished reading, put his hand back into his breast pocket, and drew out something else.\par
\ldblquote Look at this,\rdblquote  he growled.\par
He held up the envelope in which Mrs. Weasley\rquote s letter had come, and Harry had to fight down a laugh. Every bit of it was covered in stamps except for a square inch on the front, into which Mrs. Weasley had squeezed the Dursleys\rquote  address in minute writing.\par
\ldblquote She did put enough stamps on, then,\rdblquote  said Harry, trying to sound as though Mrs. Weasley\rquote s was a mistake anyone could make. His uncle\rquote s eyes flashed.\par
\ldblquote The postman noticed,\rdblquote  he said through gritted teeth. \ldblquote Very in\-terested to know where this letter came from, he was. That\rquote s why he rang the doorbell. Seemed to think it was \i funny.\i0\rdblquote\par
Harry didn\rquote t say anything. Other people might not understand why Uncle Vernon was making a fuss about too many stamps, but Harry had lived with the Dursleys too long not to know how touchy they were about anything even slightly out of the ordinary. Their worst fear was that someone would find out that they were connected (however distantly) with people like Mrs. Weasley.\par
Uncle Vernon was still glaring at Harry, who tried to keep his ex\-pression neutral. If he didn\rquote t do or say anything stupid, he might just be in for the treat of a lifetime. He waited for Uncle Vernon to say something, but he merely continued to glare. Harry decided to break the silence.\par
\ldblquote So \emdash  can I go then?\rdblquote  he asked.\par
A slight spasm crossed Uncle Vernon\rquote s large purple face. The mustache bristled. Harry thought he knew what was going on be\-hind the mustache: a furious battle as two of Uncle Vernon\rquote s most fundamental instincts came into conflict. Allowing Harry to go would make Harry happy, something Uncle Vernon had struggled against for thirteen years. On the other hand, allowing Harry to disappear to the Weasleys\rquote  for the rest of the summer would get rid of him two weeks earlier than anyone could have hoped, and Uncle Vernon hated having Harry in the house. To give himself thinking time, it seemed, he looked down at Mrs. Weasley\rquote s letter again.\par
\ldblquote Who is this woman?\rdblquote  he said, staring at the signature with distaste.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve seen her,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote She\rquote s my friend Ron\rquote s mother, she was meeting him off the Hog \emdash  off the school train at the end of last term.\rdblquote\par
He had almost said \ldblquote Hogwarts Express,\rdblquote  and that was a sure way to get his uncle\rquote s temper up. Nobody ever mentioned the name of Harry\rquote s school aloud in the Dursley household.\par
Uncle Vernon screwed up his enormous face as though trying to remember something very unpleasant.\par
\ldblquote Dumpy sort of woman?\rdblquote  he growled finally. \ldblquote Load of children with red hair?\rdblquote\par
Harry frowned. He thought it was a bit rich of Uncle Vernon to call anyone \ldblquote dumpy,\rdblquote  when his own son, Dudley, had finally achieved what he\rquote d been threatening to do since the age of three, and become wider than he was tall.\par
Uncle Vernon was perusing the letter again.\par
\ldblquote Quidditch,\rdblquote  he muttered under his breath. \ldblquote\i Quidditch\i0  \emdash  what is this rubbish?\rdblquote\par
Harry felt a second stab of annoyance.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s a sport,\rdblquote  he said shortly. \ldblquote Played on broom \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right, all right!\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon loudly. Harry saw, with some satisfaction, that his uncle looked vaguely panicky. Appar\-ently his nerves couldn\rquote t stand the sound of the word \ldblquote broom\-sticks\rdblquote  in his living room. He took refuge in perusing the letter again. Harry saw his lips form the words \ldblquote send us your answer \'85 in the normal way.\rdblquote  He scowled.\par
\ldblquote What does she mean, \lquote the normal way\rquote ?\rdblquote  he spat.\par
\ldblquote Normal for us,\rdblquote  said Harry, and before his uncle could stop him, he added, \ldblquote you know, owl post. That\rquote s what\rquote s normal for wizards.\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon looked as outraged as if Harry had just uttered a disgusting swear word. Shaking with anger, he shot a nervous look through the window, as though expecting to see some of the neigh\-bors with their ears pressed against the glass.\par
\ldblquote How many times do I have to tell you not to mention that un\-naturalness under my roof?\rdblquote  he hissed, his face now a rich plum color. \ldblquote You stand there, in the clothes Petunia and I have put on your ungrateful back \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Only after Dudley finished with them,\rdblquote  said Harry coldly, and indeed, he was dressed in a sweatshirt so large for him that he had had to roll back the sleeves five times so as to be able to use his hands, and which fell past the knees of his extremely baggy jeans.\par
\ldblquote I will not be spoken to like that!\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, trembling with rage.\par
But Harry wasn\rquote t going to stand for this. Gone were the days when he had been forced to take every single one of the Dursleys\rquote  stupid rules. He wasn\rquote t following Dudley\rquote s diet, and he wasn\rquote t going to let Uncle Vernon stop him from going to the Quidditch World Cup, not if he could help it. Harry took a deep, steadying breath and then said, \ldblquote Okay, I can\rquote t see the World Cup. Can I go now, then? Only I\rquote ve got a letter to Sirius I want to finish. You know \emdash  my godfather.\rdblquote\par
He had done it. He had said the magic words. Now he watched the purple recede blotchily from Uncle Vernon\rquote s face, making it look like badly mixed black currant ice cream.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re \emdash  you\rquote re writing to him, are you?\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, in a would-be calm voice \emdash  but Harry had seen the pupils of his tiny eyes contract with sudden fear.\par
\ldblquote Well \emdash  yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, casually. \ldblquote It\rquote s been a while since he heard from me, and, you know, if he doesn\rquote t, he might start think\-ing something\rquote s wrong.\rdblquote\par
He stopped there to enjoy the effect of these words. He could al\-most see the cogs working under Uncle Vernon\rquote s thick, dark, neatly parted hair. If he tried to stop Harry writing to Sirius, Sirius would think Harry was being mistreated. If he told Harry he couldn\rquote t go to the Quidditch World Cup, Harry would write and tell Sirius, who would \i know\i0  Harry was being mistreated. There was only one thing for Uncle Vernon to do. Harry could see the conclusion forming in his uncle\rquote s mind as though the great mustached face were transparent. Harry tried not to smile, to keep his own face as blank as possible. And then \emdash\par
\ldblquote Well, all right then. You can go to this ruddy \'85 this stupid \'85 this World Cup thing. You write and tell these \emdash  these \i Weasleys \i0 they\rquote re to pick you up, mind. I haven\rquote t got time to go dropping you off all over the country. And you can spend the rest of the summer there. And you can tell your \emdash  your godfather \'85 tell him \'85 tell him you\rquote re going.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Okay then,\rdblquote  said Harry brightly.\par
He turned and walked toward the living room door, fighting the urge to jump into the air and whoop. He was going \'85 he was going to the Weasleys\rquote , he was going to watch the Quidditch World Cup!\par
Outside in the hall he nearly ran into Dudley, who had been lurking behind the door, clearly hoping to overhear Harry being told off. He looked shocked to see the broad grin on Harry\rquote s face.\par
\ldblquote That was an \i excellent\i0  breakfast, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I feel really full, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
Laughing at the astonished look on Dudley\rquote s face, Harry took the stairs three at a time, and hurled himself back into his bedroom.\par
The first thing he saw was that Hedwig was back. She was sitting in her cage, staring at Harry with her enormous amber eyes, and clicking her beak in the way that meant she was annoyed about something. Exactly what was annoying her became apparent al\-most at once.\par
\ldblquote OUCH!\rdblquote  said Harry as what appeared to be a small, gray, feathery tennis ball collided with the side of his head. Harry mas\-saged the spot furiously, looking up to see what had hit him, and saw a minute owl, small enough to fit into the palm of his hand, whizzing excitedly around the room like a loose firework. Harry then realized that the owl had dropped a letter at his feet. Harry bent down, recognized Ron\rquote s handwriting, then tore open the en\-velope. Inside was a hastily scribbled note.\par
\par
\i Harry \emdash  DAD GOT THE TICKETS \i0\emdash  \i Ireland versus Bulgaria, Monday night. Mum\rquote s writing to the Muggles to ask you to stay. They might already have the letter, I don\rquote t know how fast Muggle post is. Thought I\rquote d send this with Pig anyway.\i0\par
\par
Harry stared at the word \ldblquote Pig,\rdblquote  then looked up at the tiny owl now zooming around the light fixture on the ceiling. He had never seen anything that looked less like a pig. Maybe he couldn\rquote t read Ron\rquote s writing. He went back to the letter:\par
\par
\i We\rquote re coming for you whether the Muggles like it or not, you can\rquote t miss the World Cup, only Mum and Dad reckon it\rquote s better if we pretend to ask their permission first. If they say yes, send Pig back with your answer pronto, and we\rquote ll come and get you at five o\rquote clock on Sunday. If they say no, send Pig back pronto and we\rquote ll come and get you at five o\rquote clock on Sunday anyway.\i0\par
\i Hermione\rquote s arriving this afternoon. Percy\rquote s started work \i0\emdash  \i the Department of International Magical Cooperation. Don\rquote t mention anything about Abroad while you\rquote re here unless you want the pants bored off you.\i0\par
\i See you soon \i0\emdash\par
\par
\i Ron\par
\i0\par
\ldblquote Calm down!\rdblquote  Harry said as the small owl flew low over his head, twittering madly with what Harry could only assume was pride at having delivered the letter to the right person. \ldblquote Come here, I need you to take my answer back!\rdblquote\par
The owl fluttered down on top of Hedwig\rquote s cage. Hedwig looked coldly up at it, as though daring it to try and come any closer.\par
Harry seized his eagle-feather quill once more, grabbed a fresh piece of parchment, and wrote:\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\i Ron, it\rquote s all okay, the Muggles say I can come. See you five o\rquote clock tomorrow. Can\rquote t wait.\par
\par
Harry\i0\par
\par
He folded this note up very small, and with immense difficulty, tied it to the tiny owl\rquote s leg as it hopped on the spot with excite\-ment. The moment the note was secure, the owl was off again; it zoomed out of the window and out of sight.\par
Harry turned to Hedwig.\par
\ldblquote Feeling up to a long journey?\rdblquote  he asked her.\par
Hedwig hooted in a dignified sort of a way.\par
\ldblquote Can you take this to Sirius for me?\rdblquote  he said, picking up his let\-ter. \ldblquote Hang on \'85 I just want to finish it.\rdblquote\par
He unfolded the parchment and hastily added a postscript.\par
\par
\i If you want to contact me, I\rquote ll be at my friend Ron Weasley\rquote s for the rest of the summer. His dad\rquote s got us tickets for the Quid\-ditch World Cup\i0 !\par
\par
The letter finished, he tied it to Hedwig\rquote s leg; she kept unusually still, as though determined to show him how a real post owl should behave.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be at Ron\rquote s when you get back, all right?\rdblquote  Harry told her.\par
She nipped his finger affectionately, then, with a soft swooshing noise, spread her enormous wings and soared out of the open window.\par
Harry watched her out of sight, then crawled under his bed, wrenched up the loose floorboard, and pulled out a large chunk of birthday cake. He sat there on the floor eating it, savoring the hap\-piness that was flooding through him. He had cake, and Dudley had nothing but grapefruit; it was a bright summer\rquote s day, he would be leaving Privet Drive tomorrow, his scar felt perfectly normal again, and he was going to watch the Quidditch World Cup. It was hard, just now, to feel worried about anything \emdash  even Lord Voldemort.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\fs36\page Chapter 4\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc Back to the Burrow\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs20\par
By twelve o\rquote clock the next day, Harry\rquote s school trunk was packed with his school things and all his most prized possessions \emdash  the Invisibility Cloak he had inherited from his father, the broom\-stick he had gotten from Sirius, the enchanted map of Hogwarts he had been given by Fred and George Weasley last year. He had emp\-tied his hiding place under the loose floorboard of all food, double-checked every nook and cranny of his bedroom for forgotten spellbooks or quills, and taken down the chart on the wall count\-ing down the days to September the first, on which he liked to cross off the days remaining until his return to Hogwarts.\par
The atmosphere inside number four, Privet Drive was extremely tense. The imminent arrival at their house of an assortment of wiz\-ards was making the Dursleys uptight and irritable. Uncle Vernon had looked downright alarmed when Harry informed him that the Weasleys would be arriving at five o\rquote clock the very next day.\par
\ldblquote I hope you told them to dress properly, these people,\rdblquote  he snarled at once. \ldblquote I\rquote ve seen the sort of stuff your lot wear. They\rquote d better have the decency to put on normal clothes, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
Harry felt a slight sense of foreboding. He had rarely seen Mr. or Mrs. Weasley wearing anything that the Dursleys would call \ldblquote nor\-mal.\rdblquote  Their children might don Muggle clothing during the holi\-days, but Mr. and Mrs. Weasley usually wore long robes in varying states of shabbiness. Harry wasn\rquote t bothered about what the neigh\-bors would think, but he was anxious about how rude the Dursleys might be to the Weasleys if they turned up looking like their worst idea of wizards.\par
Uncle Vernon had put on his best suit. To some people, this might have looked like a gesture of welcome, but Harry knew it was because Uncle Vernon wanted to look impressive and intimi\-dating. Dudley, on the other hand, looked somehow diminished. This was not because the diet was at last taking effect, but due to fright. Dudley had emerged from his last encounter with a fully-grown wizard with a curly pig\rquote s tail poking out of the seat of his trousers, and Aunt Petunia and Uncle Vernon had had to pay for its removal at a private hospital in London. It wasn\rquote t altogether sur\-prising, therefore, that Dudley kept running his hand nervously over his backside, and walking sideways from room to room, so as not to present the same target to the enemy.\par
Lunch was an almost silent meal. Dudley didn\rquote t even protest at the food (cottage cheese and grated celery). Aunt Petunia wasn\rquote t eating anything at all. Her arms were folded, her lips were pursed, and she seemed to be chewing her tongue, as though biting back the furious diatribe she longed to throw at Harry.\par
\ldblquote They\rquote ll be driving, of course?\rdblquote  Uncle Vernon barked across the table.\par
\ldblquote Er,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
He hadn\rquote t thought of that. How \i were\i0  the Weasleys going to pick him up? They didn\rquote t have a car anymore; the old Ford Anglia they had once owned was currently running wild in the Forbidden For\-est at Hogwarts. But Mr. Weasley had borrowed a Ministry of Magic car last year; possibly he would do the same today?\par
\ldblquote I think so,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Uncle Vernon snorted into his mustache. Normally, Uncle Ver\-non would have asked what car Mr. Weasley drove; he tended to judge other men by how big and expensive their cars were. But Harry doubted whether Uncle Vernon would have taken to Mr. Weasley even if he drove a Ferrari.\par
Harry spent most of the afternoon in his bedroom; he couldn\rquote t stand watching Aunt Petunia peer out through the net curtains every few seconds, as though there had been a warning about an es\-caped rhinoceros. Finally, at a quarter to five, Harry went back downstairs and into the living room.\par
Aunt Petunia was compulsively straightening cushions. Uncle Vernon was pretending to read the paper, but his tiny eyes were not moving, and Harry was sure he was really listening with all his might for the sound of an approaching car. Dudley was crammed into an armchair, his porky hands beneath him, clamped firmly around his bottom. Harry couldn\rquote t take the tension; he left the room and went and sat on the stairs in the hall, his eyes on his watch and his heart pumping fast from excitement and nerves.\par
But five o\rquote clock came and then went. Uncle Vernon, perspiring slightly in his suit, opened the front door, peered up and down the street, then withdrew his head quickly.\par
\ldblquote They\rquote re late!\rdblquote  he snarled at Harry.\par
\ldblquote I know,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Maybe \emdash  er \emdash  the traffic\rquote s bad, or something.\rdblquote\par
Ten past five \'85 then a quarter past five \'85 Harry was starting to feel anxious himself now. At half past, he heard Uncle Vernon and Aunt Petunia conversing in terse mutters in the living room.\par
\ldblquote No consideration at all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We might\rquote ve had an engagement.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Maybe they think they\rquote ll get invited to dinner if they\rquote re late.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, they most certainly won\rquote t be,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, and Harry heard him stand up and start pacing the living room. \ldblquote They\rquote ll take the boy and go, there\rquote ll be no hanging around. That\rquote s if they\rquote re coming at all. Probably mistaken the day. I daresay \i their kind\i0  don\rquote t set much store by punctuality. Either that or they drive some tin-pot car that\rquote s broken d \emdash  AAAAAAAARRRRRGH!\rdblquote\par
Harry jumped up. From the other side of the living room door came the sounds of the three Dursleys scrambling, panic-stricken, across the room. Next moment Dudley came flying into the hall, looking terrified.\par
\ldblquote What happened?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote\par
But Dudley didn\rquote t seem able to speak. Hands still clamped over his buttocks, he waddled as fast as he could into the kitchen. Harry hurried into the living room.\par
Loud hangings and scrapings were coming from behind the Dursleys\rquote  boarded-up fireplace, which had a fake coal fire plugged in front of it.\par
\ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote  gasped Aunt Petunia, who had backed into the wall and was staring, terrified, toward the fire. \ldblquote What is it, Vernon?\rdblquote\par
But they were left in doubt barely a second longer. Voices could be heard from inside the blocked fireplace.\par
\ldblquote Ouch! Fred, no \emdash  go back, go back, there\rquote s been some kind of mistake \emdash  tell George not to \emdash  OUCH! George, no, there\rquote s no room, go back quickly and tell Ron \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Maybe Harry can hear us, Dad \emdash  maybe he\rquote ll be able to let us out \emdash\rdblquote\par
There was a loud hammering of fists on the boards behind the electric fire.\par
\ldblquote Harry? Harry, can you hear us?\rdblquote\par
The Dursleys rounded on Harry like a pair of angry wolverines.\par
\ldblquote What is this?\rdblquote  growled Uncle Vernon. \ldblquote What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They \emdash  they\rquote ve tried to get here by Floo powder,\rdblquote  said Harry, fighting a mad desire to laugh. \ldblquote They can travel by fire \emdash  only you\rquote ve blocked the fireplace \emdash  hang on \emdash\rdblquote\par
He approached the fireplace and called through the boards.\par
\ldblquote Mr. Weasley? Can you hear me?\rdblquote\par
The hammering stopped. Somebody inside the chimney piece said, \ldblquote Shh!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mr. Weasley, it\rquote s Harry \'85 the fireplace has been blocked up. You won\rquote t be able to get through there.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Damn!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley\rquote s voice. \ldblquote What on earth did they want to block up the fireplace for?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They\rquote ve got an electric fire,\rdblquote  Harry explained.\par
\ldblquote Really?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley\rquote s voice excitedly. \ldblquote Eclectic, you say? With a \i plug\i0 ? Gracious, I must see that. \'85 Let\rquote s think \'85 ouch, Ron!\rdblquote\par
Ron\rquote s voice now joined the others\rquote .\par
\ldblquote What are we doing here? Has something gone wrong?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh no, Ron,\rdblquote  came Fred\rquote s voice, very sarcastically. \ldblquote No, this is exactly where we wanted to end up.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, we\rquote re having the time of our lives here,\rdblquote  said George, whose voice sounded muffled, as though he was squashed against the wall.\par
\ldblquote Boys, boys \'85\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley vaguely. \ldblquote I\rquote m trying to think what to do. \'85 Yes \'85 only way \'85 Stand back, Harry.\rdblquote\par
Harry retreated to the sofa. Uncle Vernon, however, moved forward.\par
\ldblquote Wait a moment!\rdblquote  he bellowed at the fire. \ldblquote What exactly are you going to \emdash\rdblquote\par
BANG.\par
The electric fire shot across the room as the boarded-up fireplace burst outward, expelling Mr. Weasley, Fred, George, and Ron in a cloud of rubble and loose chippings. Aunt Petunia shrieked and fell backward over the coffee table; Uncle Vernon caught her before she hit the floor, and gaped, speechless, at the Weasleys, all of whom had bright red hair, including Fred and George, who were identical to the last freckle.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s better,\rdblquote  panted Mr. Weasley, brushing dust from his long green robes and straightening his glasses. \ldblquote Ah \emdash  you must be Harry\rquote s aunt and uncle!\rdblquote\par
Tall, thin, and balding, he moved toward Uncle Vernon, his hand outstretched, but Uncle Vernon backed away several paces, dragging Aunt Petunia. Words utterly failed Uncle Vernon. His best suit was covered in white dust, which had settled in his hair and mustache and made him look as though he had just aged thirty years.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  yes \emdash  sorry about that,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, lowering his hand and looking over his shoulder at the blasted fireplace. \ldblquote It\rquote s all my fault. It just didn\rquote t occur to me that we wouldn\rquote t be able to get out at the other end. I had your fireplace connected to the Floo Network, you see \emdash  just for an afternoon, you know, so we could get Harry. Muggle fireplaces aren\rquote t supposed to be connected, strictly speaking \emdash  but I\rquote ve got a useful contact at the Floo Regu\-lation Panel and he fixed it for me. I can put it right in a jiffy, though, don\rquote t worry. I\rquote ll light a fire to send the boys back, and then I can repair your fireplace before I Disapparate.\rdblquote\par
Harry was ready to bet that the Dursleys hadn\rquote t understood a single word of this. They were still gaping at Mr. Weasley, thun\-derstruck. Aunt Petunia staggered upright again and hid behind Uncle Vernon.\par
\ldblquote Hello, Harry!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley brightly. \ldblquote Got your trunk ready?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s upstairs,\rdblquote  said Harry, grinning back.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ll get it,\rdblquote  said Fred at once. Winking at Harry, he and George left the room. They knew where Harry\rquote s bedroom was, hav\-ing once rescued him from it in the dead of night. Harry suspected that Fred and George were hoping for a glimpse of Dudley; they had heard a lot about him from Harry.\par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, swinging his arms slightly, while he tried to find words to break the very nasty silence. \ldblquote Very \emdash  erm \emdash  very nice place you\rquote ve got here.\rdblquote\par
As the usually spotless living room was now covered in dust and bits of brick, this remark didn\rquote t go down too well with the Durs\-leys. Uncle Vernon\rquote s face purpled once more, and Aunt Petunia started chewing her tongue again. However, they seemed too scared to actually say anything.\par
Mr. Weasley was looking around. He loved everything to do with Muggles. Harry could see him itching to go and examine the television and the video recorder.\par
\ldblquote They run off eckeltricity, do they?\rdblquote  he said knowledgeably. \ldblquote Ah yes, I can see the plugs. I collect plugs,\rdblquote  he added to Uncle Vernon. \ldblquote And batteries. Got a very large collection of batteries. My wife thinks I\rquote m mad, but there you are.\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon clearly thought Mr. Weasley was mad too. He moved ever so slightly to the right, screening Aunt Petunia from view, as though he thought Mr. Weasley might suddenly run at them and attack.\par
Dudley suddenly reappeared in the room. Harry could hear the clunk of his trunk on the stairs, and knew that the sounds had scared Dudley out of the kitchen. Dudley edged along the wall, gazing at Mr. Weasley with terrified eyes, and attempted to conceal himself behind his mother and father. Unfortunately, Uncle Ver\-non\rquote s bulk, while sufficient to hide bony Aunt Petunia, was nowhere near enough to conceal Dudley.\par
\ldblquote Ah, this is your cousin, is it, Harry?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, taking another brave stab at making conversation.\par
\ldblquote Yep,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote that\rquote s Dudley.\rdblquote\par
He and Ron exchanged glances and then quickly looked away from each other; the temptation to burst out laughing was almost overwhelming. Dudley was still clutching his bottom as though afraid it might fall off. Mr. Weasley, however, seemed genuinely concerned at Dudley\rquote s peculiar behavior. Indeed, from the tone of his voice when he next spoke, Harry was quite sure that Mr. Weasley thought Dudley was quite as mad as the Dursleys thought \i he \i0 was, except that Mr. Weasley felt sympathy rather than fear.\par
\ldblquote Having a good holiday, Dudley?\rdblquote  he said kindly.\par
Dudley whimpered. Harry saw his hands tighten still harder over his massive backside.\par
Fred and George came back into the room carrying Harry\rquote s school trunk. They glanced around as they entered and spotted Dudley. Their faces cracked into identical evil grins.\par
\ldblquote Ah, right,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Better get cracking then.\rdblquote\par
He pushed up the sleeves of his robes and took out his wand. Harry saw the Dursleys draw back against the wall as one.\par
\ldblquote\i Incendio\i0 !\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, pointing his wand at the hole in the wall behind him.\par
Flames rose at once in the fireplace, crackling merrily as though they had been burning for hours. Mr. Weasley took a small draw\-string bag from his pocket, untied it, took a pinch of the powder inside, and threw it onto the flames, which turned emerald green and roared higher than ever.\par
\ldblquote Off you go then, Fred,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Coming,\rdblquote  said Fred. \ldblquote Oh no \emdash  hang on \emdash\rdblquote\par
A bag of sweets had spilled out of Fred\rquote s pocket and the contents were now rolling in every direction \emdash  big, fat toffees in brightly colored wrappers.\par
Fred scrambled around, cramming them back into his pocket, then gave the Dursleys a cheery wave, stepped forward, and walked right into the fire, saying \ldblquote the Burrow!\rdblquote  Aunt Petunia gave a little shuddering gasp. There was a whooshing sound, and Fred vanished.\par
\ldblquote Right then, George,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote you and the trunk.\rdblquote\par
Harry helped George carry the trunk forward into the flames and turn it onto its end so that he could hold it better. Then, with a second whoosh, George had cried \ldblquote the Burrow!\rdblquote  and vanished too.\par
\ldblquote Ron, you next,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote See you,\rdblquote  said Ron brightly to the Dursleys. He grinned broadly at Harry, then stepped into the fire, shouted \ldblquote the Burrow!\rdblquote  and disappeared.\par
Now Harry and Mr. Weasley alone remained.\par
\ldblquote Well \'85 \rquote bye then,\rdblquote  Harry said to the Dursleys.\par
They didn\rquote t say anything at all. Harry moved toward the fire, but just as he reached the edge of the hearth, Mr. Weasley put out a hand and held him back. He was looking at the Dursleys in amazement.\par
\ldblquote Harry said good-bye to you,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Didn\rquote t you hear him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter,\rdblquote  Harry muttered to Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Honestly, I don\rquote t care.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Weasley did not remove his hand from Harry\rquote s shoulder.\par
\ldblquote You aren\rquote t going to see your nephew till next summer,\rdblquote  he said to Uncle Vernon in mild indignation. \ldblquote Surely you\rquote re going to say good-bye?\rdblquote\par
Uncle Vernon\rquote s face worked furiously. The idea of being taught consideration by a man who had just blasted away half his living room wall seemed to be causing him intense suffering. But Mr. Weasley\rquote s wand was still in his hand, and Uncle Vernon\rquote s tiny eyes darted to it once, before he said, very resentfully, \ldblquote Good-bye, then.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote See you,\rdblquote  said Harry, putting one foot forward into the green flames, which felt pleasantly like warm breath. At that moment, however, a horrible gagging sound erupted behind him, and Aunt Petunia started to scream.\par
Harry wheeled around. Dudley was no longer standing behind his parents. He was kneeling beside the coffee table, and he was gagging and sputtering on a foot-long, purple, slimy thing that was protruding from his mouth. One bewildered second later, Harry realized that the foot-long thing was Dudley\rquote s tongue \emdash  and that a brightly colored toffee wrapper lay on the floor before him.\par
Aunt Petunia hurled herself onto the ground beside Dudley, seized the end of his swollen tongue, and attempted to wrench it out of his mouth; unsurprisingly, Dudley yelled and sputtered worse than ever, trying to fight her off. Uncle Vernon was bellow\-ing and waving his arms around, and Mr. Weasley had to shout to make himself heard.\par
\ldblquote Not to worry, I can sort him out!\rdblquote  he yelled, advancing on Dudley with his wand outstretched, but Aunt Petunia screamed worse than ever and threw herself on top of Dudley, shielding him from Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote No, really!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley desperately. \ldblquote It\rquote s a simple process \emdash  it was the toffee \emdash  my son Fred \emdash  real practical joker \emdash  but it\rquote s only an Engorgement Charm \emdash  at least, I think it is \emdash  please, I can correct it \emdash\rdblquote\par
But far from being reassured, the Dursleys became more panic-stricken; Aunt Petunia was sobbing hysterically, tugging Dudley\rquote s tongue as though determined to rip it out; Dudley appeared to be suffocating under the combined pressure of his mother and his tongue; and Uncle Vernon, who had lost control completely, seized a china figure from on top of the sideboard and threw it very hard at Mr. Weasley, who ducked, causing the ornament to shatter in the blasted fireplace.\par
\ldblquote Now really!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley angrily, brandishing his wand. \ldblquote I\rquote m trying to \i help\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Bellowing like a wounded hippo, Uncle Vernon snatched up an\-other ornament.\par
\ldblquote Harry, go! Just go!\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley shouted, his wand on Uncle Vernon. \ldblquote I\rquote ll sort this out!\rdblquote\par
Harry didn\rquote t want to miss the fun, but Uncle Vernon\rquote s second or\-nament narrowly missed his left ear, and on balance he thought it best to leave the situation to Mr. Weasley. He stepped into the fire, looking over his shoulder as he said \ldblquote the Burrow!\rdblquote  His last fleeting glimpse of the living room was of Mr. Weasley blasting a third or\-nament out of Uncle Vernon\rquote s hand with his wand, Aunt Petunia screaming and lying on top of Dudley, and Dudley\rquote s tongue lolling around like a great slimy python. But next moment Harry had be\-gun to spin very fast, and the Dursleys\rquote  living room was whipped out of sight in a rush of emerald-green flames.\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sa120\qc\fs36\page Chapter 5\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc Weasleys\rquote  Wizard Wheezes\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs20\par
Harry spun faster and faster, elbows tucked tightly to his sides, blurred fireplaces flashing past him, until he started to feel sick and closed his eyes. Then, when at last he felt himself slowing down, he threw out his hands and came to a halt in time to prevent himself from falling face forward out of the Weasleys\rquote  kitchen fire.\par
\ldblquote Did he eat it?\rdblquote  said Fred excitedly, holding out a hand to pull Harry to his feet.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, straightening up. \ldblquote What \i was\i0  it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ton-Tongue Toffee,\rdblquote  said Fred brightly. \ldblquote George and I in\-vented them, and we\rquote ve been looking for someone to test them on all summer. \'85\rdblquote\par
The tiny kitchen exploded with laughter; Harry looked around and saw that Ron and George were sitting at the scrubbed wooden table with two red-haired people Harry had never seen before, though he knew immediately who they must be: Bill and Charlie, the two eldest Weasley brothers.\par
\ldblquote How\rquote re you doing, Harry?\rdblquote  said the nearer of the two, grinning at him and holding out a large hand, which Harry shook, feeling calluses and blisters under his fingers. This had to be Charlie, who worked with dragons in Romania. Charlie was built like the twins, shorter and stockier than Percy and Ron, who were both long and lanky. He had a broad, good-natured face, which was weather-beaten and so freckly that he looked almost tanned; his arms were muscular, and one of them had a large, shiny burn on it.\par
Bill got to his feet, smiling, and also shook Harry\rquote s hand. Bill came as something of a surprise. Harry knew that he worked for the wizarding bank, Gringotts, and that Bill had been Head Boy at Hogwarts; Harry had always imagined Bill to be an older version of Percy: fussy about rule-breaking and fond of bossing everyone around. However, Bill was \emdash  there was no other word for it \emdash  \i cool.\i0  He was tall, with long hair that he had tied back in a ponytail. He was wearing an earring with what looked like a fang dangling from it. Bill\rquote s clothes would not have looked out of place at a rock concert, except that Harry recognized his boots to be made, not of leather, but of dragon hide.\par
Before any of them could say anything else, there was a faint popping noise, and Mr. Weasley appeared out of thin air at George\rquote s shoulder. He was looking angrier than Harry had ever seen him.\par
\ldblquote That \i wasn\rquote t funny,\i0  Fred!\rdblquote  he shouted. \ldblquote What on earth did you give that Muggle boy?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I didn\rquote t give him anything,\rdblquote  said Fred, with another evil grin. \ldblquote I just \i dropped \i0 it. \'85 It was his fault he went and ate it, I never told him to.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You dropped it on purpose!\rdblquote  roared Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote You knew he\rquote d eat it, you knew he was on a diet \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How big did his tongue get?\rdblquote  George asked eagerly.\par
\ldblquote It was four feet long before his parents would let me shrink it!\rdblquote\par
Harry and the Weasleys roared with laughter again.\par
\ldblquote It \i isn\rquote t funny\i0 !\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley shouted. \ldblquote That sort of behavior se\-riously undermines wizard\endash Muggle relations! I spend half my life campaigning against the mistreatment of Muggles, and my own sons \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We didn\rquote t give it to him because he\rquote s a Muggle!\rdblquote  said Fred indignantly.\par
\ldblquote No, we gave it to him because he\rquote s a great bullying git,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t he, Harry?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, he is, Mr. Weasley,\rdblquote  said Harry earnestly.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s not the point!\rdblquote  raged Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote You wait until I tell your mother \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Tell me what?\rdblquote  said a voice behind them.\par
Mrs. Weasley had just entered the kitchen. She was a short, plump woman with a very kind face, though her eyes were presently narrowed with suspicion.\par
\ldblquote Oh hello, Harry, dear,\rdblquote  she said, spotting him and smiling. Then her eyes snapped back to her husband. \ldblquote Tell me \i what,\i0  Arthur?\rdblquote\par
Mr. Weasley hesitated. Harry could tell that, however angry he was with Fred and George, he hadn\rquote t really intended to tell Mrs. Weasley what had happened. There was a silence, while Mr. Weasley eyed his wife nervously. Then two girls appeared in the kitchen doorway behind Mrs. Weasley. One, with very bushy brown hair and rather large front teeth, was Harry\rquote s and Ron\rquote s friend, Hermione Granger. The other, who was small and red-haired, was Ron\rquote s younger sister, Ginny. Both of them smiled at Harry, who grinned back, which made Ginny go scarlet \emdash  she had been very taken with Harry ever since his first visit to the Burrow.\par
\ldblquote Tell me \i what,\i0  Arthur?\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley repeated, in a dangerous sort of voice.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s nothing, Molly,\rdblquote  mumbled Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote Fred and George just \emdash  but I\rquote ve had words with them \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What have they done this time?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote If it\rquote s got anything to do with Weasleys\rquote  Wizard Wheezes \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why don\rquote t you show Harry where he\rquote s sleeping, Ron?\rdblquote  said Hermione from the doorway.\par
\ldblquote He knows where he\rquote s sleeping,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote in my room, he slept there last \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We can all go,\rdblquote  said Hermione pointedly.\par
\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Ron, cottoning on. \ldblquote Right.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, we\rquote ll come too,\rdblquote  said George.\par
\ldblquote\i You stay where you are\i0 !\rdblquote  snarled Mrs. Weasley.\par
Harry and Ron edged out of the kitchen, and they, Hermione, and Ginny set off along the narrow hallway and up the rickety staircase that zigzagged through the house to the upper stories.\par
\ldblquote What are Weasleys\rquote  Wizard Wheezes?\rdblquote  Harry asked as they climbed.\par
Ron and Ginny both laughed, although Hermione didn\rquote t.\par
\ldblquote Mum found this stack of order forms when she was cleaning Fred and George\rquote s room,\rdblquote  said Ron quietly. \ldblquote Great long price lists for stuff they\rquote ve invented. Joke stuff, you know. Fake wands and trick sweets, loads of stuff. It was brilliant, I never knew they\rquote d been inventing all that \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ve been hearing explosions out of their room for ages, but we never thought they were actually \i making\i0  things,\rdblquote  said Ginny. \ldblquote We thought they just liked the noise.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Only, most of the stuff \emdash  well, all of it, really \emdash  was a bit dan\-gerous,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote and, you know, they were planning to sell it at Hogwarts to make some money, and Mum went mad at them. Told them they weren\rquote t allowed to make any more of it, and burned all the order forms. \'85 She\rquote s furious at them anyway. They didn\rquote t get as many O.W.L.s as she expected.\rdblquote\par
O.W.L.s were Ordinary Wizarding Levels, the examinations Hogwarts students took at the age of fifteen.\par
\ldblquote And then there was this big row,\rdblquote  Ginny said, \ldblquote because Mum wants them to go into the Ministry of Magic like Dad, and they told her all they want to do is open a joke shop.\rdblquote\par
Just then a door on the second landing opened, and a face poked out wearing horn-rimmed glasses and a very annoyed expression.\par
\ldblquote Hi, Percy,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Oh hello, Harry,\rdblquote  said Percy. \ldblquote I was wondering who was mak\-ing all the noise. I\rquote m trying to work in here, you know \emdash  I\rquote ve got a report to finish for the office \emdash  and it\rquote s rather difficult to con\-centrate when people keep thundering up and down the stairs.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re not \i thundering,\i0\rdblquote  said Ron irritably. \ldblquote We\rquote re walking. Sorry if we\rquote ve disturbed the top-secret workings of the Ministry of Magic.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What are you working on?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote A report for the Department of International Magical Cooper\-ation,\rdblquote  said Percy smugly. \ldblquote We\rquote re trying to standardize cauldron thickness. Some of these foreign imports are just a shade too thin \emdash  leakages have been increasing at a rate of almost three per\-cent a year \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote ll change the world, that report will,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Front page of the \i Daily Prophet,\i0  I expect, cauldron leaks.\rdblquote\par
Percy went slightly pink.\par
\ldblquote You might sneer, Ron,\rdblquote  he said heatedly, \ldblquote but unless some sort of international law is imposed we might well find the market flooded with flimsy, shallow-bottomed products that seriously endanger \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, yeah, all right,\rdblquote  said Ron, and he started off upstairs again. Percy slammed his bedroom door shut. As Harry, Hermi\-one, and Ginny followed Ron up three more flights of stairs, shouts from the kitchen below echoed up to them. It sounded as though Mr. Weasley had told Mrs. Weasley about the toffees.\par
The room at the top of the house where Ron slept looked much as it had the last time that Harry had come to stay: the same posters of Ron\rquote s favorite Quidditch team, the Chudley Cannons, were whirling and waving on the walls and sloping ceiling, and the fish tank on the windowsill, which had previously held frog spawn, now contained one extremely large frog. Ron\rquote s old rat, Scabbers, was here no more, but instead there was the tiny gray owl that had delivered Ron\rquote s letter to Harry in Privet Drive. It was hopping up and down in a small cage and twittering madly.\par
\ldblquote Shut \i up,\i0  Pig,\rdblquote  said Ron, edging his way between two of the four beds that had been squeezed into the room. \ldblquote Fred and George are in here with us, because Bill and Charlie are in their room,\rdblquote  he told Harry. \ldblquote Percy gets to keep his room all to himself because he\rquote s got to \i work.\i0\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  why are you calling that owl Pig?\rdblquote  Harry asked Ron.\par
\ldblquote Because he\rquote s being stupid,\rdblquote  said Ginny. \ldblquote Its proper name is Pigwidgeon.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, and that\rquote s not a stupid name at all,\rdblquote  said Ron sarcastically. \ldblquote Ginny named him,\rdblquote  he explained to Harry. \ldblquote She reckons it\rquote s sweet. And I tried to change it, but it was too late, he won\rquote t answer to anything else. So now he\rquote s Pig. I\rquote ve got to keep him up here be\-cause he annoys Errol and Hermes. He annoys me too, come to that.\rdblquote\par
Pigwidgeon zoomed happily around his cage, hooting shrilly. Harry knew Ron too well to take him seriously. He had moaned continually about his old rat, Scabbers, but had been most upset when Hermione\rquote s cat, Crookshanks, appeared to have eaten him.\par
\ldblquote Where\rquote s Crookshanks?\rdblquote  Harry asked Hermione now.\par
\ldblquote Out in the garden, I expect,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote He likes chasing gnomes. He\rquote s never seen any before.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Percy\rquote s enjoying work, then?\rdblquote  said Harry, sitting down on one of the beds and watching the Chudley Cannons zooming in and out of the posters on the ceiling.\par
\ldblquote Enjoying it?\rdblquote  said Ron darkly. \ldblquote I don\rquote t reckon he\rquote d come home if Dad didn\rquote t make him. He\rquote s obsessed. Just don\rquote t get him onto the subject of his boss. \i According to Mr. Crouch\i0  \'85 \i as I was saying to Mr. Crouch\i0  \'85 \i Mr. Crouch is of the opinion\i0  \'85 \i Mr. Crouch was telling me\i0  \'85 They\rquote ll be announcing their engagement any day now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Have you had a good summer, Harry?\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Did you get our food parcels and everything?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, thanks a lot,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote They saved my life, those cakes.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And have you heard from \emdash  ?\rdblquote  Ron began, but at a look from Hermione he fell silent. Harry knew Ron had been about to ask about Sirius. Ron and Hermione had been so deeply involved in helping Sirius escape from the Ministry of Magic that they were almost as concerned about Harry\rquote s godfather as he was. However, discussing him in front of Ginny was a bad idea. Nobody but themselves and Professor Dumbledore knew about how Sirius had escaped, or believed in his innocence.\par
\ldblquote I think they\rquote ve stopped arguing,\rdblquote  said Hermione, to cover the awkward moment, because Ginny was looking curiously from Ron to Harry. \ldblquote Shall we go down and help your mum with dinner?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, all right,\rdblquote  said Ron. The four of them left Ron\rquote s room and went back downstairs to find Mrs. Weasley alone in the kitchen, looking extremely bad-tempered.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re eating out in the garden,\rdblquote  she said when they came in. \ldblquote There\rquote s just not room for eleven people in here. Could you take the plates outside, girls? Bill and Charlie are setting up the tables. Knives and forks, please, you two,\rdblquote  she said to Ron and Harry, pointing her wand a little more vigorously than she had intended at a pile of potatoes in the sink, which shot out of their skins so fast that they ricocheted off the walls and ceiling.\par
\ldblquote Oh for heaven\rquote s \i sake,\i0\rdblquote  she snapped, now directing her wand at a dustpan, which hopped off the sideboard and started skating across the floor, scooping up the potatoes. \ldblquote Those two!\rdblquote  she burst out savagely, now pulling pots and pans out of a cupboard, and Harry knew she meant Fred and George. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know what\rquote s go\-ing to happen to them, I really don\rquote t. No ambition, unless you count making as much trouble as they possibly can. \'85\rdblquote\par
Mrs. Weasley slammed a large copper saucepan down on the kitchen table and began to wave her wand around inside it. A creamy sauce poured from the wand tip as she stirred.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s not as though they haven\rquote t got brains,\rdblquote  she continued irrita\-bly, taking the saucepan over to the stove and lighting it with a fur\-ther poke of her wand, \ldblquote but they\rquote re wasting them, and unless they pull themselves together soon, they\rquote ll be in real trouble. I\rquote ve had more owls from Hogwarts about them than the rest put together. If they carry on the way they\rquote re going, they\rquote ll end up in front of the Improper Use of Magic Office.\rdblquote\par
Mrs. Weasley jabbed her wand at the cutlery drawer, which shot open. Harry and Ron both jumped out of the way as several knives soared out of it, flew across the kitchen, and began chopping the potatoes, which had just been tipped back into the sink by the dustpan.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know where we went wrong with them,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, putting down her wand and starting to pull out still more saucepans. \ldblquote It\rquote s been the same for years, one thing after another, and they won\rquote t listen to \emdash  OH NOT \i AGAIN\i0 !\rdblquote\par
She had picked up her wand from the table, and it had emitted a loud squeak and turned into a giant rubber mouse.\par
\ldblquote One of their fake wands again!\rdblquote  she shouted. \ldblquote How many times have I told them not to leave them lying around?\rdblquote\par
She grabbed her real wand and turned around to find that the sauce on the stove was smoking.\par
\ldblquote C\rquote mon,\rdblquote  Ron said hurriedly to Harry, seizing a handful of cut\-lery from the open drawer, \ldblquote let\rquote s go and help Bill and Charlie.\rdblquote\par
They left Mrs. Weasley and headed out the back door into the yard.\par
They had only gone a few paces when Hermione\rquote s bandy-legged ginger cat, Crookshanks, came pelting out of the garden, bottle-brush tail held high in the air, chasing what looked like a muddy potato on legs. Harry recognized it instantly as a gnome. Barely ten inches high, its horny little feet pattered very fast as it sprinted across the yard and dived headlong into one of the Wellington boots that lay scattered around the door. Harry could hear the gnome giggling madly as Crookshanks inserted a paw into the boot, trying to reach it. Meanwhile, a very loud crashing noise was coming from the other side of the house. The source of the com\-motion was revealed as they entered the garden, and saw that Bill and Charlie both had their wands out, and were making two bat\-tered old tables fly high above the lawn, smashing into each other, each attempting to knock the other\rquote s out of the air. Fred and George were cheering, Ginny was laughing, and Hermione was hovering near the hedge, apparently torn between amusement and anxiety.\par
Bill\rquote s table caught Charlie\rquote s with a huge bang and knocked one of its legs off. There was a clatter from overhead, and they all looked up to see Percy\rquote s head poking out of a window on the sec\-ond floor.\par
\ldblquote Will you keep it down?!\rdblquote  he bellowed.\par
\ldblquote Sorry, Perce,\rdblquote  said Bill, grinning. \ldblquote How\rquote re the cauldron bot\-toms coming on?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Very badly,\rdblquote  said Percy peevishly, and he slammed the window shut. Chuckling, Bill and Charlie directed the tables safely onto the grass, end to end, and then, with a flick of his wand, Bill reattached the table leg and conjured tablecloths from nowhere.\par
By seven o\rquote clock, the two tables were groaning under dishes and dishes of Mrs. Weasley\rquote s excellent cooking, and the nine Weasleys, Harry, and Hermione were settling themselves down to eat beneath a clear, deep-blue sky. To somebody who had been living on meals of increasingly stale cake all summer, this was paradise, and at first, Harry listened rather than talked as he helped himself to chicken and ham pie, boiled potatoes, and salad.\par
At the far end of the table, Percy was telling his father all about his report on cauldron bottoms.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve told Mr. Crouch that I\rquote ll have it ready by Tuesday,\rdblquote  Percy was saying pompously. \ldblquote That\rquote s a bit sooner than he expected it, but I like to keep on top of things. I think he\rquote ll be grateful I\rquote ve done it in good time, I mean, it\rquote s extremely busy in our department just now, what with all the arrangements for the World Cup. We\rquote re just not getting the support we need from the Department of Magical Games and Sports. Ludo Bagman \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I like Ludo,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley mildly. \ldblquote He was the one who got us such good tickets for the Cup. I did him a bit of a favor: His brother, Otto, got into a spot of trouble \emdash  a lawnmower with un\-natural powers \emdash  I smoothed the whole thing over.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh Bagman\rquote s \i likable\i0  enough, of course,\rdblquote  said Percy dismis\-sively, \ldblquote but how he ever got to be Head of Department \'85 when I compare him to Mr. Crouch! I can\rquote t see Mr. Crouch losing a mem\-ber of our department and not trying to find out what\rquote s happened to them. You realize Bertha Jorkins has been missing for over a month now? Went on holiday to Albania and never came back?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, I was asking Ludo about that,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, frowning. \ldblquote He says Bertha\rquote s gotten lost plenty of times before now \emdash  though I must say, if it was someone in my department, I\rquote d be worried. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh Bertha\rquote s \i hopeless,\i0  all right,\rdblquote  said Percy. \ldblquote I hear she\rquote s been shunted from department to department for years, much more trouble than she\rquote s worth \'85 but all the same, Bagman ought to be trying to find her. Mr. Crouch has been taking a personal interest, she worked in our department at one time, you know, and I think Mr. Crouch was quite fond of her \emdash  but Bagman just keeps laugh\-ing and saying she probably misread the map and ended up in Aus\-tralia instead of Albania. However\rdblquote  \emdash  Percy heaved an impressive sigh and took a deep swig of elderflower wine \emdash  \ldblquote we\rquote ve got quite enough on our plates at the Department of International Magical Cooperation without trying to find members of other departments too. As you know, we\rquote ve got another big event to organize right af\-ter the World Cup.\rdblquote\par
Percy cleared his throat significantly and looked down toward the end of the table where Harry, Ron, and Hermione were sitting. \ldblquote\i You\i0  know the one I\rquote m talking about, Father.\rdblquote  He raised his voice slightly. \ldblquote The top-secret one.\rdblquote\par
Ron rolled his eyes and muttered to Harry and Hermione, \ldblquote He\rquote s been trying to get us to ask what that event is ever since he started work. Probably an exhibition of thick-bottomed cauldrons.\rdblquote\par
In the middle of the table, Mrs. Weasley was arguing with Bill about his earring, which seemed to be a recent acquisition.\par
\ldblquote\'85 with a horrible great fang on it. Really, Bill, what do they say at the bank?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mum, no one at the bank gives a damn how I dress as long as I bring home plenty of treasure,\rdblquote  said Bill patiently.\par
\ldblquote And your hair\rquote s getting silly, dear,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, fingering her wand lovingly. \ldblquote I wish you\rquote d let me give it a trim. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I like it,\rdblquote  said Ginny, who was sitting beside Bill. \ldblquote You\rquote re so old-fashioned, Mum. Anyway, it\rquote s nowhere near as long as Professor Dumbledore\rquote s. \'85\rdblquote\par
Next to Mrs. Weasley, Fred, George, and Charlie were all talking spiritedly about the World Cup.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s got to be Ireland,\rdblquote  said Charlie thickly, through a mouthful of potato. \ldblquote They flattened Peru in the semifinals.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Bulgaria has got Viktor Krum, though,\rdblquote  said Fred.\par
\ldblquote Krum\rquote s one decent player, Ireland has got seven,\rdblquote  said Charlie shortly. \ldblquote I wish England had got through. That was embarrassing, that was.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What happened?\rdblquote  said Harry eagerly, regretting more than ever his isolation from the wizarding world when he was stuck on Privet Drive.\par
\ldblquote Went down to Transylvania, three hundred and ninety to ten,\rdblquote  said Charlie gloomily. \ldblquote Shocking performance. And Wales lost to Uganda, and Scotland was slaughtered by Luxembourg.\rdblquote\par
Harry had been on the Gryffindor House Quidditch team ever since his first year at Hogwarts and owned one of the best racing brooms in the world, a Firebolt. Flying came more naturally to Harry than anything else in the magical world, and he played in the position of Seeker on the Gryffindor House team.\par
Mr. Weasley conjured up candles to light the darkening garden before they had their homemade strawberry ice cream, and by the time they had finished, moths were fluttering low over the table, and the warm air was perfumed with the smells of grass and hon\-eysuckle. Harry was feeling extremely well fed and at peace with the world as he watched several gnomes sprinting through the rose\-bushes, laughing madly and closely pursued by Crookshanks.\par
Ron looked carefully up the table to check that the rest of the family were all busy talking, then he said very quietly to Harry, \ldblquote So \emdash  \i have\i0  you heard from Sirius lately?\rdblquote\par
Hermione looked around, listening closely.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry softly, \ldblquote twice. He sounds okay. I wrote to him yesterday. He might write back while I\rquote m here.\rdblquote\par
He suddenly remembered the reason he had written to Sirius, and for a moment was on the verge of telling Ron and Hermione about his scar hurting again, and about the dream that had awoken him \'85 but he really didn\rquote t want to worry them just now, not when he himself was feeling so happy and peaceful.\par
\ldblquote Look at the time,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley said suddenly, checking her wristwatch. \ldblquote You really should be in bed, the whole lot of you \emdash  you\rquote ll be up at the crack of dawn to get to the Cup. Harry, if you leave your school list out, I\rquote ll get your things for you tomorrow in Diagon Alley. I\rquote m getting everyone else\rquote s. There might not be time after the World Cup, the match went on for five days last time.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Wow \emdash  hope it does this time!\rdblquote  said Harry enthusiastically.\par
\ldblquote Well, I certainly don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Percy sanctimoniously. \ldblquote I \i shudder \i0 to think what the state of my in-tray would be if I was away from work for five days.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, someone might slip dragon dung in it again, eh, Perce?\rdblquote  said Fred.\par
\ldblquote That was a sample of fertilizer from Norway!\rdblquote  said Percy, going very red in the face. \ldblquote It was nothing \i personal\i0 !\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was,\rdblquote  Fred whispered to Harry as they got up from the table. \ldblquote We sent it.\rdblquote\par
