Harry felt as though he had barely lain down to sleep in Ron\rquote s room when he was being shaken awake by Mrs. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Time to go, Harry, dear,\rdblquote  she whispered, moving away to wake Ron.\par
Harry felt around for his glasses, put them on, and sat up. It was still dark outside. Ron muttered indistinctly as his mother roused him. At the foot of Harry\rquote s mattress he saw two large, disheveled shapes emerging from tangles of blankets.\par
\ldblquote  \rquote S\rquote  time already?\rdblquote  said Fred groggily.\par
They dressed in silence, too sleepy to talk, then, yawning and stretching, the four of them headed downstairs into the kitchen.\par
Mrs. Weasley was stirring the contents of a large pot on the stove, while Mr. Weasley was sitting at the table, checking a sheaf of large parchment tickets. He looked up as the boys entered and spread his arms so that they could see his clothes more clearly. He was wearing what appeared to be a golfing sweater and a very old pair of jeans, slightly too big for him and held up with a thick leather belt.\par
\ldblquote What d\rquote you think?\rdblquote  he asked anxiously. \ldblquote We\rquote re supposed to go incognito \emdash  do I look like a Muggle, Harry?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, smiling, \ldblquote very good.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Where\rquote re Bill and Charlie and Per-Per-Percy?\rdblquote  said George, fail\-ing to stifle a huge yawn.\par
\ldblquote Well, they\rquote re Apparating, aren\rquote t they?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, heav\-ing the large pot over to the table and starting to ladle porridge into bowls. \ldblquote So they can have a bit of a lie-in.\rdblquote\par
Harry knew that Apparating meant disappearing from one place and reappearing almost instantly in another, but had never known any Hogwarts student to do it, and understood that it was very difficult.\par
\ldblquote So they\rquote re still in bed?\rdblquote  said Fred grumpily, pulling his bowl of porridge toward him. \ldblquote Why can\rquote t we Apparate too?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Because you\rquote re not of age and you haven\rquote t passed your test,\rdblquote  snapped Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote And where have those girls got to?\rdblquote\par
She bustled out of the kitchen and they heard her climbing the stairs.\par
\ldblquote You have to pass a test to Apparate?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\par
\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, tucking the tickets safely into the back pocket of his jeans. \ldblquote The Department of Magical Transporta\-tion had to fine a couple of people the other day for Apparating without a license. It\rquote s not easy, Apparition, and when it\rquote s not done properly it can lead to nasty complications. This pair I\rquote m talking about went and splinched themselves.\rdblquote\par
Everyone around the table except Harry winced.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  \i splinched\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote They left half of themselves behind,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, now spooning large amounts of treacle onto his porridge. \ldblquote So, of course, they were stuck. Couldn\rquote t move either way. Had to wait for the Accidental Magic Reversal Squad to sort them out. Meant a fair old bit of paperwork, I can tell you, what with the Muggles who spot\-ted the body parts they\rquote d left behind. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry had a sudden vision of a pair of legs and an eyeball lying abandoned on the pavement of Privet Drive.\par
\ldblquote Were they okay?\rdblquote  he asked, startled.\par
\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley matter-of-factly. \ldblquote But they got a heavy fine, and I don\rquote t think they\rquote ll be trying it again in a hurry. You don\rquote t mess around with Apparition. There are plenty of adult wizards who don\rquote t bother with it. Prefer brooms \emdash  slower, but safer.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But Bill and Charlie and Percy can all do it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Charlie had to take the test twice,\rdblquote  said Fred, grinning. \ldblquote He failed the first time, Apparated five miles south of where he meant to, right on top of some poor old dear doing her shopping, remember?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, well, he passed the second time,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, marching back into the kitchen amid hearty sniggers.\par
\ldblquote Percy only passed two weeks ago,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote He\rquote s been Apparating downstairs every morning since, just to prove he can.\rdblquote\par
There were footsteps down the passageway and Hermione and Ginny came into the kitchen, both looking pale and drowsy.\par
\ldblquote Why do we have to be up so early?\rdblquote  Ginny said, rubbing her eyes and sitting down at the table.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ve got a bit of a walk,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Walk?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote What, are we walking to the World Cup?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, no, that\rquote s miles away,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, smiling. \ldblquote We only need to walk a short way. It\rquote s just that it\rquote s very difficult for a large number of wizards to congregate without attracting Muggle atten\-tion. We have to be very careful about how we travel at the best of times, and on a huge occasion like the Quidditch World Cup \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote George!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley sharply, and they all jumped.\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said George, in an innocent tone that deceived nobody.\par
\ldblquote What is that in your pocket?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nothing!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t you lie to me!\rdblquote\par
Mrs. Weasley pointed her wand at George\rquote s pocket and said, \ldblquote\i Accio\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Several small, brightly colored objects zoomed out of George\rquote s pocket; he made a grab for them but missed, and they sped right into Mrs. Weasley\rquote s outstretched hand.\par
\ldblquote We told you to destroy them!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley furiously, holding up what were unmistakably more Ton-Tongue Toffees. \ldblquote We told you to get rid of the lot! Empty your pockets, go on, both of you!\rdblquote\par
It was an unpleasant scene; the twins had evidently been trying to smuggle as many toffees out of the house as possible, and it was only by using her Summoning Charm that Mrs. Weasley managed to find them all.\par
\ldblquote\i Accio\i0 ! \i Accio\i0 ! \i Accio\i0 !\rdblquote  she shouted, and toffees zoomed from all sorts of unlikely places, including the lining of George\rquote s jacket and the turn-ups of Fred\rquote s jeans.\par
\ldblquote We spent six months developing those!\rdblquote  Fred shouted at his mother as she threw the toffees away.\par
\ldblquote Oh a fine way to spend six months!\rdblquote  she shrieked. \ldblquote No wonder you didn\rquote t get more O.W.L.s!\rdblquote\par
All in all, the atmosphere was not very friendly as they took their departure. Mrs. Weasley was still glowering as she kissed Mr. Weasley on the cheek, though not nearly as much as the twins, who had each hoisted their rucksacks onto their backs and walked out without a word to her.\par
\ldblquote Well, have a lovely time,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, \ldblquote and \i behave your\-selves,\i0\rdblquote  she called after the twins\rquote  retreating backs, but they did not look back or answer. \ldblquote I\rquote ll send Bill, Charlie, and Percy along around midday,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley said to Mr. Weasley, as he, Harry, Ron, Hermione, and Ginny set off across the dark yard after Fred and George.\par
It was chilly and the moon was still out. Only a dull, greenish tinge along the horizon to their right showed that daybreak was drawing closer. Harry, having been thinking about thousands of wizards speeding toward the Quidditch World Cup, sped up to walk with Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote So how \i does\i0  everyone get there without all the Muggles notic\-ing?\rdblquote  he asked.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s been a massive organizational problem,\rdblquote  sighed Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote The trouble is, about a hundred thousand wizards turn up at the World Cup, and of course, we just haven\rquote t got a magical site big enough to accommodate them all. There are places Mug\-gles can\rquote t penetrate, but imagine trying to pack a hundred thousand wizards into Diagon Alley or platform nine and three-quarters. So we had to find a nice deserted moor, and set up as many anti-Muggle precautions as possible. The whole Ministry\rquote s been work\-ing on it for months. First, of course, we have to stagger the arrivals. People with cheaper tickets have to arrive two weeks beforehand. A limited number use Muggle transport, but we can\rquote t have too many clogging up their buses and trains \emdash  remember, wizards are coming from all over the world. Some Apparate, of course, but we have to set up safe points for them to appear, well away from Muggles. I believe there\rquote s a handy wood they\rquote re using as the Apparition point. For those who don\rquote t want to Apparate, or can\rquote t, we use Portkeys. They\rquote re objects that are used to transport wizards from one spot to another at a prearranged time. You can do large groups at a time if you need to. There have been two hundred Portkeys placed at strategic points around Britain, and the nearest one to us is up at the top of Stoatshead Hill, so that\rquote s where we\rquote re headed.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Weasley pointed ahead of them, where a large black mass rose beyond the village of Ottery St. Catchpole.\par
\ldblquote What sort of objects are Portkeys?\rdblquote  said Harry curiously.\par
\ldblquote Well, they can be anything,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Unobtrusive things, obviously, so Muggles don\rquote t go picking them up and play\-ing with them \'85 stuff they\rquote ll just think is litter. \'85\rdblquote\par
They trudged down the dark, dank lane toward the village, the silence broken only by their footsteps. The sky lightened very slowly as they made their way through the village, its inky black\-ness diluting to deepest blue. Harry\rquote s hands and feet were freezing. Mr. Weasley kept checking his watch.\par
They didn\rquote t have breath to spare for talking as they began to climb Stoatshead Hill, stumbling occasionally in hidden rabbit holes, slipping on thick black tuffets of grass. Each breath Harry took was sharp in his chest and his legs were starting to seize up when, at last, his feet found level ground.\par
\ldblquote Whew,\rdblquote  panted Mr. Weasley, taking off his glasses and wiping them on his sweater. \ldblquote Well, we\rquote ve made good time \emdash  we\rquote ve got ten minutes. \'85\rdblquote\par
Hermione came over the crest of the hill last, clutching a stitch in her side.\par
\ldblquote Now we just need the Portkey,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, replacing his glasses and squinting around at the ground. \ldblquote It won\rquote t be big. \'85 Come on \'85\rdblquote\par
They spread out, searching. They had only been at it for a cou\-ple of minutes, however, when a shout rent the still air.\par
\ldblquote Over here, Arthur! Over here, son, we\rquote ve got it!\rdblquote\par
Two tall figures were silhouetted against the starry sky on the other side of the hilltop.\par
\ldblquote Amos!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, smiling as he strode over to the man who had shouted. The rest of them followed.\par
Mr. Weasley was shaking hands with a ruddy-faced wizard with a scrubby brown beard, who was holding a moldy-looking old boot in his other hand.\par
\ldblquote This is Amos Diggory, everyone,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote He works for the Department for the Regulation and Control of Magical Creatures. And I think you know his son, Cedric?\rdblquote\par
Cedric Diggory was an extremely handsome boy of around sev\-enteen. He was Captain and Seeker of the Hufflepuff House Quid\-ditch team at Hogwarts.\par
\ldblquote Hi,\rdblquote  said Cedric, looking around at them all.\par
Everybody said hi back except Fred and George, who merely nodded. They had never quite forgiven Cedric for beating their team, Gryffindor, in the first Quidditch match of the previous year.\par
\ldblquote Long walk, Arthur?\rdblquote  Cedric\rquote s father asked.\par
\ldblquote Not too bad,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote We live just on the other side of the village there. You?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Had to get up at two, didn\rquote t we, Ced? I tell you, I\rquote ll be glad when he\rquote s got his Apparition test. Still \'85 not complaining \'85 Quidditch World Cup, wouldn\rquote t miss it for a sackful of Gal\-leons \emdash  and the tickets cost about that. Mind you, looks like I got off easy. \'85\rdblquote  Amos Diggory peered good-naturedly around at the three Weasley boys, Harry, Hermione, and Ginny. \ldblquote All these yours, Arthur?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh no, only the redheads,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, pointing out his children. \ldblquote This is Hermione, friend of Ron\rquote s \emdash  and Harry, an\-other friend \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Merlin\rquote s beard,\rdblquote  said Amos Diggory, his eyes widening. \ldblquote Harry? Harry \i Potter\i0 ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Harry was used to people looking curiously at him when they met him, used to the way their eyes moved at once to the lightning scar on his forehead, but it always made him feel uncomfortable.\par
\ldblquote Ced\rquote s talked about you, of course,\rdblquote  said Amos Diggory. \ldblquote Told us all about playing against you last year. \'85 I said to him, I said \emdash  Ced, that\rquote ll be something to tell your grandchildren, that will. \'85 \i You beat Harry Potter\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Harry couldn\rquote t think of any reply to this, so he remained silent. Fred and George were both scowling again. Cedric looked slightly embarrassed.\par
\ldblquote Harry fell off his broom, Dad,\rdblquote  he muttered. \ldblquote I told you \'85 it was an accident. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, but \i you\i0  didn\rquote t fall off, did you?\rdblquote  roared Amos genially, slap\-ping his son on his back. \ldblquote Always modest, our Ced, always the gen\-tleman \'85 but the best man won, I\rquote m sure Harry\rquote d say the same, wouldn\rquote t you, eh? One falls off his broom, one stays on, you don\rquote t need to be a genius to tell which one\rquote s the better flier!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Must be nearly time,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quickly, pulling out his watch again. \ldblquote Do you know whether we\rquote re waiting for any more, Amos?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, the Lovegoods have been there for a week already and the Fawcetts couldn\rquote t get tickets,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory. \ldblquote There aren\rquote t any more of us in this area, are there?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not that I know of,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Yes, it\rquote s a minute off. \'85 We\rquote d better get ready. \'85\rdblquote\par
He looked around at Harry and Hermione.\par
\ldblquote You just need to touch the Portkey, that\rquote s all, a finger will do \emdash\rdblquote\par
With difficulty, owing to their bulky backpacks, the nine of them crowded around the old boot held out by Amos Diggory.\par
They all stood there, in a tight circle, as a chill breeze swept over the hilltop. Nobody spoke. It suddenly occurred to Harry how odd this would look if a Muggle were to walk up here now \'85 nine people, two of them grown men, clutching this manky old boot in the semidarkness, waiting. \'85\par
\ldblquote Three \'85\rdblquote  muttered Mr. Weasley, one eye still on his watch, \ldblquote two \'85 one \'85\rdblquote\par
It happened immediately: Harry felt as though a hook just be\-hind his navel had been suddenly jerked irresistibly forward. His feet left the ground; he could feel Ron and Hermione on either side of him, their shoulders banging into his; they were all speeding for\-ward in a howl of wind and swirling color; his forefinger was stuck to the boot as though it was pulling him magnetically onward and then \emdash\par
His feet slammed into the ground; Ron staggered into him and he fell over; the Portkey hit the ground near his head with a heavy thud.\par
Harry looked up. Mr. Weasley, Mr. Diggory, and Cedric were still standing, though looking very windswept; everybody else was on the ground.\par
\ldblquote Seven past five from Stoatshead Hill,\rdblquote  said a voice.\par
\par
