Harry disentangled himself from Ron and got to his feet. They had arrived on what appeared to be a deserted stretch of misty moor. In front of them was a pair of tired and grumpy-looking wizards, one of whom was holding a large gold watch, the other a thick roll of parchment and a quill. Both were dressed as Muggles, though very inexpertly: The man with the watch wore a tweed suit with thigh-length galoshes; his colleague, a kilt and a poncho.\par
\ldblquote Morning, Basil,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, picking up the boot and handing it to the kilted wizard, who threw it into a large box of used Portkeys beside him; Harry could see an old newspaper, an empty drinks can, and a punctured football.\par
\ldblquote Hello there, Arthur,\rdblquote  said Basil wearily. \ldblquote Not on duty, eh? It\rquote s all right for some. \'85 We\rquote ve been here all night. \'85 You\rquote d better get out of the way, we\rquote ve got a big party coming in from the Black For\-est at five-fifteen. Hang on, I\rquote ll find your campsite. \'85 Weasley \'85 Weasley \'85\rdblquote  He consulted his parchment list. \ldblquote About a quarter of a mile\rquote s walk over there, first field you come to. Site manager\rquote s called Mr. Roberts. Diggory \'85 second field \'85 ask for Mr. Payne.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thanks, Basil,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, and he beckoned everyone to follow him.\par
They set off across the deserted moor, unable to make out much through the mist. After about twenty minutes, a small stone cot\-tage next to a gate swam into view. Beyond it, Harry could just make out the ghostly shapes of hundreds and hundreds of tents, rising up the gentle slope of a large field toward a dark wood on the horizon. They said good-bye to the Diggorys and approached the cottage door.\par
A man was standing in the doorway, looking out at the tents. Harry knew at a glance that this was the only real Muggle for sev\-eral acres. When he heard their footsteps, he turned his head to look at them.\par
\ldblquote Morning!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley brightly.\par
\ldblquote Morning,\rdblquote  said the Muggle.\par
\ldblquote Would you be Mr. Roberts?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Aye, I would,\rdblquote  said Mr. Roberts. \ldblquote And who\rquote re you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Weasley \emdash  two tents, booked a couple of days ago?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Aye,\rdblquote  said Mr. Roberts, consulting a list tacked to the door. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got a space up by the wood there. Just the one night?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s it,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ll be paying now, then?\rdblquote  said Mr. Roberts.\par
\ldblquote Ah \emdash  right \emdash  certainly \emdash\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. He retreated a short distance from the cottage and beckoned Harry toward him. \ldblquote Help me, Harry,\rdblquote  he muttered, pulling a roll of Muggle money from his pocket and starting to peel the notes apart. \ldblquote This one\rquote s a \emdash  a \emdash  a ten? Ah yes, I see the little number on it now. \'85 So this is a five?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A twenty,\rdblquote  Harry corrected him in an undertone, uncomfort\-ably aware of Mr. Roberts trying to catch every word.\par
\ldblquote Ah yes, so it is. \'85 I don\rquote t know, these little bits of paper \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You foreign?\rdblquote  said Mr. Roberts as Mr. Weasley returned with the correct notes.\par
\ldblquote Foreign?\rdblquote  repeated Mr. Weasley, puzzled.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re not the first one who\rquote s had trouble with money,\rdblquote  said Mr. Roberts, scrutinizing Mr. Weasley closely. \ldblquote I had two try and pay me with great gold coins the size of hubcaps ten minutes ago.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Did you really?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley nervously.\par
Mr. Roberts rummaged around in a tin for some change.\par
\ldblquote Never been this crowded,\rdblquote  he said suddenly, looking out over the misty field again. \ldblquote Hundreds of pre-bookings. People usually just turn up. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Is that right?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, his hand held out for his change, but Mr. Roberts didn\rquote t give it to him.\par
\ldblquote Aye,\rdblquote  he said thoughtfully. \ldblquote People from all over. Loads of for\-eigners. And not just foreigners. Weirdos, you know? There\rquote s a bloke walking \rquote round in a kilt and a poncho.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Shouldn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley anxiously.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s like some sort of \'85 I dunno \'85 like some sort of rally,\rdblquote  said Mr. Roberts. \ldblquote They all seem to know each other. Like a big party.\rdblquote\par
At that moment, a wizard in plus-fours appeared out of thin air next to Mr. Roberts\rquote s front door.\par
\ldblquote\i Obliviate\i0 !\rdblquote  he said sharply, pointing his wand at Mr. Roberts.\par
Instantly, Mr. Roberts\rquote s eyes slid out of focus, his brows unknitted, and a look of dreamy unconcern fell over his face. Harry recognized the symptoms of one who had just had his mem\-ory modified.\par
\ldblquote A map of the campsite for you,\rdblquote  Mr. Roberts said placidly to Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote And your change.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thanks very much,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\par
The wizard in plus-fours accompanied them toward the gate to the campsite. He looked exhausted: His chin was blue with stubble and there were deep purple shadows under his eyes. Once out of earshot of Mr. Roberts, he muttered to Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote Been having a lot of trouble with him. Needs a Memory Charm ten times a day to keep him happy. And Ludo Bagman\rquote s not helping. Trotting around talking about Bludgers and Quaffles at the top of his voice, not a worry about anti-Muggle security. Blimey, I\rquote ll be glad when this is over. See you later, Arthur.\rdblquote\par
He Disapparated.\par
\ldblquote I thought Mr. Bagman was Head of Magical Games and Sports,\rdblquote  said Ginny, looking surprised. \ldblquote He should know better than to talk about Bludgers near Muggles, shouldn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He should,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, smiling, and leading them through the gates into the campsite, \ldblquote but Ludo\rquote s always been a bit \'85 well \'85 \i lax\i0  about security. You couldn\rquote t wish for a more enthusiastic head of the sports department though. He played Quidditch for England himself, you know. And he was the best Beater the Wimbourne Wasps ever had.\rdblquote\par
They trudged up the misty field between long rows of tents. Most looked almost ordinary; their owners had clearly tried to make them as Muggle-like as possible, but had slipped up by adding chimneys, or bellpulls, or weather vanes. However, here and there was a tent so obviously magical that Harry could hardly be surprised that Mr. Roberts was getting suspicious. Halfway up the field stood an extravagant confection of striped silk like a miniature palace, with several live peacocks tethered at the entrance. A little farther on they passed a tent that had three floors and several tur\-rets; and a short way beyond that was a tent that had a front garden attached, complete with birdbath, sundial, and fountain.\par
\ldblquote Always the same,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, smiling. \ldblquote We can\rquote t resist showing off when we get together. Ah, here we are, look, this is us.\rdblquote\par
They had reached the very edge of the wood at the top of the field, and here was an empty space, with a small sign hammered into the ground that read WEEZLY.\par
\ldblquote Couldn\rquote t have a better spot!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley happily. \ldblquote The field is just on the other side of the wood there, we\rquote re as close as we could be.\rdblquote  He hoisted his backpack from his shoulders. \ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  he said excitedly, \ldblquote no magic allowed, strictly speaking, not when we\rquote re out in these numbers on Muggle land. We\rquote ll be putting these tents up by hand! Shouldn\rquote t be too difficult. \'85 Muggles do it all the time. \'85 Here, Harry, where do you reckon we should start?\rdblquote\par
Harry had never been camping in his life; the Dursleys had never taken him on any kind of holiday, preferring to leave him with Mrs. Figg, an old neighbor. However, he and Hermione worked out where most of the poles and pegs should go, and though Mr. Weasley was more of a hindrance than a help, because he got thoroughly overexcited when it came to using the mallet, they finally managed to erect a pair of shabby two-man tents.\par
All of them stood back to admire their handiwork. Nobody looking at these tents would guess they belonged to wizards, Harry thought, but the trouble was that once Bill, Charlie, and Percy arrived, they would be a party of ten. Hermione seemed to have spotted this problem too; she gave Harry a quizzical look as Mr. Weasley dropped to his hands and knees and entered the first tent.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ll be a bit cramped,\rdblquote  he called, \ldblquote but I think we\rquote ll all squeeze in. Come and have a look.\rdblquote\par
Harry bent down, ducked under the tent flap, and felt his jaw drop. He had walked into what looked like an old-fashioned, three-room flat, complete with bathroom and kitchen. Oddly enough, it was furnished in exactly the same sort of style as Mrs. Figg\rquote s house: There were crocheted covers on the mismatched chairs and a strong smell of cats.\par
\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s not for long,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, mopping his bald patch with a handkerchief and peering in at the four bunk beds that stood in the bedroom. \ldblquote I borrowed this from Perkins at the of\-fice. Doesn\rquote t camp much anymore, poor fellow, he\rquote s got lumbago.\rdblquote\par
He picked up the dusty kettle and peered inside it. \ldblquote We\rquote ll need water. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s a tap marked on this map the Muggle gave us,\rdblquote  said Ron, who had followed Harry inside the tent and seemed com\-pletely unimpressed by its extraordinary inner proportions. \ldblquote It\rquote s on the other side of the field.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, why don\rquote t you, Harry, and Hermione go and get us some water then\rdblquote  \emdash  Mr. Weasley handed over the kettle and a couple of saucepans \emdash  \ldblquote and the rest of us will get some wood for a fire?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But we\rquote ve got an oven,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Why can\rquote t we just \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ron, anti-Muggle security!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, his face shining with anticipation. \ldblquote When real Muggles camp, they cook on fires outdoors. I\rquote ve seen them at it!\rdblquote\par
After a quick tour of the girls\rquote  tent, which was slightly smaller than the boys\rquote , though without the smell of cats, Harry, Ron, and Hermione set off across the campsite with the kettle and saucepans.\par
Now, with the sun newly risen and the mist lifting, they could see the city of tents that stretched in every direction. They made their way slowly through the rows, staring eagerly around. It was only just dawning on Harry how many witches and wizards there must be in the world; he had never really thought much about those in other countries.\par
Their fellow campers were starting to wake up. First to stir were the families with small children; Harry had never seen witches and wizards this young before. A tiny boy no older than two was crouched outside a large pyramid-shaped tent, holding a wand and poking happily at a slug in the grass, which was swelling slowly to the size of a salami. As they drew level with him, his mother came hurrying out of the tent.\par
\ldblquote\i How\i0  many times, Kevin? You \i don\rquote t\i0  \emdash  \i touch\i0  \emdash  \i Daddy\rquote s\i0  \emdash  \i wand\i0  \emdash  yecchh!\rdblquote\par
She had trodden on the giant slug, which burst. Her scolding carried after them on the still air, mingling with the little boy\rquote s yells \emdash  \ldblquote You bust slug! You bust slug!\rdblquote\par
A short way farther on, they saw two little witches, barely older than Kevin, who were riding toy broomsticks that rose only high enough for the girls\rquote  toes to skim the dewy grass. A Ministry wiz\-ard had already spotted them; as he hurried past Harry, Ron, and Hermione he muttered distractedly, \ldblquote In broad daylight! Parents having a lie-in, I suppose \emdash\rdblquote\par
Here and there adult wizards and witches were emerging from their tents and starting to cook breakfast. Some, with furtive looks around them, conjured fires with their wands; others were striking matches with dubious looks on their faces, as though sure this couldn\rquote t work. Three African wizards sat in serious conversation, all of them wearing long white robes and roasting what looked like a rabbit on a bright purple fire, while a group of middle-aged American witches sat gossiping happily beneath a spangled banner stretched between their tents that read: THE SALEM WITCHES\rquote  INSTITUTE. Harry caught snatches of conversation in strange lan\-guages from the inside of tents they passed, and though he couldn\rquote t understand a word, the tone of every single voice was excited.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  is it my eyes, or has everything gone green?\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
It wasn\rquote t just Ron\rquote s eyes. They had walked into a patch of tents that were all covered with a thick growth of shamrocks, so that it looked as though small, oddly shaped hillocks had sprouted out of the earth. Grinning faces could be seen under those that had their flaps open. Then, from behind them, they heard their names.\par
\ldblquote Harry! Ron! Hermione!\rdblquote\par
It was Seamus Finnigan, their fellow Gryffindor fourth year. He was sitting in front of his own shamrock-covered tent, with a sandy-haired woman who had to be his mother, and his best friend, Dean Thomas, also of Gryffindor.\par
\ldblquote Like the decorations?\rdblquote  said Seamus, grinning. \ldblquote The Ministry\rquote s not too happy.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ah, why shouldn\rquote t we show our colors?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Finnigan. \ldblquote You should see what the Bulgarians have got dangling all over \i their\i0  tents. You\rquote ll be supporting Ireland, of course?\rdblquote  she added, eye\-ing Harry, Ron, and Hermione beadily. When they had assured her that they were indeed supporting Ireland, they set off again, though, as Ron said, \ldblquote Like we\rquote d say anything else surrounded by that lot.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I wonder what the Bulgarians have got dangling all over their tents?\rdblquote  said Hermione.\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s go and have a look,\rdblquote  said Harry, pointing to a large patch of tents upheld, where the Bulgarian flag \emdash  white, green, and red \emdash  was fluttering in the breeze.\par
The tents here had not been bedecked with plant life, but each and every one of them had the same poster attached to it, a poster of a very surly face with heavy black eyebrows. The picture was, of course, moving, but all it did was blink and scowl.\par
\ldblquote Krum,\rdblquote  said Ron quietly.\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Hermione.\par
\ldblquote Krum!\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Viktor Krum, the Bulgarian Seeker!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He looks really grumpy,\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking around at the many Krums blinking and scowling at them.\par
\ldblquote  \lquote\i Really grumpy\i0\rquote ?\rdblquote  Ron raised his eyes to the heavens. \ldblquote Who cares what he looks like? He\rquote s unbelievable. He\rquote s really young too. Only just eighteen or something. He\rquote s a \i genius,\i0  you wait until tonight, you\rquote ll see.\rdblquote\par
There was already a small queue for the tap in the corner of the field. Harry, Ron, and Hermione joined it, right behind a pair of men who were having a heated argument. One of them was a very old wizard who was wearing a long flowery nightgown. The other was clearly a Ministry wizard; he was holding out a pair of pin\-striped trousers and almost crying with exasperation.\par
\ldblquote Just put them on, Archie, there\rquote s a good chap. You can\rquote t walk around like that, the Muggle at the gate\rquote s already getting suspi\-cious \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I bought this in a Muggle shop,\rdblquote  said the old wizard stubbornly. \ldblquote Muggles wear them.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Muggle \i women\i0  wear them, Archie, not the men, they wear \i these,\i0\rdblquote  said the Ministry wizard, and he brandished the pinstriped trousers.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not putting them on,\rdblquote  said old Archie in indignation. \ldblquote I like a healthy breeze \rquote round my privates, thanks.\rdblquote\par
Hermione was overcome with such a strong fit of the giggles at this point that she had to duck out of the queue and only returned when Archie had collected his water and moved away.\par
Walking more slowly now, because of the weight of the water, they made their way back through the campsite. Here and there, they saw more familiar faces: other Hogwarts students with their families. Oliver Wood, the old captain of Harry\rquote s House Quidditch team, who had just left Hogwarts, dragged Harry over to his par\-ents\rquote  tent to introduce him, and told him excitedly that he had just been signed to the Puddlemere United reserve team. Next they were hailed by Ernie Macmillan, a Hufflepuff fourth year, and a lit\-tle farther on they saw Cho Chang, a very pretty girl who played Seeker on the Ravenclaw team. She waved and smiled at Harry, who slopped quite a lot of water down his front as he waved back. More to stop Ron from smirking than anything, Harry hurriedly pointed out a large group of teenagers whom he had never seen before.\par
\ldblquote Who d\rquote you reckon they are?\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote They don\rquote t go to Hog\-warts, do they?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote  \rquote Spect they go to some foreign school,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote I know there are others. Never met anyone who went to one, though. Bill had a penfriend at a school in Brazil \'85 this was years and years ago \'85 and he wanted to go on an exchange trip but Mum and Dad couldn\rquote t afford it. His penfriend got all offended when he said he wasn\rquote t going and sent him a cursed hat. It made his ears shrivel up.\rdblquote\par
Harry laughed but didn\rquote t voice the amazement he felt at hearing about other wizarding schools. He supposed, now that he saw rep\-resentatives of so many nationalities in the campsite, that he had been stupid never to realize that Hogwarts couldn\rquote t be the only one. He glanced at Hermione, who looked utterly unsurprised by the information. No doubt she had run across the news about other wizarding schools in some book or other.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve been ages,\rdblquote  said George when they finally got back to the Weasleys\rquote  tents.\par
\ldblquote Met a few people,\rdblquote  said Ron, setting the water down. \ldblquote You not got that fire started yet?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Dad\rquote s having fun with the matches,\rdblquote  said Fred.\par
Mr. Weasley was having no success at all in lighting the fire, but it wasn\rquote t for lack of trying. Splintered matches littered the ground around him, but he looked as though he was having the time of his life.\par
\ldblquote Oops!\rdblquote  he said as he managed to light a match and promptly dropped it in surprise.\par
\ldblquote Come here, Mr. Weasley,\rdblquote  said Hermione kindly, taking the box from him, and showing him how to do it properly.\par
At last they got the fire lit, though it was at least another hour before it was hot enough to cook anything. There was plenty to watch while they waited, however. Their tent seemed to be pitched right alongside a kind of thoroughfare to the field, and Ministry members kept hurrying up and down it, greeting Mr. Weasley cor\-dially as they passed. Mr. Weasley kept up a running commentary, mainly for Harry\rquote s and Hermione\rquote s benefit; his own children knew too much about the Ministry to be greatly interested.\par
\ldblquote That was Cuthbert Mockridge, Head of the Goblin Liaison Office. \'85 Here comes Gilbert Wimple; he\rquote s with the Committee on Experimental Charms; he\rquote s had those horns for a while now. \'85 Hello, Arnie \'85 Arnold Peasegood, he\rquote s an Obliviator \emdash  member of the Accidental Magic Reversal Squad, you know. \'85 and that\rquote s Bode and Croaker \'85 they\rquote re Unspeakables. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They\rquote re what?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote From the Department of Mysteries, top secret, no idea what they get up to. \'85\rdblquote\par
At last, the fire was ready, and they had just started cooking eggs and sausages when Bill, Charlie, and Percy came strolling out of the woods toward them.\par
\ldblquote Just Apparated, Dad,\rdblquote  said Percy loudly. \ldblquote Ah, excellent, lunch!\rdblquote\par
They were halfway through their plates of eggs and sausages when Mr. Weasley jumped to his feet, waving and grinning at a man who was striding toward them. \ldblquote Aha!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote The man of the moment! Ludo!\rdblquote\par
Ludo Bagman was easily the most noticeable person Harry had seen so far, even including old Archie in his flowered nightdress. He was wearing long Quidditch robes in thick horizontal stripes of bright yellow and black. An enormous picture of a wasp was splashed across his chest. He had the look of a powerfully built man gone slightly to seed; the robes were stretched tightly across a large belly he surely had not had in the days when he had played Quidditch for England. His nose was squashed (probably broken by a stray Bludger, Harry thought), but his round blue eyes, short blond hair, and rosy complexion made him look like a very over\-grown schoolboy.\par
\ldblquote Ahoy there!\rdblquote  Bagman called happily. He was walking as though he had springs attached to the balls of his feet and was plainly in a state of wild excitement.\par
\ldblquote Arthur, old man,\rdblquote  he puffed as he reached the campfire, \ldblquote what a day, eh? What a day! Could we have asked for more perfect weather? A cloudless night coming \'85 and hardly a hiccough in the arrangements. \'85 Not much for me to do!\rdblquote\par
Behind him, a group of haggard-looking Ministry wizards rushed past, pointing at the distant evidence of some sort of a mag\-ical fire that was sending violet sparks twenty feet into the air.\par
Percy hurried forward with his hand outstretched. Apparently his disapproval of the way Ludo Bagman ran his department did not prevent him from wanting to make a good impression.\par
\ldblquote Ah \emdash  yes,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, grinning, \ldblquote this is my son Percy. He\rquote s just started at the Ministry \emdash  and this is Fred \emdash  no, George, sorry \emdash  \i that\rquote s\i0  Fred \emdash  Bill, Charlie, Ron \emdash  my daughter, Ginny \emdash  and Ron\rquote s friends, Hermione Granger and Harry Potter.\rdblquote\par
Bagman did the smallest of double takes when he heard Harry\rquote s name, and his eyes performed the familiar flick upward to the scar on Harry\rquote s forehead.\par
\ldblquote Everyone,\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley continued, \ldblquote this is Ludo Bagman, you know who he is, it\rquote s thanks to him we\rquote ve got such good tickets \emdash\rdblquote\par
Bagman beamed and waved his hand as if to say it had been nothing.\par
\ldblquote Fancy a flutter on the match, Arthur?\rdblquote  he said eagerly, jingling what seemed to be a large amount of gold in the pockets of his yellow-and-black robes. \ldblquote I\rquote ve already got Roddy Pontner betting me Bulgaria will score first \emdash  I offered him nice odds, considering Ireland\rquote s front three are the strongest I\rquote ve seen in years \emdash  and little Agatha Timms has put up half shares in her eel farm on a week-long match.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh \'85 go on then,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Let\rquote s see \'85 a Galleon on Ireland to win?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A Galleon?\rdblquote  Ludo Bagman looked slightly disappointed, but re\-covered himself. \ldblquote Very well, very well \'85 any other takers?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They\rquote re a bit young to be gambling,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Molly wouldn\rquote t like \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ll bet thirty-seven Galleons, fifteen Sickles, three Knuts,\rdblquote  said Fred as he and George quickly pooled all their money, \ldblquote that Ireland wins \emdash  but Viktor Krum gets the Snitch. Oh and we\rquote ll throw in a fake wand.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t want to go showing Mr. Bagman rubbish like that \emdash\rdblquote  Percy hissed, but Bagman didn\rquote t seem to think the wand was rubbish at all; on the contrary, his boyish face shone with excitement as he took it from Fred, and when the wand gave a loud squawk and turned into a rubber chicken, Bagman roared with laughter.\par
\ldblquote Excellent! I haven\rquote t seen one that convincing in years! I\rquote d pay five Galleons for that!\rdblquote\par
Percy froze in an attitude of stunned disapproval.\par
\ldblquote Boys,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley under his breath, \ldblquote I don\rquote t want you betting. \'85 That\rquote s all your savings. \'85 Your mother \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be a spoilsport, Arthur!\rdblquote  boomed Ludo Bagman, rattling his pockets excitedly. \ldblquote They\rquote re old enough to know what they want! You reckon Ireland will win but Krum\rquote ll get the Snitch? Not a chance, boys, not a chance. \'85 I\rquote ll give you excellent odds on that one. \'85 We\rquote ll add five Galleons for the funny wand, then, shall we. \'85\rdblquote\par
Mr. Weasley looked on helplessly as Ludo Bagman whipped out a notebook and quill and began jotting down the twins\rquote  names.\par
\ldblquote Cheers,\rdblquote  said George, taking the slip of parchment Bagman handed him and tucking it away carefully. Bagman turned most cheerfully back to Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Couldn\rquote t do me a brew, I suppose? I\rquote m keeping an eye out for Barty Crouch. My Bulgarian opposite number\rquote s making difficul\-ties, and I can\rquote t understand a word he\rquote s saying. Barty\rquote ll be able to sort it out. He speaks about a hundred and fifty languages.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mr. Crouch?\rdblquote  said Percy, suddenly abandoning his look of poker-stiff disapproval and positively writhing with excitement. \ldblquote He speaks over two hundred! Mermish and Gobbledegook and Troll \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Anyone can speak Troll,\rdblquote  said Fred dismissively. \ldblquote All you have to do is point and grunt.\rdblquote\par
Percy threw Fred an extremely nasty look and stoked the fire vig\-orously to bring the kettle back to the boil.\par
\ldblquote Any news of Bertha Jorkins yet, Ludo?\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley asked as Bagman settled himself down on the grass beside them all.\par
\ldblquote Not a dicky bird,\rdblquote  said Bagman comfortably. \ldblquote But she\rquote ll turn up. Poor old Bertha \'85 memory like a leaky cauldron and no sense of direction. Lost, you take my word for it. She\rquote ll wander back into the office sometime in October, thinking it\rquote s still July.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t think it might be time to send someone to look for her?\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley suggested tentatively as Percy handed Bagman his tea.\par
\ldblquote Barty Crouch keeps saying that,\rdblquote  said Bagman, his round eyes widening innocently, \ldblquote but we really can\rquote t spare anyone at the mo\-ment. Oh \emdash  talk of the devil! Barty!\rdblquote\par
A wizard had just Apparated at their fireside, and he could not have made more of a contrast with Ludo Bagman, sprawled on the grass in his old Wasp robes. Barty Crouch was a stiff, upright, el\-derly man, dressed in an impeccably crisp suit and tie. The parting in his short gray hair was almost unnaturally straight, and his nar\-row toothbrush mustache looked as though he trimmed it using a slide rule. His shoes were very highly polished. Harry could see at once why Percy idolized him. Percy was a great believer in rigidly following rules, and Mr. Crouch had complied with the rule about Muggle dressing so thoroughly that he could have passed for a bank manager; Harry doubted even Uncle Vernon would have spotted him for what he really was.\par
\ldblquote Pull up a bit of grass, Barty,\rdblquote  said Ludo brightly, patting the ground beside him.\par
\ldblquote No thank you, Ludo,\rdblquote  said Crouch, and there was a bite of im\-patience in his voice. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been looking for you everywhere. The Bulgarians are insisting we add another twelve seats to the Top Box.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh is \i that\i0  what they\rquote re after?\rdblquote  said Bagman. \ldblquote I thought the chap was asking to borrow a pair of tweezers. Bit of a strong accent.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mr. Crouch!\rdblquote  said Percy breathlessly, sunk into a kind of half-bow that made him look like a hunchback. \ldblquote Would you like a cup of tea?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch, looking over at Percy in mild surprise. \ldblquote Yes \emdash  thank you, Weatherby\rdblquote\par
Fred and George choked into their own cups. Percy, very pink around the ears, busied himself with the kettle.\par
\ldblquote Oh and I\rquote ve been wanting a word with you too, Arthur,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch, his sharp eyes falling upon Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Ali Bashir\rquote s on the warpath. He wants a word with you about your embargo on flying carpets.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Weasley heaved a deep sigh.\par
\ldblquote I sent him an owl about that just last week. If I\rquote ve told him once I\rquote ve told him a hundred times: Carpets are defined as a Muggle Ar\-tifact by the Registry of Proscribed Charmable Objects, but will he listen?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I doubt it,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch, accepting a cup from Percy. \ldblquote He\rquote s desperate to export here.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, they\rquote ll never replace brooms in Britain, will they?\rdblquote  said Bagman.\par
\ldblquote Ali thinks there\rquote s a niche in the market for a family vehicle,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch. \ldblquote I remember my grandfather had an Axminster that could seat twelve \emdash  but that was before carpets were banned, of course.\rdblquote\par
He spoke as though he wanted to leave nobody in any doubt that all his ancestors had abided strictly by the law.\par
\ldblquote So, been keeping busy, Barty?\rdblquote  said Bagman breezily.\par
\ldblquote Fairly,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch dryly. \ldblquote Organizing Portkeys across five continents is no mean feat, Ludo.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I expect you\rquote ll both be glad when this is over?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\par
Ludo Bagman looked shocked.\par
\ldblquote Glad! Don\rquote t know when I\rquote ve had more fun. \'85 Still, it\rquote s not as though we haven\rquote t got anything to look forward to, eh, Barty? Eh? Plenty left to organize, eh?\rdblquote\par
Mr. Crouch raised his eyebrows at Bagman.\par
\ldblquote We agreed not to make the announcement until all the details \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh details!\rdblquote  said Bagman, waving the word away like a cloud of midges. \ldblquote They\rquote ve signed, haven\rquote t they? They\rquote ve agreed, haven\rquote t they? I bet you anything these kids\rquote ll know soon enough anyway. I mean, it\rquote s happening at Hogwarts \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ludo, we need to meet the Bulgarians, you know,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch sharply, cutting Bagman\rquote s remarks short. \ldblquote Thank you for the tea, Weatherby.\rdblquote\par
He pushed his undrunk tea back at Percy and waited for Ludo to rise; Bagman struggled to his feet, swigging down the last of his tea, the gold in his pockets chinking merrily.\par
\ldblquote See you all later!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote You\rquote ll be up in the Top Box with me \emdash  I\rquote m commentating!\rdblquote  He waved, Barty Crouch nodded curtly, and both of them Disapparated.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s happening at Hogwarts, Dad?\rdblquote  said Fred at once. \ldblquote What were they talking about?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ll find out soon enough,\rdblquote  said Mr.Weasley, smiling.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s classified information, until such time as the Ministry de\-cides to release it,\rdblquote  said Percy stiffly. \ldblquote Mr. Crouch was quite right not to disclose it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh shut up, Weatherby,\rdblquote  said Fred.\par
A sense of excitement rose like a palpable cloud over the camp\-site as the afternoon wore on. By dusk, the still summer air itself seemed to be quivering with anticipation, and as darkness spread like a curtain over the thousands of waiting wizards, the last vestiges of pretence disappeared: the Ministry seemed to have bowed to the inevitable and stopped fighting the signs of blatant magic now breaking out everywhere.\par
Salesmen were Apparating every few feet, carrying trays and pushing carts full of extraordinary merchandise. There were lumi\-nous rosettes \emdash  green for Ireland, red for Bulgaria \emdash  which were squealing the names of the players, pointed green hats bedecked with dancing shamrocks, Bulgarian scarves adorned with lions that really roared, flags from both countries that played their national anthems as they were waved; there were tiny models of Firebolts that really flew, and collectible figures of famous players, which strolled across the palm of your hand, preening themselves.\par
\ldblquote Been saving my pocket money all summer for this,\rdblquote  Ron told Harry as they and Hermione strolled through the salesmen, buying souvenirs. Though Ron purchased a dancing shamrock hat and a large green rosette, he also bought a small figure of Viktor Krum, the Bulgarian Seeker. The miniature Krum walked backward and forward over Ron\rquote s hand, scowling up at the green rosette above him.\par
\ldblquote Wow, look at these!\rdblquote  said Harry, hurrying over to a cart piled high with what looked like brass binoculars, except that they were covered with all sorts of weird knobs and dials.\par
\ldblquote Omnioculars,\rdblquote  said the saleswizard eagerly. \ldblquote You can replay ac\-tion \'85 slow everything down \'85 and they flash up a play-by-play breakdown if you need it. Bargain \emdash  ten Galleons each.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Wish I hadn\rquote t bought this now,\rdblquote  said Ron, gesturing at his dancing shamrock hat and gazing longingly at the Omnioculars.\par
\ldblquote Three pairs,\rdblquote  said Harry firmly to the wizard.\par
\ldblquote No \emdash  don\rquote t bother,\rdblquote  said Ron, going red. He was always touchy about the fact that Harry, who had inherited a small for\-tune from his parents, had much more money than he did.\par
\ldblquote You won\rquote t be getting anything for Christmas,\rdblquote  Harry told him, thrusting Omnioculars into his and Hermione\rquote s hands. \ldblquote For about ten years, mind.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Fair enough,\rdblquote  said Ron, grinning.\par
\ldblquote Oooh, thanks, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote And I\rquote ll get us some programs, look \emdash\rdblquote\par
Their money bags considerably lighter, they went back to the tents. Bill, Charlie, and Ginny were all sporting green rosettes too, and Mr. Weasley was carrying an Irish flag. Fred and George had no souvenirs as they had given Bagman all their gold.\par
And then a deep, booming gong sounded somewhere beyond the woods, and at once, green and red lanterns blazed into life in the trees, lighting a path to the field.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s time!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, looking as excited as any of them. \ldblquote Come on, let\rquote s go!\rdblquote\par
