Clutching their purchases, Mr. Weasley in the lead, they all hurried into the wood, following the lantern-lit trail. They could hear the sounds of thousands of people moving around them, shouts and laughter, snatches of singing. The atmosphere of feverish excitement was highly infectious; Harry couldn\rquote t stop grin\-ning. They walked through the wood for twenty minutes, talking and joking loudly, until at last they emerged on the other side and found themselves in the shadow of a gigantic stadium. Though Harry could see only a fraction of the immense gold walls sur\-rounding the field, he could tell that ten cathedrals would fit com\-fortably inside it.\par
\ldblquote Seats a hundred thousand,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, spotting the awestruck look on Harry\rquote s face. \ldblquote Ministry task force of five hun\-dred have been working on it all year. Muggle Repelling Charms on every inch of it. Every time Muggles have got anywhere near here all year, they\rquote ve suddenly remembered urgent appointments and had to dash away again \'85 bless them,\rdblquote  he added fondly, lead\-ing the way toward the nearest entrance, which was already sur\-rounded by a swarm of shouting witches and wizards.\par
\ldblquote Prime seats!\rdblquote  said the Ministry witch at the entrance when she checked their tickets. \ldblquote Top Box! Straight upstairs, Arthur, and as high as you can go.\rdblquote\par
The stairs into the stadium were carpeted in rich purple. They clambered upward with the rest of the crowd, which slowly filtered away through doors into the stands to their left and right. Mr. Weasley\rquote s party kept climbing, and at last they reached the top of the staircase and found themselves in a small box, set at the high\-est point of the stadium and situated exactly halfway between the golden goal posts. About twenty purple-and-gilt chairs stood in two rows here, and Harry, filing into the front seats with the Weasleys, looked down upon a scene the likes of which he could never have imagined.\par
A hundred thousand witches and wizards were taking their places in the seats, which rose in levels around the long oval field. Everything was suffused with a mysterious golden light, which seemed to come from the stadium itself. The field looked smooth as velvet from their lofty position. At either end of the field stood three goal hoops, fifty feet high; right opposite them, almost at Harry\rquote s eye level, was a gigantic blackboard. Gold writing kept dashing across it as though an invisible giant\rquote s hand were scrawling upon the blackboard and then wiping it off again; watching it, Harry saw that it was flashing advertisements across the field.\par
\i The Bluebottle: A Broom for All the Family \emdash  safe, reliable, and with Built-in Anti-Burglar Buzzer \'85 Mrs. Skower\rquote s All-Purpose Magical Mess Remover: No Pain, No Stain! \'85 Gladrags Wizardwear \emdash  London, Paris, Hogsmeade \'85\par
\i0 Harry tore his eyes away from the sign and looked over his shoulder to see who else was sharing the box with them. So far it was empty, except for a tiny creature sitting in the second from last seat at the end of the row behind them. The creature, whose legs were so short they stuck out in front of it on the chair, was wearing a tea towel draped like a toga, and it had its face hidden in its hands. Yet those long, batlike ears were oddly familiar. \'85\par
\ldblquote\i Dobby\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Harry incredulously.\par
The tiny creature looked up and stretched its fingers, revealing enormous brown eyes and a nose the exact size and shape of a large tomato. It wasn\rquote t Dobby \emdash  it was, however, unmistakably a house-elf, as Harry\rquote s friend Dobby had been. Harry had set Dobby free from his old owners, the Malfoy family.\par
\ldblquote Did sir just call me Dobby?\rdblquote  squeaked the elf curiously from between its fingers. Its voice was higher even than Dobby\rquote s had been, a teeny, quivering squeak of a voice, and Harry suspected \emdash  though it was very hard to tell with a house-elf \emdash  that this one might just be female. Ron and Hermione spun around in their seats to look. Though they had heard a lot about Dobby from Harry, they had never actually met him. Even Mr. Weasley looked around in interest.\par
\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  Harry told the elf, \ldblquote I just thought you were someone I knew.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But I knows Dobby too, sir!\rdblquote  squeaked the elf. She was shield\-ing her face, as though blinded by light, though the Top Box was not brightly lit. \ldblquote My name is Winky, sir \emdash  and you, sir \emdash\rdblquote  Her dark brown eyes widened to the size of side plates as they rested upon Harry\rquote s scar. \ldblquote You is surely Harry Potter!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, I am,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote But Dobby talks of you all the time, sir!\rdblquote  she said, lowering her hands very slightly and looking awestruck.\par
\ldblquote How is he?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote How\rquote s freedom suiting him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ah, sir,\rdblquote  said Winky, shaking her head, \ldblquote ah sir, meaning no dis\-respect, sir, but I is not sure you did Dobby a favor, sir, when you is setting him free.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  said Harry, taken aback. \ldblquote What\rquote s wrong with him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Freedom is going to Dobby\rquote s head, sir,\rdblquote  said Winky sadly. \ldblquote Ideas above his station, sir. Can\rquote t get another position, sir.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Winky lowered her voice by a half-octave and whispered, \ldblquote\i He is wanting paying for his work, sir.\i0\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Paying?\rdblquote  said Harry blankly. \ldblquote Well \emdash  why shouldn\rquote t he be paid?\rdblquote\par
Winky looked quite horrified at the idea and closed her fingers slightly so that her face was half-hidden again.\par
\ldblquote House-elves is not paid, sir!\rdblquote  she said in a muffled squeak. \ldblquote No, no, no. I says to Dobby, I says, go find yourself a nice family and settle down, Dobby. He is getting up to all sorts of high jinks, sir, what is unbecoming to a house-elf. You goes racketing around like this, Dobby, I says, and next thing I hear you\rquote s up in front of the Department for the Regulation and Control of Magical Creatures, like some common goblin.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s about time he had a bit of fun,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote House-elves is not supposed to have fun, Harry Potter,\rdblquote  said Winky firmly, from behind her hands. \ldblquote House-elves does what they is told. I is not liking heights at all, Harry Potter\rdblquote  \emdash  she glanced toward the edge of the box and gulped \emdash  \ldblquote but my master sends me to the Top Box and I comes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why\rquote s he sent you up here, if he knows you don\rquote t like heights?\rdblquote  said Harry, frowning.\par
\ldblquote Master \emdash  master wants me to save him a seat, Harry Potter. He is very busy,\rdblquote  said Winky, tilting her head toward the empty space beside her. \ldblquote Winky is wishing she is back in master\rquote s tent, Harry Potter, but Winky does what she is told. Winky is a good house-elf.\rdblquote\par
She gave the edge of the box another frightened look and hid her eyes completely again. Harry turned back to the others.\par
\ldblquote So that\rquote s a house-elf?\rdblquote  Ron muttered. \ldblquote Weird things, aren\rquote t they?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Dobby was weirder,\rdblquote  said Harry fervently.\par
Ron pulled out his Omnioculars and started testing them, star\-ing down into the crowd on the other side of the stadium.\par
\ldblquote Wild!\rdblquote  he said, twiddling the replay knob on the side. \ldblquote I can make that old bloke down there pick his nose again \'85 and again \'85 and again \'85\rdblquote\par
Hermione, meanwhile, was skimming eagerly through her velvet-covered, tasseled program.\par
\ldblquote  \lquote A display from the team mascots will precede the match,\rquote  \rdblquote  she read aloud.\par
\ldblquote Oh that\rquote s always worth watching,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote National teams bring creatures from their native land, you know, to put on a bit of a show.\rdblquote\par
The box filled gradually around them over the next half hour. Mr. Weasley kept shaking hands with people who were obviously very important wizards. Percy jumped to his feet so often that he looked as though he were trying to sit on a hedgehog. When Cor\-nelius Fudge, the Minister of Magic himself, arrived, Percy bowed so low that his glasses fell off and shattered. Highly embarrassed, he repaired them with his wand and thereafter remained in his seat, throwing jealous looks at Harry, whom Cornelius Fudge had greeted like an old friend. They had met before, and Fudge shook Harry\rquote s hand in a fatherly fashion, asked how he was, and intro\-duced him to the wizards on either side of him.\par
\ldblquote Harry Potter, you know,\rdblquote  he told the Bulgarian minister loudly, who was wearing splendid robes of black velvet trimmed with gold and didn\rquote t seem to understand a word of English. \ldblquote\i Harry Potter\i0  \'85 oh come on now, you know who he is \'85 the boy who survived You-Know-Who \'85 you \i do\i0  know who he is \emdash\rdblquote\par
The Bulgarian wizard suddenly spotted Harry\rquote s scar and started gabbling loudly and excitedly, pointing at it.\par
\ldblquote Knew we\rquote d get there in the end,\rdblquote  said Fudge wearily to Harry. \ldblquote I\rquote m no great shakes at languages; I need Barty Crouch for this sort of thing. Ah, I see his house-elf\rquote s saving him a seat. \'85 Good job too, these Bulgarian blighters have been trying to cadge all the best places \'85 ah, and here\rquote s Lucius!\rdblquote\par
Harry, Ron, and Hermione turned quickly. Edging along the second row to three still-empty seats right behind Mr. Weasley were none other than Dobby the house-elf\rquote s former owners: Lucius Malfoy; his son, Draco; and a woman Harry supposed must be Draco\rquote s mother.\par
Harry and Draco Malfoy had been enemies ever since their very first journey to Hogwarts. A pale boy with a pointed face and white-blond hair, Draco greatly resembled his father. His mother was blonde too; tall and slim, she would have been nice-looking if she hadn\rquote t been wearing a look that suggested there was a nasty smell under her nose.\par
\ldblquote Ah, Fudge,\rdblquote  said Mr. Malfoy, holding out his hand as he reached the Minister of Magic. \ldblquote How are you? I don\rquote t think you\rquote ve met my wife, Narcissa? Or our son, Draco?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How do you do, how do you do?\rdblquote  said Fudge, smiling and bowing to Mrs. Malfoy. \ldblquote And allow me to introduce you to Mr. Oblansk \emdash  Obalonsk \emdash  Mr. \emdash  well, he\rquote s the Bulgarian Minister of Magic, and he can\rquote t understand a word I\rquote m saying anyway, so never mind. And let\rquote s see who else \emdash  you know Arthur Weasley, I daresay?\rdblquote\par
It was a tense moment. Mr. Weasley and Mr. Malfoy looked at each other and Harry vividly recalled the last time they had come face-to-face: It had been in Flourish and Blotts\rquote  bookshop, and they had had a fight. Mr. Malfoy\rquote s cold gray eyes swept over Mr. Weasley, and then up and down the row.\par
\ldblquote Good lord, Arthur,\rdblquote  he said softly. \ldblquote What did you have to sell to get seats in the Top Box? Surely your house wouldn\rquote t have fetched this much?\rdblquote\par
Fudge, who wasn\rquote t listening, said, \ldblquote Lucius has just given a \i very \i0 generous contribution to St. Mungo\rquote s Hospital for Magical Mal\-adies and Injuries, Arthur. He\rquote s here as my guest.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How \emdash  how nice,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, with a very strained smile.\par
Mr. Malfoy\rquote s eyes had returned to Hermione, who went slightly pink, but stared determinedly back at him. Harry knew exactly what was making Mr. Malfoy\rquote s lip curl like that. The Malfoys prided themselves on being purebloods; in other words, they con\-sidered anyone of Muggle descent, like Hermione, second-class. However, under the gaze of the Minister of Magic, Mr. Malfoy did\-n\rquote t dare say anything. He nodded sneeringly to Mr. Weasley and continued down the line to his seats. Draco shot Harry, Ron, and Hermione one contemptuous look, then settled himself between his mother and father.\par
\ldblquote Slimy gits,\rdblquote  Ron muttered as he, Harry, and Hermione turned to face the field again. Next moment, Ludo Bagman charged into the box.\par
\ldblquote Everyone ready?\rdblquote  he said, his round face gleaming like a great, excited Edam. \ldblquote Minister \emdash  ready to go?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ready when you are, Ludo,\rdblquote  said Fudge comfortably.\par
Ludo whipped out his wand, directed it at his own throat, and said \ldblquote\i Sonorus\i0 !\rdblquote  and then spoke over the roar of sound that was now filling the packed stadium; his voice echoed over them, booming into every corner of the stands.\par
\ldblquote Ladies and gentlemen \'85 welcome! Welcome to the final of the four hundred and twenty-second Quidditch World Cup!\rdblquote\par
The spectators screamed and clapped. Thousands of flags waved, adding their discordant national anthems to the racket. The huge blackboard opposite them was wiped clear of its last message (\i Bertie Bott\rquote s Every Flavor Beans \emdash  A Risk With Every Mouthful\i0 !) and now showed BULGARIA: 0, IRELAND: 0.\par
\ldblquote And now, without further ado, allow me to introduce \'85 the Bulgarian National Team Mascots!\rdblquote\par
The right-hand side of the stands, which was a solid block of scarlet, roared its approval.\par
\ldblquote I wonder what they\rquote ve brought,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, leaning for\-ward in his seat. \ldblquote Aaah!\rdblquote  He suddenly whipped off his glasses and polished them hurriedly on his robes. \ldblquote\i Veela\i0 !\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What are veel \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
But a hundred veela were now gliding out onto the field, and Harry\rquote s question was answered for him. Veela were women \'85 the most beautiful women Harry had ever seen \'85 except that they weren\rquote t \emdash  they couldn\rquote t be \emdash  human. This puzzled Harry for a moment while he tried to guess what exactly they could be; what could make their skin shine moon-bright like that, or their white-gold hair fan out behind them without wind \'85 but then the mu\-sic started, and Harry stopped worrying about them not being human \emdash  in fact, he stopped worrying about anything at all.\par
The veela had started to dance, and Harry\rquote s mind had gone com\-pletely and blissfully blank. All that mattered in the world was that he kept watching the veela, because if they stopped dancing, terri\-ble things would happen. \'85\par
And as the veela danced faster and faster, wild, half-formed thoughts started chasing through Harry\rquote s dazed mind. He wanted to do something very impressive, right now. Jumping from the box into the stadium seemed a good idea \'85 but would it be good enough?\par
\ldblquote Harry, what \i are\i0  you doing?\rdblquote  said Hermione\rquote s voice from a long way off.\par
The music stopped. Harry blinked. He was standing up, and one of his legs was resting on the wall of the box. Next to him, Ron was frozen in an attitude that looked as though he were about to dive from a springboard.\par
Angry yells were filling the stadium. The crowd didn\rquote t want the veela to go. Harry was with them; he would, of course, be sup\-porting Bulgaria, and he wondered vaguely why he had a large green shamrock pinned to his chest. Ron, meanwhile, was absent-mindedly shredding the shamrocks on his hat. Mr. Weasley, smil\-ing slightly, leaned over to Ron and tugged the hat out of his hands.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ll be wanting that,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote once Ireland have had their say.\par
\ldblquote Huh?\rdblquote  said Ron, staring openmouthed at the veela, who had now lined up along one side of the field.\par
Hermione made a loud tutting noise. She reached up and pulled Harry back into his seat. \ldblquote\i Honestly\i0 !\rdblquote  she said.\par
\ldblquote And now,\rdblquote  roared Ludo Bagman\rquote s voice, \ldblquote kindly put your wands in the air \'85 for the Irish National Team Mascots!\rdblquote\par
Next moment, what seemed to be a great green-and-gold comet came zooming into the stadium. It did one circuit of the stadium, then split into two smaller comets, each hurtling toward the goal posts. A rainbow arced suddenly across the field, connecting the two balls of light. The crowd oooohed and aaaaahed, as though at a fireworks display. Now the rainbow faded and the balls of light re\-united and merged; they had formed a great shimmering sham\-rock, which rose up into the sky and began to soar over the stands. Something like golden rain seemed to be falling from it \emdash\par
\ldblquote Excellent!\rdblquote  yelled Ron as the shamrock soared over them, and heavy gold coins rained from it, bouncing off their heads and seats. Squinting up at the shamrock, Harry realized that it was actually comprised of thousands of tiny little bearded men with red vests, each carrying a minute lamp of gold or green.\par
\ldblquote Leprechauns!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley over the tumultuous applause of the crowd, many of whom were still fighting and rummaging around under their chairs to retrieve the gold.\par
\ldblquote There you go,\rdblquote  Ron yelled happily, stuffing a fistful of gold coins into Harry\rquote s hand, \ldblquote for the Omnioculars! Now you\rquote ve got to buy me a Christmas present, ha!\rdblquote\par
The great shamrock dissolved, the leprechauns drifted down onto the field on the opposite side from the veela, and settled themselves cross-legged to watch the match.\par
\ldblquote And now, ladies and gentlemen, kindly welcome \emdash  the Bulgar\-ian National Quidditch Team! I give you \emdash  Dimitrov!\rdblquote\par
A scarlet-clad figure on a broomstick, moving so fast it was blurred, shot out onto the field from an entrance far below, to wild applause from the Bulgarian supporters.\par
\ldblquote Ivanova!\rdblquote\par
A second scarlet-robed player zoomed out.\par
\ldblquote Zograf! Levski! Vulchanov! Volkov! Aaaaaaand \emdash  \i Krum\i0 !\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s him, that\rquote s him!\rdblquote  yelled Ron, following Krum with his Omnioculars. Harry quickly focused his own.\par
Viktor Krum was thin, dark, and sallow-skinned, with a large curved nose and thick black eyebrows. He looked like an over\-grown bird of prey. It was hard to believe he was only eighteen.\par
\ldblquote And now, please greet \emdash  the Irish National Quidditch Team!\rdblquote  yelled Bagman. \ldblquote Presenting \emdash  Connolly! Ryan! Troy! Mullet! Moran! Quigley! Aaaaaand \emdash  \i Lynch\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Seven green blurs swept onto the field; Harry spun a small dial on the side of his Omnioculars and slowed the players down enough to read the word \ldblquote Firebolt\rdblquote  on each of their brooms and see their names, embroidered in silver, upon their backs.\par
\ldblquote And here, all the way from Egypt, our referee, acclaimed Chairwizard of the International Association of Quidditch, Hassan Mostafa!\rdblquote\par
A small and skinny wizard, completely bald but with a mustache to rival Uncle Vernon\rquote s, wearing robes of pure gold to match the stadium, strode out onto the field. A silver whistle was protruding from under the mustache, and he was carrying a large wooden crate under one arm, his broomstick under the other. Harry spun the speed dial on his Omnioculars back to normal, watching closely as Mostafa mounted his broomstick and kicked the crate open \emdash  four balls burst into the air: the scarlet Quaffle, the two black Bludgers, and (Harry saw it for the briefest moment, before it sped out of sight) the minuscule, winged Golden Snitch. With a sharp blast on his whistle, Mostafa shot into the air after the balls.\par
\ldblquote Theeeeeeeey\rquote re OFF!\rdblquote  screamed Bagman. \ldblquote And it\rquote s Mullet! Troy! Moran! Dimitrov! Back to Mullet! Troy! Levski! Moran!\rdblquote\par
It was Quidditch as Harry had never seen it played before. He was pressing his Omnioculars so hard to his glasses that they were cutting into the bridge of his nose. The speed of the players was in\-credible \emdash  the Chasers were throwing the Quaffle to one another so fast that Bagman only had time to say their names. Harry spun the slow dial on the right of his Omnioculars again, pressed the play-by-play button on the top, and he was immediately watching in slow motion, while glittering purple lettering flashed across the lenses and the noise of the crowd pounded against his eardrums.\par
\i Hawkshead Attacking Formation,\i0  he read as he watched the three Irish Chasers zoom closely together, Troy in the center, slightly ahead of Mullet and Moran, bearing down upon the Bul\-garians. \i Porskoff Ploy\i0  flashed up next, as Troy made as though to dart upward with the Quaffle, drawing away the Bulgarian Chaser Ivanova and dropping the Quaffle to Moran. One of the Bulgarian Beaters, Volkov, swung hard at a passing Bludger with his small club, knocking it into Moran\rquote s path; Moran ducked to avoid the Bludger and dropped the Quaffle; and Levski, soaring beneath, caught it \emdash\par
\ldblquote TROY SCORES!\rdblquote  roared Bagman, and the stadium shuddered with a roar of applause and cheers. \ldblquote Ten zero to Ireland!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  Harry yelled, looking wildly around through his Om\-nioculars. \ldblquote But Levski\rquote s got the Quaffle!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Harry, if you\rquote re not going to watch at normal speed, you\rquote re go\-ing to miss things!\rdblquote  shouted Hermione, who was dancing up and down, waving her arms in the air while Troy did a lap of honor around the field. Harry looked quickly over the top of his Omni-oculars and saw that the leprechauns watching from the sidelines had all risen into the air again and formed the great, glittering shamrock. Across the field, the veela were watching them sulkily.\par
Furious with himself, Harry spun his speed dial back to normal as play resumed.\par
Harry knew enough about Quidditch to see that the Irish Chasers were superb. They worked as a seamless team, their move\-ments so well coordinated that they appeared to be reading one another\rquote s minds as they positioned themselves, and the rosette on Harry\rquote s chest kept squeaking their names: \ldblquote\i Troy\i0  \emdash  \i Mullet\i0  \emdash  \i Moran\i0 !\rdblquote  And within ten minutes, Ireland had scored twice more, bringing their lead to thirty-zero and causing a thunderous tide of roars and applause from the green-clad supporters.\par
The match became still faster, but more brutal. Volkov and Vulchanov, the Bulgarian Beaters, were whacking the Bludgers as fiercely as possible at the Irish Chasers, and were starting to prevent them from using some of their best moves; twice they were forced to scatter, and then, finally, Ivanova managed to break through their ranks; dodge the Keeper, Ryan; and score Bulgaria\rquote s first goal.\par
\ldblquote Fingers in your ears!\rdblquote  bellowed Mr. Weasley as the veela started to dance in celebration. Harry screwed up his eyes too; he wanted to keep his mind on the game. After a few seconds, he chanced a glance at the field. The veela had stopped dancing, and Bulgaria was again in possession of the Quaffle.\par
\ldblquote Dimitrov! Levski! Dimitrov! Ivanova \emdash  oh I say!\rdblquote  roared Bagman.\par
One hundred thousand wizards gasped as the two Seekers, Krum and Lynch, plummeted through the center of the Chasers, so fast that it looked as though they had just jumped from airplanes without parachutes. Harry followed their descent through his Om\-nioculars, squinting to see where the Snitch was \emdash\par
\ldblquote They\rquote re going to crash!\rdblquote  screamed Hermione next to Harry.\par
She was half right \emdash  at the very last second, Viktor Krum pulled out of the dive and spiraled off. Lynch, however, hit the ground with a dull thud that could be heard throughout the sta\-dium. A huge groan rose from the Irish seats.\par
\ldblquote Fool!\rdblquote  moaned Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Krum was feinting!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s time-out!\rdblquote  yelled Bagman\rquote s voice, \ldblquote as trained mediwizards hurry onto the field to examine Aidan Lynch!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote ll be okay, he only got ploughed!\rdblquote  Charlie said reassuringly to Ginny, who was hanging over the side of the box, looking horror-struck. \ldblquote Which is what Krum was after, of course. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry hastily pressed the replay and play-by-play buttons on his Omnioculars, twiddled the speed dial, and put them back up to his eyes.\par
He watched as Krum and Lynch dived again in slow motion. \i Wronski Defensive Feint \emdash  dangerous Seeker diversion \i0 read the shining purple lettering across his lenses. He saw Krum\rquote s face contorted with concentration as he pulled out of the dive just in time, while Lynch was flattened, and he understood \emdash  Krum hadn\rquote t seen the Snitch at all, he was just making Lynch copy him. Harry had never seen anyone fly like that; Krum hardly looked as though he was using a broomstick at all; he moved so easily through the air that he looked unsupported and weightless. Harry turned his Omnioculars back to normal and focused them on Krum. He was now circling high above Lynch, who was being re\-vived by mediwizards with cups of potion. Harry, focusing still more closely upon Krum\rquote s face, saw his dark eyes darting all over the ground a hundred feet below. He was using the time while Lynch was revived to look for the Snitch without interference.\par
Lynch got to his feet at last, to loud cheers from the green-clad supporters, mounted his Firebolt, and kicked back off into the air. His revival seemed to give Ireland new heart. When Mostafa blew his whistle again, the Chasers moved into action with a skill unri\-valed by anything Harry had seen so far.\par
After fifteen more fast and furious minutes, Ireland had pulled ahead by ten more goals. They were now leading by one hundred and thirty points to ten, and the game was starting to get dirtier.\par
As Mullet shot toward the goal posts yet again, clutching the Quaffle tightly under her arm, the Bulgarian Keeper, Zograf, flew out to meet her. Whatever happened was over so quickly Harry didn\rquote t catch it, but a scream of rage from the Irish crowd, and Mostafa\rquote s long, shrill whistle blast, told him it had been a foul.\par
\ldblquote And Mostafa takes the Bulgarian Keeper to task for cobbing \emdash  excessive use of elbows!\rdblquote  Bagman informed the roaring spectators. \ldblquote And \emdash  yes, it\rquote s a penalty to Ireland!\rdblquote\par
The leprechauns, who had risen angrily into the air like a swarm of glittering hornets when Mullet had been fouled, now darted to\-gether to form the words \ldblquote HA, HA, HA!\rdblquote  The veela on the other side of the field leapt to their feet, tossed their hair angrily, and started to dance again.\par
As one, the Weasley boys and Harry stuffed their fingers into their ears, but Hermione, who hadn\rquote t bothered, was soon tugging on Harry\rquote s arm. He turned to look at her, and she pulled his fingers impatiently out of his ears.\par
\ldblquote Look at the referee!\rdblquote  she said, giggling.\par
Harry looked down at the field. Hassan Mostafa had landed right in front of the dancing veela, and was acting very oddly indeed. He was flexing his muscles and smoothing his mustache excitedly.\par
\ldblquote Now, we can\rquote t have that!\rdblquote  said Ludo Bagman, though he sounded highly amused. \ldblquote Somebody slap the referee!\rdblquote\par
A mediwizard came tearing across the field, his fingers stuffed into his own ears, and kicked Mostafa hard in the shins. Mostafa seemed to come to himself; Harry, watching through the Om\-nioculars again, saw that he looked exceptionally embarrassed and had started shouting at the veela, who had stopped dancing and were looking mutinous.\par
\ldblquote And unless I\rquote m much mistaken, Mostafa is actually attempting to send off the Bulgarian team mascots!\rdblquote  said Bagman\rquote s voice. \ldblquote Now \i there\rquote s\i0  something we haven\rquote t seen before. \'85 Oh this could turn nasty. \'85\rdblquote\par
It did: The Bulgarian Beaters, Volkov and Vulchanov, landed on either side of Mostafa and began arguing furiously with him, gesticulating toward the leprechauns, who had now gleefully formed the words \ldblquote HEE, HEE, HEE.\rdblquote  Mostafa was not impressed by the Bulgarians\rquote  arguments, however; he was jabbing his finger into the air, clearly telling them to get flying again, and when they refused, he gave two short blasts on his whistle.\par
\ldblquote\i Two\i0  penalties for Ireland!\rdblquote  shouted Bagman, and the Bulgarian crowd howled with anger. \ldblquote And Volkov and Vulchanov had better get back on those brooms \'85 yes \'85 there they go \'85 and Troy takes the Quaffle \'85\rdblquote\par
Play now reached a level of ferocity beyond anything they had yet seen. The Beaters on both sides were acting without mercy: Volkov and Vulchanov in particular seemed not to care whether their clubs made contact with Bludger or human as they swung them violently through the air. Dimitrov shot straight at Moran, who had the Quaffle, nearly knocking her off her broom.\par
\ldblquote\i Foul\i0 !\rdblquote  roared the Irish supporters as one, all standing up in a great wave of green.\par
\ldblquote Foul!\rdblquote  echoed Ludo Bagman\rquote s magically magnified voice. \ldblquote Dimitrov skins Moran \emdash  deliberately flying to collide there \emdash  and it\rquote s got to be another penalty \emdash  yes, there\rquote s the whistle!\rdblquote\par
The leprechauns had risen into the air again, and this time, they formed a giant hand, which was making a very rude sign indeed at the veela across the field. At this, the veela lost control. Instead of dancing, they launched themselves across the field and began throwing what seemed to be handfuls of fire at the leprechauns. Watching through his Omnioculars, Harry saw that they didn\rquote t look remotely beautiful now. On the contrary, their faces were elongating into sharp, cruel-beaked bird heads, and long, scaly wings were bursting from their shoulders \emdash\par
\ldblquote And \i that,\i0  boys,\rdblquote  yelled Mr. Weasley over the tumult of the crowd below, \ldblquote is why you should never go for looks alone!\rdblquote\par
Ministry wizards were flooding onto the field to separate the veela and the leprechauns, but with little success; meanwhile, the pitched battle below was nothing to the one taking place above. Harry turned this way and that, staring through his Omnioculars, as the Quaffle changed hands with the speed of a bullet.\par
\ldblquote Levski \emdash  Dimitrov \emdash  Moran \emdash  Troy \emdash  Mullet \emdash  Ivanova \emdash  Moran again \emdash  Moran \emdash  MORAN SCORES!\rdblquote\par
But the cheers of the Irish supporters were barely heard over the shrieks of the veela, the blasts now issuing from the Ministry mem\-bers\rquote  wands, and the furious roars of the Bulgarians. The game recommenced immediately; now Levski had the Quaffle, now Dimitrov \emdash\par
The Irish Beater Quigley swung heavily at a passing Bludger, and hit it as hard as possible toward Krum, who did not duck quickly enough. It hit him full in the face.\par
There was a deafening groan from the crowd; Krum\rquote s nose looked broken, there was blood everywhere, but Hassan Mostafa didn\rquote t blow his whistle. He had become distracted, and Harry couldn\rquote t blame him; one of the veela had thrown a handful of fire and set his broom tail alight.\par
Harry wanted someone to realize that Krum was injured; even though he was supporting Ireland, Krum was the most exciting player on the field. Ron obviously felt the same.\par
\ldblquote Time-out! Ah, come on, he can\rquote t play like that, look at him \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i Look at Lynch\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry yelled.\par
For the Irish Seeker had suddenly gone into a dive, and Harry was quite sure that this was no Wronski Feint; this was the real thing. \'85\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s seen the Snitch!\rdblquote  Harry shouted. \ldblquote He\rquote s seen it! Look at him go!\rdblquote\par
Half the crowd seemed to have realized what was happening; the Irish supporters rose in another great wave of green, screaming their Seeker on \'85 but Krum was on his tail. How he could see where he was going, Harry had no idea; there were flecks of blood flying through the air behind him, but he was drawing level with Lynch now as the pair of them hurtled toward the ground again \emdash\par
\ldblquote They\rquote re going to crash!\rdblquote  shrieked Hermione.\par
\ldblquote They\rquote re not!\rdblquote  roared Ron.\par
\ldblquote Lynch is!\rdblquote  yelled Harry.\par
And he was right \emdash  for the second time, Lynch hit the ground with tremendous force and was immediately stampeded by a horde of angry veela.\par
\ldblquote The Snitch, where\rquote s the Snitch?\rdblquote  bellowed Charlie, along the row.\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s got it \emdash  Krum\rquote s got it \emdash  it\rquote s all over!\rdblquote  shouted Harry.\par
Krum, his red robes shining with blood from his nose, was ris\-ing gently into the air, his fist held high, a glint of gold in his hand.\par
The scoreboard was flashing BULGARIA: 160, IRELAND: 170 across the crowd, who didn\rquote t seem to have realized what had hap\-pened. Then, slowly, as though a great jumbo jet were revving up, the rumbling from the Ireland supporters grew louder and louder and erupted into screams of delight.\par
\ldblquote IRELAND WINS!\rdblquote  Bagman shouted, who like the Irish, seemed to be taken aback by the sudden end of the match. \ldblquote KRUM GETS THE SNITCH \emdash  BUT IRELAND WINS \emdash  good lord, I don\rquote t think any of us were expecting that!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What did he catch the Snitch for?\rdblquote  Ron bellowed, even as he jumped up and down, applauding with his hands over his head. \ldblquote He ended it when Ireland were a hundred and sixty points ahead, the idiot!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He knew they were never going to catch up!\rdblquote  Harry shouted back over all the noise, also applauding loudly. \ldblquote The Irish Chasers were too good. \'85 He wanted to end it on his terms, that\rquote s all. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He was very brave, wasn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  Hermione said, leaning forward to watch Krum land as a swarm of mediwizards blasted a path through the battling leprechauns and veela to get to him. \ldblquote He looks a terrible mess. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry put his Omnioculars to his eyes again. It was hard to see what was happening below, because leprechauns were zooming de\-lightedly all over the field, but he could just make out Krum, sur\-rounded by mediwizards. He looked surlier than ever and refused to let them mop him up. His team members were around him, shaking their heads and looking dejected; a short way away, the Irish players were dancing gleefully in a shower of gold descending from their mascots. Flags were waving all over the stadium, the Irish national anthem blared from all sides; the veela were shrink\-ing back into their usual, beautiful selves now, though looking dispirited and forlorn.\par
\ldblquote Vell, ve fought bravely,\rdblquote  said a gloomy voice behind Harry. He looked around; it was the Bulgarian Minister of Magic.\par
\ldblquote You can speak English!\rdblquote  said Fudge, sounding outraged. \ldblquote And you\rquote ve been letting me mime everything all day!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Vell, it vos very funny,\rdblquote  said the Bulgarian minister, shrugging.\par
\ldblquote And as the Irish team performs a lap of honor, flanked by their mascots, the Quidditch World Cup itself is brought into the Top Box!\rdblquote  roared Bagman.\par
Harry\rquote s eyes were suddenly dazzled by a blinding white light, as the Top Box was magically illuminated so that everyone in the stands could see the inside. Squinting toward the entrance, he saw two panting wizards carrying a vast golden cup into the box, which they handed to Cornelius Fudge, who was still looking very dis\-gruntled that he\rquote d been using sign language all day for nothing.\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s have a really loud hand for the gallant losers \emdash  Bulgaria!\rdblquote  Bagman shouted.\par
And up the stairs into the box came the seven defeated Bulgar\-ian players. The crowd below was applauding appreciatively; Harry could see thousands and thousands of Omniocular lenses flashing and winking in their direction.\par
One by one, the Bulgarians filed between the rows of seats in the box, and Bagman called out the name of each as they shook hands with their own minister and then with Fudge. Krum, who was last in line, looked a real mess. Two black eyes were blooming spectac\-ularly on his bloody face. He was still holding the Snitch. Harry noticed that he seemed much less coordinated on the ground. He was slightly duck-footed and distinctly round-shouldered. But when Krum\rquote s name was announced, the whole stadium gave him a resounding, earsplitting roar.\par
And then came the Irish team. Aidan Lynch was being sup\-ported by Moran and Connolly; the second crash seemed to have dazed him and his eyes looked strangely unfocused. But he grinned happily as Troy and Quigley lifted the Cup into the air and the crowd below thundered its approval. Harry\rquote s hands were numb with clapping.\par
At last, when the Irish team had left the box to perform another lap of honor on their brooms (Aidan Lynch on the back of Con\-nolly\rquote s, clutching hard around his waist and still grinning in a be\-mused sort of way), Bagman pointed his wand at his throat and muttered, \ldblquote\i Quietus.\i0\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They\rquote ll be talking about this one for years,\rdblquote  he said hoarsely, \ldblquote a really unexpected twist, that. \'85 shame it couldn\rquote t have lasted longer. \'85 Ah yes. \'85 yes, I owe you \'85 how much?\rdblquote\par
For Fred and George had just scrambled over the backs of their seats and were standing in front of Ludo Bagman with broad grins on their faces, their hands outstretched.\par
