\ldblquote\i Don\rquote t\i0  tell your mother you\rquote ve been gambling,\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley implored Fred and George as they all made their way slowly down the purple-carpeted stairs.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry, Dad,\rdblquote  said Fred gleefully, \ldblquote we\rquote ve got big plans for this money. We don\rquote t want it confiscated.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Weasley looked for a moment as though he was going to ask what these big plans were, but seemed to decide, upon reflection, that he didn\rquote t want to know.\par
They were soon caught up in the crowds now flooding out of the stadium and back to their campsites. Raucous singing was borne toward them on the night air as they retraced their steps along the lantern-lit path, and leprechauns kept shooting over their heads, cackling and waving their lanterns. When they finally reached the tents, nobody felt like sleeping at all, and given the level of noise around them, Mr. Weasley agreed that they could all have one last cup of cocoa together before turning in. They were soon arguing enjoyably about the match; Mr. Weasley got drawn into a disagree\-ment about cobbing with Charlie, and it was only when Ginny fell asleep right at the tiny table and spilled hot chocolate all over the floor that Mr. Weasley called a halt to the verbal replays and in\-sisted that everyone go to bed. Hermione and Ginny went into the next tent, and Harry and the rest of the Weasleys changed into pa\-jamas and clambered into their bunks. From the other side of the campsite they could still hear much singing and the odd echoing bang.\par
\ldblquote Oh I am glad I\rquote m not on duty,\rdblquote  muttered Mr. Weasley sleepily. \ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t fancy having to go and tell the Irish they\rquote ve got to stop celebrating.\rdblquote\par
Harry, who was on a top bunk above Ron, lay staring up at the canvas ceiling of the tent, watching the glow of an occasional lep\-rechaun lantern flying overhead, and picturing again some of Krum\rquote s more spectacular moves. He was itching to get back on his own Firebolt and try out the Wronski Feint. \'85 Somehow Oliver Wood had never managed to convey with all his wriggling dia\-grams what that move was supposed to look like. \'85 Harry saw himself in robes that had his name on the back, and imagined the sensation of hearing a hundred-thousand-strong crowd roar, as Ludo Bagman\rquote s voice echoed throughout the stadium, \ldblquote I give you \'85 \i Potter\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Harry never knew whether or not he had actually dropped off to sleep \emdash  his fantasies of flying like Krum might well have slipped into actual dreams \emdash  all he knew was that, quite suddenly, Mr. Weasley was shouting.\par
\ldblquote Get up! Ron \emdash  Harry \emdash  come on now, get up, this is urgent!\rdblquote\par
Harry sat up quickly and the top of his head hit canvas.\par
\ldblquote  \rquote S\rquote  matter?\rdblquote  he said.\par
Dimly, he could tell that something was wrong. The noises in the campsite had changed. The singing had stopped. He could hear screams, and the sound of people running. He slipped down from the bunk and reached for his clothes, but Mr. Weasley, who had pulled on his jeans over his own pajamas, said, \ldblquote No time, Harry \emdash  just grab a jacket and get outside \emdash  quickly!\rdblquote\par
Harry did as he was told and hurried out of the tent, Ron at his heels.\par
By the light of the few fires that were still burning, he could see people running away into the woods, fleeing something that was moving across the field toward them, something that was emitting odd flashes of light and noises like gunfire. Loud jeering, roars of laughter, and drunken yells were drifting toward them; then came a burst of strong green light, which illuminated the scene.\par
A crowd of wizards, tightly packed and moving together with wands pointing straight upward, was marching slowly across the field. Harry squinted at them. \'85 They didn\rquote t seem to have faces. \'85 Then he realized that their heads were hooded and their faces masked. High above them, floating along in midair, four struggling figures were being contorted into grotesque shapes. It was as though the masked wizards on the ground were puppeteers, and the people above them were marionettes operated by invisible strings that rose from the wands into the air. Two of the figures were very small.\par
More wizards were joining the marching group, laughing and pointing up at the floating bodies. Tents crumpled and fell as the marching crowd swelled. Once or twice Harry saw one of the marchers blast a tent out of his way with his wand. Several caught fire. The screaming grew louder.\par
The floating people were suddenly illuminated as they passed over a burning tent and Harry recognized one of them: Mr. Roberts, the campsite manager. The other three looked as though they might be his wife and children. One of the marchers below flipped Mrs. Roberts upside down with his wand; her nightdress fell down to reveal voluminous drawers and she struggled to cover herself up as the crowd below her screeched and hooted with glee.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s sick,\rdblquote  Ron muttered, watching the smallest Muggle child, who had begun to spin like a top, sixty feet above the ground, his head flopping limply from side to side. \ldblquote That is really sick. \'85\rdblquote\par
Hermione and Ginny came hurrying toward them, pulling coats over their nightdresses, with Mr. Weasley right behind them. At the same moment, Bill, Charlie, and Percy emerged from the boys\rquote  tent, fully dressed, with their sleeves rolled up and their wands out.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re going to help the Ministry!\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley shouted over all the noise, rolling up his own sleeves. \ldblquote You lot \emdash  get into the woods, and \i stick together.\i0  I\rquote ll come and fetch you when we\rquote ve sorted this out!\rdblquote\par
Bill, Charlie, and Percy were already sprinting away toward the oncoming marchers; Mr. Weasley tore after them. Ministry wizards were dashing from every direction toward the source of the trouble. The crowd beneath the Roberts family was coming ever closer.\par
\ldblquote C\rquote mon,\rdblquote  said Fred, grabbing Ginny\rquote s hand and starting to pull her toward the wood. Harry, Ron, Hermione, and George fol\-lowed. They all looked back as they reached the trees. The crowd beneath the Roberts family was larger than ever; they could see the Ministry wizards trying to get through it to the hooded wizards in the center, but they were having great difficulty. It looked as though they were scared to perform any spell that might make the Roberts family fall.\par
The colored lanterns that had lit the path to the stadium had been extinguished. Dark figures were blundering through the trees; children were crying; anxious shouts and panicked voices were re\-verberating around them in the cold night air. Harry felt himself being pushed hither and thither by people whose faces he could not see. Then he heard Ron yell with pain.\par
\ldblquote What happened?\rdblquote  said Hermione anxiously, stopping so abruptly that Harry walked into her. \ldblquote Ron, where are you? Oh this is stupid \emdash  \i lumos\i0 !\rdblquote\par
She illuminated her wand and directed its narrow beam across the path. Ron was lying sprawled on the ground.\par
\ldblquote Tripped over a tree root,\rdblquote  he said angrily, getting to his feet again.\par
\ldblquote Well, with feet that size, hard not to,\rdblquote  said a drawling voice from behind them.\par
Harry, Ron, and Hermione turned sharply. Draco Malfoy was standing alone nearby, leaning against a tree, looking utterly re\-laxed. His arms folded, he seemed to have been watching the scene at the campsite through a gap in the trees.\par
Ron told Malfoy to do something that Harry knew he would never have dared say in front of Mrs. Weasley\par
\ldblquote Language, Weasley,\rdblquote  said Malfoy, his pale eyes glittering. \ldblquote Had\-n\rquote t you better be hurrying along, now? You wouldn\rquote t like \i her\i0  spot\-ted, would you?\rdblquote\par
He nodded at Hermione, and at the same moment, a blast like a bomb sounded from the campsite, and a flash of green light mo\-mentarily lit the trees around them.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s that supposed to mean?\rdblquote  said Hermione defiantly.\par
\ldblquote Granger, they\rquote re after \i Muggles,\i0\rdblquote  said Malfoy. \ldblquote D\rquote you want to be showing off your knickers in midair? Because if you do, hang around \'85 they\rquote re moving this way, and it would give us all a laugh.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hermione\rquote s a witch,\rdblquote  Harry snarled.\par
\ldblquote Have it your own way, Potter,\rdblquote  said Malfoy, grinning mali\-ciously. \ldblquote If you think they can\rquote t spot a Mudblood, stay where you are.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You watch your mouth!\rdblquote  shouted Ron. Everybody present knew that \ldblquote Mudblood\rdblquote  was a very offensive term for a witch or wizard of Muggle parentage.\par
\ldblquote Never mind, Ron,\rdblquote  said Hermione quickly, seizing Ron\rquote s arm to restrain him as he took a step toward Malfoy.\par
There came a bang from the other side of the trees that was louder than anything they had heard. Several people nearby screamed. Malfoy chuckled softly.\par
\ldblquote Scare easily, don\rquote t they?\rdblquote  he said lazily. \ldblquote I suppose your daddy told you all to hide? What\rquote s he up to \emdash  trying to rescue the Muggles?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Where\rquote re \i your\i0  parents?\rdblquote  said Harry, his temper rising. \ldblquote Out there wearing masks, are they?\rdblquote\par
Malfoy turned his face to Harry, still smiling.\par
\ldblquote Well \'85 if they were, I wouldn\rquote t be likely to tell you, would I, Potter?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh come on,\rdblquote  said Hermione, with a disgusted look at Malfoy, \ldblquote let\rquote s go and find the others.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Keep that big bushy head down, Granger,\rdblquote  sneered Malfoy.\par
\ldblquote Come \i on,\i0\rdblquote  Hermione repeated, and she pulled Harry and Ron up the path again.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll bet you anything his dad \i is\i0  one of that masked lot!\rdblquote  said Ron hotly.\par
\ldblquote Well, with any luck, the Ministry will catch him!\rdblquote  said Her\-mione fervently. \ldblquote Oh I can\rquote t believe this. Where have the others got to?\rdblquote\par
Fred, George, and Ginny were nowhere to be seen, though the path was packed with plenty of other people, all looking nervously over their shoulders toward the commotion back at the campsite. A huddle of teenagers in pajamas was arguing vociferously a little way along the path. When they saw Harry, Ron, and Hermione, a girl with thick curly hair turned and said quickly, \ldblquote\i O\'f9 est Madame Maxime? Nous l\rquote avons perdue\i0  \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  what?\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Oh \'85\rdblquote  The girl who had spoken turned her back on him, and as they walked on they distinctly heard her say, \ldblquote  \rquote Ogwarts.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Beauxbatons,\rdblquote  muttered Hermione.\par
\ldblquote Sorry?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote They must go to Beauxbatons,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote You know \'85 Beauxbatons Academy of Magic \'85 I read about it in \i An Appraisal of Magical Education in Europe.\i0\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh \'85 yeah \'85 right,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Fred and George can\rquote t have gone that far,\rdblquote  said Ron, pulling out his wand, lighting it like Hermione\rquote s, and squinting up the path. Harry dug in the pockets of his jacket for his own wand \emdash  but it wasn\rquote t there. The only thing he could find was his Omnioculars.\par
\ldblquote Ah, no, I don\rquote t believe it \'85 I\rquote ve lost my wand!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re kidding!\rdblquote\par
Ron and Hermione raised their wands high enough to spread the narrow beams of light farther on the ground; Harry looked all around him, but his wand was nowhere to be seen.\par
\ldblquote Maybe it\rquote s back in the tent,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Maybe it fell out of your pocket when we were running?\rdblquote  Hermione suggested anxiously.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote maybe \'85\rdblquote\par
He usually kept his wand with him at all times in the wizarding world, and finding himself without it in the midst of a scene like this made him feel very vulnerable.\par
A rustling noise nearby made all three of them jump. Winky the house-elf was fighting her way out of a clump of bushes nearby. She was moving in a most peculiar fashion, apparently with great diffi\-culty; it was as though someone invisible were trying to hold her back.\par
\ldblquote There is bad wizards about!\rdblquote  she squeaked distractedly as she leaned forward and labored to keep running. \ldblquote People high \emdash  high in the air! Winky is getting out of the way!\rdblquote\par
And she disappeared into the trees on the other side of the path, panting and squeaking as she fought the force that was restraining her.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s up with her?\rdblquote  said Ron, looking curiously after Winky. \ldblquote Why can\rquote t she run properly?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Bet she didn\rquote t ask permission to hide,\rdblquote  said Harry. He was thinking of Dobby: Every time he had tried to do something the Malfoys wouldn\rquote t like, the house-elf had been forced to start beat\-ing himself up.\par
\ldblquote You know, house-elves get a \i very\i0  raw deal!\rdblquote  said Hermione in\-dignantly. \ldblquote It\rquote s slavery, that\rquote s what it is! That Mr. Crouch made her go up to the top of the stadium, and she was terrified, and he\rquote s got her bewitched so she can\rquote t even run when they start trampling tents! Why doesn\rquote t anyone \i do\i0  something about it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, the elves are happy, aren\rquote t they?\rdblquote  Ron said. \ldblquote You heard old Winky back at the match \'85 \lquote House-elves is not supposed to have fun\rquote  \'85 that\rquote s what she likes, being bossed around. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s people like \i you,\i0  Ron,\rdblquote  Hermione began hotly, \ldblquote who prop up rotten and unjust systems, just because they\rquote re too lazy to \emdash\rdblquote\par
Another loud bang echoed from the edge of the wood.\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s just keep moving, shall we?\rdblquote  said Ron, and Harry saw him glance edgily at Hermione. Perhaps there was truth in what Malfoy had said; perhaps Hermione \i was\i0  in more danger than they were. They set off again, Harry still searching his pockets, even though he knew his wand wasn\rquote t there.\par
They followed the dark path deeper into the wood, still keeping an eye out for Fred, George, and Ginny. They passed a group of goblins who were cackling over a sack of gold that they had un\-doubtedly won betting on the match, and who seemed quite unperturbed by the trouble at the campsite. Farther still along the path, they walked into a patch of silvery light, and when they looked through the trees, they saw three tall and beautiful veela standing in a clearing, surrounded by a gaggle of young wizards, all of whom were talking very loudly.\par
\ldblquote I pull down about a hundred sacks of Galleons a year!\rdblquote  one of them shouted. \ldblquote I\rquote m a dragon killer for the Committee for the Dis\-posal of Dangerous Creatures.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, you\rquote re not!\rdblquote  yelled his friend. \ldblquote You\rquote re a dishwasher at the Leaky Cauldron. \'85 but I\rquote m a vampire hunter, I\rquote ve killed about ninety so far \emdash\rdblquote\par
A third young wizard, whose pimples were visible even by the dim, silvery light of the veela, now cut in, \ldblquote I\rquote m about to become the youngest ever Minister of Magic, I am.\rdblquote\par
Harry snorted with laughter. He recognized the pimply wizard: His name was Stan Shunpike, and he was in fact a conductor on the triple-decker Knight Bus. He turned to tell Ron this, but Ron\rquote s face had gone oddly slack, and next second Ron was yelling, \ldblquote Did I tell you I\rquote ve invented a broomstick that\rquote ll reach Jupiter?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i Honestly\i0 !\rdblquote  said Hermione, and she and Harry grabbed Ron firmly by the arms, wheeled him around, and marched him away. By the time the sounds of the veela and their admirers had faded completely, they were in the very heart of the wood. They seemed to be alone now; everything was much quieter.\par
Harry looked around. \ldblquote I reckon we can just wait here, you know. We\rquote ll hear anyone coming a mile off.\rdblquote\par
The words were hardly out of his mouth, when Ludo Bagman emerged from behind a tree right ahead of them.\par
Even by the feeble light of the two wands, Harry could see that a great change had come over Bagman. He no longer looked buoy\-ant and rosy-faced; there was no more spring in his step. He looked very white and strained.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s that?\rdblquote  he said, blinking down at them, trying to make out their faces. \ldblquote What are you doing in here, all alone?\rdblquote\par
They looked at one another, surprised.\par
\ldblquote Well \emdash  there\rquote s a sort of riot going on,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
Bagman stared at him.\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote At the campsite \'85 some people have got hold of a family of Muggles. \'85\rdblquote\par
Bagman swore loudly.\par
\ldblquote Damn them!\rdblquote  he said, looking quite distracted, and without another word, he Disapparated with a small \i pop\i0 !\par
\ldblquote Not exactly on top of things, Mr. Bagman, is he?\rdblquote  said Hermione, frowning.\par
\ldblquote He was a great Beater, though,\rdblquote  said Ron, leading the way off the path into a small clearing, and sitting down on a patch of dry grass at the foot of a tree. \ldblquote The Wimbourne Wasps won the league three times in a row while he was with them.\rdblquote\par
He took his small figure of Krum out of his pocket, set it down on the ground, and watched it walk around. Like the real Krum, the model was slightly duck-footed and round-shouldered, much less impressive on his splayed feet than on his broomstick. Harry was listening for noise from the campsite. Everything seemed much quieter; perhaps the riot was over.\par
\ldblquote I hope the others are okay,\rdblquote  said Hermione after a while.\par
\ldblquote They\rquote ll be fine,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Imagine if your dad catches Lucius Malfoy,\rdblquote  said Harry, sitting down next to Ron and watching the small figure of Krum slouch\-ing over the fallen leaves. \ldblquote He\rquote s always said he\rquote d like to get some\-thing on him.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote d wipe the smirk off old Draco\rquote s face, all right,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Those poor Muggles, though,\rdblquote  said Hermione nervously. \ldblquote What if they can\rquote t get them down?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They will,\rdblquote  said Ron reassuringly. \ldblquote They\rquote ll find a way.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mad, though, to do something like that when the whole Min\-istry of Magic\rquote s out here tonight!\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote I mean, how do they expect to get away with it? Do you think they\rquote ve been drink\-ing, or are they just \emdash\rdblquote\par
But she broke off abruptly and looked over her shoulder. Harry and Ron looked quickly around too. It sounded as though some\-one was staggering toward their clearing. They waited, listening to the sounds of the uneven steps behind the dark trees. But the foot\-steps came to a sudden halt.\par
\ldblquote Hello?\rdblquote  called Harry.\par
There was silence. Harry got to his feet and peered around the tree. It was too dark to see very far, but he could sense somebody standing just beyond the range of his vision.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  he said.\par
And then, without warning, the silence was rent by a voice un\-like any they had heard in the wood; and it uttered, not a panicked shout, but what sounded like a spell.\par
\ldblquote\i MORSMORDRE\i0 !\rdblquote\par
And something vast, green, and glittering erupted from the patch of darkness Harry\rquote s eyes had been struggling to penetrate; it flew up over the treetops and into the sky.\par
\ldblquote What the \emdash  ?\rdblquote  gasped Ron as he sprang to his feet again, star\-ing up at the thing that had appeared.\par
For a split second, Harry thought it was another leprechaun for\-mation. Then he realized that it was a colossal skull, comprised of what looked like emerald stars, with a serpent protruding from its mouth like a tongue. As they watched, it rose higher and higher, blazing in a haze of greenish smoke, etched against the black sky like a new constellation.\par
Suddenly, the wood all around them erupted with screams. Harry didn\rquote t understand why, but the only possible cause was the sudden appearance of the skull, which had now risen high enough to illuminate the entire wood like some grisly neon sign. He scanned the darkness for the person who had conjured the skull, but he couldn\rquote t see anyone.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  he called again.\par
\ldblquote Harry, come on, \i move\i0 !\rdblquote  Hermione had seized the collar of his jacket and was tugging him backward.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote  Harry said, startled to see her face so white and terrified.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s the Dark Mark, Harry!\rdblquote  Hermione moaned, pulling him as hard as she could. \ldblquote You-Know-Who\rquote s sign!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i Voldemort\rquote s\i0  \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Harry, come \i on\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Harry turned \emdash  Ron was hurriedly scooping up his miniature Krum \emdash  the three of them started across the clearing \emdash  but be\-fore they had taken a few hurried steps, a series of popping noises announced the arrival of twenty wizards, appearing from thin air, surrounding them.\par
Harry whirled around, and in an instant, he registered one fact: Each of these wizards had his wand out, and every wand was point\-ing right at himself, Ron, and Hermione.\par
Without pausing to think, he yelled, \ldblquote DUCK!\rdblquote\par
He seized the other two and pulled them down onto the ground.\par
\ldblquote\i STUPEFY\i0 !\rdblquote  roared twenty voices \emdash  there was a blinding series of flashes and Harry felt the hair on his head ripple as though a powerful wind had swept the clearing. Raising his head a fraction of an inch he saw jets of fiery red light flying over them from the wizards\rquote  wands, crossing one another, bouncing off tree trunks, re\-bounding into the darkness \emdash\par
\ldblquote Stop!\rdblquote  yelled a voice he recognized. \ldblquote STOP! \i That\rquote s my son\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s hair stopped blowing about. He raised his head a little higher. The wizard in front of him had lowered his wand. He rolled over and saw Mr. Weasley striding toward them, looking terrified.\par
\ldblquote Ron \emdash  Harry\rdblquote  \emdash  his voice sounded shaky \emdash  \ldblquote Hermione \emdash  are you all right?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Out of the way, Arthur,\rdblquote  said a cold, curt voice.\par
It was Mr. Crouch. He and the other Ministry wizards were clos\-ing in on them. Harry got to his feet to face them. Mr. Crouch\rquote s face was taut with rage.\par
\ldblquote Which of you did it?\rdblquote  he snapped, his sharp eyes darting be\-tween them. \ldblquote Which of you conjured the Dark Mark?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We didn\rquote t do that!\rdblquote  said Harry, gesturing up at the skull.\par
\ldblquote We didn\rquote t do anything!\rdblquote  said Ron, who was rubbing his elbow and looking indignantly at his father. \ldblquote What did you want to at\-tack us for?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do not lie, sir!\rdblquote  shouted Mr. Crouch. His wand was still point\-ing directly at Ron, and his eyes were popping \emdash  he looked slightly mad. \ldblquote You have been discovered at the scene of the crime!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Barty,\rdblquote  whispered a witch in a long woolen dressing gown, \ldblquote they\rquote re kids, Barty, they\rquote d never have been able to \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Where did the Mark come from, you three?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quickly.\par
\ldblquote Over there,\rdblquote  said Hermione shakily, pointing at the place where they had heard the voice. \ldblquote There was someone behind the trees \'85 they shouted words \emdash  an incantation \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, stood over there, did they?\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch, turning his popping eyes on Hermione now, disbelief etched all over his face. \ldblquote Said an incantation, did they? You seem very well informed about how that Mark is summoned, missy \emdash\rdblquote\par
But none of the Ministry wizards apart from Mr. Crouch seemed to think it remotely likely that Harry, Ron, or Hermione had conjured the skull; on the contrary, at Hermione\rquote s words, they had all raised their wands again and were pointing in the direction she had indicated, squinting through the dark trees.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re too late,\rdblquote  said the witch in the woolen dressing gown, shaking her head. \ldblquote They\rquote ll have Disapparated.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t think so,\rdblquote  said a wizard with a scrubby brown beard. It was Amos Diggory, Cedric\rquote s father. \ldblquote Our Stunners went right through those trees. \'85 There\rquote s a good chance we got them. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Amos, be careful!\rdblquote  said a few of the wizards warningly as Mr. Diggory squared his shoulders, raised his wand, marched across the clearing, and disappeared into the darkness. Hermione watched him vanish with her hands over her mouth.\par
A few seconds later, they heard Mr. Diggory shout.\par
\ldblquote Yes! We got them! There\rquote s someone here! Unconscious! It\rquote s \emdash  but \emdash  blimey \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve got someone?\rdblquote  shouted Mr. Crouch, sounding highly disbelieving. \ldblquote Who? Who is it?\rdblquote\par
They heard snapping twigs, the rustling of leaves, and then crunching footsteps as Mr. Diggory reemerged from behind the trees. He was carrying a tiny, limp figure in his arms. Harry recog\-nized the tea towel at once. It was Winky.\par
Mr. Crouch did not move or speak as Mr. Diggory deposited his elf on the ground at his feet. The other Ministry wizards were all staring at Mr. Crouch. For a few seconds Crouch remained trans\-fixed, his eyes blazing in his white face as he stared down at Winky. Then he appeared to come to life again.\par
\ldblquote This \emdash  cannot \emdash  be,\rdblquote  he said jerkily. \ldblquote No \emdash\rdblquote\par
He moved quickly around Mr. Diggory and strode off toward the place where he had found Winky.\par
\ldblquote No point, Mr. Crouch,\rdblquote  Mr. Diggory called after him. \ldblquote There\rquote s no one else there.\rdblquote\par
But Mr. Crouch did not seem prepared to take his word for it. They could hear him moving around and the rustling of leaves as he pushed the bushes aside, searching.\par
\ldblquote Bit embarrassing,\rdblquote  Mr. Diggory said grimly, looking down at Winky\rquote s unconscious form. \ldblquote Barty Crouch\rquote s house-elf \'85 I mean to say \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Come off it, Amos,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quietly, \ldblquote you don\rquote t seriously think it was the elf? The Dark Mark\rquote s a wizard\rquote s sign. It requires a wand.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory, \ldblquote and she \i had\i0  a wand.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i What\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Here, look.\rdblquote  Mr. Diggory held up a wand and showed it to Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Had it in her hand. So that\rquote s clause three of the Code of Wand Use broken, for a start. \i No non-human creature is permitted to carry or use a wand.\i0\rdblquote\par
Just then there was another \i pop,\i0  and Ludo Bagman Apparated right next to Mr. Weasley. Looking breathless and disorientated, he spun on the spot, goggling upward at the emerald-green skull.\par
\ldblquote The Dark Mark!\rdblquote  he panted, almost trampling Winky as he turned inquiringly to his colleagues. \ldblquote Who did it? Did you get them? Barty! What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote\par
Mr. Crouch had returned empty-handed. His face was still ghostly white, and his hands and his toothbrush mustache were both twitching.\par
\ldblquote Where have you been, Barty?\rdblquote  said Bagman. \ldblquote Why weren\rquote t you at the match? Your elf was saving you a seat too \emdash  gulping gar\-goyles!\rdblquote  Bagman had just noticed Winky lying at his feet. \ldblquote What happened to \i her\i0 ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I have been busy, Ludo,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch, still talking in the same jerky fashion, barely moving his lips. \ldblquote And my elf has been stunned.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Stunned? By you lot, you mean? But why \emdash  ?\rdblquote\par
Comprehension dawned suddenly on Bagman\rquote s round, shiny face; he looked up at the skull, down at Winky, and then at Mr. Crouch.\par
\ldblquote\i No\i0 !\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Winky? Conjure the Dark Mark? She wouldn\rquote t know how! She\rquote d need a wand, for a start!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And she had one,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory. \ldblquote I found her holding one, Ludo. If it\rquote s all right with you, Mr. Crouch, I think we should hear what she\rquote s got to say for herself.\rdblquote\par
Crouch gave no sign that he had heard Mr. Diggory, but Mr. Diggory seemed to take his silence for assent. He raised his own wand, pointed it at Winky, and said, \ldblquote\i Rennervate\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Winky stirred feebly. Her great brown eyes opened and she blinked several times in a bemused sort of way. Watched by the silent wizards, she raised herself shakily into a sitting position. She caught sight of Mr. Diggory\rquote s feet, and slowly, tremulously, raised her eyes to stare up into his face; then, more slowly still, she looked up into the sky. Harry could see the floating skull reflected twice in her enormous, glassy eyes. She gave a gasp, looked wildly around the crowded clearing, and burst into terrified sobs.\par
\ldblquote Elf!\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory sternly. \ldblquote Do you know who I am? I\rquote m a member of the Department for the Regulation and Control of Magical Creatures!\rdblquote\par
Winky began to rock backward and forward on the ground, her breath coming in sharp bursts. Harry was reminded forcibly of Dobby in his moments of terrified disobedience.\par
\ldblquote As you see, elf, the Dark Mark was conjured here a short while ago,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory. \ldblquote And you were discovered moments later, right beneath it! An explanation, if you please!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I \emdash  I \emdash  I is not doing it, sir!\rdblquote  Winky gasped. \ldblquote I is not know\-ing how, sir!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You were found with a wand in your hand!\rdblquote  barked Mr. Dig\-gory, brandishing it in front of her. And as the wand caught the green light that was filling the clearing from the skull above, Harry recognized it.\par
\ldblquote Hey \emdash  that\rquote s mine!\rdblquote  he said.\par
Everyone in the clearing looked at him.\par
\ldblquote Excuse me?\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory, incredulously.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s my wand!\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I dropped it!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You dropped it?\rdblquote  repeated Mr. Diggory in disbelief. \ldblquote Is this a confession? You threw it aside after you conjured the Mark?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Amos, think who you\rquote re talking to!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, very an\-grily. \ldblquote Is \i Harry Potter\i0  likely to conjure the Dark Mark?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  of course not,\rdblquote  mumbled Mr. Diggory. \ldblquote Sorry \'85 car\-ried away \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I didn\rquote t drop it there, anyway,\rdblquote  said Harry, jerking his thumb toward the trees beneath the skull. \ldblquote I missed it right after we got into the wood.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory, his eyes hardening as he turned to look at Winky again, cowering at his feet. \ldblquote You found this wand, eh, elf? And you picked it up and thought you\rquote d have some fun with it, did you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I is not doing magic with it, sir!\rdblquote  squealed Winky, tears stream\-ing down the sides of her squashed and bulbous nose. \ldblquote I is \'85 I is \'85 I is just picking it up, sir! I is not making the Dark Mark, sir, I is not knowing how!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t her!\rdblquote  said Hermione. She looked very nervous, speak\-ing up in front of all these Ministry wizards, yet determined all the same. \ldblquote Winky\rquote s got a squeaky little voice, and the voice we heard doing the incantation was much deeper!\rdblquote  She looked around at Harry and Ron, appealing for their support. \ldblquote It didn\rquote t sound any\-thing like Winky, did it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, shaking his head. \ldblquote It definitely didn\rquote t sound like an elf.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, it was a human voice,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Well, we\rquote ll soon see,\rdblquote  growled Mr. Diggory, looking unim\-pressed. \ldblquote There\rquote s a simple way of discovering the last spell a wand performed, elf, did you know that?\rdblquote\par
Winky trembled and shook her head frantically, her ears flap\-ping, as Mr. Diggory raised his own wand again and placed it tip to tip with Harry\rquote s.\par
\ldblquote\i Prior Incantato\i0 !\rdblquote  roared Mr. Diggory.\par
Harry heard Hermione gasp, horrified, as a gigantic serpent-tongued skull erupted from the point where the two wands met, but it was a mere shadow of the green skull high above them; it looked as though it were made of thick gray smoke: the ghost of a spell.\par
\ldblquote\i Deletrius\i0 !\rdblquote  Mr. Diggory shouted, and the smoky skull vanished in a wisp of smoke.\par
\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory with a kind of savage triumph, looking down upon Winky, who was still shaking convulsively.\par
\ldblquote I is not doing it!\rdblquote  she squealed, her eyes rolling in terror. \ldblquote I is not, I is not, I is not knowing how! I is a good elf, I isn\rquote t using wands, I isn\rquote t knowing how!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i You\rquote ve been caught red-handed, elf\i0 !\rdblquote  Mr. Diggory roared. \ldblquote\i Caught with the guilty wand in your hand\i0 !\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Amos,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley loudly, \ldblquote think about it \'85 precious few wizards know how to do that spell. \'85 Where would she have learned it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Perhaps Amos is suggesting,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch, cold anger in every syllable, \ldblquote that I routinely teach my servants to conjure the Dark Mark?\rdblquote\par
There was a deeply unpleasant silence. Amos Diggory looked horrified. \ldblquote Mr. Crouch \'85 not \'85 not at all \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You have now come very close to accusing the two people in this clearing who are \i least\i0  likely to conjure that Mark!\rdblquote  barked Mr. Crouch. \ldblquote Harry Potter \emdash  and myself! I suppose you are familiar with the boy\rquote s story, Amos?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course \emdash  everyone knows \emdash\rdblquote  muttered Mr. Diggory, look\-ing highly discomforted.\par
\ldblquote And I trust you remember the many proofs I have given, over a long career, that I despise and detest the Dark Arts and those who practice them?\rdblquote  Mr. Crouch shouted, his eyes bulging again.\par
\ldblquote Mr. Crouch, I \emdash  I never suggested you had anything to do with it!\rdblquote  Amos Diggory muttered again, now reddening behind his scrubby brown beard.\par
\ldblquote If you accuse my elf, you accuse me, Diggory!\rdblquote  shouted Mr. Crouch. \ldblquote Where else would she have learned to conjure it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She \emdash  she might\rquote ve picked it up anywhere \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Precisely, Amos,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote\i She might have picked it up anywhere. \'85\i0  Winky?\rdblquote  he said kindly, turning to the elf, but she flinched as though he too was shouting at her. \ldblquote Where exactly did you find Harry\rquote s wand?\rdblquote\par
Winky was twisting the hem of her tea towel so violently that it was fraying beneath her fingers.\par
\ldblquote I \emdash  I is finding it \'85 finding it there, sir. \'85\rdblquote  she whispered, \ldblquote there \'85 in the trees, sir. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You see, Amos?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Whoever conjured the Mark could have Disapparated right after they\rquote d done it, leaving Harry\rquote s wand behind. A clever thing to do, not using their own wand, which could have betrayed them. And Winky here had the misfortune to come across the wand moments later and pick it up.\par
\ldblquote But then, she\rquote d have been only a few feet away from the real culprit!\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory impatiently. \ldblquote Elf? Did you see anyone?\rdblquote\par
Winky began to tremble worse than ever. Her giant eyes flick\-ered from Mr. Diggory, to Ludo Bagman, and onto Mr. Crouch. Then she gulped and said, \ldblquote I is seeing no one, sir \'85 no one \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Amos,\rdblquote  said Mr. Crouch curtly, \ldblquote I am fully aware that, in the ordinary course of events, you would want to take Winky into your department for questioning. I ask you, however, to allow me to deal with her.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Diggory looked as though he didn\rquote t think much of this sug\-gestion at all, but it was clear to Harry that Mr. Crouch was such an important member of the Ministry that he did not dare refuse him.\par
\ldblquote You may rest assured that she will be punished,\rdblquote  Mr. Crouch added coldly.\par
\ldblquote M-m-master \'85\rdblquote  Winky stammered, looking up at Mr. Crouch, her eyes brimming with tears. \ldblquote M-m-master, p-p-please \'85\rdblquote\par
Mr. Crouch stared back, his face somehow sharpened, each line upon it more deeply etched. There was no pity in his gaze.\par
\ldblquote Winky has behaved tonight in a manner I would not have be\-lieved possible,\rdblquote  he said slowly. \ldblquote I told her to remain in the tent. I told her to stay there while I went to sort out the trouble. And I find that she disobeyed me. \i This means clothes.\i0\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  shrieked Winky, prostrating herself at Mr. Crouch\rquote s feet. \ldblquote No, master! Not clothes, not clothes!\rdblquote\par
Harry knew that the only way to turn a house-elf free was to pre\-sent it with proper garments. It was pitiful to see the way Winky clutched at her tea towel as she sobbed over Mr. Crouch\rquote s feet.\par
\ldblquote But she was frightened!\rdblquote  Hermione burst out angrily, glaring at Mr. Crouch. \ldblquote Your elf\rquote s scared of heights, and those wizards in masks were levitating people! You can\rquote t blame her for wanting to get out of their way!\rdblquote\par
Mr. Crouch took a step backward, freeing himself from contact with the elf, whom he was surveying as though she were something filthy and rotten that was contaminating his over-shined shoes.\par
\ldblquote I have no use for a house-elf who disobeys me,\rdblquote  he said coldly, looking over at Hermione. \ldblquote I have no use for a servant who forgets what is due to her master, and to her master\rquote s reputation.\rdblquote\par
Winky was crying so hard that her sobs echoed around the clear\-ing. There was a very nasty silence, which was ended by Mr. Weasley, who said quietly, \ldblquote Well, I think I\rquote ll take my lot back to the tent, if nobody\rquote s got any objections. Amos, that wand\rquote s told us all it can \emdash  if Harry could have it back, please \emdash\rdblquote\par
Mr. Diggory handed Harry his wand and Harry pocketed it.\par
\ldblquote Come on, you three,\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley said quietly. But Hermione didn\rquote t seem to want to move; her eyes were still upon the sobbing elf. \ldblquote Hermione!\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley said, more urgently. She turned and followed Harry and Ron out of the clearing and off through the trees.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s going to happen to Winky?\rdblquote  said Hermione, the mo\-ment they had left the clearing.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote The way they were treating her!\rdblquote  said Hermione furiously. \ldblquote Mr. Diggory, calling her \lquote elf\rquote  all the time \'85 and Mr. Crouch! He knows she didn\rquote t do it and he\rquote s still going to sack her! He didn\rquote t care how frightened she\rquote d been, or how upset she was \emdash  it was like she wasn\rquote t even human!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, she\rquote s not,\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
Hermione rounded on him.\par
\ldblquote That doesn\rquote t mean she hasn\rquote t got feelings, Ron. It\rquote s disgusting the way \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hermione, I agree with you,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quickly, beck\-oning her on, \ldblquote but now is not the time to discuss elf rights. I want to get back to the tent as fast as we can. What happened to the others?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We lost them in the dark,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Dad, why was everyone so uptight about that skull thing?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll explain everything back at the tent,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley tensely.\par
But when they reached the edge of the wood, their progress was impeded. A large crowd of frightened-looking witches and wizards was congregated there, and when they saw Mr. Weasley coming to\-ward them, many of them surged forward.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s going on in there?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Who conjured it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Arthur \emdash  it\rquote s not \emdash  \i Him\i0 ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course it\rquote s not Him,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley impatiently. \ldblquote We don\rquote t know who it was; it looks like they Disapparated. Now excuse me, please, I want to get to bed.\rdblquote\par
He led Harry, Ron, and Hermione through the crowd and back into the campsite. All was quiet now; there was no sign of the masked wizards, though several ruined tents were still smoking.\par
Charlie\rquote s head was poking out of the boys\rquote  tent.\par
\ldblquote Dad, what\rquote s going on?\rdblquote  he called through the dark. \ldblquote Fred, George, and Ginny got back okay, but the others \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve got them here,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, bending down and en\-tering the tent. Harry, Ron, and Hermione entered after him.\par
Bill was sitting at the small kitchen table, holding a bedsheet to his arm, which was bleeding profusely. Charlie had a large rip in his shirt, and Percy was sporting a bloody nose. Fred, George, and Ginny looked unhurt, though shaken.\par
\ldblquote Did you get them, Dad?\rdblquote  said Bill sharply. \ldblquote The person who conjured the Mark?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote We found Barty Crouch\rquote s elf holding Harry\rquote s wand, but we\rquote re none the wiser about who actually con\-jured the Mark.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i What\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Bill, Charlie, and Percy together.\par
\ldblquote Harry\rquote s wand?\rdblquote  said Fred.\par
\ldblquote\i Mr. Crouch\rquote s elf\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Percy, sounding thunderstruck.\par
With some assistance from Harry, Ron, and Hermione, Mr. Weasley explained what had happened in the woods. When they had finished their story, Percy swelled indignantly.\par
\ldblquote Well, Mr. Crouch is quite right to get rid of an elf like that!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Running away when he\rquote d expressly told her not to \'85 em\-barrassing him in front of the whole Ministry \'85 how would that have looked, if she\rquote d been brought up in front of the Department for the Regulation and Control \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She didn\rquote t do anything \emdash  she was just in the wrong place at the wrong time!\rdblquote  Hermione snapped at Percy, who looked very taken aback. Hermione had always got on fairly well with Percy \emdash  better, indeed, than any of the others.\par
\ldblquote Hermione, a wizard in Mr. Crouch\rquote s position can\rquote t afford a house-elf who\rquote s going to run amok with a wand!\rdblquote  said Percy pompously, recovering himself.\par
\ldblquote She didn\rquote t run amok!\rdblquote  shouted Hermione. \ldblquote She just picked it up off the ground!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Look, can someone just explain what that skull thing was?\rdblquote  said Ron impatiently. \ldblquote It wasn\rquote t hurting anyone. \'85 Why\rquote s it such a big deal?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I told you, it\rquote s You-Know-Who\rquote s symbol, Ron,\rdblquote  said Hermione, before anyone else could answer. \ldblquote I read about it in \i The Rise and Fall of the Dark Arts.\i0\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And it hasn\rquote t been seen for thirteen years,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quietly. \ldblquote Of course people panicked \'85 it was almost like seeing You-Know-Who back again.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t get it,\rdblquote  said Ron, frowning. \ldblquote I mean \'85 it\rquote s still only a shape in the sky. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ron, You-Know-Who and his followers sent the Dark Mark into the air whenever they killed,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote The terror it inspired \'85 you have no idea, you\rquote re too young. Just picture com\-ing home and finding the Dark Mark hovering over your house, and knowing what you\rquote re about to find inside. \'85\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley winced. \ldblquote Everyone\rquote s worst fear \'85 the very worst \'85\rdblquote\par
There was silence for a moment. Then Bill, removing the sheet from his arm to check on his cut, said, \ldblquote Well, it didn\rquote t help us tonight, whoever conjured it. It scared the Death Eaters away the moment they saw it. They all Disapparated before we\rquote d got near enough to unmask any of them. We caught the Robertses before they hit the ground, though. They\rquote re having their memories modi\-fied right now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Death Eaters?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote What are Death Eaters?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s what You-Know-Who\rquote s supporters called themselves,\rdblquote  said Bill. \ldblquote I think we saw what\rquote s left of them tonight \emdash  the ones who managed to keep themselves out of Azkaban, anyway.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We can\rquote t prove it was them, Bill,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Though it probably was,\rdblquote  he added hopelessly.\par
\ldblquote Yeah, I bet it was!\rdblquote  said Ron suddenly. \ldblquote Dad, we met Draco Malfoy in the woods, and he as good as told us his dad was one of those nutters in masks! And we all know the Malfoys were right in with You-Know-Who!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But what were Voldemort\rquote s supporters \emdash\rdblquote  Harry began. Everybody flinched \emdash  like most of the wizarding world, the Weasleys always avoided saying Voldemort\rquote s name. \ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote What were You-Know-Who\rquote s supporters up to, levitating Muggles? I mean, what was the point?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The point?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley with a hollow laugh. \ldblquote Harry, that\rquote s their idea of fun. Half the Muggle killings back when You-Know-Who was in power were done for fun. I suppose they had a few drinks tonight and couldn\rquote t resist reminding us all that lots of them are still at large. A nice little reunion for them,\rdblquote  he finished disgustedly.\par
\ldblquote But if they \i were\i0  the Death Eaters, why did they Disapparate when they saw the Dark Mark?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote They\rquote d have been pleased to see it, wouldn\rquote t they?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Use your brains, Ron,\rdblquote  said Bill. \ldblquote If they really were Death Eaters, they worked very hard to keep out of Azkaban when You-Know-Who lost power, and told all sorts of lies about him forcing them to kill and torture people. I bet they\rquote d be even more fright\-ened than the rest of us to see him come back. They denied they\rquote d ever been involved with him when he lost his powers, and went back to their daily lives. \'85 I don\rquote t reckon he\rquote d be over-pleased with them, do you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So \'85 whoever conjured the Dark Mark \'85\rdblquote  said Hermione slowly, \ldblquote were they doing it to show support for the Death Eaters, or to scare them away?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Your guess is as good as ours, Hermione,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote But I\rquote ll tell you this \'85 it was only the Death Eaters who ever knew how to conjure it. I\rquote d be very surprised if the person who did it hadn\rquote t been a Death Eater once, even if they\rquote re not now. \'85 Listen, it\rquote s very late, and if your mother hears what\rquote s happened she\rquote ll be worried sick. We\rquote ll get a few more hours sleep and then try and get an early Portkey out of here.\rdblquote\par
Harry got back into his bunk with his head buzzing. He knew he ought to feel exhausted: It was nearly three in the morning, but he felt wide-awake \emdash  wide-awake, and worried.\par
Three days ago \emdash  it felt like much longer, but it had only been three days \emdash  he had awoken with his scar burning. And tonight, for the first time in thirteen years, Lord Voldemort\rquote s mark had ap\-peared in the sky. What did these things mean?\par
He thought of the letter he had written to Sirius before leaving Privet Drive. Would Sirius have gotten it yet? When would he reply? Harry lay looking up at the canvas, but no flying fantasies came to him now to ease him to sleep, and it was a long time after Charlie\rquote s snores filled the tent that Harry finally dozed off.\par
