Mr. Weasley woke them after only a few hours sleep. He used magic to pack up the tents, and they left the campsite as quickly as possible, passing Mr. Roberts at the door of his cottage. Mr. Roberts had a strange, dazed look about him, and he waved them off with a vague \ldblquote Merry Christmas.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote ll be all right,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley quietly as they marched off onto the moor. \ldblquote Sometimes, when a person\rquote s memory\rquote s modified, it makes him a bit disorientated for a while \'85 and that was a big thing they had to make him forget.\rdblquote\par
They heard urgent voices as they approached the spot where the Portkeys lay, and when they reached it, they found a great number of witches and wizards gathered around Basil, the keeper of the Portkeys, all clamoring to get away from the campsite as quickly as possible. Mr. Weasley had a hurried discussion with Basil; they joined the queue, and were able to take an old rubber tire back to Stoatshead Hill before the sun had really risen. They walked back through Ottery St. Catchpole and up the damp lane toward the Burrow in the dawn light, talking very little because they were so exhausted, and thinking longingly of their breakfast. As they rounded the corner and the Burrow came into view, a cry echoed along the lane.\par
\ldblquote Oh thank goodness, thank goodness!\rdblquote\par
Mrs. Weasley, who had evidently been waiting for them in the front yard, came running toward them, still wearing her bedroom slippers, her face pale and strained, a rolled-up copy of the \i Daily Prophet\i0  clutched in her hand.\par
\ldblquote Arthur \emdash  I\rquote ve been so worried \emdash  \i so worried\i0  \emdash\rdblquote\par
She flung her arms around Mr. Weasley\rquote s neck, and the \i Daily Prophet\i0  fell out of her limp hand onto the ground. Looking down, Harry saw the headline: \i SCENES OF TERROR AT THE QUID\-DITCH WORLD CUP\i0 , complete with a twinkling black-and-white photograph of the Dark Mark over the treetops.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re all right,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley muttered distractedly, releasing Mr. Weasley and staring around at them all with red eyes, \ldblquote you\rquote re alive. \'85 Oh \i boys\i0  \'85\rdblquote\par
And to everybody\rquote s surprise, she seized Fred and George and pulled them both into such a tight hug that their heads banged together.\par
\ldblquote\i Ouch\i0 ! Mum \emdash  you\rquote re strangling us \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I shouted at you before you left!\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley said, starting to sob. \ldblquote It\rquote s all I\rquote ve been thinking about! What if You-Know-Who had got you, and the last thing I ever said to you was that you didn\rquote t get enough O.W.L.s? Oh Fred \'85 George \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Come on, now, Molly, we\rquote re all perfectly okay,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley soothingly, prising her off the twins and leading her back toward the house. \ldblquote Bill,\rdblquote  he added in an undertone, \ldblquote pick up that paper, I want to see what it says. \'85\rdblquote\par
When they were all crammed into the tiny kitchen, and Hermione had made Mrs. Weasley a cup of very strong tea, into which Mr. Weasley insisted on pouring a shot of Ogdens Old Firewhiskey, Bill handed his father the newspaper. Mr. Weasley scanned the front page while Percy looked over his shoulder.\par
\ldblquote I knew it,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley heavily. \ldblquote\i Ministry blunders\i0  \'85 \i cul\-prits not apprehended\i0  \'85 \i lax security\i0  \'85 \i Dark wizards running unchecked\i0  \'85 \i national disgrace\i0  \'85 Who wrote this? Ah \'85 of course \'85 Rita Skeeter.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That woman\rquote s got it in for the Ministry of Magic!\rdblquote  said Percy furiously. \ldblquote Last week she was saying we\rquote re wasting our time quib\-bling about cauldron thickness, when we should be stamping out vampires! As if it wasn\rquote t \i specifically\i0  stated in paragraph twelve of the Guidelines for the Treatment of Non-Wizard Part-Humans \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do us a favor, Perce,\rdblquote  said Bill, yawning, \ldblquote and shut up.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m mentioned,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, his eyes widening behind his glasses as he reached the bottom of the \i Daily Prophet\i0  article.\par
\ldblquote Where?\rdblquote  spluttered Mrs. Weasley, choking on her tea and whiskey. \ldblquote If I\rquote d seen that, I\rquote d have known you were alive!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not by name,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Listen to this: \lquote\i If the terrified wizards and witches who waited breathlessly for news at the edge of the wood expected reassurance from the Ministry of Magic, they were sadly disappointed. A Ministry official emerged some time after the appear\-ance of the Dark Mark alleging that nobody had been hurt, but refus\-ing to give any more information. Whether this statement will be enough to quash the rumors that several bodies were removed from the woods an hour later, remains to be seen\i0 .\rquote  Oh really,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley in exasperation, handing the paper to Percy. \ldblquote Nobody \i was\i0  hurt. What was I supposed to say? \i Rumors that several bodies were re\-moved from the woods\i0  \'85 well, there certainly will be rumors now she\rquote s printed that.\rdblquote\par
He heaved a deep sigh. \ldblquote Molly, I\rquote m going to have to go into the office; this is going to take some smoothing over.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll come with you, Father,\rdblquote  said Percy importantly. \ldblquote Mr. Crouch will need all hands on deck. And I can give him my caul\-dron report in person.\rdblquote\par
He bustled out of the kitchen. Mrs. Weasley looked most upset.\par
\ldblquote Arthur, you\rquote re supposed to be on holiday! This hasn\rquote t got any\-thing to do with your office; surely they can handle this without you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve got to go, Molly,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote I\rquote ve made things worse. I\rquote ll just change into my robes and I\rquote ll be off. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mrs. Weasley,\rdblquote  said Harry suddenly, unable to contain himself, \ldblquote Hedwig hasn\rquote t arrived with a letter for me, has she?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hedwig, dear?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley distractedly. \ldblquote No \'85 no, there hasn\rquote t been any post at all.\rdblquote\par
Ron and Hermione looked curiously at Harry. With a meaning\-ful look at both of them he said, \ldblquote All right if I go and dump my stuff in your room, Ron?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah \'85 think I will too,\rdblquote  said Ron at once. \ldblquote Hermione?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  she said quickly, and the three of them marched out of the kitchen and up the stairs.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s up, Harry?\rdblquote  said Ron, the moment they had closed the door of the attic room behind them.\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s something I haven\rquote t told you,\rdblquote  Harry said. \ldblquote On Satur\-day morning, I woke up with my scar hurting again.\rdblquote\par
Ron\rquote s and Hermione\rquote s reactions were almost exactly as Harry had imagined them back in his bedroom on Privet Drive. Hermione gasped and started making suggestions at once, mentioning a number of reference books, and everybody from Albus Dumble\-dore to Madam Pomfrey, the Hogwarts nurse. Ron simply looked dumbstruck.\par
\ldblquote But \emdash  he wasn\rquote t there, was he? You-Know-Who? I mean \emdash  last time your scar kept hurting, he was at Hogwarts, wasn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m sure he wasn\rquote t on Privet Drive,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote But I was dreaming about him \'85 him and Peter \emdash  you know, Wormtail. I can\rquote t remember all of it now, but they were plotting to kill \'85 someone.\rdblquote\par
He had teetered for a moment on the verge of saying \ldblquote me,\rdblquote  but couldn\rquote t bring himself to make Hermione look any more horrified than she already did.\par
\ldblquote It was only a dream,\rdblquote  said Ron bracingly. \ldblquote Just a nightmare.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, but was it, though?\rdblquote  said Harry, turning to look out of the window at the brightening sky. \ldblquote It\rquote s weird, isn\rquote t it? \'85 My scar hurts, and three days later the Death Eaters are on the march, and Voldemort\rquote s sign\rquote s up in the sky again.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t \emdash  say \emdash  his \emdash  name!\rdblquote  Ron hissed through gritted teeth.\par
\ldblquote And remember what Professor Trelawney said?\rdblquote  Harry went on, ignoring Ron. \ldblquote At the end of last year?\rdblquote\par
Professor Trelawney was their Divination teacher at Hogwarts. Hermione\rquote s terrified look vanished as she let out a derisive snort.\par
\ldblquote Oh Harry, you aren\rquote t going to pay attention to anything that old fraud says?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You weren\rquote t there,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You didn\rquote t hear her. This time was different. I told you, she went into a trance \emdash  a real one. And she said the Dark Lord would rise again \'85 \i greater and more terri\-ble than ever before\i0  \'85 and he\rquote d manage it because his servant was going to go back to him \'85 and that night Wormtail escaped.\rdblquote\par
There was a silence in which Ron fidgeted absentmindedly with a hole in his Chudley Cannons bedspread.\par
\ldblquote Why were you asking if Hedwig had come, Harry?\rdblquote  Hermione asked. \ldblquote Are you expecting a letter?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I told Sirius about my scar,\rdblquote  said Harry, shrugging. \ldblquote I\rquote m wait\-ing for his answer.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good thinking!\rdblquote  said Ron, his expression clearing. \ldblquote I bet Sir\-ius\rquote ll know what to do!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I hoped he\rquote d get back to me quickly,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote But we don\rquote t know where Sirius is \'85 he could be in Africa or somewhere, couldn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said Hermione reasonably. \ldblquote Hedwig\rquote s not going to manage \i that\i0  journey in a few days.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, I know,\rdblquote  said Harry, but there was a leaden feeling in his stomach as he looked out of the window at the Hedwig-free sky.\par
\ldblquote Come and have a game of Quidditch in the orchard, Harry,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Come on \emdash  three on three, Bill and Charlie and Fred and George will play. \'85 You can try out the Wronski Feint. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ron,\rdblquote  said Hermione, in an I-don\rquote t-think-you\rquote re-being-very-sensitive sort of voice, \ldblquote Harry doesn\rquote t want to play Quidditch right now. \'85 He\rquote s worried, and he\rquote s tired. \'85 We all need to go to bed. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, I want to play Quidditch,\rdblquote  said Harry suddenly. \ldblquote Hang on, I\rquote ll get my Firebolt.\rdblquote\par
Hermione left the room, muttering something that sounded very much like \ldblquote\i Boys.\i0\rdblquote\par
