\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj Neither Mr. Weasley nor Percy was at home much over the follow\-ing week. Both left the house each morning before the rest of the family got up, and returned well after dinner every night.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s been an absolute uproar,\rdblquote  Percy told them importantly the Sunday evening before they were due to return to Hogwarts. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been putting out fires all week. People keep sending Howlers, and of course, if you don\rquote t open a Howler straight away, it explodes. Scorch marks all over my desk and my best quill reduced to cinders.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why are they all sending Howlers?\rdblquote  asked Ginny, who was mending her copy of \i One Thousand Magical Herbs and Fungi\i0  with Spellotape on the rug in front of the living room fire.\par
\ldblquote Complaining about security at the World Cup,\rdblquote  said Percy. \ldblquote They want compensation for their ruined property. Mundungus Fletcher\rquote s put in a claim for a twelve-bedroomed tent with en-suite Jacuzzi, but I\rquote ve got his number. I know for a fact he was sleeping under a cloak propped on sticks.\rdblquote\par
Mrs. Weasley glanced at the grandfather clock in the corner. Harry liked this clock. It was completely useless if you wanted to know the time, but otherwise very informative. It had nine golden hands, and each of them was engraved with one of the Weasley family\rquote s names. There were no numerals around the face, but de\-scriptions of where each family member might be. \ldblquote Home,\rdblquote  \ldblquote school,\rdblquote  and \ldblquote work\rdblquote  were there, but there was also \ldblquote traveling,\rdblquote  \ldblquote lost,\rdblquote  \ldblquote hospital,\rdblquote  \ldblquote prison,\rdblquote  and, in the position where the number twelve would be on a normal clock, \ldblquote mortal peril.\rdblquote\par
Eight of the hands were currently pointing to the \ldblquote home\rdblquote  position, but Mr. Weasley\rquote s, which was the longest, was still point\-ing to \ldblquote work.\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley sighed.\par
\ldblquote Your father hasn\rquote t had to go into the office on weekends since the days of You-Know-Who,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote They\rquote re working him far too hard. His dinner\rquote s going to be ruined if he doesn\rquote t come home soon.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, Father feels he\rquote s got to make up for his mistake at the match, doesn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said Percy. \ldblquote If truth be told, he was a tad un\-wise to make a public statement without clearing it with his Head of Department first \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t you dare blame your father for what that wretched Skeeter woman wrote!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, flaring up at once.\par
\ldblquote If Dad hadn\rquote t said anything, old Rita would just have said it was disgraceful that nobody from the Ministry had commented,\rdblquote  said Bill, who was playing chess with Ron. \ldblquote Rita Skeeter never makes anyone look good. Remember, she interviewed all the Gringotts\rquote  Charm Breakers once, and called me \lquote a long-haired pillock\rquote ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, it \i is\i0  a bit long, dear,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley gently. \ldblquote If you\rquote d just let me \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i No,\i0  Mum.\rdblquote\par
Rain lashed against the living room window. Hermione was im\-mersed in \i The Standard Book of Spells, Grade 4,\i0  copies of which Mrs. Weasley had bought for her, Harry, and Ron in Diagon Alley. Charlie was darning a fireproof balaclava. Harry was polishing his Firebolt, the broomstick servicing kit Hermione had given him for his thirteenth birthday open at his feet. Fred and George were sit\-ting in a far corner, quills out, talking in whispers, their heads bent over a piece of parchment.\par
\ldblquote What are you two up to?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley sharply, her eyes on the twins.\par
\ldblquote Homework,\rdblquote  said Fred vaguely.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be ridiculous, you\rquote re still on holiday,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Yeah, we\rquote ve left it a bit late,\rdblquote  said George.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re not by any chance writing out a new \i order form,\i0  are you?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley shrewdly. \ldblquote You wouldn\rquote t be thinking of re\-starting Weasleys\rquote  Wizard Wheezes, by any chance?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Now, Mum,\rdblquote  said Fred, looking up at her, a pained look on his face. \ldblquote If the Hogwarts Express crashed tomorrow, and George and I died, how would you feel to know that the last thing we ever heard from you was an unfounded accusation?\rdblquote\par
Everyone laughed, even Mrs. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Oh your father\rquote s coming!\rdblquote  she said suddenly, looking up at the clock again.\par
Mr. Weasley\rquote s hand had suddenly spun from \ldblquote work\rdblquote  to \ldblquote travel\-ing\rdblquote ; a second later it had shuddered to a halt on \ldblquote home\rdblquote  with the others, and they heard him calling from the kitchen.\par
\ldblquote Coming, Arthur!\rdblquote  called Mrs. Weasley, hurrying out of the room.\par
A few moments later, Mr. Weasley came into the warm liv\-ing room carrying his dinner on a tray. He looked completely exhausted.\par
\ldblquote Well, the fat\rquote s really in the fire now,\rdblquote  he told Mrs. Weasley as he sat down in an armchair near the hearth and toyed unenthusiasti\-cally with his somewhat shriveled cauliflower. \ldblquote Rita Skeeter\rquote s been ferreting around all week, looking for more Ministry mess-ups to report. And now she\rquote s found out about poor old Bertha going missing, so that\rquote ll be the headline in the \i Prophet\i0  tomorrow. I \i told \i0 Bagman he should have sent someone to look for her ages ago.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mr. Crouch has been saying it for weeks and weeks,\rdblquote  said Percy swiftly.\par
\ldblquote Crouch is very lucky Rita hasn\rquote t found out about Winky,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley irritably. \ldblquote There\rquote d be a week\rquote s worth of headlines in his house-elf being caught holding the wand that conjured the Dark Mark.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I thought we were all agreed that that elf, while irresponsible, did \i not\i0  conjure the Mark?\rdblquote  said Percy hotly.\par
\ldblquote If you ask me, Mr. Crouch is very lucky no one at the \i Daily Prophet\i0  knows how mean he is to elves!\rdblquote  said Hermione angrily.\par
\ldblquote Now look here, Hermione!\rdblquote  said Percy. \ldblquote A high-ranking Min\-istry official like Mr. Crouch deserves unswerving obedience from his servants \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote His \i slave,\i0  you mean!\rdblquote  said Hermione, her voice rising passion\-ately, \ldblquote because he didn\rquote t \i pay\i0  Winky, did he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I think you\rquote d all better go upstairs and check that you\rquote ve packed properly!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, breaking up the argument. \ldblquote Come on now, all of you. \'85\rdblquote\par
Harry repacked his broomstick servicing kit, put his Firebolt over his shoulder, and went back upstairs with Ron. The rain sounded even louder at the top of the house, accompanied by loud whistlings and moans from the wind, not to mention sporadic howls from the ghoul who lived in the attic. Pigwidgeon began twittering and zooming around his cage when they entered. The sight of the half-packed trunks seemed to have sent him into a frenzy of excitement.\par
\ldblquote Bung him some Owl Treats,\rdblquote  said Ron, throwing a packet across to Harry. \ldblquote It might shut him up.\rdblquote\par
Harry poked a few Owl Treats through the bars of Pigwidgeon\rquote s cage, then turned to his trunk. Hedwig\rquote s cage stood next to it, still empty.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s been over a week,\rdblquote  Harry said, looking at Hedwig\rquote s deserted perch. \ldblquote Ron, you don\rquote t reckon Sirius has been caught, do you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nah, it would\rquote ve been in the \i Daily Prophet,\i0\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote The Ministry would want to show they\rquote d caught \i someone,\i0  wouldn\rquote t they?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, I suppose. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Look, here\rquote s the stuff Mum got for you in Diagon Alley. And she\rquote s got some gold out of your vault for you \'85 and she\rquote s washed all your socks.\rdblquote\par
He heaved a pile of parcels onto Harry\rquote s camp bed and dropped the money bag and a load of socks next to it. Harry started un\-wrapping the shopping. Apart from \i The Standard Book of Spells, Grade 4,\i0  by Miranda Goshawk, he had a handful of new quills, a dozen rolls of parchment, and refills for his potion-making kit \emdash  he had been running low on spine of lionfish and essence of bel\-ladonna. He was just piling underwear into his cauldron when Ron made a loud noise of disgust behind him.\par
\ldblquote What is \i that\i0  supposed to be?\rdblquote\par
He was holding up something that looked to Harry like a long, maroon velvet dress. It had a moldy-looking lace frill at the collar and matching lace cuffs.\par
There was a knock on the door, and Mrs. Weasley entered, car\-rying an armful of freshly laundered Hogwarts robes.\par
\ldblquote Here you are,\rdblquote  she said, sorting them into two piles. \ldblquote Now, mind you pack them properly so they don\rquote t crease.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mum, you\rquote ve given me Ginny\rquote s new dress,\rdblquote  said Ron, handing it out to her.\par
\ldblquote Of course I haven\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote That\rquote s for you. Dress robes.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i What\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Ron, looking horror-struck.\par
\ldblquote Dress robes!\rdblquote  repeated Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote It says on your school list that you\rquote re supposed to have dress robes this year \'85 robes for for\-mal occasions.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve got to be kidding,\rdblquote  said Ron in disbelief. \ldblquote I\rquote m not wear\-ing that, no way.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Everyone wears them, Ron!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley crossly. \ldblquote They\rquote re all like that! Your father\rquote s got some for smart parties!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll go starkers before I put that on,\rdblquote  said Ron stubbornly.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be so silly,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got to have dress robes, they\rquote re on your list! I got some for Harry too \'85 show him, Harry. \'85\rdblquote\par
In some trepidation, Harry opened the last parcel on his camp bed. It wasn\rquote t as bad as he had expected, however; his dress robes didn\rquote t have any lace on them at all \emdash  in fact, they were more or less the same as his school ones, except that they were bottle green in\-stead of black.\par
\ldblquote I thought they\rquote d bring out the color of your eyes, dear,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley fondly.\par
\ldblquote Well, they\rquote re okay!\rdblquote  said Ron angrily, looking at Harry\rquote s robes. \ldblquote Why couldn\rquote t I have some like that?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Because \'85 well, I had to get yours secondhand, and there wasn\rquote t a lot of choice!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, flushing.\par
Harry looked away. He would willingly have split all the money in his Gringotts vault with the Weasleys, but he knew they would never take it.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m never wearing them,\rdblquote  Ron was saying stubbornly. \ldblquote Never.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  snapped Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote Go naked. And, Harry, make sure you get a picture of him. Goodness knows I could do with a laugh.\rdblquote\par
She left the room, slamming the door behind her. There was a funny spluttering noise from behind them. Pigwidgeon was chok\-ing on an overlarge Owl Treat.\par
\ldblquote Why is everything I own rubbish?\rdblquote  said Ron furiously, striding across the room to unstick Pigwidgeon\rquote s beak.\par
