There was a definite end-of-the-holidays gloom in the air when Harry awoke next morning. Heavy rain was still splat\-tering against the window as he got dressed in jeans and a sweat\-shirt; they would change into their school robes on the Hogwarts Express.\par
He, Ron, Fred, and George had just reached the first-floor land\-ing on their way down to breakfast, when Mrs. Weasley appeared at the foot of the stairs, looking harassed.\par
\ldblquote Arthur!\rdblquote  she called up the staircase. \ldblquote Arthur! Urgent message from the Ministry!\rdblquote\par
Harry flattened himself against the wall as Mr. Weasley came clattering past with his robes on back-to-front and hurtled out of sight. When Harry and the others entered the kitchen, they saw Mrs. Weasley rummaging anxiously in the drawers \emdash  \ldblquote I\rquote ve got a quill here somewhere!\rdblquote  \emdash  and Mr. Weasley bending over the fire, talking to \emdash\par
Harry shut his eyes hard and opened them again to make sure that they were working properly.\par
Amos Diggory\rquote s head was sitting in the middle of the flames like a large, bearded egg. It was talking very fast, completely unper\-turbed by the sparks flying around it and the flames licking its ears.\par
\ldblquote\'85 Muggle neighbors heard bangs and shouting, so they went and called those what-d\rquote you-call-\rquote ems \emdash  please-men. Arthur, you\rquote ve got to get over there \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Here!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley breathlessly, pushing a piece of parch\-ment, a bottle of ink, and a crumpled quill into Mr. Weasley\rquote s hands.\par
\ldblquote\emdash  it\rquote s a real stroke of luck I heard about it,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory\rquote s head. \ldblquote I had to come into the office early to send a couple of owls, and I found the Improper Use of Magic lot all setting off \emdash  if Rita Skeeter gets hold of this one, Arthur \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What does Mad-Eye say happened?\rdblquote  asked Mr. Weasley, un\-screwing the ink bottle, loading up his quill, and preparing to take notes.\par
Mr. Diggory\rquote s head rolled its eyes. \ldblquote Says he heard an intruder in his yard. Says he was creeping toward the house, but was ambushed by his dustbins.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What did the dustbins do?\rdblquote  asked Mr. Weasley, scribbling frantically.\par
\ldblquote Made one hell of a noise and fired rubbish everywhere, as far as I can tell,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory. \ldblquote Apparently one of them was still rocketing around when the please-men turned up \emdash\rdblquote\par
Mr. Weasley groaned.\par
\ldblquote And what about the intruder?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Arthur, you know Mad-Eye,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory\rquote s head, rolling its eyes again. \ldblquote Someone creeping into his yard in the dead of night? More likely there\rquote s a very shell-shocked cat wandering around somewhere, covered in potato peelings. But if the Improper Use of Magic lot get their hands on Mad-Eye, he\rquote s had it \emdash  think of his record \emdash  we\rquote ve got to get him off on a minor charge, some\-thing in your department \emdash  what are exploding dustbins worth?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Might be a caution,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, still writing very fast, his brow furrowed. \ldblquote Mad-Eye didn\rquote t use his wand? He didn\rquote t actually attack anyone?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll bet he leapt out of bed and started jinxing everything he could reach through the window,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory, \ldblquote but they\rquote ll have a job proving it, there aren\rquote t any casualties.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right, I\rquote m off,\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley said, and he stuffed the parch\-ment with his notes on it into his pocket and dashed out of the kitchen again.\par
Mr. Diggory\rquote s head looked around at Mrs. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Sorry about this, Molly,\rdblquote  it said, more calmly, \ldblquote bothering you so early and everything \'85 but Arthur\rquote s the only one who can get Mad-Eye off, and Mad-Eye\rquote s supposed to be starting his new job today. Why he had to choose last night \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Never mind, Amos,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. \ldblquote Sure you won\rquote t have a bit of toast or anything before you go?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh go on, then,\rdblquote  said Mr. Diggory.\par
Mrs. Weasley took a piece of buttered toast from a stack on the kitchen table, put it into the fire tongs, and transferred it into Mr. Diggory\rquote s mouth.\par
\ldblquote Fanks,\rdblquote  he said in a muffled voice, and then, with a small \i pop,\i0  vanished.\par
Harry could hear Mr. Weasley calling hurried good-byes to Bill, Charlie, Percy, and the girls. Within five minutes, he was back in the kitchen, his robes on the right way now, dragging a comb through his hair.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote d better hurry \emdash  you have a good term, boys,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley to Harry, Ron, and the twins, fastening a cloak over his shoulders and preparing to Disapparate. \ldblquote Molly, are you going to be all right taking the kids to King\rquote s Cross?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course I will,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote You just look after Mad-Eye, we\rquote ll be fine.\rdblquote\par
As Mr. Weasley vanished, Bill and Charlie entered the kitchen.\par
\ldblquote Did someone say Mad-Eye?\rdblquote  Bill asked. \ldblquote What\rquote s he been up to now?\par
\ldblquote He says someone tried to break into his house last night,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley.\par
\ldblquote Mad-Eye Moody?\rdblquote  said George thoughtfully, spreading mar\-malade on his toast. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t he that nutter \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Your father thinks very highly of Mad-Eye Moody,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley sternly.\par
\ldblquote Yeah, well, Dad collects plugs, doesn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said Fred quietly as Mrs. Weasley left the room. \ldblquote Birds of a feather \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Moody was a great wizard in his time,\rdblquote  said Bill.\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s an old friend of Dumbledore\rquote s, isn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said Charlie.\par
\ldblquote Dumbledore\rquote s not what you\rquote d call \i normal,\i0  though, is he?\rdblquote  said Fred. \ldblquote I mean, I know he\rquote s a genius and everything \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Who \i is\i0  Mad-Eye?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s retired, used to work at the Ministry,\rdblquote  said Charlie. \ldblquote I met him once when Dad took me into work with him. He was an Auror \emdash  one of the best \'85 a Dark wizard catcher,\rdblquote  he added, see\-ing Harry\rquote s blank look. \ldblquote Half the cells in Azkaban are full because of him. He made himself loads of enemies, though \'85 the families of people he caught, mainly \'85 and I heard he\rquote s been getting really paranoid in his old age. Doesn\rquote t trust anyone anymore. Sees Dark wizards everywhere.\rdblquote\par
Bill and Charlie decided to come and see everyone off at King\rquote s Cross station, but Percy, apologizing most profusely, said that he really needed to get to work.\par
\ldblquote I just can\rquote t justify taking more time off at the moment,\rdblquote  he told them. \ldblquote Mr. Crouch is really starting to rely on me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, you know what, Percy?\rdblquote  said George seriously. \ldblquote I reckon he\rquote ll know your name soon.\rdblquote\par
Mrs. Weasley had braved the telephone in the village post office to order three ordinary Muggle taxis to take them into London.\par
\ldblquote Arthur tried to borrow Ministry cars for us,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley whispered to Harry as they stood in the rain-washed yard, watch\-ing the taxi drivers heaving six heavy Hogwarts trunks into their cars. \ldblquote But there weren\rquote t any to spare. \'85 Oh dear, they don\rquote t look happy, do they?\rdblquote\par
