The next two days passed without great incident, unless you counted Neville melting his sixth cauldron in Potions. Pro\-fessor Snape, who seemed to have attained new levels of vindictive\-ness over the summer, gave Neville detention, and Neville returned from it in a state of nervous collapse, having been made to disem\-bowel a barrel full of horned toads.\par
\ldblquote You know why Snape\rquote s in such a foul mood, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Ron to Harry as they watched Hermione teaching Neville a Scour\-ing Charm to remove the frog guts from under his fingernails.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Moody.\rdblquote\par
It was common knowledge that Snape really wanted the Dark Arts job, and he had now failed to get it for the fourth year run\-ning. Snape had disliked all of their previous Dark Arts teachers, and shown it \emdash  but he seemed strangely wary of displaying overt animosity to Mad-Eye Moody. Indeed, whenever Harry saw the two of them together \emdash  at mealtimes, or when they passed in the corridors \emdash  he had the distinct impression that Snape was avoid\-ing Moody\rquote s eye, whether magical or normal.\par
\ldblquote I reckon Snape\rquote s a bit scared of him, you know,\rdblquote  Harry said thoughtfully.\par
\ldblquote Imagine if Moody turned Snape into a horned toad,\rdblquote  said Ron, his eyes misting over, \ldblquote and bounced him all around his dungeon. \'85\rdblquote\par
The Gryffindor fourth years were looking forward to Moody\rquote s first lesson so much that they arrived early on Thursday lunchtime and queued up outside his classroom before the bell had even rung. The only person missing was Hermione, who turned up just in time for the lesson.\par
\ldblquote Been in the \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Library.\rdblquote  Harry finished her sentence for her. \ldblquote C\rquote mon, quick, or we won\rquote t get decent seats.\rdblquote\par
They hurried into three chairs right in front of the teacher\rquote s desk, took out their copies of \i The Dark Forces: A Guide to Self-Protection,\i0  and waited, unusually quiet. Soon they heard Moody\rquote s distinctive clunking footsteps coming down the corridor, and he entered the room, looking as strange and frightening as ever. They could just see his clawed, wooden foot protruding from under\-neath his robes.\par
\ldblquote You can put those away,\rdblquote  he growled, stumping over to his desk and sitting down, \ldblquote those books. You won\rquote t need them.\rdblquote\par
They returned the books to their bags, Ron looking excited.\par
Moody took out a register, shook his long mane of grizzled gray hair out of his twisted and scarred face, and began to call out names, his normal eye moving steadily down the list while his mag\-ical eye swiveled around, fixing upon each student as he or she answered.\par
\ldblquote Right then,\rdblquote  he said, when the last person had declared them\-selves present, \ldblquote I\rquote ve had a letter from Professor Lupin about this class. Seems you\rquote ve had a pretty thorough grounding in tackling Dark creatures \emdash  you\rquote ve covered boggarts, Red Caps, hinkypunks, grindylows, Kappas, and werewolves, is that right?\rdblquote\par
There was a general murmur of assent.\par
\ldblquote But you\rquote re behind \emdash  very behind \emdash  on dealing with curses,\rdblquote  said Moody. \ldblquote So I\rquote m here to bring you up to scratch on what wiz\-ards can do to each other. I\rquote ve got one year to teach you how to deal with Dark \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What, aren\rquote t you staying?\rdblquote  Ron blurted out.\par
Moody\rquote s magical eye spun around to stare at Ron; Ron looked extremely apprehensive, but after a moment Moody smiled \emdash  the first time Harry had seen him do so. The effect was to make his heavily scarred face look more twisted and contorted than ever, but it was nevertheless good to know that he ever did anything as friendly as smile. Ron looked deeply relieved.\par
