Madame Maxime closed the door behind her, Hagrid offered her his arm, and they set off around the edge of the paddock con\-taining Madame Maxime\rquote s giant winged horses, with Harry, totally bewildered, running to keep up with them. Had Hagrid wanted to show him Madame Maxime? He could see her any old time he wanted \'85 she wasn\rquote t exactly hard to miss. \'85\par
But it seemed that Madame Maxime was in for the same treat as Harry, because after a while she said playfully, \ldblquote Wair is it you are taking me, \rquote Agrid?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeh\rquote ll enjoy this,\rdblquote  said Hagrid gruffly, \ldblquote worth seein\rquote , trust me. On\rquote y \emdash  don\rquote  go tellin\rquote  anyone I showed yeh, right? Yeh\rquote re not s\rquote posed ter know.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course not,\rdblquote  said Madame Maxime, fluttering her long black eyelashes.\par
And still they walked, Harry getting more and more irritated as he jogged along in their wake, checking his watch every now and then. Hagrid had some harebrained scheme in hand, which might make him miss Sirius. If they didn\rquote t get there soon, he was going to turn around, go straight back to the castle, and leave Hagrid to en\-joy his moonlit stroll with Madame Maxime. \'85\par
But then \emdash  when they had walked so far around the perimeter of the forest that the castle and the lake were out of sight \emdash  Harry heard something. Men were shouting up ahead \'85 then came a deafening, earsplitting roar. \'85\par
Hagrid led Madame Maxime around a clump of trees and came to a halt. Harry hurried up alongside them \emdash  for a split second, he thought he was seeing bonfires, and men darting around them \emdash  and then his mouth fell open.\par
\i Dragons.\i0\par
Four fully grown, enormous, vicious-looking dragons were rear\-ing onto their hind legs inside an enclosure fenced with thick planks of wood, roaring and snorting \emdash  torrents of fire were shooting into the dark sky from their open, fanged mouths, fifty feet above the ground on their outstretched necks. There was a silvery-blue one with long, pointed horns, snapping and snarling at the wizards on the ground; a smooth-scaled green one, which was writhing and stamping with all its might; a red one with an odd fringe of fine gold spikes around its face, which was shooting mushroom-shaped fire clouds into the air; and a gigantic black one, more lizard-like than the others, which was nearest to them.\par
At least thirty wizards, seven or eight to each dragon, were attempting to control them, pulling on the chains connected to heavy leather straps around their necks and legs. Mesmerized, Harry looked up, high above him, and saw the eyes of the black dragon, with vertical pupils like a cat\rquote s, bulging with either fear or rage, he couldn\rquote t tell which. \'85 It was making a horrible noise, a yowling, screeching scream. \'85\par
\ldblquote Keep back there, Hagrid!\rdblquote  yelled a wizard near the fence, strain\-ing on the chain he was holding. \ldblquote They can shoot fire at a range of twenty feet, you know! I\rquote ve seen this Horntail do forty!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Is\rquote n\rquote  it beautiful?\rdblquote  said Hagrid softly.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s no good!\rdblquote  yelled another wizard. \ldblquote Stunning Spells, on the count of three!\rdblquote\par
Harry saw each of the dragon keepers pull out his wand.\par
\ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote  they shouted in unison, and the Stunning Spells shot into the darkness like fiery rockets, bursting in showers of stars on the dragons\rquote  scaly hides \emdash\par
Harry watched the dragon nearest to them teeter dangerously on its back legs; its jaws stretched wide in a silent howl; its nostrils were suddenly devoid of flame, though still smoking \emdash  then, very slowly, it fell. Several tons of sinewy, scaly-black dragon hit the ground with a thud that Harry could have sworn made the trees behind him quake.\par
The dragon keepers lowered their wands and walked forward to their fallen charges, each of which was the size of a small hill. They hurried to tighten the chains and fasten them securely to iron pegs, which they forced deep into the ground with their wands.\par
\ldblquote Wan\rquote  a closer look?\rdblquote  Hagrid asked Madame Maxime excitedly. The pair of them moved right up to the fence, and Harry followed. The wizard who had warned Hagrid not to come any closer turned, and Harry realized who it was: Charlie Weasley.\par
\ldblquote All right, Hagrid?\rdblquote  he panted, coming over to talk. \ldblquote They should be okay now \emdash  we put them out with a Sleeping Draft on the way here, thought it might be better for them to wake up in the dark and the quiet \emdash  but, like you saw, they weren\rquote t happy, not happy at all \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What breeds you got here, Charlie?\rdblquote  said Hagrid, gazing at the closest dragon, the black one, with something close to reverence. Its eyes were still just open. Harry could see a strip of gleaming yel\-low beneath its wrinkled black eyelid.\par
\ldblquote This is a Hungarian Horntail,\rdblquote  said Charlie. \ldblquote There\rquote s a Com\-mon Welsh Green over there, the smaller one \emdash  a Swedish Short-Snout, that blue-gray \emdash  and a Chinese Fireball, that\rquote s the red.\rdblquote\par
Charlie looked around; Madame Maxime was strolling away around the edge of the enclosure, gazing at the stunned dragons.\par
\ldblquote I didn\rquote t know you were bringing her, Hagrid,\rdblquote  Charlie said, frowning. \ldblquote The champions aren\rquote t supposed to know what\rquote s com\-ing \emdash  she\rquote s bound to tell her student, isn\rquote t she?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jus\rquote  thought she\rquote d like ter see \rquote em,\rdblquote  shrugged Hagrid, still gaz\-ing, enraptured, at the dragons.\par
\ldblquote Really romantic date, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Charlie, shaking his head.\par
\ldblquote Four \'85\rdblquote  said Hagrid, \ldblquote so it\rquote s one fer each o\rquote  the champions, is it? What\rquote ve they gotta do \emdash  fight \rquote em?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Just get past them, I think,\rdblquote  said Charlie. \ldblquote We\rquote ll be on hand if it gets nasty, Extinguishing Spells at the ready. They wanted nest\-ing mothers, I don\rquote t know why \'85 but I tell you this, I don\rquote t envy the one who gets the Horntail. Vicious thing. Its back end\rquote s as dan\-gerous as its front, look.\rdblquote\par
Charlie pointed toward the Horntail\rquote s tail, and Harry saw long, bronze-colored spikes protruding along it every few inches.\par
Five of Charlie\rquote s fellow keepers staggered up to the Horntail at that moment, carrying a clutch of huge granite-gray eggs between them in a blanket. They placed them carefully at the Horntail\rquote s side. Hagrid let out a moan of longing.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve got them counted, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Charlie sternly. Then he said, \ldblquote How\rquote s Harry?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. He was still gazing at the eggs.\par
\ldblquote Just hope he\rquote s still fine after he\rquote s faced this lot,\rdblquote  said Charlie grimly, looking out over the dragons\rquote  enclosure. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t dare tell Mum what he\rquote s got to do for the first task; she\rquote s already having kit\-tens about him. \'85\rdblquote  Charlie imitated his mother\rquote s anxious voice. \ldblquote  \lquote\i How could they let him enter that tournament, he\rquote s much too young\i0 ! \i I thought they were all safe, I thought there was going to be an age\i0  \i limit\i0 !\rquote  She was in floods after that \i Daily Prophet\i0  article about him. \lquote\i He still cries about his parents\i0 ! \i Oh bless him, I never knew\i0 !\rquote  \rdblquote\par
Harry had had enough. Trusting to the fact that Hagrid wouldn\rquote t miss him, with the attractions of four dragons and Madame Maxime to occupy him, he turned silently and began to walk away, back to the castle.\par
He didn\rquote t know whether he was glad he\rquote d seen what was coming or not. Perhaps this way was better. The first shock was over now. Maybe if he\rquote d seen the dragons for the first time on Tuesday, he would have passed out cold in front of the whole school \'85 but maybe he would anyway. \'85 He was going to be armed with his wand \emdash  which, just now, felt like nothing more than a narrow strip of wood \emdash  against a fifty-foot-high, scaly, spike-ridden, fire-breathing dragon. And he had to get past it. With everyone watch\-ing. \i How\i0 ?\par
Harry sped up, skirting the edge of the forest; he had just under fifteen minutes to get back to the fireside and talk to Sirius, and he couldn\rquote t remember, ever, wanting to talk to someone more than he did right now \emdash  when, without warning, he ran into something very solid.\par
Harry fell backward, his glasses askew, clutching the cloak around him. A voice nearby said, \ldblquote Ouch! Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote\par
Harry hastily checked that the cloak was covering him and lay very still, staring up at the dark outline of the wizard he had hit. He recognized the goatee \'85 it was Karkaroff.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  said Karkaroff again, very suspiciously, looking around in the darkness. Harry remained still and silent. After a minute or so, Karkaroff seemed to decide that he had hit some sort of animal; he was looking around at waist height, as though ex\-pecting to see a dog. Then he crept back under the cover of the trees and started to edge forward toward the place where the drag\-ons were.\par
Very slowly and very carefully, Harry got to his feet and set off again as fast as he could without making too much noise, hurrying through the darkness back toward Hogwarts.\par
He had no doubt whatsoever what Karkaroff was up to. He had sneaked off his ship to try and find out what the first task was going to be. He might even have spotted Hagrid and Madame Maxime heading off around the forest together \emdash  they were hardly difficult to spot at a distance \'85 and now all Karkaroff had to do was fol\-low the sound of voices, and he, like Madame Maxime, would know what was in store for the champions.\par
By the looks of it, the only champion who would be facing the unknown on Tuesday was Cedric.\par
Harry reached the castle, slipped in through the front doors, and began to climb the marble stairs; he was very out of breath, but he didn\rquote t dare slow down. \'85 He had less than five minutes to get up to the fire. \'85\par
\ldblquote Balderdash!\rdblquote  he gasped at the Fat Lady, who was snoozing in her frame in front of the portrait hole.\par
\ldblquote If you say so,\rdblquote  she muttered sleepily, without opening her eyes, and the picture swung forward to admit him. Harry climbed in\-side. The common room was deserted, and, judging by the fact that it smelled quite normal, Hermione had not needed to set off any Dungbombs to ensure that he and Sirius got privacy.\par
Harry pulled off the Invisibility Cloak and threw himself into an armchair in front of the fire. The room was in semidarkness; the flames were the only source of light. Nearby, on a table, the \i Support Cedric Diggory\i0 ! badges the Creeveys had been trying to improve were glinting in the firelight. They now read \i POTTER REALLY STINKS. \i0 Harry looked back into the flames, and jumped.\par
Sirius\rquote s head was sitting in the fire. If Harry hadn\rquote t seen Mr. Dig\-gory do exactly this back in the Weasleys\rquote  kitchen, it would have scared him out of his wits. Instead, his face breaking into the first smile he had worn for days, he scrambled out of his chair, crouched down by the hearth, and said, \ldblquote Sirius \emdash  how\rquote re you doing?\rdblquote\par
Sirius looked different from Harry\rquote s memory of him. When they had said good-bye, Sirius\rquote s face had been gaunt and sunken, sur\-rounded by a quantity of long, black, matted hair \emdash  but the hair was short and clean now, Sirius\rquote s face was fuller, and he looked younger, much more like the only photograph Harry had of him, which had been taken at the Potters\rquote  wedding.\par
\ldblquote Never mind me, how are you?\rdblquote  said Sirius seriously.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m \emdash\rdblquote  For a second, Harry tried to say \ldblquote fine\rdblquote  \emdash  but he couldn\rquote t do it. Before he could stop himself, he was talking more than he\rquote d talked in days \emdash  about how no one believed he hadn\rquote t entered the tournament of his own free will, how Rita Skeeter had lied about him in the \i Daily Prophet,\i0  how he couldn\rquote t walk down a corridor without being sneered at \emdash  and about Ron, Ron not believing him, Ron\rquote s jealousy \'85\par
\ldblquote\'85 and now Hagrid\rquote s just shown me what\rquote s coming in the first task, and it\rquote s dragons, Sirius, and I\rquote m a goner,\rdblquote  he finished des\-perately.\par
Sirius looked at him, eyes full of concern, eyes that had not yet lost the look that Azkaban had given them \emdash  that deadened, haunted look. He had let Harry talk himself into silence without interruption, but now he said, \ldblquote Dragons we can deal with, Harry, but we\rquote ll get to that in a minute \emdash  I haven\rquote t got long here \'85 I\rquote ve broken into a wizarding house to use the fire, but they could be back at any time. There are things I need to warn you about.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry, feeling his spirits slip a further few notches. \'85 Surely there could be nothing worse than dragons coming?\par
\ldblquote Karkaroff,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote Harry, he was a Death Eater. You know what Death Eaters are, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes \emdash  he \emdash  what?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He was caught, he was in Azkaban with me, but he got released. I\rquote d bet everything that\rquote s why Dumbledore wanted an Auror at Hogwarts this year \emdash  to keep an eye on him. Moody caught Karkaroff. Put him into Azkaban in the first place.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Karkaroff got released?\rdblquote  Harry said slowly \emdash  his brain seemed to be struggling to absorb yet another piece of shocking informa\-tion. \ldblquote Why did they release him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He did a deal with the Ministry of Magic,\rdblquote  said Sirius bitterly. \ldblquote He said he\rquote d seen the error of his ways, and then he named names \'85 he put a load of other people into Azkaban in his place. \'85 He\rquote s not very popular in there, I can tell you. And since he got out, from what I can tell, he\rquote s been teaching the Dark Arts to every student who passes through that school of his. So watch out for the Durmstrang champion as well.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Harry slowly. \ldblquote But \'85 are you saying Karkaroff put my name in the goblet? Because if he did, he\rquote s a really good actor. He seemed furious about it. He wanted to stop me from competing.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We know he\rquote s a good actor,\rdblquote  said Sirius, \ldblquote because he convinced the Ministry of Magic to set him free, didn\rquote t he? Now, I\rquote ve been keeping an eye on the \i Daily Prophet,\i0  Harry \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\emdash  you and the rest of the world,\rdblquote  said Harry bitterly.\par
\ldblquote\emdash  and reading between the lines of that Skeeter woman\rquote s arti\-cle last month, Moody was attacked the night before he started at Hogwarts. Yes, I know she says it was another false alarm,\rdblquote  Sirius said hastily, seeing Harry about to speak, \ldblquote but I don\rquote t think so, somehow. I think someone tried to stop him from getting to Hog\-warts. I think someone knew their job would be a lot more difficult with him around. And no one\rquote s going to look into it too closely; Mad-Eye\rquote s heard intruders a bit too often. But that doesn\rquote t mean he can\rquote t still spot the real thing. Moody was the best Auror the Min\-istry ever had.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So \'85 what are you saying?\rdblquote  said Harry slowly. \ldblquote Karkaroff\rquote s trying to kill me? But \emdash  why?\rdblquote\par
Sirius hesitated.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve been hearing some very strange things,\rdblquote  he said slowly. \ldblquote The Death Eaters seem to be a bit more active than usual lately. They showed themselves at the Quidditch World Cup, didn\rquote t they? Someone set off the Dark Mark \'85 and then \emdash  did you hear about that Ministry of Magic witch who\rquote s gone missing?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Bertha Jorkins?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Exactly \'85 she disappeared in Albania, and that\rquote s definitely where Voldemort was rumored to be last \'85 and she would have known the Triwizard Tournament was coming up, wouldn\rquote t she?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, but \'85 it\rquote s not very likely she\rquote d have walked straight into Voldemort, is it?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Listen, I knew Bertha Jorkins,\rdblquote  said Sirius grimly. \ldblquote She was at Hogwarts when I was, a few years above your dad and me. And she was an idiot. Very nosy, but no brains, none at all. It\rquote s not a good combination, Harry. I\rquote d say she\rquote d be very easy to lure into a trap.\par
\ldblquote So \'85 so Voldemort could have found out about the tourna\-ment?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Is that what you mean? You think Karkaroff might be here on his orders?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Sirius slowly, \ldblquote I just don\rquote t know \'85 Karkaroff doesn\rquote t strike me as the type who\rquote d go back to Voldemort unless he knew Voldemort was powerful enough to protect him. But whoever put your name in that goblet did it for a reason, and I can\rquote t help thinking the tournament would be a very good way to attack you and make it look like an accident.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Looks like a really good plan from where I\rquote m standing,\rdblquote  said Harry grinning bleakly. \ldblquote They\rquote ll just have to stand back and let the dragons do their stuff.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Right \emdash  these dragons,\rdblquote  said Sirius, speaking very quickly now. \ldblquote There\rquote s a way, Harry. Don\rquote t be tempted to try a Stunning Spell \emdash  dragons are strong and too powerfully magical to be knocked out by a single Stunner, you need about half a dozen wiz\-ards at a time to overcome a dragon \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, I know, I just saw,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote But you can do it alone,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote There is a way, and a sim\-ple spell\rquote s all you need. Just \emdash\rdblquote\par
But Harry held up a hand to silence him, his heart suddenly pounding as though it would burst. He could hear footsteps com\-ing down the spiral staircase behind him.\par
\ldblquote Go!\rdblquote  he hissed at Sirius. \ldblquote\i Go\i0 ! There\rquote s someone coming!\rdblquote\par
Harry scrambled to his feet, hiding the fire \emdash  if someone saw Sirius\rquote s face within the walls of Hogwarts, they would raise an almighty uproar \emdash  the Ministry would get dragged in \emdash  he, Harry, would be questioned about Sirius\rquote s whereabouts \emdash\par
Harry heard a tiny \i pop\i0 ! in the fire behind him and knew Sirius had gone. He watched the bottom of the spiral staircase. Who had decided to go for a stroll at one o\rquote clock in the morning, and stopped Sirius from telling him how to get past a dragon?\par
It was Ron. Dressed in his maroon paisley pajamas, Ron stopped dead facing Harry across the room, and looked around.\par
\ldblquote Who were you talking to?\rdblquote  he said.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s that got to do with you?\rdblquote  Harry snarled. \ldblquote What are you doing down here at this time of night?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I just wondered where you \emdash\rdblquote  Ron broke off, shrugging. \ldblquote Nothing. I\rquote m going back to bed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Just thought you\rquote d come nosing around, did you?\rdblquote  Harry shouted. He knew that Ron had no idea what he\rquote d walked in on, knew he hadn\rquote t done it on purpose, but he didn\rquote t care \emdash  at this moment he hated everything about Ron, right down to the several inches of bare ankle showing beneath his pajama trousers.\par
\ldblquote Sorry about that,\rdblquote  said Ron, his face reddening with anger. \ldblquote Should\rquote ve realized you didn\rquote t want to be disturbed. I\rquote ll let you get on with practicing for your next interview in peace.\rdblquote\par
Harry seized one of the \i POTTER REALLY STINKS \i0 badges off the table and chucked it, as hard as he could, across the room. It hit Ron on the forehead and bounced off.\par
\ldblquote There you go,\rdblquote  Harry said. \ldblquote Something for you to wear on Tuesday. You might even have a scar now, if you\rquote re lucky. \'85 That\rquote s what you want, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
He strode across the room toward the stairs; he half expected Ron to stop him, he would even have liked Ron to throw a punch at him, but Ron just stood there in his too-small pajamas, and Harry, having stormed upstairs, lay awake in bed fuming for a long time afterward and didn\rquote t hear him come up to bed.\par
