Harry got up on Sunday morning and dressed so inatten\-tively that it was a while before he realized he was trying to pull his hat onto his foot instead of his sock. When he\rquote d finally got all his clothes on the right parts of his body, he hurried off to find Hermione, locating her at the Gryffindor table in the Great Hall, where she was eating breakfast with Ginny. Feeling too queasy to eat, Harry waited until Hermione had swallowed her last spoonful of porridge, then dragged her out onto the grounds. There, he told her all about the dragons, and about everything Sirius had said, while they took another long walk around the lake.\par
Alarmed as she was by Sirius\rquote s warnings about Karkaroff, Hermione still thought that the dragons were the more pressing problem.\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s just try and keep you alive until Tuesday evening,\rdblquote  she said desperately, \ldblquote and then we can worry about Karkaroff.\rdblquote\par
They walked three times around the lake, trying all the way to think of a simple spell that would subdue a dragon. Nothing what\-soever occurred to them, so they retired to the library instead. Here, Harry pulled down every book he could find on dragons, and both of them set to work searching through the large pile.\par
\ldblquote  \lquote\i Talon-clipping by charms\i0  \'85 \i treating scale-rot\i0  \'85\rquote  This is no good, this is for nutters like Hagrid who want to keep them healthy. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote  \lquote\i Dragons are extremely difficult to slay, owing to the ancient magic that imbues their thick hides, which none but the most powerful spells can penetrate\i0  \'85\rquote  But Sirius said a simple one would do it. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s try some simple spellbooks, then,\rdblquote  said Harry, throwing aside \i Men Who Love Dragons Too Much.\i0\par
He returned to the table with a pile of spellbooks, set them down, and began to flick through each in turn, Hermione whis\-pering nonstop at his elbow.\par
\ldblquote Well, there are Switching Spells \'85 but what\rquote s the point of Switching it? Unless you swapped its fangs for wine-gums or some\-thing that would make it less dangerous. \'85 The trouble is, like that book said, not much is going to get through a dragon\rquote s hide. \'85 I\rquote d say Transfigure it, but something that big, you really haven\rquote t got a hope, I doubt even Professor McGonagall \'85 unless you\rquote re supposed to put the spell on \i yourself\i0 ? Maybe to give yourself extra powers? But \i they\rquote re\i0  not simple spells, I mean, we haven\rquote t done any of those in class, I only know about them because I\rquote ve been do\-ing O.W.L. practice papers. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hermione,\rdblquote  Harry said, through gritted teeth, \ldblquote will you shut up for a bit, please? I\rquote m trying to concentrate.\rdblquote\par
But all that happened, when Hermione fell silent, was that Harry\rquote s brain filled with a sort of blank buzzing, which didn\rquote t seem to allow room for concentration. He stared hopelessly down the in\-dex of \i Basic Hexes for the Busy and Vexed. Instant scalping\i0  \'85 but dragons had no hair \'85 \i pepper breath\i0  \'85 that would probably in\-crease a dragon\rquote s firepower \'85 \i horn tongue\i0  \'85 just what he needed, to give it an extra weapon \'85\par
\ldblquote Oh no, he\rquote s back \i again,\i0  why can\rquote t he read on his stupid ship?\rdblquote  said Hermione irritably as Viktor Krum slouched in, cast a surly look over at the pair of them, and settled himself in a distant cor\-ner with a pile of books. \ldblquote Come on, Harry, we\rquote ll go back to the common room \'85 his fan club\rquote ll be here in a moment, twittering away. \'85\rdblquote\par
And sure enough, as they left the library, a gang of girls tiptoed past them, one of them wearing a Bulgaria scarf tied around her waist.\par
\par
Harry barely slept that night. When he awoke on Monday morn\-ing, he seriously considered for the first time ever just running away from Hogwarts. But as he looked around the Great Hall at breakfast time, and thought about what leaving the castle would mean, he knew he couldn\rquote t do it. It was the only place he had ever been happy \'85 well, he supposed he must have been happy with his parents too, but he couldn\rquote t remember that.\par
Somehow, the knowledge that he would rather be here and fac\-ing a dragon than back on Privet Drive with Dudley was good to know; it made him feel slightly calmer. He finished his bacon with difficulty (his throat wasn\rquote t working too well), and as he and Hermione got up, he saw Cedric Diggory leaving the Hufflepuff table.\par
Cedric still didn\rquote t know about the dragons \'85 the only cham\-pion who didn\rquote t, if Harry was right in thinking that Maxime and Karkaroff would have told Fleur and Krum. \'85\par
\ldblquote Hermione, I\rquote ll see you in the greenhouses,\rdblquote  Harry said, coming to his decision as he watched Cedric leaving the Hall. \ldblquote Go on, I\rquote ll catch you up.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Harry, you\rquote ll be late, the bell\rquote s about to ring \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll catch you up, okay?\rdblquote\par
By the time Harry reached the bottom of the marble staircase, Cedric was at the top. He was with a load of sixth-year friends. Harry didn\rquote t want to talk to Cedric in front of them; they were among those who had been quoting Rita Skeeter\rquote s article at him every time he went near them. He followed Cedric at a distance and saw that he was heading toward the Charms corridor. This gave Harry an idea. Pausing at a distance from them, he pulled out his wand, and took careful aim.\par
\ldblquote\i Diffindo\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Cedric\rquote s bag split. Parchment, quills, and books spilled out of it onto the floor. Several bottles of ink smashed.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t bother,\rdblquote  said Cedric in an exasperated voice as his friends bent down to help him. \ldblquote Tell Flitwick I\rquote m coming, go on. \'85\rdblquote\par
This was exactly what Harry had been hoping for. He slipped his wand back into his robes, waited until Cedric\rquote s friends had disap\-peared into their classroom, and hurried up the corridor, which was now empty of everyone but himself and Cedric.\par
\ldblquote Hi,\rdblquote  said Cedric, picking up a copy of \i A Guide to Advanced Transfiguration\i0  that was now splattered with ink. \ldblquote My bag just split \'85 brand-new and all \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Cedric,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote the first task is dragons.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Cedric, looking up.\par
\ldblquote Dragons,\rdblquote  said Harry, speaking quickly, in case Professor Flit\-wick came out to see where Cedric had got to. \ldblquote They\rquote ve got four, one for each of us, and we\rquote ve got to get past them.\rdblquote\par
Cedric stared at him. Harry saw some of the panic he\rquote d been feeling since Saturday night flickering in Cedric\rquote s gray eyes.\par
\ldblquote Are you sure?\rdblquote  Cedric said in a hushed voice.\par
\ldblquote Dead sure,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I\rquote ve seen them.\rdblquote\par
