He let out a short, harsh laugh, and pointed to the large trunk under the window. It had seven keyholes in a row. Harry wondered what was in there, until Moody\rquote s next question brought him sharply back to earth.\par
\ldblquote So \'85 found out about the dragons, have you?\rdblquote\par
Harry hesitated. He\rquote d been afraid of this \emdash  but he hadn\rquote t told Cedric, and he certainly wasn\rquote t going to tell Moody, that Hagrid had broken the rules.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s all right,\rdblquote  said Moody, sitting down and stretching out his wooden leg with a groan. \ldblquote Cheating\rquote s a traditional part of the Tri-wizard Tournament and always has been.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I didn\rquote t cheat,\rdblquote  said Harry sharply. \ldblquote It was \emdash  a sort of accident that I found out.\rdblquote\par
Moody grinned. \ldblquote I wasn\rquote t accusing you, laddie. I\rquote ve been telling Dumbledore from the start, he can be as high-minded as he likes, but you can bet old Karkaroff and Maxime won\rquote t be. They\rquote ll have told their champions everything they can. They want to win. They want to beat Dumbledore. They\rquote d like to prove he\rquote s only human.\rdblquote\par
Moody gave another harsh laugh, and his magical eye swiveled around so fast it made Harry feel queasy to watch it.\par
\ldblquote So \'85 got any ideas how you\rquote re going to get past your dragon yet?\rdblquote  said Moody.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Well, I\rquote m not going to tell you,\rdblquote  said Moody gruffly. \ldblquote I don\rquote t show favoritism, me. I\rquote m just going to give you some good, general advice. And the first bit is \emdash  \i play to your strengths.\i0\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I haven\rquote t got any,\rdblquote  said Harry, before he could stop himself.\par
\ldblquote Excuse me,\rdblquote  growled Moody, \ldblquote you\rquote ve got strengths if I say you\rquote ve got them. Think now. What are you best at?\rdblquote\par
Harry tried to concentrate. What \i was\i0  he best at? Well, that was easy, really \emdash\par
\ldblquote Quidditch,\rdblquote  he said dully, \ldblquote and a fat lot of help \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Moody, staring at him very hard, his magical eye barely moving at all. \ldblquote You\rquote re a damn good flier from what I\rquote ve heard.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, but \'85\rdblquote  Harry stared at him. \ldblquote I\rquote m not allowed a broom, I\rquote ve only got my wand \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My second piece of general advice,\rdblquote  said Moody loudly, inter\-rupting him, \ldblquote is to use a nice, simple spell that will enable you to \i get what you need.\i0\rdblquote\par
Harry looked at him blankly. What did he need?\par
\ldblquote Come on, boy \'85\rdblquote  whispered Moody. \ldblquote Put them together \'85 it\rquote s not that difficult. \'85\rdblquote\par
And it clicked. He was best at flying. He needed to pass the dragon in the air. For that, he needed his Firebolt. And for his Fire\-bolt, he needed \emdash\par
\par
\ldblquote Hermione,\rdblquote  Harry whispered, when he had sped into greenhouse three minutes later, uttering a hurried apology to Professor Sprout as he passed her. \ldblquote Hermione \emdash  I need you to help me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What d\rquote you think I\rquote ve been trying to do, Harry?\rdblquote  she whis\-pered back, her eyes round with anxiety over the top of the quiver\-ing Flutterby Bush she was pruning.\par
