\par
Harry had been focusing so hard on learning the Summoning Charm that evening that some of his blind panic had left him. It re\-turned in full measure, however, on the following morning. The at\-mosphere in the school was one of great tension and excitement. Lessons were to stop at midday, giving all the students time to get down to the dragons\rquote  enclosure \emdash  though of course, they didn\rquote t yet know what they would find there.\par
Harry felt oddly separate from everyone around him, whether they were wishing him good luck or hissing \ldblquote\i We\rquote ll have a box of tis\-sues ready, Potter\i0\rdblquote  as he passed. It was a state of nervousness so ad\-vanced that he wondered whether he mightn\rquote t just lose his head when they tried to lead him out to his dragon, and start trying to curse everyone in sight. Time was behaving in a more peculiar fash\-ion than ever, rushing past in great dollops, so that one moment he seemed to be sitting down in his first lesson, History of Magic, and the next, walking into lunch \'85 and then (where had the morning gone? the last of the dragon-free hours?), Professor McGonagall was hurrying over to him in the Great Hall. Lots of people were watching.\par
\ldblquote Potter, the champions have to come down onto the grounds now. \'85 You have to get ready for your first task.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Harry, standing up, his fork falling onto his plate with a clatter.\par
\ldblquote Good luck, Harry,\rdblquote  Hermione whispered. \ldblquote You\rquote ll be fine!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry in a voice that was most unlike his own.\par
He left the Great Hall with Professor McGonagall. She didn\rquote t seem herself either; in fact, she looked nearly as anxious as Her\-mione. As she walked him down the stone steps and out into the cold November afternoon, she put her hand on his shoulder.\par
\ldblquote Now, don\rquote t panic,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote just keep a cool head. \'85 We\rquote ve got wizards standing by to control the situation if it gets out of hand. \'85 The main thing is just to do your best, and nobody will think any the worse of you. \'85 Are you all right?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  Harry heard himself say. \ldblquote Yes, I\rquote m fine.\rdblquote\par
She was leading him toward the place where the dragons were, around the edge of the forest, but when they approached the clump of trees behind which the enclosure would be clearly visible, Harry saw that a tent had been erected, its entrance facing them, screen\-ing the dragons from view.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re to go in here with the other champions,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, in a rather shaky sort of voice, \ldblquote and wait for your turn, Potter. Mr. Bagman is in there \'85 he\rquote ll be telling you the \emdash  the procedure. \'85 Good luck.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry, in a flat, distant voice. She left him at the entrance of the tent. Harry went inside.\par
Fleur Delacour was sitting in a corner on a low wooden stool. She didn\rquote t look nearly as composed as usual, but rather pale and clammy. Viktor Krum looked even surlier than usual, which Harry supposed was his way of showing nerves. Cedric was pacing up and down. When Harry entered, Cedric gave him a small smile, which Harry returned, feeling the muscles in his face working rather hard, as though they had forgotten how to do it.\par
\ldblquote Harry! Good-o!\rdblquote  said Bagman happily, looking around at him. \ldblquote Come in, come in, make yourself at home!\rdblquote\par
Bagman looked somehow like a slightly overblown cartoon fig\-ure, standing amid all the pale-faced champions. He was wearing his old Wasp robes again.\par
\ldblquote Well, now we\rquote re all here \emdash  time to fill you in!\rdblquote  said Bagman brightly. \ldblquote When the audience has assembled, I\rquote m going to be offering each of you this bag\rdblquote  \emdash  he held up a small sack of purple silk and shook it at them \emdash  \ldblquote from which you will each select a small model of the thing you are about to face! There are different \emdash  er \emdash  varieties, you see. And I have to tell you something else too \'85 ah, yes \'85 your task is to \i collect the golden egg\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Harry glanced around. Cedric had nodded once, to show that he understood Bagman\rquote s words, and then started pacing around the tent again; he looked slightly green. Fleur Delacour and Krum hadn\rquote t reacted at all. Perhaps they thought they might be sick if they opened their mouths; that was certainly how Harry felt. But they, at least, had volunteered for this. \'85\par
And in no time at all, hundreds upon hundreds of pairs of feet could be heard passing the tent, their owners talking excitedly, laughing, joking. \'85 Harry felt as separate from the crowd as though they were a different species. And then \emdash  it seemed like about a second later to Harry \emdash  Bagman was opening the neck of the purple silk sack.\par
\ldblquote Ladies first,\rdblquote  he said, offering it to Fleur Delacour.\par
She put a shaking hand inside the bag and drew out a tiny, per\-fect model of a dragon \emdash  a Welsh Green. It had the number two around its neck. And Harry knew, by the fact that Fleur showed no sign of surprise, but rather a determined resignation, that he had been right: Madame Maxime had told her what was coming.\par
The same held true for Krum. He pulled out the scarlet Chinese Fireball. It had a number three around its neck. He didn\rquote t even blink, just sat back down and stared at the ground.\par
Cedric put his hand into the bag, and out came the blueish-gray Swedish Short-Snout, the number one tied around its neck. Know\-ing what was left, Harry put his hand into the silk bag and pulled out the Hungarian Horntail, and the number four. It stretched its wings as he looked down at it, and bared its minuscule fangs.\par
\ldblquote Well, there you are!\rdblquote  said Bagman. \ldblquote You have each pulled out the dragon you will face, and the numbers refer to the order in which you are to take on the dragons, do you see? Now, I\rquote m going to have to leave you in a moment, because I\rquote m commentating. Mr. Diggory, you\rquote re first, just go out into the enclosure when you hear a whistle, all right? Now \'85 Harry \'85 could I have a quick word? Outside?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Er \'85 yes,\rdblquote  said Harry blankly, and he got up and went out of the tent with Bagman, who walked him a short distance away, into the trees, and then turned to him with a fatherly expression on his face.\par
\ldblquote Feeling all right, Harry? Anything I can get you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I \emdash  no, nothing.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Got a plan?\rdblquote  said Bagman, lowering his voice conspiratorially. \ldblquote Because I don\rquote t mind sharing a few pointers, if you\rquote d like them, you know. I mean,\rdblquote  Bagman continued, lowering his voice still fur\-ther, \ldblquote you\rquote re the underdog here, Harry. \'85 Anything I can do to help \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry so quickly he knew he had sounded rude, \ldblquote no \emdash  I \emdash  I know what I\rquote m going to do, thanks.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nobody would \i know,\i0  Harry,\rdblquote  said Bagman, winking at him.\par
\ldblquote No, I\rquote m fine,\rdblquote  said Harry, wondering why he kept telling peo\-ple this, and wondering whether he had ever been less fine. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got a plan worked out, I \emdash\rdblquote\par
A whistle had blown somewhere.\par
\ldblquote Good lord, I\rquote ve got to run!\rdblquote  said Bagman in alarm, and he hur\-ried off.\par
Harry walked back to the tent and saw Cedric emerging from it, greener than ever. Harry tried to wish him luck as he walked past, but all that came out of his mouth was a sort of hoarse grunt.\par
Harry went back inside to Fleur and Krum. Seconds later, they heard the roar of the crowd, which meant Cedric had entered the enclosure and was now face-to-face with the living counterpart of his model. \'85\par
It was worse than Harry could ever have imagined, sitting there and listening. The crowd screamed \'85 yelled \'85 gasped like a sin\-gle many-headed entity, as Cedric did whatever he was doing to get past the Swedish Short-Snout. Krum was still staring at the ground. Fleur had now taken to retracing Cedric\rquote s steps, around and around the tent. And Bagman\rquote s commentary made everything much, much worse. \'85 Horrible pictures formed in Harry\rquote s mind as he heard: \ldblquote Oooh, narrow miss there, very narrow\rdblquote  \'85 \ldblquote He\rquote s tak\-ing risks, this one!\rdblquote  \'85 \ldblquote\i Clever\i0  move \emdash  pity it didn\rquote t work!\rdblquote\par
And then, after about fifteen minutes, Harry heard the deafen\-ing roar that could mean only one thing: Cedric had gotten past his dragon and captured the golden egg.\par
\ldblquote Very good indeed!\rdblquote  Bagman was shouting. \ldblquote And now the marks from the judges!\rdblquote\par
But he didn\rquote t shout out the marks; Harry supposed the judges were holding them up and showing them to the crowd.\par
\ldblquote One down, three to go!\rdblquote  Bagman yelled as the whistle blew again. \ldblquote Miss Delacour, if you please!\rdblquote\par
Fleur was trembling from head to foot; Harry felt more warmly toward her than he had done so far as she left the tent with her head held high and her hand clutching her wand. He and Krum were left alone, at opposite sides of the tent, avoiding each other\rquote s gaze.\par
The same process started again. \'85 \ldblquote Oh I\rquote m not sure that was wise!\rdblquote  they could hear Bagman shouting gleefully. \ldblquote Oh \'85 nearly! Careful now \'85 good lord, I thought she\rquote d had it then!\rdblquote\par
Ten minutes later, Harry heard the crowd erupt into applause once more. \'85 Fleur must have been successful too. A pause, while Fleur\rquote s marks were being shown \'85 more clapping \'85 then, for the third time, the whistle.\par
\ldblquote And here comes Mr. Krum!\rdblquote  cried Bagman, and Krum slouched out, leaving Harry quite alone.\par
He felt much more aware of his body than usual; very aware of the way his heart was pumping fast, and his fingers tingling with fear \'85 yet at the same time, he seemed to be outside himself, see\-ing the walls of the tent, and hearing the crowd, as though from far away. \'85\par
\ldblquote Very daring!\rdblquote  Bagman was yelling, and Harry heard the Chi\-nese Fireball emit a horrible, roaring shriek, while the crowd drew its collective breath. \ldblquote That\rquote s some nerve he\rquote s showing \emdash  and \emdash  yes, he\rquote s got the egg!\rdblquote\par
Applause shattered the wintery air like breaking glass; Krum had finished \emdash  it would be Harry\rquote s turn any moment.\par
He stood up, noticing dimly that his legs seemed to be made of marshmallow. He waited. And then he heard the whistle blow. He walked out through the entrance of the tent, the panic rising into a crescendo inside him. And now he was walking past the trees, through a gap in the enclosure fence.\par
He saw everything in front of him as though it was a very highly colored dream. There were hundreds and hundreds of faces staring down at him from stands that had been magicked there since he\rquote d last stood on this spot. And there was the Horntail, at the other end of the enclosure, crouched low over her clutch of eggs, her wings half-furled, her evil, yellow eyes upon him, a monstrous, scaly, black lizard, thrashing her spiked tail, leaving yard-long gouge marks in the hard ground. The crowd was making a great deal of noise, but whether friendly or not, Harry didn\rquote t know or care. It was time to do what he had to do \'85 to focus his mind, entirely and absolutely, upon the thing that was his only chance. \'85\par
He raised his wand.\par
\ldblquote\i Accio Firebolt\i0 !\rdblquote  he shouted.\par
Harry waited, every fiber of him hoping, praying. \'85 If it hadn\rquote t worked \'85 if it wasn\rquote t coming \'85 He seemed to be looking at everything around him through some sort of shimmering, trans\-parent barrier, like a heat haze, which made the enclosure and the hundreds of faces around him swim strangely. \'85\par
And then he heard it, speeding through the air behind him; he turned and saw his Firebolt hurtling toward him around the edge of the woods, soaring into the enclosure, and stopping dead in midair beside him, waiting for him to mount. The crowd was mak\-ing even more noise. \'85 Bagman was shouting something \'85 but Harry\rquote s ears were not working properly anymore \'85 listening wasn\rquote t important. \'85\par
He swung his leg over the broom and kicked off from the ground. And a second later, something miraculous happened. \'85\par
As he soared upward, as the wind rushed through his hair, as the crowd\rquote s faces became mere flesh-colored pinpricks below, and the Horntail shrank to the size of a dog, he realized that he had left not only the ground behind, but also his fear. \'85 He was back where he belonged. \'85\par
This was just another Quidditch match, that was all \'85 just an\-other Quidditch match, and that Horntail was just another ugly opposing team. \'85\par
He looked down at the clutch of eggs and spotted the gold one, gleaming against its cement-colored fellows, residing safely be\-tween the dragon\rquote s front legs. \ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  Harry told himself, \ldblquote diver\-sionary tactics \'85 let\rquote s go. \'85\rdblquote\par
He dived. The Horntail\rquote s head followed him; he knew what it was going to do and pulled out of the dive just in time; a jet of fire had been released exactly where he would have been had he not swerved away \'85 but Harry didn\rquote t care \'85 that was no more than dodging a Bludger. \'85\par
\ldblquote Great Scott, he can fly!\rdblquote  yelled Bagman as the crowd shrieked and gasped. \ldblquote Are you watching this, Mr. Krum?\rdblquote\par
Harry soared higher in a circle; the Horntail was still following his progress; its head revolving on its long neck \emdash  if he kept this up, it would be nicely dizzy \emdash  but better not push it too long, or it would be breathing fire again \emdash\par
Harry plummeted just as the Horntail opened its mouth, but this time he was less lucky \emdash  he missed the flames, but the tail came whipping up to meet him instead, and as he swerved to the left, one of the long spikes grazed his shoulder, ripping his robes \emdash\par
He could feel it stinging, he could hear screaming and groans from the crowd, but the cut didn\rquote t seem to be deep. \'85 Now he zoomed around the back of the Horntail, and a possibility occurred to him. \'85\par
The Horntail didn\rquote t seem to want to take off, she was too pro\-tective of her eggs. Though she writhed and twisted, furling and unfurling her wings and keeping those fearsome yellow eyes on Harry, she was afraid to move too far from them \'85 but he had to persuade her to do it, or he\rquote d never get near them. \'85 The trick was to do it carefully, gradually. \'85\par
He began to fly, first this way, then the other, not near enough to make her breathe fire to stave him off, but still posing a sufficient threat to ensure she kept her eyes on him. Her head swayed this way and that, watching him out of those vertical pupils, her fangs bared. \'85\par
He flew higher. The Horntail\rquote s head rose with him, her neck now stretched to its fullest extent, still swaying, like a snake before its charmer. \'85\par
Harry rose a few more feet, and she let out a roar of exaspera\-tion. He was like a fly to her, a fly she was longing to swat; her tail thrashed again, but he was too high to reach now. \'85 She shot fire into the air, which he dodged. \'85 Her jaws opened wide. \'85\par
\ldblquote Come on,\rdblquote  Harry hissed, swerving tantalizingly above her, \ldblquote come on, come and get me \'85 up you get now \'85\rdblquote\par
And then she reared, spreading her great, black, leathery wings at last, as wide as those of a small airplane \emdash  and Harry dived. Before the dragon knew what he had done, or where he had dis\-appeared to, he was speeding toward the ground as fast as he could go, toward the eggs now unprotected by her clawed front legs \emdash  he had taken his hands off his Firebolt \emdash  he had seized the golden egg \emdash\par
And with a huge spurt of speed, he was off, he was soaring out over the stands, the heavy egg safely under his uninjured arm, and it was as though somebody had just turned the volume back up \emdash  for the first time, he became properly aware of the noise of the crowd, which was screaming and applauding as loudly as the Irish supporters at the World Cup \emdash\par
\ldblquote Look at that!\rdblquote  Bagman was yelling. \ldblquote Will you look at that! Our youngest champion is quickest to get his egg! Well, this is going to shorten the odds on Mr. Potter!\rdblquote\par
Harry saw the dragon keepers rushing forward to subdue the Horntail, and, over at the entrance to the enclosure, Professor McGonagall, Professor Moody, and Hagrid hurrying to meet him, all of them waving him toward them, their smiles evident even from this distance. He flew back over the stands, the noise of the crowd pounding his eardrums, and came in smoothly to land, his heart lighter than it had been in weeks. \'85 He had got through the first task, he had survived. \'85\par
\ldblquote That was excellent, Potter!\rdblquote  cried Professor McGonagall as he got off the Firebolt \emdash  which from her was extravagant praise. He noticed that her hand shook as she pointed at his shoulder. \ldblquote You\rquote ll need to see Madam Pomfrey before the judges give out your score. \'85 Over there, she\rquote s had to mop up Diggory already. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeh did it, Harry!\rdblquote  said Hagrid hoarsely. \ldblquote Yeh did it! An\rquote  agains\rquote  the Horntail an\rquote  all, an\rquote  yeh know Charlie said that was the wors\rquote  \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thanks, Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Harry loudly, so that Hagrid wouldn\rquote t blunder on and reveal that he had shown Harry the dragons beforehand.\par
Professor Moody looked very pleased too; his magical eye was dancing in its socket.\par
\ldblquote Nice and easy does the trick, Potter,\rdblquote  he growled.\par
\ldblquote Right then, Potter, the first aid tent, please \'85\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall.\par
Harry walked out of the enclosure, still panting, and saw Madam Pomfrey standing at the mouth of a second tent, looking worried.\par
\ldblquote Dragons!\rdblquote  she said, in a disgusted tone, pulling Harry inside. The tent was divided into cubicles; he could make out Cedric\rquote s shadow through the canvas, but Cedric didn\rquote t seem to be badly in\-jured; he was sitting up, at least. Madam Pomfrey examined Harry\rquote s shoulder, talking furiously all the while. \ldblquote Last year demen\-tors, this year dragons, what are they going to bring into this school next? You\rquote re very lucky \'85 this is quite shallow \'85 it\rquote ll need clean\-ing before I heal it up, though. \'85\rdblquote\par
She cleaned the cut with a dab of some purple liquid that smoked and stung, but then poked his shoulder with her wand, and he felt it heal instantly.\par
\ldblquote Now, just sit quietly for a minute \emdash  \i sit\i0 ! And then you can go and get your score.\rdblquote\par
She bustled out of the tent and he heard her go next door and say, \ldblquote How does it feel now, Diggory?\rdblquote\par
Harry didn\rquote t want to sit still: He was too full of adrenaline. He got to his feet, wanting to see what was going on outside, but be\-fore he\rquote d reached the mouth of the tent, two people had come dart\-ing inside \emdash  Hermione, followed closely by Ron.\par
\ldblquote Harry, you were brilliant!\rdblquote  Hermione said squeakily. There were fingernail marks on her face where she had been clutching it in fear. \ldblquote You were amazing! You really were!\rdblquote\par
But Harry was looking at Ron, who was very white and staring at Harry as though he were a ghost.\par
\ldblquote Harry,\rdblquote  he said, very seriously, \ldblquote whoever put your name in that goblet \emdash  I \emdash  I reckon they\rquote re trying to do you in!\rdblquote\par
It was as though the last few weeks had never happened \emdash  as though Harry were meeting Ron for the first time, right after he\rquote d been made champion.\par
\ldblquote Caught on, have you?\rdblquote  said Harry coldly. \ldblquote Took you long enough.\rdblquote\par
Hermione stood nervously between them, looking from one to the other. Ron opened his mouth uncertainly. Harry knew Ron was about to apologize and suddenly he found he didn\rquote t need to hear it.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s okay,\rdblquote  he said, before Ron could get the words out. \ldblquote Forget it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Ron, \ldblquote I shouldn\rquote t\rquote ve \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i Forget it,\i0\rdblquote  Harry said.\par
Ron grinned nervously at him, and Harry grinned back.\par
Hermione burst into tears.\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s nothing to cry about!\rdblquote  Harry told her, bewildered.\par
\ldblquote You two are so \i stupid\i0 !\rdblquote  she shouted, stamping her foot on the ground, tears splashing down her front. Then, before either of them could stop her, she had given both of them a hug and dashed away, now positively howling.\par
\ldblquote Barking mad,\rdblquote  said Ron, shaking his head. \ldblquote Harry, c\rquote mon, they\rquote ll be putting up your scores. \'85\rdblquote\par
Picking up the golden egg and his Firebolt, feeling more elated than he would have believed possible an hour ago, Harry ducked out of the tent, Ron by his side, talking fast.\par
\ldblquote You were the best, you know, no competition. Cedric did this weird thing where he Transfigured a rock on the ground \'85 turned it into a dog \'85 he was trying to make the dragon go for the dog instead of him. Well, it was a pretty cool bit of Transfiguration, and it sort of worked, because he did get the egg, but he got burned as well \emdash  the dragon changed its mind halfway through and decided it would rather have him than the Labrador; he only just got away. And that Fleur girl tried this sort of charm, I think she was trying to put it into a trance \emdash  well, that kind of worked too, it went all sleepy, but then it snored, and this great jet of flame shot out, and her skirt caught fire \emdash  she put it out with a bit of water out of her wand. And Krum \emdash  you won\rquote t believe this, but he didn\rquote t even think of flying! He was probably the best after you, though. Hit it with some sort of spell right in the eye. Only thing is, it went tram\-pling around in agony and squashed half the real eggs \emdash  they took marks off for that, he wasn\rquote t supposed to do any damage to them.\rdblquote\par
Ron drew breath as he and Harry reached the edge of the enclo\-sure. Now that the Horntail had been taken away, Harry could see where the five judges were sitting \emdash  right at the other end, in raised seats draped in gold.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s marks out of ten from each one,\rdblquote  Ron said, and Harry, squinting up the field, saw the first judge \emdash  Madame Maxime \emdash  raise her wand in the air. What looked like a long silver ribbon shot out of it, which twisted itself into a large figure eight.\par
\ldblquote Not bad!\rdblquote  said Ron as the crowd applauded. \ldblquote I suppose she took marks off for your shoulder. \'85\rdblquote\par
Mr. Crouch came next. He shot a number nine into the air.\par
\ldblquote Looking good!\rdblquote  Ron yelled, thumping Harry on the back.\par
Next, Dumbledore. He too put up a nine. The crowd was cheer\-ing harder than ever.\par
Ludo Bagman \emdash  \i ten.\i0\par
\ldblquote Ten?\rdblquote  said Harry in disbelief. \ldblquote But \'85 I got hurt. \'85 What\rquote s he playing at?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Harry, don\rquote t complain!\rdblquote  Ron yelled excitedly.\par
And now Karkaroff raised his wand. He paused for a moment, and then a number shot out of his wand too \emdash  four.\par
\ldblquote\i What\i0 ?\rdblquote  Ron bellowed furiously. \ldblquote\i Four\i0 ? You lousy, biased scum\-bag, you gave Krum ten!\rdblquote\par
But Harry didn\rquote t care, he wouldn\rquote t have cared if Karkaroff had given him zero; Ron\rquote s indignation on his behalf was worth about a hundred points to him. He didn\rquote t tell Ron this, of course, but his heart felt lighter than air as he turned to leave the enclosure. And it wasn\rquote t just Ron \'85 those weren\rquote t only Gryffindors cheering in the crowd. When it had come to it, when they had seen what he was facing, most of the school had been on his side as well as Cedric\rquote s. \'85 He didn\rquote t care about the Slytherins, he could stand whatever they threw at him now.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re tied in first place, Harry! You and Krum!\rdblquote  said Charlie Weasley, hurrying to meet them as they set off back toward the school. \ldblquote Listen, I\rquote ve got to run, I\rquote ve got to go and send Mum an owl, I swore I\rquote d tell her what happened \emdash  but that was unbeliev\-able! Oh yeah \emdash  and they told me to tell you you\rquote ve got to hang around for a few more minutes. \'85 Bagman wants a word, back in the champions\rquote  tent.\rdblquote\par
Ron said he would wait, so Harry reentered the tent, which somehow looked quite different now: friendly and welcoming. He thought back to how he\rquote d felt while dodging the Horntail, and compared it to the long wait before he\rquote d walked out to face it. \'85 There was no comparison; the wait had been immeasurably worse.\par
Fleur, Cedric, and Krum all came in together. One side of Cedric\rquote s face was covered in a thick orange paste, which was pre\-sumably mending his burn. He grinned at Harry when he saw him.\par
\ldblquote Good one, Harry.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And you,\rdblquote  said Harry, grinning back.\par
\ldblquote Well done, \i all\i0  of you!\rdblquote  said Ludo Bagman, bouncing into the tent and looking as pleased as though he personally had just got past a dragon. \ldblquote Now, just a quick few words. You\rquote ve got a nice long break before the second task, which will take place at half past nine on the morning of February the twenty-fourth \emdash  but we\rquote re giving you something to think about in the meantime! If you look down at those golden eggs you\rquote re all holding, you will see that they open \'85 see the hinges there? You need to solve the clue inside the egg \emdash  because it will tell you what the second task is, and enable you to prepare for it! All clear? Sure? Well, off you go, then!\rdblquote\par
Harry left the tent, rejoined Ron, and they started to walk back around the edge of the forest, talking hard; Harry wanted to hear what the other champions had done in more detail. Then, as they rounded the clump of trees behind which Harry had first heard the dragons roar, a witch leapt out from behind them.\par
It was Rita Skeeter. She was wearing acid-green robes today; the Quick-Quotes Quill in her hand blended perfectly against them.\par
\ldblquote Congratulations, Harry!\rdblquote  she said, beaming at him. \ldblquote I wonder if you could give me a quick word? How you felt facing that dragon? How you feel \i now,\i0  about the fairness of the scoring?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, you can have a word,\rdblquote  said Harry savagely. \ldblquote\i Good-bye.\i0\rdblquote\par
And he set off back to the castle with Ron.\par
