Harry, Ron, and Hermione went up to the Owlery that evening to find Pigwidgeon, so that Harry could send Sirius a letter telling him that he had managed to get past his dragon unscathed. On the way, Harry filled Ron in on everything Sirius had told him about Karkaroff. Though shocked at first to hear that Karkaroff had been a Death Eater, by the time they en\-tered the Owlery Ron was saying that they ought to have suspected it all along.\par
\ldblquote Fits, doesn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Remember what Malfoy said on the train, about his dad being friends with Karkaroff? Now we know where they knew each other. They were probably running around in masks together at the World Cup. \'85 I\rquote ll tell you one thing, though, Harry, if it \i was\i0  Karkaroff who put your name in the gob\-let, he\rquote s going to be feeling really stupid now, isn\rquote t he? Didn\rquote t work, did it? You only got a scratch! Come here \emdash  I\rquote ll do it \emdash\rdblquote\par
Pigwidgeon was so overexcited at the idea of a delivery he was flying around and around Harry\rquote s head, hooting incessantly. Ron snatched Pigwidgeon out of the air and held him still while Harry attached the letter to his leg.\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s no way any of the other tasks are going to be that dan\-gerous, how could they be?\rdblquote  Ron went on as he carried Pigwidgeon to the window. \ldblquote You know what? I reckon you could win this tour\-nament, Harry, I\rquote m serious.\rdblquote\par
Harry knew that Ron was only saying this to make up for his be\-havior of the last few weeks, but he appreciated it all the same. Hermione, however, leaned against the Owlery wall, folded her arms, and frowned at Ron.\par
\ldblquote Harry\rquote s got a long way to go before he finishes this tourna\-ment,\rdblquote  she said seriously. \ldblquote If that was the first task, I hate to think what\rquote s coming next.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Right little ray of sunshine, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote You and Professor Trelawney should get together sometime.\rdblquote\par
He threw Pigwidgeon out of the window. Pigwidgeon plum\-meted twelve feet before managing to pull himself back up again; the letter attached to his leg was much longer and heavier than usual \emdash  Harry hadn\rquote t been able to resist giving Sirius a blow-by-blow account of exactly how he had swerved, circled, and dodged the Horntail. They watched Pigwidgeon disappear into the dark\-ness, and then Ron said, \ldblquote Well, we\rquote d better get downstairs for your surprise party, Harry \emdash  Fred and George should have nicked enough food from the kitchens by now.\rdblquote\par
Sure enough, when they entered the Gryffindor common room it exploded with cheers and yells again. There were mountains of cakes and flagons of pumpkin juice and butterbeer on every surface; Lee Jordan had let off some Filibuster\rquote s Fireworks, so that the air was thick with stars and sparks; and Dean Thomas, who was very good at drawing, had put up some impressive new banners, most of which depicted Harry zooming around the Horntail\rquote s head on his Firebolt, though a couple showed Cedric with his head on fire.\par
Harry helped himself to food; he had almost forgotten what it was like to feel properly hungry, and sat down with Ron and Hermione. He couldn\rquote t believe how happy he felt; he had Ron back on his side, he\rquote d gotten through the first task, and he wouldn\rquote t have to face the second one for three months.\par
\ldblquote Blimey, this is heavy,\rdblquote  said Lee Jordan, picking up the golden egg, which Harry had left on a table, and weighing it in his hands. \ldblquote Open it, Harry, go on! Let\rquote s just see what\rquote s inside it!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s supposed to work out the clue on his own,\rdblquote  Hermione said swiftly. \ldblquote It\rquote s in the tournament rules. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I was supposed to work out how to get past the dragon on my own too,\rdblquote  Harry muttered, so only Hermione could hear him, and she grinned rather guiltily.\par
\ldblquote Yeah, go on, Harry, open it!\rdblquote  several people echoed.\par
Lee passed Harry the egg, and Harry dug his fingernails into the groove that ran all the way around it and prised it open.\par
It was hollow and completely empty \emdash  but the moment Harry opened it, the most horrible noise, a loud and screechy wailing, filled the room. The nearest thing to it Harry had ever heard was the ghost orchestra at Nearly Headless Nick\rquote s deathday party, who had all been playing the musical saw.\par
\ldblquote Shut it!\rdblquote  Fred bellowed, his hands over his ears.\par
\ldblquote What was that?\rdblquote  said Seamus Finnigan, staring at the egg as Harry slammed it shut again. \ldblquote Sounded like a banshee. \'85 Maybe you\rquote ve got to get past one of those next, Harry!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was someone being tortured!\rdblquote  said Neville, who had gone very white and spilled sausage rolls all over the floor. \ldblquote You\rquote re going to have to fight the Cruciatus Curse!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be a prat, Neville, that\rquote s illegal,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote They wouldn\rquote t use the Cruciatus Curse on the champions. I thought it sounded a bit like Percy singing \'85 maybe you\rquote ve got to attack him while he\rquote s in the shower, Harry.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Want a jam tart, Hermione?\rdblquote  said Fred.\par
Hermione looked doubtfully at the plate he was offering her. Fred grinned.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s all right,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I haven\rquote t done anything to them. It\rquote s the custard creams you\rquote ve got to watch \emdash\rdblquote\par
Neville, who had just bitten into a custard cream, choked and spat it out. Fred laughed.\par
\ldblquote Just my little joke, Neville. \'85\rdblquote\par
Hermione took a jam tart. Then she said, \ldblquote Did you get all this from the kitchens, Fred?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yep,\rdblquote  said Fred, grinning at her. He put on a high-pitched squeak and imitated a house-elf. \ldblquote  \lquote Anything we can get you, sir, anything at all!\rquote  They\rquote re dead helpful \'85 get me a roast ox if I said I was peckish.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How do you get in there?\rdblquote  Hermione said in an innocently casual sort of voice.\par
\ldblquote Easy,\rdblquote  said Fred, \ldblquote concealed door behind a painting of a bowl of fruit. Just tickle the pear, and it giggles and \emdash\rdblquote  He stopped and looked suspiciously at her. \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  said Hermione quickly.\par
\ldblquote Going to try and lead the house-elves out on strike now, are you?\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote Going to give up all the leaflet stuff and try and stir them up into rebellion?\rdblquote\par
Several people chortled. Hermione didn\rquote t answer.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t you go upsetting them and telling them they\rquote ve got to take clothes and salaries!\rdblquote  said Fred warningly \ldblquote You\rquote ll put them off their cooking!\rdblquote\par
Just then, Neville caused a slight diversion by turning into a large canary.\par
\ldblquote Oh \emdash  sorry, Neville!\rdblquote  Fred shouted over all the laughter. \ldblquote I for\-got \emdash  it \i was\i0  the custard creams we hexed \emdash\rdblquote\par
Within a minute, however, Neville had molted, and once his feathers had fallen off, he reappeared looking entirely normal. He even joined in laughing.\par
\ldblquote Canary Creams!\rdblquote  Fred shouted to the excitable crowd. \ldblquote George and I invented them \emdash  seven Sickles each, a bargain!\rdblquote\par
It was nearly one in the morning when Harry finally went up to the dormitory with Ron, Neville, Seamus, and Dean. Before he pulled the curtains of his four-poster shut, Harry set his tiny model of the Hungarian Horntail on the table next to his bed, where it yawned, curled up, and closed its eyes. \i Really,\i0  Harry thought, as he pulled the hangings on his four-poster closed, \i Hagrid had a point\i0  \'85 \i they were all right, really, dragons. \'85\i0\par
\par
The start of December brought wind and sleet to Hogwarts. Drafty though the castle always was in winter, Harry was glad of its fires and thick walls every time he passed the Durmstrang ship on the lake, which was pitching in the high winds, its black sails billowing against the dark skies. He thought the Beauxbatons caravan was likely to be pretty chilly too. Hagrid, he noticed, was keeping Madame Maxime\rquote s horses well provided with their preferred drink of single-malt whiskey; the fumes wafting from the trough in the corner of their paddock was enough to make the entire Care of Magical Creatures class light-headed. This was unhelpful, as they were still tending the horrible skrewts and needed their wits about them.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not sure whether they hibernate or not,\rdblquote  Hagrid told the shivering class in the windy pumpkin patch next lesson. \ldblquote Thought we\rquote d jus\rquote  try an\rquote  see if they fancied a kip \'85 we\rquote ll jus\rquote  settle \rquote em down in these boxes. \'85\rdblquote\par
There were now only ten skrewts left; apparently their desire to kill one another had not been exercised out of them. Each of them was now approaching six feet in length. Their thick gray armor; their powerful, scuttling legs; their fire-blasting ends; their stings and their suckers, combined to make the skrewts the most repul\-sive things Harry had ever seen. The class looked dispiritedly at the enormous boxes Hagrid had brought out, all lined with pillows and fluffy blankets.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ll jus\rquote  lead \rquote em in here,\rdblquote  Hagrid said, \ldblquote an\rquote  put the lids on, and we\rquote ll see what happens.\rdblquote\par
But the skrewts, it transpired, did \i not\i0  hibernate, and did not ap\-preciate being forced into pillow-lined boxes and nailed in. Hagrid was soon yelling, \ldblquote Don\rquote  panic, now, don\rquote  panic!\rdblquote  while the skrewts rampaged around the pumpkin patch, now strewn with the smol\-dering wreckage of the boxes. Most of the class \emdash  Malfoy, Crabbe, and Goyle in the lead \emdash  had fled into Hagrid\rquote s cabin through the back door and barricaded themselves in; Harry, Ron, and Hermi\-one, however, were among those who remained outside trying to help Hagrid. Together they managed to restrain and tie up nine of the skrewts, though at the cost of numerous burns and cuts; finally, only one skrewt was left.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote  frighten him, now!\rdblquote  Hagrid shouted as Ron and Harry used their wands to shoot jets of fiery sparks at the skrewt, which was advancing menacingly on them, its sting arched, quivering, over its back. \ldblquote Jus\rquote  try an\rquote  slip the rope \rquote round his sting, so he won\rquote  hurt any o\rquote  the others!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, we wouldn\rquote t want that!\rdblquote  Ron shouted angrily as he and Harry backed into the wall of Hagrid\rquote s cabin, still holding the skrewt off with their sparks.\par
\ldblquote Well, well, well \'85 this \i does\i0  look like fun.\rdblquote\par
Rita Skeeter was leaning on Hagrid\rquote s garden fence, looking in at the mayhem. She was wearing a thick magenta cloak with a furry purple collar today, and her crocodile-skin handbag was over her arm.\par
Hagrid launched himself forward on top of the skrewt that was cornering Harry and Ron and flattened it; a blast of fire shot out of its end, withering the pumpkin plants nearby.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote re you?\rdblquote  Hagrid asked Rita Skeeter as he slipped a loop of rope around the skrewt\rquote s sting and tightened it.\par
\ldblquote Rita Skeeter, \i Daily Prophet\i0  reporter,\rdblquote  Rita replied, beaming at him. Her gold teeth glinted.\par
\ldblquote Thought Dumbledore said you weren\rquote  allowed inside the school anymore,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, frowning slightly as he got off the slightly squashed skrewt and started tugging it over to its fellows.\par
Rita acted as though she hadn\rquote t heard what Hagrid had said.\par
\ldblquote What are these fascinating creatures called?\rdblquote  she asked, beam\-ing still more widely.\par
\ldblquote Blast-Ended Skrewts,\rdblquote  grunted Hagrid.\par
\ldblquote Really?\rdblquote  said Rita, apparently full of lively interest. \ldblquote I\rquote ve never heard of them before \'85 where do they come from?\rdblquote\par
Harry noticed a dull red flush rising up out of Hagrid\rquote s wild black beard, and his heart sank. Where \i had\i0  Hagrid got the skrewts from? Hermione, who seemed to be thinking along these lines, said quickly, \ldblquote They\rquote re very interesting, aren\rquote t they? Aren\rquote t they, Harry?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What? Oh yeah \'85 ouch \'85 interesting,\rdblquote  said Harry as she stepped on his foot.\par
\ldblquote Ah, \i you\rquote re\i0  here, Harry!\rdblquote  said Rita Skeeter as she looked around. \ldblquote So you like Care of Magical Creatures, do you? One of your fa\-vorite lessons?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry stoutly. Hagrid beamed at him.\par
\ldblquote Lovely,\rdblquote  said Rita. \ldblquote Really lovely. Been teaching long?\rdblquote  she added to Hagrid.\par
Harry noticed her eyes travel over Dean (who had a nasty cut across one cheek), Lavender (whose robes were badly singed), Sea\-mus (who was nursing several burnt fingers), and then to the cabin windows, where most of the class stood, their noses pressed against the glass waiting to see if the coast was clear.\par
\ldblquote This is o\rquote ny me second year,\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
\ldblquote Lovely\'85 I don\rquote t suppose you\rquote d like to give an interview, would you? Share some of your experience of magical creatures? The \i Prophet\i0  does a zoological column every Wednesday, as I\rquote m sure you know. We could feature these \emdash  er \emdash  Bang-Ended Scoots.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Blast-Ended Skrewts,\rdblquote  Hagrid said eagerly. \ldblquote Er \emdash  yeah, why not?\rdblquote\par
Harry had a very bad feeling about this, but there was no way of communicating it to Hagrid without Rita Skeeter seeing, so he had to stand and watch in silence as Hagrid and Rita Skeeter made arrangements to meet in the Three Broomsticks for a good long in\-terview later that week. Then the bell rang up at the castle, signal\-ing the end of the lesson.\par
\ldblquote Well, good-bye, Harry!\rdblquote  Rita Skeeter called merrily to him as he set off with Ron and Hermione. \ldblquote Until Friday night, then, Hagrid!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She\rquote ll twist everything he says,\rdblquote  Harry said under his breath.\par
\ldblquote Just as long as he didn\rquote t import those skrewts illegally or any\-thing,\rdblquote  said Hermione desperately. They looked at one another \emdash  it was exactly the sort of thing Hagrid might do.\par
\ldblquote Hagrid\rquote s been in loads of trouble before, and Dumbledore\rquote s never sacked him,\rdblquote  said Ron consolingly. \ldblquote Worst that can happen is Hagrid\rquote ll have to get rid of the skrewts. Sorry \'85 did I say worst? I meant best.\rdblquote\par
Harry and Hermione laughed, and, feeling slightly more cheer\-ful, went off to lunch.\par
Harry thoroughly enjoyed double Divination that afternoon; they were still doing star charts and predictions, but now that he and Ron were friends once more, the whole thing seemed very funny again. Professor Trelawney, who had been so pleased with the pair of them when they had been predicting their own horrific deaths, quickly became irritated as they sniggered through her explanation of the various ways in which Pluto could disrupt everyday life.\par
\ldblquote I would \i think,\i0\rdblquote  she said, in a mystical whisper that did not con\-ceal her obvious annoyance, \ldblquote that \i some\i0  of us\rdblquote  \emdash  she stared very meaningfully at Harry \emdash  \ldblquote might be a little less \i frivolous\i0  had they seen what I have seen during my crystal gazing last night. As I sat here, absorbed in my needlework, the urge to consult the orb over\-powered me. I arose, I settled myself before it, and I gazed into its crystalline depths \'85 and what do you think I saw gazing back at me?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote An ugly old bat in outsize specs?\rdblquote  Ron muttered under his breath.\par
Harry fought hard to keep his face straight.\par
\ldblquote\i Death,\i0  my dears.\rdblquote\par
Parvati and Lavender both put their hands over their mouths, looking horrified.\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney, nodding impressively, \ldblquote it comes, ever closer, it circles overhead like a vulture, ever lower \'85 ever lower over the castle. \'85\rdblquote\par
She stared pointedly at Harry, who yawned very widely and obviously.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote d be a bit more impressive if she hadn\rquote t done it about eighty times before,\rdblquote  Harry said as they finally regained the fresh air of the staircase beneath Professor Trelawney\rquote s room. \ldblquote But if I\rquote d dropped dead every time she\rquote s told me I\rquote m going to, I\rquote d be a medical miracle.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote d be a sort of extra-concentrated ghost,\rdblquote  said Ron, chortling, as they passed the Bloody Baron going in the opposite direction, his wide eyes staring sinisterly. \ldblquote At least we didn\rquote t get homework. I hope Hermione got loads off Professor Vector, I love not working when she is. \'85\rdblquote\par
But Hermione wasn\rquote t at dinner, nor was she in the library when they went to look for her afterward. The only person in there was Viktor Krum. Ron hovered behind the bookshelves for a while, watching Krum, debating in whispers with Harry whether he should ask for an autograph \emdash  but then Ron realized that six or seven girls were lurking in the next row of books, debating exactly the same thing, and he lost his enthusiasm for the idea.\par
\ldblquote Wonder where she\rquote s got to?\rdblquote  Ron said as he and Harry went back to Gryffindor Tower.\par
\ldblquote Dunno \'85 balderdash.\rdblquote\par
But the Fat Lady had barely begun to swing forward when the sound of racing feet behind them announced Hermione\rquote s arrival.\par
\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  she panted, skidding to a halt beside him (the Fat Lady stared down at her, eyebrows raised). \ldblquote Harry, you\rquote ve got to come \emdash  you\rquote ve \i got\i0  to come, the most amazing thing\rquote s happened \emdash  please \emdash\rdblquote\par
She seized Harry\rquote s arm and started to try to drag him back along the corridor.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote  Harry said.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll show you when we get there \emdash  oh come on, quick \emdash\rdblquote\par
Harry looked around at Ron; he looked back at Harry, intrigued.\par
\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  Harry said, starting off back down the corridor with Hermione, Ron hurrying to keep up.\par
\ldblquote Oh don\rquote t mind me!\rdblquote  the Fat Lady called irritably after them. \ldblquote Don\rquote t apologize for bothering me! I\rquote ll just hang here, wide open, until you get back, shall I?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, thanks!\rdblquote  Ron shouted over his shoulder.\par
\ldblquote Hermione, where are we going?\rdblquote  Harry asked, after she had led them down through six floors, and started down the marble stair\-case into the entrance hall.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ll see, you\rquote ll see in a minute!\rdblquote  said Hermione excitedly.\par
She turned left at the bottom of the staircase and hurried toward the door through which Cedric Diggory had gone the night after the Goblet of Fire had regurgitated his and Harry\rquote s names. Harry had never been through here before. He and Ron followed Hermione down a flight of stone steps, but instead of ending up in a gloomy underground passage like the one that led to Snape\rquote s dun\-geon, they found themselves in a broad stone corridor, brightly lit with torches, and decorated with cheerful paintings that were mainly of food.\par
\ldblquote Oh hang on \'85\rdblquote  said Harry slowly, halfway down the corridor. \ldblquote Wait a minute, Hermione. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  She turned around to look at him, anticipation all over her face.\par
\ldblquote I know what this is about,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
He nudged Ron and pointed to the painting just behind Hermione. It showed a gigantic silver fruit bowl.\par
\ldblquote Hermione!\rdblquote  said Ron, cottoning on. \ldblquote You\rquote re trying to rope us into that spew stuff again!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, no, I\rquote m not!\rdblquote  she said hastily. \ldblquote And it\rquote s not \i spew,\i0  Ron \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Changed the name, have you?\rdblquote  said Ron, frowning at her. \ldblquote What are we now, then, the House-Elf Liberation Front? I\rquote m not barging into that kitchen and trying to make them stop work, I\rquote m not doing it \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not asking you to!\rdblquote  Hermione said impatiently. \ldblquote I came down here just now, to talk to them all, and I found \emdash  oh come \i on,\i0  Harry, I want to show you!\rdblquote\par
She seized his arm again, pulled him in front of the picture of the giant fruit bowl, stretched out her forefinger, and tickled the huge green pear. It began to squirm, chuckling, and suddenly turned into a large green door handle. Hermione seized it, pulled the door open, and pushed Harry hard in the back, forcing him inside.\par
He had one brief glimpse of an enormous, high-ceilinged room, large as the Great Hall above it, with mounds of glittering brass pots and pans heaped around the stone walls, and a great brick fire\-place at the other end, when something small hurtled toward him from the middle of the room, squealing, \ldblquote Harry Potter, sir! \i Harry Potter\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Next second all the wind had been knocked out of him as the squealing elf hit him hard in the midriff, hugging him so tightly he thought his ribs would break.\par
\ldblquote D-Dobby?\rdblquote  Harry gasped.\par
\ldblquote It \i is\i0  Dobby, sir, it is!\rdblquote  squealed the voice from somewhere around his navel. \ldblquote Dobby has been hoping and hoping to see Harry Potter, sir, and Harry Potter has come to see him, sir!\rdblquote\par
Dobby let go and stepped back a few paces, beaming up at Harry, his enormous, green, tennis-ball-shaped eyes brimming with tears of happiness. He looked almost exactly as Harry remem\-bered him; the pencil-shaped nose, the batlike ears, the long fingers and feet \emdash  all except the clothes, which were very different.\par
When Dobby had worked for the Malfoys, he had always worn the same filthy old pillowcase. Now, however, he was wearing the strangest assortment of garments Harry had ever seen; he had done an even worse job of dressing himself than the wizards at the World Cup. He was wearing a tea cozy for a hat, on which he had pinned a number of bright badges; a tie patterned with horseshoes over a bare chest, a pair of what looked like children\rquote s soccer shorts, and odd socks. One of these, Harry saw, was the black one Harry had removed from his own foot and tricked Mr. Malfoy into giving Dobby, thereby setting Dobby free. The other was covered in pink and orange stripes.\par
\ldblquote Dobby, what\rquote re you doing here?\rdblquote  Harry said in amazement.\par
\ldblquote Dobby has come to work at Hogwarts, sir!\rdblquote  Dobby squealed excitedly. \ldblquote Professor Dumbledore gave Dobby and Winky jobs, sir!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Winky?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote She\rquote s here too?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, sir, yes!\rdblquote  said Dobby, and he seized Harry\rquote s hand and pulled him off into the kitchen between the four long wooden tables that stood there. Each of these tables, Harry noticed as he passed them, was positioned exactly beneath the four House tables above, in the Great Hall. At the moment, they were clear of food, dinner having finished, but he supposed that an hour ago they had been laden with dishes that were then sent up through the ceiling to their counterparts above.\par
At least a hundred little elves were standing around the kitchen, beaming, bowing, and curtsying as Dobby led Harry past them. They were all wearing the same uniform: a tea towel stamped with the Hogwarts crest, and tied, as Winky\rquote s had been, like a toga.\par
Dobby stopped in front of the brick fireplace and pointed.\par
\ldblquote Winky, sir!\rdblquote  he said.\par
Winky was sitting on a stool by the fire. Unlike Dobby, she had obviously not foraged for clothes. She was wearing a neat little skirt and blouse with a matching blue hat, which had holes in it for her large ears. However, while every one of Dobby\rquote s strange collection of garments was so clean and well cared for that it looked brand-new, Winky was plainly not taking care of her clothes at all. There were soup stains all down her blouse and a burn in her skirt.\par
\ldblquote Hello, Winky,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Winky\rquote s lip quivered. Then she burst into tears, which spilled out of her great brown eyes and splashed down her front, just as they had done at the Quidditch World Cup.\par
\ldblquote Oh dear,\rdblquote  said Hermione. She and Ron had followed Harry and Dobby to the end of the kitchen. \ldblquote Winky, don\rquote t cry, please don\rquote t \'85\rdblquote\par
But Winky cried harder than ever. Dobby, on the other hand, beamed up at Harry.\par
\ldblquote Would Harry Potter like a cup of tea?\rdblquote  he squeaked loudly, over Winky\rquote s sobs.\par
\ldblquote Er \emdash  yeah, okay,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Instantly, about six house-elves came trotting up behind him, bearing a large silver tray laden with a teapot, cups for Harry, Ron, and Hermione, a milk jug, and a large plate of biscuits.\par
\ldblquote Good service!\rdblquote  Ron said, in an impressed voice. Hermione frowned at him, but the elves all looked delighted; they bowed very low and retreated.\par
\ldblquote How long have you been here, Dobby?\rdblquote  Harry asked as Dobby handed around the tea.\par
\ldblquote Only a week, Harry Potter, sir!\rdblquote  said Dobby happily. \ldblquote Dobby came to see Professor Dumbledore, sir. You see, sir, it is very diffi\-cult for a house-elf who has been dismissed to get a new position, sir, very difficult indeed \emdash\rdblquote\par
At this, Winky howled even harder, her squashed-tomato of a nose dribbling all down her front, though she made no effort to stem the flow.\par
\ldblquote Dobby has traveled the country for two whole years, sir, trying to find work!\rdblquote  Dobby squeaked. \ldblquote But Dobby hasn\rquote t found work, sir, because Dobby wants paying now!\rdblquote\par
The house-elves all around the kitchen, who had been listening and watching with interest, all looked away at these words, as though Dobby had said something rude and embarrassing. Hermione, however, said, \ldblquote Good for you, Dobby!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thank you, miss!\rdblquote  said Dobby, grinning toothily at her. \ldblquote But most wizards doesn\rquote t want a house-elf who wants paying, miss. \lquote That\rquote s not the point of a house-elf,\rquote  they says, and they slammed the door in Dobby\rquote s face! Dobby likes work, but he wants to wear clothes and he wants to be paid, Harry Potter. \'85 Dobby likes be\-ing free!\rdblquote\par
The Hogwarts house-elves had now started edging away from Dobby, as though he were carrying something contagious. Winky, however, remained where she was, though there was a definite in\-crease in the volume of her crying.\par
\ldblquote And then, Harry Potter, Dobby goes to visit Winky, and finds out Winky has been freed too, sir!\rdblquote  said Dobby delightedly.\par
At this, Winky flung herself forward off her stool and lay face\-down on the flagged stone floor, beating her tiny fists upon it and positively screaming with misery. Hermione hastily dropped down to her knees beside her and tried to comfort her, but nothing she said made the slightest difference. Dobby continued with his story, shouting shrilly over Winky\rquote s screeches.\par
\ldblquote And then Dobby had the idea, Harry Potter, sir! \lquote Why doesn\rquote t Dobby and Winky find work together?\rquote  Dobby says. \lquote Where is there enough work for two house-elves?\rquote  says Winky. And Dobby thinks, and it comes to him, sir! \i Hogwarts\i0 ! So Dobby and Winky came to see Professor Dumbledore, sir, and Professor Dumbledore took us on!\rdblquote\par
Dobby beamed very brightly, and happy tears welled in his eyes again.\par
\ldblquote And Professor Dumbledore says he will pay Dobby, sir, if Dobby wants paying! And so Dobby is a free elf, sir, and Dobby gets a Galleon a week and one day off a month!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s not very much!\rdblquote  Hermione shouted indignantly from the floor, over Winky\rquote s continued screaming and fist-beating.\par
\ldblquote Professor Dumbledore offered Dobby ten Galleons a week, and weekends off,\rdblquote  said Dobby, suddenly giving a little shiver, as though the prospect of so much leisure and riches were frightening, \ldblquote but Dobby beat him down, miss. \'85 Dobby likes freedom, miss, but he isn\rquote t wanting too much, miss, he likes work better.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And how much is Professor Dumbledore paying \i you,\i0  Winky?\rdblquote  Hermione asked kindly.\par
If she had thought this would cheer up Winky, she was wildly mistaken. Winky did stop crying, but when she sat up she was glar\-ing at Hermione through her massive brown eyes, her whole face sopping wet and suddenly furious.\par
\ldblquote Winky is a disgraced elf, but Winky is not yet getting paid!\rdblquote  she squeaked. \ldblquote Winky is not sunk so low as that! Winky is properly ashamed of being freed!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ashamed?\rdblquote  said Hermione blankly. \ldblquote But \emdash  Winky, come on! It\rquote s Mr. Crouch who should be ashamed, not you! You didn\rquote t do anything wrong, he was really horrible to you \emdash\rdblquote\par
But at these words, Winky clapped her hands over the holes in her hat, flattening her ears so that she couldn\rquote t hear a word, and screeched, \ldblquote You is not insulting my master, miss! You is not insult\-ing Mr. Crouch! Mr. Crouch is a good wizard, miss! Mr. Crouch is right to sack bad Winky!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Winky is having trouble adjusting, Harry Potter,\rdblquote  squeaked Dobby confidentially. \ldblquote Winky forgets she is not bound to Mr. Crouch anymore; she is allowed to speak her mind now, but she won\rquote t do it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t house-elves speak their minds about their masters, then?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\par
\ldblquote Oh no, sir, no,\rdblquote  said Dobby, looking suddenly serious. \ldblquote  \rquote Tis part of the house-elf\rquote s enslavement, sir. We keeps their secrets and our silence, sir. We upholds the family\rquote s honor, and we never speaks ill of them \emdash  though Professor Dumbledore told Dobby he does not insist upon this. Professor Dumbledore said we is free to \emdash  to \emdash\rdblquote\par
Dobby looked suddenly nervous and beckoned Harry closer. Harry bent forward. Dobby whispered, \ldblquote He said we is free to call him a \emdash  a barmy old codger if we likes, sir!\rdblquote\par
Dobby gave a frightened sort of giggle.\par
\ldblquote But Dobby is not wanting to, Harry Potter,\rdblquote  he said, talking normally again, and shaking his head so that his ears flapped. \ldblquote Dobby likes Professor Dumbledore very much, sir, and is proud to keep his secrets and our silence for him.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But you can say what you like about the Malfoys now?\rdblquote  Harry asked him, grinning.\par
A slightly fearful look came into Dobby\rquote s immense eyes.\par
\ldblquote Dobby \emdash  Dobby could,\rdblquote  he said doubtfully. He squared his small shoulders. \ldblquote Dobby could tell Harry Potter that his old mas\-ters were \emdash  were \emdash  \i bad Dark wizards\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Dobby stood for a moment, quivering all over, horror-struck by his own daring \emdash  then he rushed over to the nearest table and be\-gan banging his head on it very hard, squealing, \ldblquote\i Bad Dobby\i0 ! \i Bad Dobby\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Harry seized Dobby by the back of his tie and pulled him away from the table.\par
\ldblquote Thank you, Harry Potter, thank you,\rdblquote  said Dobby breathlessly, rubbing his head.\par
\ldblquote You just need a bit of practice,\rdblquote  Harry said.\par
\ldblquote Practice!\rdblquote  squealed Winky furiously. \ldblquote You is ought to be ashamed of yourself, Dobby, talking that way about your masters!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They isn\rquote t my masters anymore, Winky!\rdblquote  said Dobby defiantly. \ldblquote Dobby doesn\rquote t care what they think anymore!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh you is a bad elf, Dobby!\rdblquote  moaned Winky, tears leaking down her face once more. \ldblquote My poor Mr. Crouch, what is he doing without Winky? He is needing me, he is needing my help! I is look\-ing after the Crouches all my life, and my mother is doing it before me, and my grandmother is doing it before her \'85 oh what is they saying if they knew Winky was freed? Oh the shame, the shame!\rdblquote  She buried her face in her skirt again and bawled.\par
\ldblquote Winky,\rdblquote  said Hermione firmly, \ldblquote I\rquote m quite sure Mr. Crouch is get\-ting along perfectly well without you. We\rquote ve seen him, you know \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You is seeing my master?\rdblquote  said Winky breathlessly, raising her tearstained face out of her skirt once more and goggling at Hermione. \ldblquote You is seeing him here at Hogwarts?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote he and Mr. Bagman are judges in the Tri-wizard Tournament.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mr. Bagman comes too?\rdblquote  squeaked Winky, and to Harry\rquote s great surprise (and Ron\rquote s and Hermione\rquote s too, by the looks on their faces), she looked angry again. \ldblquote Mr. Bagman is a bad wizard! A very bad wizard! My master isn\rquote t liking him, oh no, not at all!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Bagman \emdash  bad?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Oh yes,\rdblquote  Winky said, nodding her head furiously. \ldblquote My master is telling Winky some things! But Winky is not saying \'85 Winky \emdash  Winky keeps her master\rquote s secrets. \'85\rdblquote\par
She dissolved yet again in tears; they could hear her sobbing into her skirt, \ldblquote Poor master, poor master, no Winky to help him no more!\par
They couldn\rquote t get another sensible word out of Winky. They left her to her crying and finished their tea, while Dobby chatted hap\-pily about his life as a free elf and his plans for his wages.\par
\ldblquote Dobby is going to buy a sweater next, Harry Potter!\rdblquote  he said happily, pointing at his bare chest.\par
\ldblquote Tell you what, Dobby,\rdblquote  said Ron, who seemed to have taken a great liking to the elf, \ldblquote I\rquote ll give you the one my mum knits me this Christmas, I always get one from her. You don\rquote t mind maroon, do you?\rdblquote\par
Dobby was delighted.\par
\ldblquote We might have to shrink it a bit to fit you,\rdblquote  Ron told him, \ldblquote but it\rquote ll go well with your tea cozy.\rdblquote\par
As they prepared to take their leave, many of the surrounding elves pressed in upon them, offering snacks to take back upstairs. Hermione refused, with a pained look at the way the elves kept bowing and curtsying, but Harry and Ron loaded their pockets with cream cakes and pies.\par
\ldblquote Thanks a lot!\rdblquote  Harry said to the elves, who had all clustered around the door to say good night. \ldblquote See you, Dobby!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Harry Potter \'85 can Dobby come and see you sometimes, sir?\rdblquote  Dobby asked tentatively.\par
\ldblquote  \rquote Course you can,\rdblquote  said Harry, and Dobby beamed.\par
\ldblquote You know what?\rdblquote  said Ron, once he, Hermione, and Harry had left the kitchens behind and were climbing the steps into the en\-trance hall again. \ldblquote All these years I\rquote ve been really impressed with Fred and George, nicking food from the kitchens \emdash  well, it\rquote s not exactly difficult, is it? They can\rquote t wait to give it away!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I think this is the best thing that could have happened to those elves, you know,\rdblquote  said Hermione, leading the way back up the mar\-ble staircase. \ldblquote Dobby coming to work here, I mean. The other elves will see how happy he is, being free, and slowly it\rquote ll dawn on them that they want that too!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s hope they don\rquote t look too closely at Winky,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Oh she\rquote ll cheer up,\rdblquote  said Hermione, though she sounded a bit doubtful. \ldblquote Once the shock\rquote s worn off, and she\rquote s got used to Hog\-warts, she\rquote ll see how much better off she is without that Crouch man.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She seems to love him,\rdblquote  said Ron thickly (he had just started on a cream cake).\par
\ldblquote Doesn\rquote t think much of Bagman, though, does she?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Wonder what Crouch says at home about him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Probably says he\rquote s not a very good Head of Department,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote and let\rquote s face it \'85 he\rquote s got a point, hasn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote d still rather work for him than old Crouch,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote At least Bagman\rquote s got a sense of humor.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t let Percy hear you saying that,\rdblquote  Hermione said, smiling slightly.\par
\ldblquote Yeah, well, Percy wouldn\rquote t want to work for anyone with a sense of humor, would he?\rdblquote  said Ron, now starting on a chocolate eclair. \ldblquote Percy wouldn\rquote t recognize a joke if it danced naked in front of him wearing Dobby\rquote s tea cozy.\rdblquote\par
