\ldblquote Potter! Weasley! \i Will you pay attention\i0 ?\rdblquote\par
Professor McGonagall\rquote s irritated voice cracked like a whip through the Transfiguration class on Thursday, and Harry and Ron both jumped and looked up.\par
It was the end of the lesson; they had finished their work; the guinea fowl they had been changing into guinea pigs had been shut away in a large cage on Professor McGonagall\rquote s desk (Neville\rquote s still had feathers); they had copied down their homework from the blackboard (\ldblquote\i Describe, with examples, the ways in which Transform\-ing Spells must be adapted when performing Cross-Species Switches\i0\rdblquote ). The bell was due to ring at any moment, and Harry and Ron, who had been having a sword fight with a couple of Fred and George\rquote s fake wands at the back of the class, looked up, Ron holding a tin parrot and Harry, a rubber haddock.\par
\ldblquote Now that Potter and Weasley have been kind enough to act their age,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, with an angry look at the pair of them as the head of Harry\rquote s haddock drooped and fell silently to the floor \emdash  Ron\rquote s parrot\rquote s beak had severed it moments before \emdash  \ldblquote I have something to say to you all.\par
\ldblquote The Yule Ball is approaching \emdash  a traditional part of the Tri-wizard Tournament and an opportunity for us to socialize with our foreign guests. Now, the ball will be open only to fourth years and above \emdash  although you may invite a younger student if you wish \emdash\rdblquote\par
Lavender Brown let out a shrill giggle. Parvati Patil nudged her hard in the ribs, her face working furiously as she too fought not to giggle. They both looked around at Harry. Professor McGonagall ignored them, which Harry thought was distinctly unfair, as she had just told off him and Ron.\par
\ldblquote Dress robes will be worn,\rdblquote  Professor McGonagall continued, \ldblquote and the ball will start at eight o\rquote clock on Christmas Day, finishing at midnight in the Great Hall. Now then \emdash\rdblquote\par
Professor McGonagall stared deliberately around the class.\par
\ldblquote The Yule Ball is of course a chance for us all to \emdash  er \emdash  let our hair down,\rdblquote  she said, in a disapproving voice.\par
Lavender giggled harder than ever, with her hand pressed hard against her mouth to stifle the sound. Harry could see what was funny this time: Professor McGonagall, with her hair in a tight bun, looked as though she had never let her hair down in any sense.\par
\ldblquote But that does NOT mean,\rdblquote  Professor McGonagall went on, \ldblquote that we will be relaxing the standards of behavior we expect from Hogwarts students. I will be most seriously displeased if a Gryffin\-dor student embarrasses the school in any way.\rdblquote\par
The bell rang, and there was the usual scuffle of activity as every\-one packed their bags and swung them onto their shoulders.\par
Professor McGonagall called above the noise, \ldblquote Potter \emdash  a word, if you please.\rdblquote\par
Assuming this had something to do with his headless rubber haddock, Harry proceeded gloomily to the teacher\rquote s desk. Professor McGonagall waited until the rest of the class had gone, and then said, \ldblquote Potter, the champions and their partners \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What partners?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Professor McGonagall looked suspiciously at him, as though she thought he was trying to be funny.\par
\ldblquote Your partners for the Yule Ball, Potter,\rdblquote  she said coldly. \ldblquote Your \i dance partners.\i0\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s insides seemed to curl up and shrivel.\par
\ldblquote Dance partners?\rdblquote  He felt himself going red. \ldblquote I don\rquote t dance,\rdblquote  he said quickly.\par
\ldblquote Oh yes, you do,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall irritably. \ldblquote That\rquote s what I\rquote m telling you. Traditionally, the champions and their part\-ners open the ball.\rdblquote\par
Harry had a sudden mental image of himself in a top hat and tails, accompanied by a girl in the sort of frilly dress Aunt Petunia always wore to Uncle Vernon\rquote s work parties.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not dancing,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\ldblquote It is traditional,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall firmly. \ldblquote You are a Hogwarts champion, and you will do what is expected of you as a representative of the school. So make sure you get yourself a part\-ner, Potter.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But \emdash  I don\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You heard me, Potter,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall in a very final sort of way.\par
\par
A week ago, Harry would have said finding a partner for a dance would be a cinch compared to taking on a Hungarian Horntail. But now that he had done the latter, and was facing the prospect of asking a girl to the ball, he thought he\rquote d rather have another round with the dragon.\par
Harry had never known so many people to put their names down to stay at Hogwarts for Christmas; he always did, of course, because the alternative was usually going back to Privet Drive, but he had always been very much in the minority before now. This year, however, everyone in the fourth year and above seemed to be staying, and they all seemed to Harry to be obsessed with the com\-ing ball \emdash  or at least all the girls were, and it was amazing how many girls Hogwarts suddenly seemed to hold; he had never quite noticed that before. Girls giggling and whispering in the corridors, girls shrieking with laughter as boys passed them, girls excitedly comparing notes on what they were going to wear on Christmas night. \'85\par
\ldblquote Why do they have to move in packs?\rdblquote  Harry asked Ron as a dozen or so girls walked past them, sniggering and staring at Harry. \ldblquote How\rquote re you supposed to get one on their own to ask them?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Lasso one?\rdblquote  Ron suggested. \ldblquote Got any idea who you\rquote re going to try?\rdblquote\par
Harry didn\rquote t answer. He knew perfectly well whom he\rquote d \i like\i0  to ask, but working up the nerve was something else. \'85 Cho was a year older than he was; she was very pretty; she was a very good Quidditch player, and she was also very popular.\par
Ron seemed to know what was going on inside Harry\rquote s head.\par
\ldblquote Listen, you\rquote re not going to have any trouble. You\rquote re a cham\-pion. You\rquote ve just beaten a Hungarian Horntail. I bet they\rquote ll be queuing up to go with you.\rdblquote\par
In tribute to their recently repaired friendship, Ron had kept the bitterness in his voice to a bare minimum. Moreover, to Harry\rquote s amazement, he turned out to be quite right.\par
A curly-haired third-year Hufflepuff girl to whom Harry had never spoken in his life asked him to go to the ball with her the very next day. Harry was so taken aback he said no before he\rquote d even stopped to consider the matter. The girl walked off looking rather hurt, and Harry had to endure Dean\rquote s, Seamus\rquote s, and Ron\rquote s taunts about her all through History of Magic. The following day, two more girls asked him, a second year and (to his horror) a fifth year who looked as though she might knock him out if he refused.\par
\ldblquote She was quite good-looking,\rdblquote  said Ron fairly, after he\rquote d stopped laughing.\par
