\ldblquote What did you know, \rquote Agrid?\rdblquote  said Madame Maxime, a purr in her low voice.\par
Harry definitely didn\rquote t want to listen to this; he knew Hagrid would hate to be overheard in a situation like this (he certainly would have) \emdash  if it had been possible he would have put his fin\-gers in his ears and hummed loudly, but that wasn\rquote t really an op\-tion. Instead he tried to interest himself in a beetle crawling along the stone reindeer\rquote s back, but the beetle just wasn\rquote t interesting enough to block out Hagrid\rquote s next words.\par
\ldblquote I jus\rquote  knew \'85 knew you were like me. \'85 Was it yer mother or yer father?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I \emdash  I don\rquote t know what you mean, \rquote Agrid. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was my mother,\rdblquote  said Hagrid quietly. \ldblquote She was one o\rquote  the las\rquote  ones in Britain. \rquote Course, I can\rquote  remember her too well \'85 she left, see. When I was abou\rquote  three. She wasn\rquote  really the maternal sort. Well \'85 it\rquote s not in their natures, is it? Dunno what happened to her \'85 might be dead fer all I know. \'85\rdblquote\par
Madame Maxime didn\rquote t say anything. And Harry, in spite of himself, took his eyes off the beetle and looked over the top of the reindeer\rquote s antlers, listening. \'85 He had never heard Hagrid talk about his childhood before.\par
\ldblquote Me dad was broken-hearted when she wen\rquote . Tiny little bloke, my dad was. By the time I was six I could lift him up an\rquote  put him on top o\rquote  the dresser if he annoyed me. Used ter make him laugh. \'85\rdblquote  Hagrid\rquote s deep voice broke. Madame Maxime was lis\-tening, motionless, apparently staring at the silvery fountain. \ldblquote Dad raised me \'85 but he died, o\rquote  course, jus\rquote  after I started school. Sorta had ter make me own way after that. Dumbledore was a real help, mind. Very kind ter me, he was. \'85\rdblquote\par
