\ldblquote Well, they were dying out anyway, and then loads got them\-selves killed by Aurors. There\rquote re supposed to be giants abroad, though. \'85 They hide out in mountains mostly. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know who Maxime thinks she\rquote s kidding,\rdblquote  Harry said, watching Madame Maxime sitting alone at the judges\rquote  table, looking very somber. \ldblquote If Hagrid\rquote s half-giant, she definitely is. Big bones \'85 the only thing that\rquote s got bigger bones than her is a dinosaur.\rdblquote\par
Harry and Ron spent the rest of the ball discussing giants in their corner, neither of them having any inclination to dance. Harry tried not to watch Cho and Cedric too much; it gave him a strong desire to kick something.\par
When the Weird Sisters finished playing at midnight, everyone gave them a last, loud round of applause and started to wend their way into the entrance hall. Many people were expressing the wish that the ball could have gone on longer, but Harry was perfectly happy to be going to bed; as far as he was concerned, the evening hadn\rquote t been much fun.\par
Out in the entrance hall, Harry and Ron saw Hermione saying good night to Krum before he went back to the Durmstrang ship. She gave Ron a very cold look and swept past him up the marble staircase without speaking. Harry and Ron followed her, but halfway up the staircase Harry heard someone calling him.\par
\ldblquote Hey \emdash  Harry!\rdblquote\par
It was Cedric Diggory. Harry could see Cho waiting for him in the entrance hall below.\par
\ldblquote Yeah?\rdblquote  said Harry coldly as Cedric ran up the stairs toward him.\par
Cedric looked as though he didn\rquote t want to say whatever it was in front of Ron, who shrugged, looking bad-tempered, and continued to climb the stairs.\par
\ldblquote Listen \'85\rdblquote  Cedric lowered his voice as Ron disappeared. \ldblquote I owe you one for telling me about the dragons. You know that golden egg? Does yours wail when you open it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Well \'85 take a bath, okay?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Take a bath, and \emdash  er \emdash  take the egg with you, and \emdash  er \emdash  just mull things over in the hot water. It\rquote ll help you think. \'85 Trust me.\par
Harry stared at him.\par
\ldblquote Tell you what,\rdblquote  Cedric said, \ldblquote use the prefects\rquote  bathroom. Fourth door to the left of that statue of Boris the Bewildered on the fifth floor. Password\rquote s \lquote pine fresh.\rquote  Gotta go \'85 want to say good night \emdash\rdblquote\par
He grinned at Harry again and hurried back down the stairs to Cho.\par
Harry walked back to Gryffindor Tower alone. That had been extremely strange advice. Why would a bath help him to work out what the wailing egg meant? Was Cedric pulling his leg? Was he trying to make Harry look like a fool, so Cho would like him even more by comparison?\par
The Fat Lady and her friend Vi were snoozing in the picture over the portrait hole. Harry had to yell \ldblquote Fairy lights!\rdblquote  before he woke them up, and when he did, they were extremely irritated. He climbed into the common room and found Ron and Hermione having a blazing row. Standing ten feet apart, they were bellowing at each other, each scarlet in the face.\par
\ldblquote Well, if you don\rquote t like it, you know what the solution is, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote  yelled Hermione; her hair was coming down out of its ele\-gant bun now, and her face was screwed up in anger.\par
\ldblquote Oh yeah?\rdblquote  Ron yelled back. \ldblquote What\rquote s that?\rdblquote\par
