Everybody got up late on Boxing Day. The Gryffindor com\-mon room was much quieter than it had been lately, many yawns punctuating the lazy conversations. Hermione\rquote s hair was bushy again; she confessed to Harry that she had used liberal amounts of Sleekeazy\rquote s Hair Potion on it for the ball, \ldblquote but it\rquote s way too much bother to do every day,\rdblquote  she said matter-of-factly, scratching a purring Crookshanks behind the ears.\par
Ron and Hermione seemed to have reached an unspoken agree\-ment not to discuss their argument. They were being quite friendly to each other, though oddly formal. Ron and Harry wasted no time in telling Hermione about the conversation they had overheard be\-tween Madame Maxime and Hagrid, but Hermione didn\rquote t seem to find the news that Hagrid was a half-giant nearly as shocking as Ron did.\par
\ldblquote Well, I thought he must be,\rdblquote  she said, shrugging. \ldblquote I knew he couldn\rquote t be pure giant because they\rquote re about twenty feet tall. But honestly, all this hysteria about giants. They can\rquote t \i all\i0  be horri\-ble. \'85 It\rquote s the same sort of prejudice that people have toward werewolves. \'85 It\rquote s just bigotry, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
Ron looked as though he would have liked to reply scathingly, but perhaps he didn\rquote t want another row, because he contented him\-self with shaking his head disbelievingly while Hermione wasn\rquote t looking.\par
It was time now to think of the homework they had neglected during the first week of the holidays. Everybody seemed to be feel\-ing rather flat now that Christmas was over \emdash  everybody except Harry, that is, who was starting (once again) to feel slightly nervous.\par
The trouble was that February the twenty-fourth looked a lot closer from this side of Christmas, and he still hadn\rquote t done any\-thing about working out the clue inside the golden egg. He there\-fore started taking the egg out of his trunk every time he went up to the dormitory, opening it, and listening intently, hoping that this time it would make some sense. He strained to think what the sound reminded him of, apart from thirty musical saws, but he had never heard anything else like it. He closed the egg, shook it vigor\-ously, and opened it again to see if the sound had changed, but it hadn\rquote t. He tried asking the egg questions, shouting over all the wailing, but nothing happened. He even threw the egg across the room \emdash  though he hadn\rquote t really expected that to help.\par
Harry had not forgotten the hint that Cedric had given him, but his less-than-friendly feelings toward Cedric just now meant that he was keen not to take his help if he could avoid it. In any case, it seemed to him that if Cedric had really wanted to give Harry a hand, he would have been a lot more explicit. He, Harry, had told Cedric exactly what was coming in the first task \emdash  and Cedric\rquote s idea of a fair exchange had been to tell Harry to take a bath. Well, he didn\rquote t need that sort of rubbishy help \emdash  not from someone who kept walking down corridors hand in hand with Cho, anyway. And so the first day of the new term arrived, and Harry set off to lessons, weighed down with books, parchment, and quills as usual, but also with the lurking worry of the egg heavy in his stomach, as though he were carrying that around with him too.\par
Snow was still thick upon the grounds, and the greenhouse win\-dows were covered in condensation so thick that they couldn\rquote t see out of them in Herbology. Nobody was looking forward to Care of Magical Creatures much in this weather, though as Ron said, the skrewts would probably warm them up nicely, either by chasing them, or blasting off so forcefully that Hagrid\rquote s cabin would catch fire.\par
When they arrived at Hagrid\rquote s cabin, however, they found an el\-derly witch with closely cropped gray hair and a very prominent chin standing before his front door.\par
\ldblquote Hurry up, now, the bell rang five minutes ago,\rdblquote  she barked at them as they struggled toward her through the snow.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote re you?\rdblquote  said Ron, staring at her. \ldblquote Where\rquote s Hagrid?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My name is Professor Grubbly-Plank,\rdblquote  she said briskly. \ldblquote I am your temporary Care of Magical Creatures teacher.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Where\rquote s Hagrid?\rdblquote  Harry repeated loudly.\par
\ldblquote He is indisposed,\rdblquote  said Professor Grubbly-Plank shortly.\par
Soft and unpleasant laughter reached Harry\rquote s ears. He turned; Draco Malfoy and the rest of the Slytherins were joining the class. All of them looked gleeful, and none of them looked surprised to see Professor Grubbly-Plank.\par
\ldblquote This way, please,\rdblquote  said Professor Grubbly-Plank, and she strode off around the paddock where the Beauxbatons horses were shiver\-ing. Harry, Ron, and Hermione followed her, looking back over their shoulders at Hagrid\rquote s cabin. All the curtains were closed. Was Hagrid in there, alone and ill?\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s wrong with Hagrid?\rdblquote  Harry said, hurrying to catch up with Professor Grubbly-Plank.\par
