\ldblquote You said you\rquote d already worked out that egg clue!\rdblquote  said Hermione indignantly.\par
\ldblquote Keep your voice down!\rdblquote  said Harry crossly. \ldblquote I just need to \emdash  sort of fine-tune it, all right?\rdblquote\par
He, Ron, and Hermione were sitting at the very back of the Charms class with a table to themselves. They were supposed to be practicing the opposite of the Summoning Charm today \emdash  the Banishing Charm. Owing to the potential for nasty accidents when objects kept flying across the room, Professor Flitwick had given each student a stack of cushions on which to practice, the theory being that these wouldn\rquote t hurt anyone if they went off target. It was a good theory, but it wasn\rquote t working very well. Neville\rquote s aim was so poor that he kept accidentally sending much heavier things flying across the room \emdash  Professor Flitwick, for instance.\par
\ldblquote Just forget the egg for a minute, all right?\rdblquote  Harry hissed as Pro\-fessor Flitwick went whizzing resignedly past them, landing on top of a large cabinet. \ldblquote I\rquote m trying to tell you about Snape and Moody. \'85\rdblquote\par
This class was an ideal cover for a private conversation, as every\-one was having far too much fun to pay them any attention. Harry had been recounting his adventures of the previous night in whis\-pered installments for the last half hour.\par
\ldblquote Snape said Moody\rquote s searched his office as well?\rdblquote  Ron whispered, his eyes alight with interest as he Banished a cushion with a sweep of his wand (it soared into the air and knocked Parvati\rquote s hat off). \ldblquote What \'85 d\rquote you reckon Moody\rquote s here to keep an eye on Snape as well as Karkaroff?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, I dunno if that\rquote s what Dumbledore asked him to do, but he\rquote s definitely doing it,\rdblquote  said Harry, waving his wand without pay\-ing much attention, so that his cushion did an odd sort of belly flop off the desk. \ldblquote Moody said Dumbledore only lets Snape stay here because he\rquote s giving him a second chance or something. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Ron, his eyes widening, his next cushion spinning high into the air, ricocheting off the chandelier, and dropping heavily onto Flitwick\rquote s desk. \ldblquote Harry \'85 maybe Moody thinks \i Snape\i0  put your name in the Goblet of Fire!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh Ron,\rdblquote  said Hermione, shaking her head sceptically, \ldblquote we thought Snape was trying to kill Harry before, and it turned out he was saving Harry\rquote s life, remember?\rdblquote\par
She Banished a cushion and it flew across the room and landed in the box they were all supposed to be aiming at. Harry looked at Hermione, thinking \'85 it was true that Snape had saved his life once, but the odd thing was, Snape definitely loathed him, just as he\rquote d loathed Harry\rquote s father when they had been at school together. Snape loved taking points from Harry, and had certainly never missed an opportunity to give him punishments, or even to suggest that he should be suspended from the school.\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t care what Moody says,\rdblquote  Hermione went on. \ldblquote Dumble\-dore\rquote s not stupid. He was right to trust Hagrid and Professor Lupin, even though loads of people wouldn\rquote t have given them jobs, so why shouldn\rquote t he be right about Snape, even if Snape is a bit \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\emdash  evil,\rdblquote  said Ron promptly. \ldblquote Come on, Hermione, why are all these Dark wizard catchers searching his office, then?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why has Mr. Crouch been pretending to be ill?\rdblquote  said Hermi\-one, ignoring Ron. \ldblquote It\rquote s a bit funny, isn\rquote t it, that he can\rquote t manage to come to the Yule Ball, but he can get up here in the middle of the night when he wants to?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You just don\rquote t like Crouch because of that elf, Winky,\rdblquote  said Ron, sending a cushion soaring into the window.\par
\ldblquote\i You\i0  just want to think Snape\rquote s up to something,\rdblquote  said Her\-mione, sending her cushion zooming neatly into the box.\par
\ldblquote I just want to know what Snape did with his first chance, if he\rquote s on his second one,\rdblquote  said Harry grimly, and his cushion, to his very great surprise, flew straight across the room and landed neatly on top of Hermione\rquote s.\par
\par
Obedient to Sirius\rquote s wish of hearing about anything odd at Hog\-warts, Harry sent him a letter by brown owl that night, explaining all about Mr. Crouch breaking into Snape\rquote s office, and Moody and Snape\rquote s conversation. Then Harry turned his attention in earnest to the most urgent problem facing him: how to survive underwater for an hour on the twenty-fourth of February.\par
Ron quite liked the idea of using the Summoning Charm again \emdash  Harry had explained about Aqua-Lungs, and Ron couldn\rquote t see why Harry shouldn\rquote t Summon one from the nearest Muggle town. Hermione squashed this plan by pointing out that, in the un\-likely event that Harry managed to learn how to operate an Aqua-Lung within the set limit of an hour, he was sure to be disqualified for breaking the International Code of Wizarding Secrecy \emdash  it was too much to hope that no Muggles would spot an Aqua-Lung zooming across the countryside to Hogwarts.\par
\ldblquote Of course, the ideal solution would be for you to Transfigure yourself into a submarine or something,\rdblquote  Hermione said. \ldblquote If only we\rquote d done human Transfiguration already! But I don\rquote t think we start that until sixth year, and it can go badly wrong if you don\rquote t know what you\rquote re doing. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, I don\rquote t fancy walking around with a periscope sticking out of my head,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I s\rquote pose I could always attack some\-one in front of Moody; he might do it for me. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t think he\rquote d let you choose what you wanted to be turned into, though,\rdblquote  said Hermione seriously. \ldblquote No, I think your best chance is some sort of charm.\rdblquote\par
So Harry, thinking that he would soon have had enough of the library to last him a lifetime, buried himself once more among the dusty volumes, looking for any spell that might enable a hu\-man to survive without oxygen. However, though he, Ron, and Hermione searched through their lunchtimes, evenings, and whole weekends \emdash  though Harry asked Professor McGonagall for a note of permission to use the Restricted Section, and even asked the ir\-ritable, vulture-like librarian, Madam Pince, for help \emdash  they found nothing whatsoever that would enable Harry to spend an hour underwater and live to tell the tale.\par
Familiar flutterings of panic were starting to disturb Harry now, and he was finding it difficult to concentrate in class again. The lake, which Harry had always taken for granted as just another fea\-ture of the grounds, drew his eyes whenever he was near a class\-room window, a great, iron-gray mass of chilly water, whose dark and icy depths were starting to seem as distant as the moon.\par
Just as it had before he faced the Horntail, time was slipping away as though somebody had bewitched the clocks to go extra-fast. There was a week to go before February the twenty-fourth (there was still time) \'85 there were five days to go (he was bound to find something soon) \'85 three days to go (\i please let me find something\i0  \'85 \i please\i0 ) \'85\par
With two days left, Harry started to go off food again. The only good thing about breakfast on Monday was the return of the brown owl he had sent to Sirius. He pulled off the parchment, unrolled it, and saw the shortest letter Sirius had ever written to him.\par
