It was an irritable sort of day after that. Harry got so tired of Ron and Hermione sniping at each other over their homework in the common room that he took Sirius\rquote s food up to the Owlery that evening on his own.\par
Pigwidgeon was much too small to carry an entire ham up to the mountain by himself, so Harry enlisted the help of two school screech owls as well. When they had set off into the dusk, looking extremely odd carrying the large package between them, Harry leaned on the windowsill, looking out at the grounds, at the dark, rustling treetops of the Forbidden Forest, and the rippling sails of the Durmstrang ship. An eagle owl flew through the coil of smoke rising from Hagrid\rquote s chimney; it soared toward the castle, around the Owlery, and out of sight. Looking down, Harry saw Hagrid digging energetically in front of his cabin. Harry wondered what he was doing; it looked as though he were making a new vegetable patch. As he watched, Madame Maxime emerged from the Beaux\-batons carriage and walked over to Hagrid. She appeared to be try\-ing to engage him in conversation. Hagrid leaned upon his spade, but did not seem keen to prolong their talk, because Madame Maxime returned to the carriage shortly afterward.\par
Unwilling to go back to Gryffindor Tower and listen to Ron and Hermione snarling at each other, Harry watched Hagrid digging until the darkness swallowed him and the owls around Harry be\-gan to awake, swooshing past him into the night.\par
\par
By breakfast the next day Ron\rquote s and Hermione\rquote s bad moods had burnt out, and to Harry\rquote s relief, Ron\rquote s dark predictions that the house-elves would send substandard food up to the Gryffindor table because Hermione had insulted them proved false; the bacon, eggs, and kippers were quite as good as usual.\par
When the post owls arrived, Hermione looked up eagerly; she seemed to be expecting something.\par
\ldblquote Percy won\rquote t\rquote ve had time to answer yet,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote We only sent Hedwig yesterday.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, it\rquote s not that,\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote I\rquote ve taken out a subscription to the \i Daily Prophet.\i0  I\rquote m getting sick of finding everything out from the Slytherins.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good thinking!\rdblquote  said Harry, also looking up at the owls. \ldblquote Hey, Hermione, I think you\rquote re in luck \emdash\rdblquote\par
A gray owl was soaring down toward Hermione.\par
\ldblquote It hasn\rquote t got a newspaper, though,\rdblquote  she said, looking disap\-pointed. \ldblquote It\rquote s \emdash\rdblquote\par
But to her bewilderment, the gray owl landed in front of her plate, closely followed by four barn owls, a brown owl, and a tawny.\par
\ldblquote How many subscriptions did you take out?\rdblquote  said Harry, seizing Hermione\rquote s goblet before it was knocked over by the cluster of owls, all of whom were jostling close to her, trying to deliver their own letter first.\par
\ldblquote What on earth \emdash  ?\rdblquote  Hermione said, taking the letter from the gray owl, opening it, and starting to read. \ldblquote Oh really!\rdblquote  she sput\-tered, going rather red.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s up?\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s \emdash  oh how ridiculous \emdash\rdblquote\par
She thrust the letter at Harry, who saw that it was not handwrit\-ten, but composed from pasted letters that seemed to have been cut out of the \i Daily Prophet.\i0\par
\par
