\ldblquote You are in luck, Wormtail,\rdblquote  said a cold, high-pitched voice from the depths of the chair in which the owl had landed. \ldblquote You are very fortunate indeed. Your blunder has not ruined everything. He is dead.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My Lord!\rdblquote  gasped the man on the floor. \ldblquote My Lord, I am \'85 I am so pleased \'85 and so sorry. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nagini,\rdblquote  said the cold voice, \ldblquote you are out of luck. I will not be feeding Wormtail to you, after all \'85 but never mind, never mind \'85 there is still Harry Potter. \'85\rdblquote\par
The snake hissed. Harry could see its tongue fluttering.\par
\ldblquote Now, Wormtail,\rdblquote  said the cold voice, \ldblquote perhaps one more little reminder why I will not tolerate another blunder from you. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My Lord \'85 no \'85 I beg you \'85\rdblquote\par
The tip of a wand emerged from around the back of the chair. It was pointing at Wormtail.\par
\ldblquote\i Crucio\i0 !\rdblquote  said the cold voice.\par
Wormtail screamed, screamed as though every nerve in his body were on fire, the screaming filled Harry\rquote s ears as the scar on his fore\-head seared with pain; he was yelling too. \'85 Voldemort would hear him, would know he was there. \'85\par
\ldblquote Harry! \i Harry\i0 !\rdblquote\par
Harry opened his eyes. He was lying on the floor of Professor Trelawney\rquote s room with his hands over his face. His scar was still burning so badly that his eyes were watering. The pain had been real. The whole class was standing around him, and Ron was kneel\-ing next to him, looking terrified.\par
\ldblquote You all right?\rdblquote  he said.\par
\ldblquote Of course he isn\rquote t!\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney, looking thor\-oughly excited. Her great eyes loomed over Harry, gazing at him. \ldblquote What was it, Potter? A premonition? An apparition? What did you see?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nothing,\rdblquote  Harry lied. He sat up. He could feel himself shaking. He couldn\rquote t stop himself from looking around, into the shadows behind him; Voldemort\rquote s voice had sounded so close. \'85\par
\ldblquote You were clutching your scar!\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney. \ldblquote You were rolling on the floor, clutching your scar! Come now, Potter, I have experience in these matters!\rdblquote\par
Harry looked up at her.\par
\ldblquote I need to go to the hospital wing, I think,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Bad headache.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My dear, you were undoubtedly stimulated by the extraordi\-nary clairvoyant vibrations of my room!\rdblquote  said Professor Trelawney \ldblquote If you leave now, you may lose the opportunity to see further than you have ever \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t want to see anything except a headache cure,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
He stood up. The class backed away. They all looked unnerved.\par
\ldblquote See you later,\rdblquote  Harry muttered to Ron, and he picked up his bag and headed for the trapdoor, ignoring Professor Trelawney, who was wearing an expression of great frustration, as though she had just been denied a real treat.\par
When Harry reached the bottom of her stepladder, however, he did not set off for the hospital wing. He had no intention whatsoever of going there. Sirius had told him what to do if his scar hurt him again, and Harry was going to follow his advice: He was going straight to Dumbledore\rquote s office. He marched down the corridors, thinking about what he had seen in the dream \'85 it had been as vivid as the one that had awoken him on Privet Drive. \'85 He ran over the details in his mind, trying to make sure he could remember them. \'85 He had heard Voldemort accusing Wormtail of making a blunder \'85 but the owl had brought good news, the blunder had been repaired, somebody was dead \'85 so Wormtail was not going to be fed to the snake \'85 he, Harry, was going to be fed to it instead. \'85\par
Harry had walked right past the stone gargoyle guarding the en\-trance to Dumbledore\rquote s office without noticing. He blinked, looked around, realized what he had done, and retraced his steps, stopping in front of it. Then he remembered that he didn\rquote t know the password.\par
\ldblquote Sherbet lemon?\rdblquote  he tried tentatively.\par
The gargoyle did not move.\par
\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Harry, staring at it, \ldblquote Pear Drop. Er \emdash  Licorice Wand. Fizzing Whizbee. Drooble\rquote s Best Blowing Gum. Bertie Bott\rquote s Every Flavor Beans \'85 oh no, he doesn\rquote t like them, does he? \'85 oh just open, can\rquote t you?\rdblquote  he said angrily. \ldblquote I really need to see him, it\rquote s urgent!\rdblquote\par
The gargoyle remained immovable.\par
Harry kicked it, achieving nothing but an excruciating pain in his big toe.\par
\ldblquote Chocolate Frog!\rdblquote  he yelled angrily, standing on one leg. \ldblquote Sugar Quill! Cockroach Cluster!\rdblquote\par
The gargoyle sprang to life and jumped aside. Harry blinked.\par
\ldblquote Cockroach Cluster?\rdblquote  he said, amazed. \ldblquote I was only joking. \'85\rdblquote\par
He hurried through the gap in the walls and stepped onto the foot of a spiral stone staircase, which moved slowly upward as the doors closed behind him, taking him up to a polished oak door with a brass door knocker.\par
He could hear voices from inside the office. He stepped off the moving staircase and hesitated, listening.\par
\ldblquote Dumbledore, I\rquote m afraid I don\rquote t see the connection, don\rquote t see it at all!\rdblquote  It was the voice of the Minister of Magic, Cornelius Fudge. \ldblquote Ludo says Bertha\rquote s perfectly capable of getting herself lost. I agree we would have expected to have found her by now, but all the same, we\rquote ve no evidence of foul play, Dumbledore, none at all. As for her disappearance being linked with Barty Crouch\rquote s!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And what do you thinks happened to Barty Crouch, Minister?\rdblquote  said Moody\rquote s growling voice.\par
\ldblquote I see two possibilities, Alastor,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote Either Crouch has finally cracked \emdash  more than likely, I\rquote m sure you\rquote ll agree, given his personal history \emdash  lost his mind, and gone wandering off some\-where \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He wandered extremely quickly, if that is the case, Cornelius,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly.\par
\ldblquote Or else \emdash  well \'85\rdblquote  Fudge sounded embarrassed. \ldblquote Well, I\rquote ll reserve judgment until after I\rquote ve seen the place where he was found, but you say it was just past the Beauxbatons carriage? Dumbledore, you know what that woman \i is\i0 ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I consider her to be a very able headmistress \emdash  and an excel\-lent dancer,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly.\par
\ldblquote Dumbledore, come!\rdblquote  said Fudge angrily. \ldblquote Don\rquote t you think you might be prejudiced in her favor because of Hagrid? They don\rquote t all turn out harmless \emdash  if, indeed, you can call Hagrid harmless, with that monster fixation he\rquote s got \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I no more suspect Madame Maxime than Hagrid,\rdblquote  said Dum\-bledore, just as calmly. \ldblquote I think it possible that it is you who are prejudiced, Cornelius.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Can we wrap up this discussion?\rdblquote  growled Moody.\par
\ldblquote Yes, yes, let\rquote s go down to the grounds, then,\rdblquote  said Fudge impa\-tiently.\par
\ldblquote No, it\rquote s not that,\rdblquote  said Moody, \ldblquote it\rquote s just that Potter wants a word with you, Dumbledore. He\rquote s just outside the door.\rdblquote\par
