\ldblquote Dumbledore reckons You-Know-Who\rquote s getting stronger again as well?\rdblquote  Ron whispered.\par
Everything Harry had seen in the Pensieve, nearly everything Dumbledore had told and shown him afterward, he had now shared with Ron and Hermione \emdash  and, of course, with Sirius, to whom Harry had sent an owl the moment he had left Dumble\-dore\rquote s office. Harry, Ron, and Hermione sat up late in the common room once again that night, talking it all over until Harry\rquote s mind was reeling, until he understood what Dumbledore had meant about a head becoming so full of thoughts that it would have been a relief to siphon them off.\par
Ron stared into the common room fire. Harry thought he saw Ron shiver slightly, even though the evening was warm.\par
\ldblquote And he trusts Snape?\rdblquote  Ron said. \ldblquote He really trusts Snape, even though he knows he was a Death Eater?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Hermione had not spoken for ten minutes. She was sitting with her forehead in her hands, staring at her knees. Harry thought she too looked as though she could have done with a Pensieve.\par
\ldblquote Rita Skeeter,\rdblquote  she muttered finally.\par
\ldblquote How can you be worrying about her now?\rdblquote  said Ron, in utter disbelief.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not worrying about her,\rdblquote  Hermione said to her knees. \ldblquote I\rquote m just thinking \'85 remember what she said to me in the Three Broomsticks? \lquote I know things about Ludo Bagman that would make your hair curl.\rquote  This is what she meant, isn\rquote t it? She reported his trial, she knew he\rquote d passed information to the Death Eaters. And Winky too, remember \'85 \lquote Ludo Bagman\rquote s a bad wizard.\rquote  Mr. Crouch would have been furious he got off, he would have talked about it at home.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah, but Bagman didn\rquote t pass information on purpose, did he?\rdblquote\par
Hermione shrugged.\par
\ldblquote And Fudge reckons \i Madame Maxime\i0  attacked Crouch?\rdblquote  Ron said, turning back to Harry.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote but he\rquote s only saying that because Crouch disappeared near the Beauxbatons carriage.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We never thought of her, did we?\rdblquote  said Ron slowly. \ldblquote Mind you, she\rquote s definitely got giant blood, and she doesn\rquote t want to admit it \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course she doesn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Hermione sharply, looking up. \ldblquote Look what happened to Hagrid when Rita found out about his mother. Look at Fudge, jumping to conclusions about her, just be\-cause she\rquote s part giant. Who needs that sort of prejudice? I\rquote d proba\-bly say I had big bones if I knew that\rquote s what I\rquote d get for telling the truth.\rdblquote\par
Hermione looked at her watch. \ldblquote We haven\rquote t done any practic\-ing!\rdblquote  she said, looking shocked. \ldblquote We were going to do the Impedi\-ment Curse! We\rquote ll have to really get down to it tomorrow! Come on, Harry, you need to get some sleep.\rdblquote\par
Harry and Ron went slowly upstairs to their dormitory. As Harry pulled on his pajamas, he looked over at Neville\rquote s bed. True to his word to Dumbledore, he had not told Ron and Hermione about Neville\rquote s parents. As Harry took off his glasses and climbed into his four-poster, he imagined how it must feel to have parents still living but unable to recognize you. He often got sympathy from strangers for being an orphan, but as he listened to Neville\rquote s snores, he thought that Neville deserved it more than he did. Lying in the darkness, Harry felt a rush of anger and hate toward the peo\-ple who had tortured Mr. and Mrs. Longbottom. \'85 He remem\-bered the jeers of the crowd as Crouch\rquote s son and his companions had been dragged from the court by the dementors. \'85 He under\-stood how they had felt. \'85 Then he remembered the milk-white face of the screaming boy and realized with a jolt that he had died a year later. \'85\par
It was Voldemort, Harry thought, staring up at the canopy of his bed in the darkness, it all came back to Voldemort. \'85 He was the one who had torn these families apart, who had ruined all these lives. \'85\par
\par
Ron and Hermione were supposed to be studying for their exams, which would finish on the day of the third task, but they were putting most of their efforts into helping Harry prepare.\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry about it,\rdblquote  Hermione said shortly when Harry pointed this out to them and said he didn\rquote t mind practicing on his own for a while, \ldblquote at least we\rquote ll get top marks in Defense Against the Dark Arts. We\rquote d never have found out about all these hexes in class.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good training for when we\rquote re all Aurors,\rdblquote  said Ron excitedly, attempting the Impediment Curse on a wasp that had buzzed into the room and making it stop dead in midair.\par
The mood in the castle as they entered June became excited and tense again. Everyone was looking forward to the third task, which would take place a week before the end of term. Harry was practic\-ing hexes at every available moment. He felt more confident about this task than either of the others. Difficult and dangerous though it would undoubtedly be, Moody was right: Harry had managed to find his way past monstrous creatures and enchanted barriers be\-fore now, and this time he had some notice, some chance to pre\-pare himself for what lay ahead.\par
Tired of walking in on Harry, Hermione, and Ron all over the school, Professor McGonagall had given them permission to use the empty Transfiguration classroom at lunchtimes. Harry had soon mastered the Impediment Curse, a spell to slow down and ob\-struct attackers; the Reductor Curse, which would enable him to blast solid objects out of his way; and the Four-Point Spell, a useful discovery of Hermione\rquote s that would make his wand point due north, therefore enabling him to check whether he was going in the right direction within the maze. He was still having trouble with the Shield Charm, though. This was supposed to cast a temporary, invisible wall around himself that deflected minor curses; Hermi\-one managed to shatter it with a well-placed Jelly-Legs Jinx, and Harry wobbled around the room for ten minutes afterward before she had looked up the counter-jinx.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re still doing really well, though,\rdblquote  Hermione said encour\-agingly, looking down her list and crossing off those spells they had already learned. \ldblquote Some of these are bound to come in handy.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Come and look at this,\rdblquote  said Ron, who was standing by the window. He was staring down onto the grounds. \ldblquote What\rquote s Malfoy doing?\rdblquote\par
