The champions nodded.\par
\ldblquote Off you go, then!\rdblquote  said Bagman brightly to the four patrollers.\par
\ldblquote Good luck, Harry,\rdblquote  Hagrid whispered, and the four of them walked away in different directions, to station themselves around the maze. Bagman now pointed his wand at his throat, muttered, \ldblquote\i Sonorus,\i0\rdblquote  and his magically magnified voice echoed into the stands.\par
\ldblquote Ladies and gentlemen, the third and final task of the Triwizard Tournament is about to begin! Let me remind you how the points currently stand! Tied in first place, with eighty-five points each \emdash  Mr. Cedric Diggory and Mr. Harry Potter, both of Hogwarts School!\rdblquote  The cheers and applause sent birds from the Forbidden Forest fluttering into the darkening sky. \ldblquote In second place, with eighty points \emdash  Mr. Viktor Krum, of Durmstrang Institute!\rdblquote  More applause. \ldblquote And in third place \emdash  Miss Fleur Delacour, of Beauxbatons Academy!\rdblquote\par
Harry could just make out Mrs. Weasley, Bill, Ron, and Hermi\-one applauding Fleur politely, halfway up the stands. He waved up at them, and they waved back, beaming at him.\par
\ldblquote So \'85 on my whistle, Harry and Cedric!\rdblquote  said Bagman. \ldblquote Three \emdash  two \emdash  one \emdash\rdblquote\par
He gave a short blast on his whistle, and Harry and Cedric hur\-ried forward into the maze.\par
The towering hedges cast black shadows across the path, and, whether because they were so tall and thick or because they had been enchanted, the sound of the surrounding crowd was silenced the moment they entered the maze. Harry felt almost as though he were underwater again. He pulled out his wand, muttered, \ldblquote\i Lumos,\i0\rdblquote  and heard Cedric do the same just behind him.\par
After about fifty yards, they reached a fork. They looked at each other.\par
\ldblquote See you,\rdblquote  Harry said, and he took the left one, while Cedric took the right.\par
Harry heard Bagman\rquote s whistle for the second time. Krum had entered the maze. Harry sped up. His chosen path seemed com\-pletely deserted. He turned right, and hurried on, holding his wand high over his head, trying to see as far ahead as possible. Still, there was nothing in sight.\par
Bagman\rquote s whistle blew in the distance for the third time. All of the champions were now inside.\par
Harry kept looking behind him. The old feeling that he was be\-ing watched was upon him. The maze was growing darker with every passing minute as the sky overhead deepened to navy. He reached a second fork.\par
\ldblquote\i Point Me,\i0\rdblquote  he whispered to his wand, holding it flat in his palm.\par
The wand spun around once and pointed toward his right, into solid hedge. That way was north, and he knew that he needed to go northwest for the center of the maze. The best he could do was to take the left fork and go right again as soon as possible.\par
The path ahead was empty too, and when Harry reached a right turn and took it, he again found his way unblocked. Harry didn\rquote t know why, but the lack of obstacles was unnerving him. Surely he should have met something by now? It felt as though the maze were luring him into a false sense of security. Then he heard movement right behind him. He held out his wand, ready to attack, but its beam fell only upon Cedric, who had just hurried out of a path on the right-hand side. Cedric looked severely shaken. The sleeve of his robe was smoking.\par
\ldblquote Hagrid\rquote s Blast-Ended Skrewts!\rdblquote  he hissed. \ldblquote They\rquote re enor\-mous \emdash  I only just got away!\rdblquote\par
He shook his head and dived out of sight, along another path. Keen to put plenty of distance between himself and the skrewts, Harry hurried off again. Then, as he turned a corner, he saw \'85 a dementor gliding toward him. Twelve feet tall, its face hidden by its hood, its rotting, scabbed hands outstretched, it advanced, sensing its way blindly toward him. Harry could hear its rattling breath; he felt clammy coldness stealing over him, but knew what he had to do. \'85\par
He summoned the happiest thought he could, concentrated with all his might on the thought of getting out of the maze and celebrating with Ron and Hermione, raised his wand, and cried, \ldblquote\i Expecto Patronum\i0 !\rdblquote\par
A silver stag erupted from the end of Harry\rquote s wand and galloped toward the dementor, which fell back and tripped over the hem of its robes. \'85 Harry had never seen a dementor stumble.\par
\ldblquote Hang on!\rdblquote  he shouted, advancing in the wake of his silver Patronus. \ldblquote You\rquote re a boggart! \i Riddikulus\i0 !\rdblquote\par
There was a loud crack, and the shape-shifter exploded in a wisp of smoke. The silver stag faded from sight. Harry wished it could have stayed, he could have used some company \'85 but he moved on, quickly and quietly as possible, listening hard, his wand held high once more.\par
Left \'85 right \'85 left again \'85 Twice he found himself facing dead ends. He did the Four-Point Spell again and found that he was going too far east. He turned back, took a right turn, and saw an odd golden mist floating ahead of him.\par
Harry approached it cautiously, pointing the wand\rquote s beam at it. This looked like some kind of enchantment. He wondered whether he might be able to blast it out of the way.\par
\ldblquote\i Reducto\i0 !\rdblquote  he said.\par
The spell shot straight through the mist, leaving it intact. He supposed he should have known better; the Reductor Curse was for solid objects. What would happen if he walked through the mist? Was it worth chancing it, or should he double back?\par
He was still hesitating when a scream shattered the silence.\par
\ldblquote Fleur?\rdblquote  Harry yelled.\par
There was silence. He stared all around him. What had hap\-pened to her? Her scream seemed to have come from somewhere ahead. He took a deep breath and ran through the enchanted mist.\par
The world turned upside down. Harry was hanging from the ground, with his hair on end, his glasses dangling off his nose, threatening to fall into the bottomless sky. He clutched them to the end of his nose and hung there, terrified. It felt as though his feet were glued to the grass, which had now become the ceiling. Below him the dark, star-spangled heavens stretched endlessly. He felt as though if he tried to move one of his feet, he would fall away from the earth completely.\par
\i Think,\i0  he told himself, as all the blood rushed to his head, \i think\i0  \'85\par
But not one of the spells he had practiced had been designed to combat a sudden reversal of ground and sky. Did he dare move his foot? He could hear the blood pounding in his ears. He had two choices \emdash  try and move, or send up red sparks, and get rescued and disqualified from the task.\par
He shut his eyes, so he wouldn\rquote t be able to see the view of end\-less space below him, and pulled his right foot as hard as he could away from the grassy ceiling.\par
Immediately, the world righted itself. Harry fell forward onto his knees onto the wonderfully solid ground. He felt temporarily limp with shock. He took a deep, steadying breath, then got up again and hurried forward, looking back over his shoulder as he ran away from the golden mist, which twinkled innocently at him in the moonlight.\par
He paused at a junction of two paths and looked around for some sign of Fleur. He was sure it had been she who had screamed. What had she met? Was she all right? There was no sign of red sparks \emdash  did that mean she had got herself out of trouble, or was she in such trouble that she couldn\rquote t reach her wand? Harry took the right fork with a feeling of increasing unease \'85 but at the same time, he couldn\rquote t help thinking, \i One champion down\i0  \'85\par
The cup was somewhere close by, and it sounded as though Fleur was no longer in the running. He\rquote d got this far, hadn\rquote t he? What if he actually managed to win? Fleetingly, and for the first time since he\rquote d found himself champion, he saw again that image of himself, raising the Triwizard Cup in front of the rest of the school. \'85\par
He met nothing for ten minutes, but kept running into dead ends. Twice he took the same wrong turning. Finally, he found a new route and started to jog along it, his wandlight waving, mak\-ing his shadow flicker and distort on the hedge walls. Then he rounded another corner and found himself facing a Blast-Ended Skrewt.\par
Cedric was right \emdash  it \i was\i0  enormous. Ten feet long, it looked more like a giant scorpion than anything. Its long sting was curled over its back. Its thick armor glinted in the light from Harry\rquote s wand, which he pointed at it.\par
\ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote\par
The spell hit the skrewt\rquote s armor and rebounded; Harry ducked just in time, but could smell burning hair; it had singed the top of his head. The skrewt issued a blast of fire from its end and flew for\-ward toward him.\par
\ldblquote\i Impedimenta\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry yelled. The spell hit the skrewt\rquote s armor again and ricocheted off; Harry staggered back a few paces and fell over. \ldblquote\i IMPEDIMENTA\i0 !\rdblquote\par
The skrewt was inches from him when it froze \emdash  he had man\-aged to hit it on its fleshy, shell-less underside. Panting, Harry pushed himself away from it and ran, hard, in the opposite direc\-tion \emdash  the Impediment Curse was not permanent; the skrewt would be regaining the use of its legs at any moment.\par
He took a left path and hit a dead end, a right, and hit another; forcing himself to stop, heart hammering, he performed the Four-Point Spell again, backtracked, and chose a path that would take him northwest.\par
He had been hurrying along the new path for a few minutes, when he heard something in the path running parallel to his own that made him stop dead.\par
\ldblquote What are you doing?\rdblquote  yelled Cedric\rquote s voice. \ldblquote What the hell d\rquote you think you\rquote re doing?\rdblquote\par
And then Harry heard Krum\rquote s voice.\par
\ldblquote\i Crucio\i0 !\rdblquote\par
The air was suddenly full of Cedric\rquote s yells. Horrified, Harry be\-gan sprinting up his path, trying to find a way into Cedric\rquote s. When none appeared, he tried the Reductor Curse again. It wasn\rquote t very ef\-fective, but it burned a small hole in the hedge through which Harry forced his leg, kicking at the thick brambles and branches until they broke and made an opening; he struggled through it, tearing his robes, and looking to his right, saw Cedric jerking and twitching on the ground, Krum standing over him.\par
Harry pulled himself up and pointed his wand at Krum just as Krum looked up. Krum turned and began to run.\par
\ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry yelled.\par
The spell hit Krum in the back; he stopped dead in his tracks, fell forward, and lay motionless, facedown in the grass. Harry dashed over to Cedric, who had stopped twitching and was lying there panting, his hands over his face.\par
\ldblquote Are you all right?\rdblquote  Harry said roughly, grabbing Cedric\rquote s arm.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  panted Cedric. \ldblquote Yeah \'85 I don\rquote t believe it \'85 he crept up behind me. \'85 I heard him, I turned around, and he had his wand on me. \'85\rdblquote\par
Cedric got up. He was still shaking. He and Harry looked down at Krum.\par
\ldblquote I can\rquote t believe this \'85 I thought he was all right,\rdblquote  Harry said, staring at Krum.\par
\ldblquote So did I,\rdblquote  said Cedric.\par
\ldblquote Did you hear Fleur scream earlier?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Cedric. \ldblquote You don\rquote t think Krum got her too?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Harry slowly.\par
\ldblquote Should we leave him here?\rdblquote  Cedric muttered.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I reckon we should send up red sparks. Someone\rquote ll come and collect him \'85 otherwise he\rquote ll probably be eaten by a skrewt.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote d deserve it,\rdblquote  Cedric muttered, but all the same, he raised his wand and shot a shower of red sparks into the air, which hov\-ered high above Krum, marking the spot where he lay.\par
Harry and Cedric stood there in the darkness for a moment, looking around them. Then Cedric said, \ldblquote Well \'85 I s\rquote pose we\rquote d better go on . \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Oh \'85 yeah \'85 right \'85\rdblquote\par
It was an odd moment. He and Cedric had been briefly united against Krum \emdash  now the fact that they were opponents came back to Harry. The two of them proceeded up the dark path without speaking, then Harry turned left, and Cedric right. Cedric\rquote s foot\-steps soon died away.\par
Harry moved on, continuing to use the Four-Point Spell, mak\-ing sure he was moving in the right direction. It was between him and Cedric now. His desire to reach the cup first was now burning stronger than ever, but he could hardly believe what he\rquote d just seen Krum do. The use of an Unforgivable Curse on a fellow human be\-ing meant a life term in Azkaban, that was what Moody had told them. Krum surely couldn\rquote t have wanted the Triwizard Cup that badly. \'85 Harry sped up.\par
Every so often he hit more dead ends, but the increasing dark\-ness made him feel sure he was getting near the heart of the maze. Then, as he strode down a long, straight path, he saw movement once again, and his beam of wandlight hit an extraordinary crea\-ture, one which he had only seen in picture form, in his \i Monster Book of Monsters.\i0\par
It was a sphinx. It had the body of an over-large lion: great clawed paws and a long yellowish tail ending in a brown tuft. Its head, how\-ever, was that of a woman. She turned her long, almond-shaped eyes upon Harry as he approached. He raised his wand, hesitating. She was not crouching as if to spring, but pacing from side to side of the path, blocking his progress. Then she spoke, in a deep, hoarse voice.\par
\ldblquote You are very near your goal. The quickest way is past me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So \'85 so will you move, please?\rdblquote  said Harry, knowing what the answer was going to be.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  she said, continuing to pace. \ldblquote Not unless you can answer my riddle. Answer on your first guess \emdash  I let you pass. Answer wrongly \emdash  I attack. Remain silent \emdash  I will let you walk away from me unscathed.\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s stomach slipped several notches. It was Hermione who was good at this sort of thing, not him. He weighed his chances. If the riddle was too hard, he could keep silent, get away from the sphinx unharmed, and try and find an alternative route to the center.\par
\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Can I hear the riddle?\rdblquote\par
The sphinx sat down upon her hind legs, in the very middle of the path, and recited:\par
\par
\ldblquote\i First think of the person who lives in disguise,\par
Who deals in secrets and tells naught but lies.\par
Next, tell me what\rquote s always the last thing to mend,\par
The middle of middle and end of the end\i0 ?\par
\i And finally give me the sound often heard\par
During the search for a hard-to-find word.\par
Now string them together, and answer me this,\par
Which creature would you be unwilling to kiss\i0 ?\rdblquote\par
\par
Harry gaped at her.\par
\ldblquote Could I have it again \'85 more slowly?\rdblquote  he asked tentatively.\par
She blinked at him, smiled, and repeated the poem.\par
\ldblquote All the clues add up to a creature I wouldn\rquote t want to kiss?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\par
She merely smiled her mysterious smile. Harry took that for a \ldblquote yes.\rdblquote  Harry cast his mind around. There were plenty of animals he wouldn\rquote t want to kiss; his immediate thought was a Blast-Ended Skrewt, but something told him that wasn\rquote t the answer. He\rquote d have to try and work out the clues. \'85\par
\ldblquote A person in disguise,\rdblquote  Harry muttered, staring at her, \ldblquote who lies \'85 er \'85 that\rquote d be a \emdash  an imposter. No, that\rquote s not my guess! A \emdash  a spy? I\rquote ll come back to that \'85 could you give me the next clue again, please?\rdblquote\par
She repeated the next lines of the poem.\par
\ldblquote  \lquote The last thing to mend,\rquote  \rdblquote  Harry repeated. \ldblquote Er \'85 no idea \'85 \lquote middle of middle\rquote  \'85 could I have the last bit again?\rdblquote\par
She gave him the last four lines.\par
\ldblquote  \lquote The sound often heard during the search for a hard-to-find word,\rquote  \rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Er \'85 that\rquote d be \'85 er \'85 hang on \emdash  \lquote er\rquote ! Er\rquote s a sound!\rdblquote\par
The sphinx smiled at him.\par
\ldblquote Spy \'85 er \'85 spy \'85 er \'85\rdblquote  said Harry, pacing up and down. \ldblquote A creature I wouldn\rquote t want to kiss \'85 \i a spider\i0 !\rdblquote\par
The sphinx smiled more broadly. She got up, stretched her front legs, and then moved aside for him to pass.\par
\ldblquote Thanks!\rdblquote  said Harry, and, amazed at his own brilliance, he dashed forward.\par
He had to be close now, he had to be. \'85 His wand was telling him he was bang on course; as long as he didn\rquote t meet anything too horrible, he might have a chance. \'85\par
Harry broke into a run. He had a choice of paths up ahead. \ldblquote\i Point Me\i0 !\rdblquote  he whispered again to his wand, and it spun around and pointed him to the right-hand one. He dashed up this one and saw light ahead.\par
The Triwizard Cup was gleaming on a plinth a hundred yards away. Suddenly a dark figure hurtled out onto the path in front of him.\par
Cedric was going to get there first. Cedric was sprinting as fast as he could toward the cup, and Harry knew he would never catch up, Cedric was much taller, had much longer legs \emdash\par
Then Harry saw something immense over a hedge to his left, moving quickly along a path that intersected with his own; it was moving so fast Cedric was about to run into it, and Cedric, his eyes on the cup, had not seen it \emdash\par
\ldblquote Cedric!\rdblquote  Harry bellowed. \ldblquote On your left!\rdblquote\par
Cedric looked around just in time to hurl himself past the thing and avoid colliding with it, but in his haste, he tripped. Harry saw Cedric\rquote s wand fly out of his hand as a gigantic spider stepped into the path and began to bear down upon Cedric.\par
\ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote  Harry yelled; the spell hit the spider\rquote s gigantic, hairy black body, but for all the good it did, he might as well have thrown a stone at it; the spider jerked, scuttled around, and ran at Harry instead.\par
\ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 ! \i Impedimenta\i0 ! \i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote\par
But it was no use \emdash  the spider was either so large, or so magical, that the spells were doing no more than aggravating it. Harry had one horrifying glimpse of eight shining black eyes and razor-sharp pincers before it was upon him.\par
He was lifted into the air in its front legs; struggling madly, he tried to kick it; his leg connected with the pincers and next moment he was in excruciating pain. He could hear Cedric yelling \ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote  too, but his spell had no more effect than Harry\rquote s \emdash  Harry raised his wand as the spider opened its pincers once more and shouted \ldblquote\i Expelliarmus\i0 !\rdblquote\par
It worked \emdash  the Disarming Spell made the spider drop him, but that meant that Harry fell twelve feet onto his already injured leg, which crumpled beneath him. Without pausing to think, he aimed high at the spider\rquote s underbelly, as he had done with the skrewt, and shouted \ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote  just as Cedric yelled the same thing.\par
The two spells combined did what one alone had not: The spi\-der keeled over sideways, flattening a nearby hedge, and strewing the path with a tangle of hairy legs.\par
\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  he heard Cedric shouting. \ldblquote You all right? Did it fall on you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  Harry called back, panting. He looked down at his leg. It was bleeding freely. He could see some sort of thick, gluey secre\-tion from the spider\rquote s pincers on his torn robes. He tried to get up, but his leg was shaking badly and did not want to support his weight. He leaned against the hedge, gasping for breath, and looked around.\par
Cedric was standing feet from the Triwizard Cup, which was gleaming behind him.\par
\ldblquote Take it, then,\rdblquote  Harry panted to Cedric. \ldblquote Go on, take it. You\rquote re there.\rdblquote\par
But Cedric didn\rquote t move. He merely stood there, looking at Harry. Then he turned to stare at the cup. Harry saw the longing expression on his face in its golden light. Cedric looked around at Harry again, who was now holding onto the hedge to support him\-self. Cedric took a deep breath.\par
\ldblquote You take it. You should win. That\rquote s twice you\rquote ve saved my neck in here.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s not how it\rquote s supposed to work,\rdblquote  Harry said. He felt an\-gry; his leg was very painful, he was aching all over from trying to throw off the spider, and after all his efforts, Cedric had beaten him to it, just as he\rquote d beaten Harry to ask Cho to the ball. \ldblquote The one who reaches the cup first gets the points. That\rquote s you. I\rquote m telling you, I\rquote m not going to win any races on this leg.\rdblquote\par
Cedric took a few paces nearer to the Stunned spider, away from the cup, shaking his head.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\ldblquote Stop being noble,\rdblquote  said Harry irritably. \ldblquote Just take it, then we can get out of here.\rdblquote\par
Cedric watched Harry steadying himself, holding tight to the hedge.\par
\ldblquote You told me about the dragons,\rdblquote  Cedric said. \ldblquote I would\rquote ve gone down in the first task if you hadn\rquote t told me what was coming.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I had help on that too,\rdblquote  Harry snapped, trying to mop up his bloody leg with his robes. \ldblquote You helped me with the egg \emdash  we\rquote re square.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I had help on the egg in the first place,\rdblquote  said Cedric.\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re still square,\rdblquote  said Harry, testing his leg gingerly; it shook violently as he put weight on it; he had sprained his ankle when the spider had dropped him.\par
\ldblquote You should\rquote ve got more points on the second task,\rdblquote  said Cedric mulishly. \ldblquote You stayed behind to get all the hostages. I should\rquote ve done that.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I was the only one who was thick enough to take that song se\-riously!\rdblquote  said Harry bitterly. \ldblquote Just take the cup!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Cedric.\par
He stepped over the spider\rquote s tangled legs to join Harry, who stared at him. Cedric was serious. He was walking away from the sort of glory Hufflepuff House hadn\rquote t had in centuries.\par
\ldblquote Go on,\rdblquote  Cedric said. He looked as though this was costing him every ounce of resolution he had, but his face was set, his arms were folded, he seemed decided.\par
Harry looked from Cedric to the cup. For one shining moment, he saw himself emerging from the maze, holding it. He saw himself holding the Triwizard Cup aloft, heard the roar of the crowd, saw Cho\rquote s face shining with admiration, more clearly than he had ever seen it before \'85 and then the picture faded, and he found himself staring at Cedric\rquote s shadowy, stubborn face.\par
\ldblquote Both of us,\rdblquote  Harry said.\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote ll take it at the same time. It\rquote s still a Hogwarts victory. We\rquote ll tie for it.\rdblquote\par
Cedric stared at Harry. He unfolded his arms.\par
\ldblquote You \emdash  you sure?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Yeah \'85 we\rquote ve helped each other out, haven\rquote t we? We both got here. Let\rquote s just take it together.\rdblquote\par
For a moment, Cedric looked as though he couldn\rquote t believe his ears; then his face split in a grin.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re on,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Come here.\rdblquote\par
He grabbed Harry\rquote s arm below the shoulder and helped Harry limp toward the plinth where the cup stood. When they had reached it, they both held a hand out over one of the cup\rquote s gleam\-ing handles.\par
\ldblquote On three, right?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote One \emdash  two \emdash  three \emdash\rdblquote\par
He and Cedric both grasped a handle.\par
Instantly, Harry felt a jerk somewhere behind his navel. His feet had left the ground. He could not unclench the hand holding the Triwizard Cup; it was pulling him onward in a howl of wind and swirling color, Cedric at his side.\par
\par
