\ldblquote Who told Cedric to open it underwater? I did. I trusted that he would pass the information on to you. Decent people are so easy to manipulate, Potter. I was sure Cedric would want to repay you for telling him about the dragons, and so he did. But even then, Potter, even then you seemed likely to fail. I was watching all the time \'85 all those hours in the library. Didn\rquote t you realize that the book you needed was in your dormitory all along? I planted it there early on, I gave it to the Longbottom boy, don\rquote t you remember? \i Magical Water Plants of the Mediterranean. \i0 It would have told you all you needed to know about gillyweed. I expected you to ask everyone and anyone you could for help. Longbottom would have told you in an instant. But you did not \'85 you did not. \'85 You have a streak of pride and independence that might have ruined all.\par
\ldblquote So what could I do? Feed you information from another inno\-cent source. You told me at the Yule Ball a house-elf called Dobby had given you a Christmas present. I called the elf to the staffroom to collect some robes for cleaning. I staged a loud conversation with Professor McGonagall about the hostages who had been taken, and whether Potter would think to use gillyweed. And your little elf friend ran straight to Snape\rquote s office and then hurried to find you. \'85\rdblquote\par
Moody\rquote s wand was still pointing directly at Harry\rquote s heart. Over his shoulder, foggy shapes were moving in the Foe-Glass on the wall.\par
\ldblquote You were so long in that lake, Potter, I thought you had drowned. But luckily, Dumbledore took your idiocy for nobility, and marked you high for it. I breathed again.\par
\ldblquote You had an easier time of it than you should have in that maze tonight, of course,\rdblquote  said Moody. \ldblquote I was patrolling around it, able to see through the outer hedges, able to curse many obstacles out of your way. I Stunned Fleur Delacour as she passed. I put the Im\-perius Curse on Krum, so that he would finish Diggory and leave your path to the cup clear.\rdblquote\par
Harry stared at Moody. He just didn\rquote t see how this could be. \'85 Dumbledore\rquote s friend, the famous Auror \'85 the one who had caught so many Death Eaters \'85 It made no sense \'85 no sense at all. \'85\par
The foggy shapes in the Foe-Glass were sharpening, had become more distinct. Harry could see the outlines of three people over Moody\rquote s shoulder, moving closer and closer. But Moody wasn\rquote t watching them. His magical eye was upon Harry.\par
\ldblquote The Dark Lord didn\rquote t manage to kill you, Potter, and he \i so \i0 wanted to,\rdblquote  whispered Moody. \ldblquote Imagine how he will reward me when he finds I have done it for him. I gave you to him \emdash  the thing he needed above all to regenerate \emdash  and then I killed you for him. I will be honored beyond all other Death Eaters. I will be his dearest, his closest supporter \'85 closer than a son. \'85\rdblquote\par
Moody\rquote s normal eye was bulging, the magical eye fixed upon Harry. The door was barred, and Harry knew he would never reach his own wand in time. \'85\par
\ldblquote The Dark Lord and I,\rdblquote  said Moody, and he looked completely insane now, towering over Harry, leering down at him, \ldblquote have much in common. Both of us, for instance, had very disappointing fathers \'85 very disappointing indeed. Both of us suffered the in\-dignity, Harry, of being named after those fathers. And both of us had the pleasure \'85 the very great pleasure \'85 of killing our fathers to ensure the continued rise of the Dark Order!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re mad,\rdblquote  Harry said \emdash  he couldn\rquote t stop himself \emdash  \ldblquote you\rquote re mad!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mad, am I?\rdblquote  said Moody, his voice rising uncontrollably. \ldblquote We\rquote ll see! We\rquote ll see who\rquote s mad, now that the Dark Lord has returned, with me at his side! He is back, Harry Potter, you did not conquer him \emdash  and now \emdash  I conquer you!\rdblquote\par
Moody raised his wand, he opened his mouth; Harry plunged his own hand into his robes \emdash\par
\ldblquote\i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote  There was a blinding flash of red light, and with a great splintering and crashing, the door of Moody\rquote s office was blasted apart \emdash\par
Moody was thrown backward onto the office floor. Harry, still staring at the place where Moody\rquote s face had been, saw Albus Dum\-bledore, Professor Snape, and Professor McGonagall looking back at him out of the Foe-Glass. He looked around and saw the three of them standing in the doorway, Dumbledore in front, his wand outstretched.\par
At that moment, Harry fully understood for the first time why people said Dumbledore was the only wizard Voldemort had ever feared. The look upon Dumbledore\rquote s face as he stared down at the unconscious form of Mad-Eye Moody was more terrible than Harry could have ever imagined. There was no benign smile upon Dumbledore\rquote s face, no twinkle in the eyes behind the spectacles. There was cold fury in every line of the ancient face; a sense of power radiated from Dumbledore as though he were giving off burning heat.\par
He stepped into the office, placed a foot underneath Moody\rquote s unconscious body, and kicked him over onto his back, so that his face was visible. Snape followed him, looking into the Foe-Glass, where his own face was still visible, glaring into the room. Profes\-sor McGonagall went straight to Harry.\par
\ldblquote Come along, Potter,\rdblquote  she whispered. The thin line of her mouth was twitching as though she was about to cry. \ldblquote Come along \'85 hospital wing \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore sharply.\par
\ldblquote Dumbledore, he ought to \emdash  look at him \emdash  he\rquote s been through enough tonight \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He will stay, Minerva, because he needs to understand,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore curtly. \ldblquote Understanding is the first step to acceptance, and only with acceptance can there be recovery. He needs to know who has put him through the ordeal he has suffered tonight, and why.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Moody,\rdblquote  Harry said. He was still in a state of complete disbe\-lief. \ldblquote How can it have been Moody?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote This is not Alastor Moody,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly. \ldblquote You have never known Alastor Moody. The real Moody would not have removed you from my sight after what happened tonight. The mo\-ment he took you, I knew \emdash  and I followed.\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore bent down over Moody\rquote s limp form and put a hand inside his robes. He pulled out Moody\rquote s hip flask and a set of keys on a ring. Then he turned to Professors McGonagall and Snape.\par
\ldblquote Severus, please fetch me the strongest Truth Potion you possess, and then go down to the kitchens and bring up the house-elf called Winky. Minerva, kindly go down to Hagrid\rquote s house, where you will find a large black dog sitting in the pumpkin patch. Take the dog up to my office, tell him I will be with him shortly, then come back here.\rdblquote\par
If either Snape or McGonagall found these instructions peculiar, they hid their confusion. Both turned at once and left the office. Dumbledore walked over to the trunk with seven locks, fitted the first key in the lock, and opened it. It contained a mass of spell-books. Dumbledore closed the trunk, placed a second key in the second lock, and opened the trunk again. The spellbooks had van\-ished; this time it contained an assortment of broken Sneako-scopes, some parchment and quills, and what looked like a silvery Invisibility Cloak. Harry watched, astounded, as Dumbledore placed the third, fourth, fifth, and sixth keys in their respective locks, reopening the trunk, and each time revealing different con\-tents. Then he placed the seventh key in the lock, threw open the lid, and Harry let out a cry of amazement.\par
He was looking down into a kind of pit, an underground room, and lying on the floor some ten feet below, apparently fast asleep, thin and starved in appearance, was the real Mad-Eye Moody. His wooden leg was gone, the socket that should have held the magical eye looked empty beneath its lid, and chunks of his grizzled hair were missing. Harry stared, thunderstruck, between the sleeping Moody in the trunk and the unconscious Moody lying on the floor of the office.\par
Dumbledore climbed into the trunk, lowered himself, and fell lightly onto the floor beside the sleeping Moody. He bent over him.\par
\ldblquote Stunned \emdash  controlled by the Imperius Curse \emdash  very weak,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Of course, they would have needed to keep him alive. Harry, throw down the imposter\rquote s cloak \emdash  he\rquote s freezing. Madam Pomfrey will need to see him, but he seems in no immediate danger.\rdblquote\par
Harry did as he was told; Dumbledore covered Moody in the cloak, tucked it around him, and clambered out of the trunk again. Then he picked up the hip flask that stood upon the desk, unscrewed it, and turned it over. A thick glutinous liquid splattered onto the office floor.\par
\ldblquote Polyjuice Potion, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote You see the sim\-plicity of it, and the brilliance. For Moody never \i does\i0  drink except from his hip flask, he\rquote s well known for it. The imposter needed, of course, to keep the real Moody close by, so that he could continue making the potion. You see his hair \'85\rdblquote  Dumbledore looked down on the Moody in the trunk. \ldblquote The imposter has been cutting it off all year, see where it is uneven? But I think, in the excitement of tonight, our fake Moody might have forgotten to take it as frequently as he should have done \'85 on the hour \'85 every hour. \'85 We shall see.\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore pulled out the chair at the desk and sat down upon it, his eyes fixed upon the unconscious Moody on the floor. Harry stared at him too. Minutes passed in silence. \'85\par
Then, before Harry\rquote s very eyes, the face of the man on the floor began to change. The scars were disappearing, the skin was becom\-ing smooth; the mangled nose became whole and started to shrink. The long mane of grizzled gray hair was withdrawing into the scalp and turning the color of straw. Suddenly, with a loud \i clunk\i0 , the wooden leg fell away as a normal leg regrew in its place; next mo\-ment, the magical eyeball had popped out of the man\rquote s face as a real eye replaced it; it rolled away across the floor and continued to swivel in every direction.\par
Harry saw a man lying before him, pale-skinned, slightly freck\-led, with a mop of fair hair. He knew who he was. He had seen him in Dumbledore\rquote s Pensieve, had watched him being led away from court by the dementors, trying to convince Mr. Crouch that he was innocent \'85 but he was lined around the eyes now and looked much older. \'85\par
There were hurried footsteps outside in the corridor. Snape had returned with Winky at his heels. Professor McGonagall was right behind them.\par
\ldblquote Crouch!\rdblquote  Snape said, stopping dead in the doorway. \ldblquote Barty Crouch!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good heavens,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall, stopping dead and staring down at the man on the floor.\par
Filthy, disheveled, Winky peered around Snape\rquote s legs. Her mouth opened wide and she let out a piercing shriek.\par
\ldblquote Master Barty, Master Barty, what is you doing here?\rdblquote\par
She flung herself forward onto the young man\rquote s chest.\par
\ldblquote You is killed him! You is killed him! You is killed Master\rquote s son!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He is simply Stunned, Winky,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Step aside, please. Severus, you have the potion?\rdblquote\par
Snape handed Dumbledore a small glass bottle of completely clear liquid: the Veritaserum with which he had threatened Harry in class. Dumbledore got up, bent over the man on the floor, and pulled him into a sitting position against the wall beneath the Foe-Glass, in which the reflections of Dumbledore, Snape, and McGonagall were still glaring down upon them all. Winky re\-mained on her knees, trembling, her hands over her face. Dum\-bledore forced the man\rquote s mouth open and poured three drops inside it. Then he pointed his wand at the man\rquote s chest and said, \ldblquote\i Rennervate.\i0\rdblquote\par
Crouch\rquote s son opened his eyes. His face was slack, his gaze unfo\-cused. Dumbledore knelt before him, so that their faces were level.\par
\ldblquote Can you hear me?\rdblquote  Dumbledore asked quietly.\par
The man\rquote s eyelids flickered.\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  he muttered.\par
\ldblquote I would like you to tell us,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore softly, \ldblquote how you came to be here. How did you escape from Azkaban?\rdblquote\par
Crouch took a deep, shuddering breath, then began to speak in a flat, expressionless voice.\par
\ldblquote My mother saved me. She knew she was dying. She persuaded my father to rescue me as a last favor to her. He loved her as he had never loved me. He agreed. They came to visit me. They gave me a draft of Polyjuice Potion containing one of my mother\rquote s hairs. She took a draft of Polyjuice Potion containing one of my hairs. We took on each other\rquote s appearance.\rdblquote\par
Winky was shaking her head, trembling.\par
\ldblquote Say no more, Master Barty, say no more, you is getting your father into trouble!\rdblquote\par
But Crouch took another deep breath and continued in the same flat voice.\par
\ldblquote The dementors are blind. They sensed one healthy, one dying person entering Azkaban. They sensed one healthy, one dying per\-son leaving it. My father smuggled me out, disguised as my mother, in case any prisoners were watching through their doors.\par
\ldblquote My mother died a short while afterward in Azkaban. She was careful to drink Polyjuice Potion until the end. She was buried un\-der my name and bearing my appearance. Everyone believed her to be me.\rdblquote\par
The man\rquote s eyelids flickered.\par
\ldblquote And what did your father do with you, when he had got you home?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quietly.\par
\ldblquote Staged my mother\rquote s death. A quiet, private funeral. That grave is empty. The house-elf nursed me back to health. Then I had to be concealed. I had to be controlled. My father had to use a number of spells to subdue me. When I had recovered my strength, I thought only of finding my master \'85 of returning to his service.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How did your father subdue you?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\par
\ldblquote The Imperius Curse,\rdblquote  Crouch said. \ldblquote I was under my father\rquote s control. I was forced to wear an Invisibility Cloak day and night. I was always with the house-elf. She was my keeper and caretaker. She pitied me. She persuaded my father to give me occasional treats. Rewards for my good behavior.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Master Barty, Master Barty,\rdblquote  sobbed Winky through her hands. \ldblquote You isn\rquote t ought to tell them, we is getting in trouble. \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Did anybody ever discover that you were still alive?\rdblquote  said Dum\-bledore softly. \ldblquote Did anyone know except your father and the house-elf?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Crouch, his eyelids flickering again. \ldblquote A witch in my father\rquote s office. Bertha Jorkins. She came to the house with papers for my father\rquote s signature. He was not at home. Winky showed her inside and returned to the kitchen, to me. But Bertha Jorkins heard Winky talking to me. She came to investigate. She heard enough to guess who was hiding under the Invisibility Cloak. My father ar\-rived home. She confronted him. He put a very powerful Memory Charm on her to make her forget what she\rquote d found out. Too pow\-erful. He said it damaged her memory permanently.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why is she coming to nose into my master\rquote s private business?\rdblquote  sobbed Winky. \ldblquote Why isn\rquote t she leaving us be?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Tell me about the Quidditch World Cup,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\par
\ldblquote Winky talked my father into it,\rdblquote  said Crouch, still in the same monotonous voice. \ldblquote She spent months persuading him. I had not left the house for years. I had loved Quidditch. Let him go, she said. He will be in his Invisibility Cloak. He can watch. Let him smell fresh air for once. She said my mother would have wanted it. She told my father that my mother had died to give me freedom. She had not saved me for a life of imprisonment. He agreed in the end.\par
\ldblquote It was carefully planned. My father led me and Winky up to the Top Box early in the day. Winky was to say that she was saving a seat for my father. I was to sit there, invisible. When everyone had left the box, we would emerge. Winky would appear to be alone. Nobody would ever know.\par
\ldblquote But Winky didn\rquote t know that I was growing stronger. I was start\-ing to fight my father\rquote s Imperius Curse. There were times when I was almost myself again. There were brief periods when I seemed outside his control. It happened, there, in the Top Box. It was like waking from a deep sleep. I found myself out in public, in the mid\-dle of the match, and I saw, in front of me, a wand sticking out of a boy\rquote s pocket. I had not been allowed a wand since before Azka\-ban. I stole it. Winky didn\rquote t know. Winky is frightened of heights. She had her face hidden.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Master Barty, you bad boy!\rdblquote  whispered Winky, tears trickling between her fingers.\par
\ldblquote So you took the wand,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote and what did you do with it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We went back to the tent,\rdblquote  said Crouch. \ldblquote Then we heard them. We heard the Death Eaters. The ones who had never been to Azka\-ban. The ones who had never suffered for my master. They had turned their backs on him. They were not enslaved, as I was. They were free to seek him, but they did not. They were merely making sport of Muggles. The sound of their voices awoke me. My mind was clearer than it had been in years. I was angry. I had the wand. I wanted to attack them for their disloyalty to my master. My father had left the tent; he had gone to free the Muggles. Winky was afraid to see me so angry. She used her own brand of magic to bind me to her. She pulled me from the tent, pulled me into the forest, away from the Death Eaters. I tried to hold her back. I wanted to return to the campsite. I wanted to show those Death Eaters what loyalty to the Dark Lord meant, and to punish them for their lack of it. I used the stolen wand to cast the Dark Mark into the sky.\par
\ldblquote Ministry wizards arrived. They shot Stunning Spells every\-where. One of the spells came through the trees where Winky and I stood. The bond connecting us was broken. We were both Stunned.\par
\ldblquote When Winky was discovered, my father knew I must be nearby. He searched the bushes where she had been found and felt me lying there. He waited until the other Ministry members had left the forest. He put me back under the Imperius Curse and took me home. He dismissed Winky. She had failed him. She had let me acquire a wand. She had almost let me escape.\rdblquote\par
Winky let out a wail of despair.\par
\ldblquote Now it was just Father and I, alone in the house. And then \'85 and then \'85\rdblquote  Crouch\rquote s head rolled on his neck, and an insane grin spread across his face. \ldblquote My master came for me.\par
\ldblquote He arrived at our house late one night in the arms of his servant Wormtail. My master had found out that I was still alive. He had captured Bertha Jorkins in Albania. He had tortured her. She told him a great deal. She told him about the Triwizard Tournament. She told him the old Auror, Moody, was going to teach at Hog\-warts. He tortured her until he broke through the Memory Charm my father had placed upon her. She told him I had escaped from Azkaban. She told him my father kept me imprisoned to prevent me from seeking my master. And so my master knew that I was still his faithful servant \emdash  perhaps the most faithful of all. My master conceived a plan, based upon the information Bertha had given him. He needed me. He arrived at our house near midnight. My father answered the door.\rdblquote\par
The smile spread wider over Crouch\rquote s face, as though recalling the sweetest memory of his life. Winky\rquote s petrified brown eyes were visible through her fingers. She seemed too appalled to speak.\par
\ldblquote It was very quick. My father was placed under the Imperius Curse by my master. Now my father was the one imprisoned, con\-trolled. My master forced him to go about his business as usual, to act as though nothing was wrong. And I was released. I awoke. I was myself again, alive as I hadn\rquote t been in years.\par
\ldblquote And what did Lord Voldemort ask you to do?\rdblquote  said Dumble\-dore.\par
\ldblquote He asked me whether I was ready to risk everything for him. I was ready. It was my dream, my greatest ambition, to serve him, to prove myself to him. He told me he needed to place a faithful ser\-vant at Hogwarts. A servant who would guide Harry Potter through the Triwizard Tournament without appearing to do so. A servant who would watch over Harry Potter. Ensure he reached the Triwizard Cup. Turn the cup into a Portkey, which would take the first person to touch it to my master. But first \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You needed Alastor Moody,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. His blue eyes were blazing, though his voice remained calm.\par
\ldblquote Wormtail and I did it. We had prepared the Polyjuice Potion beforehand. We journeyed to his house. Moody put up a struggle. There was a commotion. We managed to subdue him just in time. Forced him into a compartment of his own magical trunk. Took some of his hair and added it to the potion. I drank it; I became Moody\rquote s double. I took his leg and his eye. I was ready to face Arthur Weasley when he arrived to sort out the Muggles who had heard a disturbance. I made the dustbins move around the yard. I told Arthur Weasley I had heard intruders in my yard, who had set off the dustbins. Then I packed up Moody\rquote s clothes and Dark detectors, put them in the trunk with Moody, and set off for Hog\-warts. I kept him alive, under the Imperius Curse. I wanted to be able to question him. To find out about his past, learn his habits, so that I could fool even Dumbledore. I also needed his hair to make the Polyjuice Potion. The other ingredients were easy. I stole boom-slang skin from the dungeons. When the Potions master found me in his office, I said I was under orders to search it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And what became of Wormtail after you attacked Moody?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\par
\ldblquote Wormtail returned to care for my master, in my father\rquote s house, and to keep watch over my father.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But your father escaped,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\par
\ldblquote Yes. After a while he began to fight the Imperius Curse just as I had done. There were periods when he knew what was happening. My master decided it was no longer safe for my father to leave the house. He forced him to send letters to the Ministry instead. He made him write and say he was ill. But Wormtail neglected his duty. He was not watchful enough. My father escaped. My master guessed that he was heading for Hogwarts. My father was going to tell Dumbledore everything, to confess. He was going to admit that he had smuggled me from Azkaban.\par
\ldblquote My master sent me word of my father\rquote s escape. He told me to stop him at all costs. So I waited and watched. I used the map I had taken from Harry Potter. The map that had almost ruined everything.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Map?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore quickly. \ldblquote What map is this?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Potter\rquote s map of Hogwarts. Potter saw me on it. Potter saw me stealing more ingredients for the Polyjuice Potion from Snape\rquote s of\-fice one night. He thought I was my father. We have the same first name. I took the map from Potter that night. I told him my father hated Dark wizards. Potter believed my father was after Snape.\par
\ldblquote For a week I waited for my father to arrive at Hogwarts. At last, one evening, the map showed my father entering the grounds. I pulled on my Invisibility Cloak and went down to meet him. He was walking around the edge of the forest. Then Potter came, and Krum. I waited. I could not hurt Potter; my master needed him. Potter ran to get Dumbledore. I Stunned Krum. I killed my father.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote\i Noooo\i0 !\rdblquote  wailed Winky. \ldblquote Master Barty, Master Barty, what is you saying?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You killed your father,\rdblquote  Dumbledore said, in the same soft voice. \ldblquote What did you do with the body?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Carried it into the forest. Covered it with the Invisibility Cloak. I had the map with me. I watched Potter run into the castle. He met Snape. Dumbledore joined them. I watched Potter bringing Dumbledore out of the castle. I walked back out of the forest, dou\-bled around behind them, went to meet them. I told Dumbledore Snape had told me where to come.\par
\ldblquote Dumbledore told me to go and look for my father. I went back to my father\rquote s body. Watched the map. When everyone was gone, I Transfigured my father\rquote s body. He became a bone \'85 I buried it, while wearing the Invisibility Cloak, in the freshly dug earth in front of Hagrid\rquote s cabin.\rdblquote\par
There was complete silence now, except for Winky\rquote s continued sobs. Then Dumbledore said, \ldblquote And tonight \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I offered to carry the Triwizard Cup into the maze before din\-ner,\rdblquote  whispered Barty Crouch. \ldblquote Turned it into a Portkey. My mas\-ter\rquote s plan worked. He is returned to power and I will be honored by him beyond the dreams of wizards.\rdblquote\par
The insane smile lit his features once more, and his head drooped onto his shoulder as Winky wailed and sobbed at his side.\par
