It seemed Fudge could think of no answer to this. He rocked backward and forward on his small feet for a moment and spun his bowler hat in his hands. Finally, he said, with a hint of a plea in his voice, \ldblquote He can\rquote t be back, Dumbledore, he just can\rquote t be \'85\rdblquote\par
Snape strode forward, past Dumbledore, pulling up the left sleeve of his robes as he went. He stuck out his forearm and showed it to Fudge, who recoiled.\par
\ldblquote There,\rdblquote  said Snape harshly. \ldblquote There. The Dark Mark. It is not as clear as it was an hour or so ago, when it burned black, but you can still see it. Every Death Eater had the sign burned into him by the Dark Lord. It was a means of distinguishing one another, and his means of summoning us to him. When he touched the Mark of any Death Eater, we were to Disapparate, and Apparate, instantly, at his side. This Mark has been growing clearer all year. Karkaroff\rquote s too. Why do you think Karkaroff fled tonight? We both felt the Mark burn. We both knew he had returned. Karkaroff fears the Dark Lord\rquote s vengeance. He betrayed too many of his fellow Death Eaters to be sure of a welcome back into the fold.\rdblquote\par
Fudge stepped back from Snape too. He was shaking his head. He did not seem to have taken in a word Snape had said. He stared, apparently repelled by the ugly mark on Snape\rquote s arm, then looked up at Dumbledore and whispered, \ldblquote I don\rquote t know what you and your staff are playing at, Dumbledore, but I have heard enough. I have no more to add. I will be in touch with you tomorrow, Dum\-bledore, to discuss the running of this school. I must return to the Ministry.\rdblquote\par
He had almost reached the door when he paused. He turned around, strode back down the dormitory, and stopped at Harry\rquote s bed.\par
\ldblquote Your winnings,\rdblquote  he said shortly, taking a large bag of gold out of his pocket and dropping it onto Harry\rquote s bedside table. \ldblquote One thousand Galleons. There should have been a presentation cere\-mony, but under the circumstances \'85\rdblquote\par
He crammed his bowler hat onto his head and walked out of the room, slamming the door behind him. The moment he had disap\-peared, Dumbledore turned to look at the group around Harry\rquote s bed.\par
\ldblquote There is work to be done,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Molly \'85 am I right in thinking that I can count on you and Arthur?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course you can,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley. She was white to the lips, but she looked resolute. \ldblquote We know what Fudge is. It\rquote s Arthur\rquote s fondness for Muggles that has held him back at the Ministry all these years. Fudge thinks he lacks proper wizarding pride.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then I need to send a message to Arthur,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote All those that we can persuade of the truth must be notified im\-mediately, and he is well placed to contact those at the Ministry who are not as shortsighted as Cornelius.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll go to Dad,\rdblquote  said Bill, standing up. \ldblquote I\rquote ll go now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Excellent,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Tell him what has happened. Tell him I will be in direct contact with him shortly. He will need to be dis\-creet, however. If Fudge thinks I am interfering at the Ministry \emdash\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Leave it to me,\rdblquote  said Bill.\par
He clapped a hand on Harry\rquote s shoulder, kissed his mother on the cheek, pulled on his cloak, and strode quickly from the room.\par
\ldblquote Minerva,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, turning to Professor McGonagall, \ldblquote I want to see Hagrid in my office as soon as possible. Also \emdash  if she will consent to come \emdash  Madame Maxime.\rdblquote\par
Professor McGonagall nodded and left without a word.\par
\ldblquote Poppy,\rdblquote  Dumbledore said to Madam Pomfrey, \ldblquote would you be very kind and go down to Professor Moody\rquote s office, where I think you will find a house-elf called Winky in considerable distress? Do what you can for her, and take her back to the kitchens. I think Dobby will look after her for us.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Very \emdash  very well,\rdblquote  said Madam Pomfrey, looking startled, and she too left.\par
Dumbledore made sure that the door was closed, and that Madam Pomfrey\rquote s footsteps had died away, before he spoke again.\par
\ldblquote And now,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote it is time for two of our number to recog\-nize each other for what they are. Sirius \'85 if you could resume your usual form.\rdblquote\par
The great black dog looked up at Dumbledore, then, in an in\-stant, turned back into a man.\par
Mrs. Weasley screamed and leapt back from the bed.\par
\ldblquote Sirius Black!\rdblquote  she shrieked, pointing at him.\par
\ldblquote Mum, shut up!\rdblquote  Ron yelled. \ldblquote It\rquote s okay!\rdblquote\par
Snape had not yelled or jumped backward, but the look on his face was one of mingled fury and horror.\par
\ldblquote Him!\rdblquote  he snarled, staring at Sirius, whose face showed equal dislike. \ldblquote What is he doing here?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He is here at my invitation,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, looking be\-tween them, \ldblquote as are you, Severus. I trust you both. It is time for you to lay aside your old differences and trust each other.\rdblquote\par
Harry thought Dumbledore was asking for a near miracle. Sirius and Snape were eyeing each other with the utmost loathing.\par
\ldblquote I will settle, in the short term,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, with a bite of impatience in his voice, \ldblquote for a lack of open hostility. You will shake hands. You are on the same side now. Time is short, and unless the few of us who know the truth do not stand united, there is no hope for any of us.\rdblquote\par
Very slowly \emdash  but still glaring at each other as though each wished the other nothing but ill \emdash  Sirius and Snape moved toward each other and shook hands. They let go extremely quickly.\par
\ldblquote That will do to be going on with,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, stepping between them once more. \ldblquote Now I have work for each of you. Fudge\rquote s attitude, though not unexpected, changes everything. Sir\-ius, I need you to set off at once. You are to alert Remus Lupin, Arabella Figg, Mundungus Fletcher \emdash  the old crowd. Lie low at Lupins for a while; I will contact you there.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
He wanted Sirius to stay. He did not want to have to say good\-bye again so quickly.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ll see me very soon, Harry,\rdblquote  said Sirius, turning to him. \ldblquote I promise you. But I must do what I can, you understand, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Yeah \'85 of course I do.\rdblquote\par
Sirius grasped his hand briefly, nodded to Dumbledore, trans\-formed again into the black dog, and ran the length of the room to the door, whose handle he turned with a paw. Then he was gone.\par
\ldblquote Severus,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, turning to Snape, \ldblquote you know what I must ask you to do. If you are ready \'85 if you are prepared \'85\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I am,\rdblquote  said Snape.\par
He looked slightly paler than usual, and his cold, black eyes glit\-tered strangely.\par
\ldblquote Then good luck,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and he watched, with a trace of apprehension on his face, as Snape swept wordlessly after Sirius.\par
It was several minutes before Dumbledore spoke again.\par
\ldblquote I must go downstairs,\rdblquote  he said finally. \ldblquote I must see the Diggorys. Harry \emdash  take the rest of your potion. I will see all of you later.\rdblquote\par
Harry slumped back against his pillows as Dumbledore disappeared. Hermione, Ron, and Mrs. Weasley were all looking at him. None of them spoke for a very long time.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve got to take the rest of your potion, Harry,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley said at last. Her hand nudged the sack of gold on his bedside cabi\-net as she reached for the bottle and the goblet. \ldblquote You have a good long sleep. Try and think about something else for a while \'85 think about what you\rquote re going to buy with your winnings!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t want that gold,\rdblquote  said Harry in an expressionless voice. \ldblquote You have it. Anyone can have it. I shouldn\rquote t have won it. It should\rquote ve been Cedric\rquote s.\rdblquote\par
The thing against which he had been fighting on and off ever since he had come out of the maze was threatening to overpower him. He could feel a burning, prickling feeling in the inner corners of his eyes. He blinked and stared up at the ceiling.\par
\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t your fault, Harry,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley whispered.\par
\ldblquote I told him to take the cup with me,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Now the burning feeling was in his throat too. He wished Ron would look away.\par
Mrs. Weasley set the potion down on the bedside cabinet, bent down, and put her arms around Harry. He had no memory of ever being hugged like this, as though by a mother. The full weight of everything he had seen that night seemed to fall in upon him as Mrs. Weasley held him to her. His mother\rquote s face, his father\rquote s voice, the sight of Cedric, dead on the ground all started spinning in his head until he could hardly bear it, until he was screwing up his face against the howl of misery fighting to get out of him.\par
There was a loud slamming noise, and Mrs. Weasley and Harry broke apart. Hermione was standing by the window. She was hold\-ing something tight in her hand.\par
\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  she whispered.\par
\ldblquote Your potion, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley quickly, wiping her eyes on the back of her hand.\par
Harry drank it in one gulp. The effect was instantaneous. Heavy, irresistible waves of dreamless sleep broke over him; he fell back onto his pillows and thought no more.\par
