When he looked back, even a month later, Harry found he had only scattered memories of the next few days. It was as though he had been through too much to take in any more. The recollections he did have were very painful. The worst, perhaps, was the meeting with the Diggorys that took place the following morning.\par
They did not blame him for what had happened; on the con\-trary, both thanked him for returning Cedric\rquote s body to them. Mr. Diggory sobbed through most of the interview. Mrs. Diggory\rquote s grief seemed to be beyond tears.\par
\ldblquote He suffered very little then,\rdblquote  she said, when Harry had told her how Cedric had died. \ldblquote And after all, Amos \'85 he died just when he\rquote d won the tournament. He must have been happy.\rdblquote\par
When they got to their feet, she looked down at Harry and said, \ldblquote You look after yourself, now.\rdblquote\par
Harry seized the sack of gold on the bedside table.\par
\ldblquote You take this,\rdblquote  he muttered to her. \ldblquote It should\rquote ve been Cedric\rquote s, he got there first, you take it \emdash\rdblquote\par
But she backed away from him.\par
\ldblquote Oh no, it\rquote s yours, dear, I couldn\rquote t \'85 you keep it.\rdblquote\par
\par
Harry returned to Gryffindor Tower the following evening. From what Hermione and Ron told him, Dumbledore had spoken to the school that morning at breakfast. He had merely requested that they leave Harry alone, that nobody ask him questions or badger him to tell the story of what had happened in the maze. Most peo\-ple, he noticed, were skirting him in the corridors, avoiding his eyes. Some whispered behind their hands as he passed. He guessed that many of them had believed Rita Skeeter\rquote s article about how disturbed and possibly dangerous he was. Perhaps they were for\-mulating their own theories about how Cedric had died. He found he didn\rquote t care very much. He liked it best when he was with Ron and Hermione and they were talking about other things, or else let\-ting him sit in silence while they played chess. He felt as though all three of them had reached an understanding they didn\rquote t need to put into words; that each was waiting for some sign, some word, of what was going on outside Hogwarts \emdash  and that it was useless to speculate about what might be coming until they knew anything for certain. The only time they touched upon the subject was when Ron told Harry about a meeting Mrs. Weasley had had with Dum\-bledore before going home.\par
\ldblquote She went to ask him if you could come straight to us this sum\-mer,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote But he wants you to go back to the Dursleys, at least at first.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote She said Dumbledore\rquote s got his reasons,\rdblquote  said Ron, shaking his head darkly. \ldblquote I suppose we\rquote ve got to trust him, haven\rquote t we?\rdblquote\par
The only person apart from Ron and Hermione that Harry felt able to talk to was Hagrid. As there was no longer a Defense Against the Dark Arts teacher, they had those lessons free. They used the one on Thursday afternoon to go down and visit Hagrid in his cabin. It was a bright and sunny day; Fang bounded out of the open door as they approached, barking and wagging his tail madly.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s that?\rdblquote  called Hagrid, coming to the door. \ldblquote\i Harry\i0 !\rdblquote\par
He strode out to meet them, pulled Harry into a one-armed hug, ruffled his hair, and said, \ldblquote Good ter see yeh, mate. Good ter see yeh.\rdblquote\par
They saw two bucket-size cups and saucers on the wooden table in front of the fireplace when they entered Hagrid\rquote s cabin.\par
\ldblquote Bin havin\rquote  a cuppa with Olympe,\rdblquote  Hagrid said. \ldblquote She\rquote s jus\rquote  left.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Who?\rdblquote  said Ron curiously.\par
\ldblquote Madame Maxime, o\rquote  course!\rdblquote  said Hagrid.\par
\ldblquote You two made up, have you?\rdblquote  said Ron.\par
\ldblquote Dunno what yeh\rquote re talkin\rquote  about,\rdblquote  said Hagrid airily, fetching more cups from the dresser. When he had made tea and offered around a plate of doughy cookies, he leaned back in his chair and surveyed Harry closely through his beetle-black eyes.\par
\ldblquote You all righ\rquote ?\rdblquote  he said gruffly.\par
\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
\ldblquote No, yeh\rquote re not,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote  \rquote Course yeh\rquote re not. But yeh will be.\rdblquote\par
Harry said nothing.\par
\ldblquote Knew he was goin\rquote  ter come back,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, and Harry, Ron, and Hermione looked up at him, shocked. \ldblquote Known it fer years, Harry. Knew he was out there, bidin\rquote  his time. It had ter hap\-pen. Well, now it has, an\rquote  we\rquote ll jus\rquote  have ter get on with it. We\rquote ll fight. Migh\rquote  be able ter stop him before he gets a good hold. That\rquote s Dumbledore\rquote s plan, anyway. Great man, Dumbledore. \rquote S long as we\rquote ve got him, I\rquote m not too worried.\rdblquote\par
Hagrid raised his bushy eyebrows at the disbelieving expressions on their faces.\par
\ldblquote No good sittin\rquote  worryin\rquote  abou\rquote  it,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote What\rquote s comin\rquote  will come, an\rquote  we\rquote ll meet it when it does. Dumbledore told me wha\rquote  you did, Harry.\rdblquote\par
Hagrid\rquote s chest swelled as he looked at Harry.\par
\ldblquote Yeh did as much as yer father would\rquote ve done, an\rquote  I can\rquote  give yeh no higher praise than that.\rdblquote\par
Harry smiled back at him. It was the first time he\rquote d smiled in days. \ldblquote What\rquote s Dumbledore asked you to do, Hagrid?\rdblquote  he asked. \ldblquote He sent Professor McGonagall to ask you and Madame Maxime to meet him \emdash  that night.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Got a little job fer me over the summer,\rdblquote  said Hagrid. \ldblquote Secret, though. I\rquote m not s\rquote pposed ter talk abou\rquote  it, no, not even ter you lot. Olympe \emdash  Madame Maxime ter you \emdash  might be comin\rquote  with me. I think she will. Think I got her persuaded.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Is it to do with Voldemort?\rdblquote\par
Hagrid flinched at the sound of the name.\par
\ldblquote Migh\rquote  be,\rdblquote  he said evasively. \ldblquote Now \'85 who\rquote d like ter come an\rquote  visit the las\rquote  skrewt with me? I was jokin\rquote  \emdash  jokin\rquote !\rdblquote  he added hastily, seeing the looks on their faces.\par
