\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj It was with a heavy heart that Harry packed his trunk up in the dormitory on the night before his return to Privet Drive. He was dreading the Leaving Feast, which was usually a cause for celebra\-tion, when the winner of the Inter-House Championship would be announced. He had avoided being in the Great Hall when it was full ever since he had left the hospital wing, preferring to eat when it was nearly empty to avoid the stares of his fellow students.\par
When he, Ron, and Hermione entered the Hall, they saw at once that the usual decorations were missing. The Great Hall was normally decorated with the winning House\rquote s colors for the Leav\-ing Feast. Tonight, however, there were black drapes on the wall behind the teachers\rquote  table. Harry knew instantly that they were there as a mark of respect to Cedric.\par
The real Mad-Eye Moody was at the staff table now, his wooden leg and his magical eye back in place. He was extremely twitchy, jumping every time someone spoke to him. Harry couldn\rquote t blame him; Moody\rquote s fear of attack was bound to have been increased by his ten-month imprisonment in his own trunk. Professor Karkar\-off\rquote s chair was empty. Harry wondered, as he sat down with the other Gryffindors, where Karkaroff was now, and whether Volde\-mort had caught up with him.\par
Madame Maxime was still there. She was sitting next to Hagrid. They were talking quietly together. Further along the table, sitting next to Professor McGonagall, was Snape. His eyes lingered on Harry for a moment as Harry looked at him. His expression was difficult to read. He looked as sour and unpleasant as ever. Harry continued to watch him, long after Snape had looked away.\par
What was it that Snape had done on Dumbledore\rquote s orders, the night that Voldemort had returned? And why \'85 \i why\i0  \'85 was Dumbledore so convinced that Snape was truly on their side? He had been their spy, Dumbledore had said so in the Pensieve. Snape had turned spy against Voldemort, \ldblquote at great personal risk.\rdblquote  Was that the job he had taken up again? Had he made contact with the Death Eaters, perhaps? Pretended that he had never really gone over to Dumbledore, that he had been, like Voldemort himself, biding his time?\par
Harry\rquote s musings were ended by Professor Dumbledore, who stood up at the staff table. The Great Hall, which in any case had been less noisy than it usually was at the Leaving Feast, became very quiet.\par
\ldblquote The end,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, looking around at them all, \ldblquote of another year.\rdblquote\par
He paused, and his eyes fell upon the Hufflepuff table. Theirs had been the most subdued table before he had gotten to his feet, and theirs were still the saddest and palest faces in the Hall.\par
\ldblquote There is much that I would like to say to you all tonight,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote but I must first acknowledge the loss of a very fine person, who should be sitting here,\rdblquote  he gestured toward the Huf\-flepuffs, \ldblquote enjoying our feast with us. I would like you all, please, to stand, and raise your glasses, to Cedric Diggory.\rdblquote\par
They did it, all of them; the benches scraped as everyone in the Hall stood, and raised their goblets, and echoed, in one loud, low, rumbling voice, \ldblquote Cedric Diggory.\rdblquote\par
Harry caught a glimpse of Cho through the crowd. There were tears pouring silently down her face. He looked down at the table as they all sat down again.\par
\ldblquote Cedric was a person who exemplified many of the qualities that distinguish Hufflepuff house,\rdblquote  Dumbledore continued. \ldblquote He was a good and loyal friend, a hard worker, he valued fair play. His death has affected you all, whether you knew him well or not. I think that you have the right, therefore, to know exactly how it came about.\rdblquote\par
Harry raised his head and stared at Dumbledore.\par
\ldblquote Cedric Diggory was murdered by Lord Voldemort.\rdblquote\par
A panicked whisper swept the Great Hall. People were staring at Dumbledore in disbelief, in horror. He looked perfectly calm as he watched them mutter themselves into silence.\par
\ldblquote The Ministry of Magic,\rdblquote  Dumbledore continued, \ldblquote does not wish me to tell you this. It is possible that some of your parents will be horrified that I have done so \emdash  either because they will not be\-lieve that Lord Voldemort has returned, or because they think I should not tell you so, young as you are. It is my belief, however, that the truth is generally preferable to lies, and that any attempt to pretend that Cedric died as the result of an accident, or some sort of blunder of his own, is an insult to his memory.\rdblquote\par
Stunned and frightened, every face in the Hall was turned toward Dumbledore now \'85 or almost every face. Over at the Slytherin table, Harry saw Draco Malfoy muttering something to Crabbe and Goyle. Harry felt a hot, sick swoop of anger in his stomach. He forced himself to look back at Dumbledore.\par
\ldblquote There is somebody else who must be mentioned in connection with Cedric\rquote s death,\rdblquote  Dumbledore went on. \ldblquote I am talking, of course, about Harry Potter.\rdblquote\par
A kind of ripple crossed the Great Hall as a few heads turned in Harry\rquote s direction before flicking back to face Dumbledore.\par
\ldblquote Harry Potter managed to escape Lord Voldemort,\rdblquote  said Dum\-bledore. \ldblquote He risked his own life to return Cedric\rquote s body to Hog\-warts. He showed, in every respect, the sort of bravery that few wizards have ever shown in facing Lord Voldemort, and for this, I honor him.\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore turned gravely to Harry and raised his goblet once more. Nearly everyone in the Great Hall followed suit. They mur\-mured his name, as they had murmured Cedric\rquote s, and drank to him. But through a gap in the standing figures, Harry saw that Malfoy, Crabbe, Goyle, and many of the other Slytherins had remained defiantly in their seats, their goblets untouched. Dumb\-ledore, who after all possessed no magical eye, did not see them.\par
When everyone had once again resumed their seats, Dumble\-dore continued, \ldblquote The Triwizard Tournament\rquote s aim was to further and promote magical understanding. In the light of what has hap\-pened \emdash  of Lord Voldemort\rquote s return \emdash  such ties are more impor\-tant than ever before.\rdblquote\par
Dumbledore looked from Madame Maxime and Hagrid, to Fleur Delacour and her fellow Beauxbatons students, to Viktor Krum and the Durmstrangs at the Slytherin table. Krum, Harry saw, looked wary, almost frightened, as though he expected Dum\-bledore to say something harsh.\par
\ldblquote Every guest in this Hall,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and his eyes lin\-gered upon the Durmstrang students, \ldblquote will be welcomed back here at any time, should they wish to come. I say to you all, once again \emdash  in the light of Lord Voldemort\rquote s return, we are only as strong as we are united, as weak as we are divided. Lord Volde\-mort\rquote s gift for spreading discord and enmity is very great. We can fight it only by showing an equally strong bond of friendship and trust. Differences of habit and language are nothing at all if our aims are identical and our hearts are open.\par
\ldblquote It is my belief \emdash  and never have I so hoped that I am mis\-taken \emdash  that we are all facing dark and difficult times. Some of you in this Hall have already suffered directly at the hands of Lord Voldemort. Many of your families have been torn asunder. A week ago, a student was taken from our midst.\par
\ldblquote Remember Cedric. Remember, if the time should come when you have to make a choice between what is right and what is easy, remember what happened to a boy who was good, and kind, and brave, because he strayed across the path of Lord Voldemort. Re\-member Cedric Diggory.\rdblquote\par
\par
Harry\rquote s trunk was packed; Hedwig was back in her cage on top of it. He, Ron, and Hermione were waiting in the crowded entrance hall with the rest of the fourth years for the carriages that would take them back to Hogsmeade station. It was another beautiful summer\rquote s day. He supposed that Privet Drive would be hot and leafy, its flower beds a riot of color, when he arrived there that evening. The thought gave him no pleasure at all.\par
\ldblquote  \rquote Arry!\rdblquote\par
He looked around. Fleur Delacour was hurrying up the stone steps into the castle. Beyond her, far across the grounds, Harry could see Hagrid helping Madame Maxime to back two of the gi\-ant horses into their harness. The Beauxbatons carriage was about to take off.\par
\ldblquote We will see each uzzer again, I \rquote ope,\rdblquote  said Fleur as she reached him, holding out her hand. \ldblquote I am \rquote oping to get a job \rquote ere, to im\-prove my Eenglish.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s very good already,\rdblquote  said Ron in a strangled sort of voice. Fleur smiled at him; Hermione scowled.\par
\ldblquote Good-bye, \rquote Arry,\rdblquote  said Fleur, turning to go. \ldblquote It \rquote az been a plea\-sure meeting you!\rdblquote\par
Harry\rquote s spirits couldn\rquote t help but lift slightly as he watched Fleur hurry back across the lawns to Madame Maxime, her silvery hair rippling in the sunlight.\par
\ldblquote Wonder how the Durmstrang students are getting back,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote D\rquote you reckon they can steer that ship without Karkaroff?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Karkaroff did not steer,\rdblquote  said a gruff voice. \ldblquote He stayed in his cabin and let us do the vork.\rdblquote\par
Krum had come to say good-bye to Hermione.\par
\ldblquote Could I have a vord?\rdblquote  he asked her.\par
\ldblquote Oh \'85 yes \'85 all right,\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking slightly flus\-tered, and following Krum through the crowd and out of sight.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote d better hurry up!\rdblquote  Ron called loudly after her. \ldblquote The car\-riages\rquote ll be here in a minute!\rdblquote\par
He let Harry keep a watch for the carriages, however, and spent the next few minutes craning his neck over the crowd to try and see what Krum and Hermione might be up to. They returned quite soon. Ron stared at Hermione, but her face was quite impassive.\par
\ldblquote I liked Diggory,\rdblquote  said Krum abruptly to Harry. \ldblquote He vos alvays polite to me. Alvays. Even though I vos from Durmstrang \emdash  with Karkaroff,\rdblquote  he added, scowling.\par
\ldblquote Have you got a new headmaster yet?\rdblquote  said Harry.\par
Krum shrugged. He held out his hand as Fleur had done, shook Harry\rquote s hand, and then Ron\rquote s. Ron looked as though he was suffer\-ing some sort of painful internal struggle. Krum had already started walking away when Ron burst out, \ldblquote Can I have your autograph?\rdblquote\par
Hermione turned away, smiling at the horseless carriages that were now trundling toward them up the drive, as Krum, looking surprised but gratified, signed a fragment of parchment for Ron.\par
